{"DRAMATIS PERSONAE":{"1":{"play":"OTHELLO, a Moorish general in the Venetian army.","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"DESDEMONA, a Venetian lady.","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"BRABANTIO, a Venetian senator, father to Desdemona.","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"IAGO, Othello's standard-bearer, or ancient.","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"EMILIA, Iago's wife and Desdemona's attendant.","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"CASSIO, Othello's second-in-command, or lieutenant.","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"RODERIGO, a Venetian gentleman.","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"DUKE OF VENICE.","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"LODOVICO.","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"GRATIANO.","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"VENETIAN GENTLEMEN, kinsmen to Brabantio.","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"VENETIAN SENATORS.","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"MONTANO, an official in Cyprus.","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"BIANCA, a woman in Cyprus in love with Cassio.","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"CLOWN, a comic servant to Othello and Desdemona.","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"GENTLEMEN OF CYPRUS.","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"SAILORS.","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"Servants, Attendants, Officers, Messengers, Herald, Musicians, Torchbearers.","notes":[]}},"ACT 1, SCENE 1":{"SD_1.1.0":{"play":"[Enter Roderigo and Iago.]","notes":["Collier: 'Of such a matter, abhorre me.' — Collier (ed. i) notes various readings and punctuation in early texts; the expression shows Brabantio's disgust at the subject mentioned."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.1.0","kind":"stage"},"1.1.1":{"play":"RODERIGO: Tush, never tell me! I take it much unkindly","notes":["Knight: 'Thou told'st me' — Knight and other editors note contraction and gloss meanings of told'st."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.1","kind":"speech"},"1.1.2":{"play":"RODERIGO: That thou, Iago, who hast had my purse","notes":["Staunton: 'Thou did'st hold him in thy hate.' — On the colloquial use of did'st and historical usages."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.2","kind":"speech"},"1.1.3":{"play":"RODERIGO: As if the strings were thine, shouldst know of this.","notes":["Editorial note: 'Despise me — I do not.' — Some texts print 'Defpise' as in older spelling; modernized here to 'Despise'."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.3","kind":"speech"},"1.1.4":{"play":"IAGO: ’Sblood, but you’ll not hear me!","notes":["Note: 'Three Great-ones of the Cittie...' — On the municipal magnates of Venice; see Contareno and Lewkenor for descriptions."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.4","kind":"speech"},"1.1.5":{"play":"IAGO: If ever I did dream of such a matter,","notes":["Editor: 'Oft-capt to him' — Variant readings: oft-capt (Folio) vs off-capt (Quartos); commentators discuss whether the phrase means 'stood cap in hand' (salaamed) or 'capped' in academic sense."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.5","kind":"speech"},"1.1.6":{"play":"IAGO: Abhor me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.6","kind":"speech"},"1.1.7":{"play":"RODERIGO: Thou toldst me thou didst hold him in thy hate.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.7","kind":"speech"},"1.1.8":{"play":"IAGO: Despise me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.8","kind":"speech"},"1.1.9":{"play":"IAGO: If I do not. Three great ones of the city,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.9","kind":"speech"},"1.1.10":{"play":"IAGO: In personal suit to make me his lieutenant,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.10","kind":"speech"},"1.1.11":{"play":"IAGO: Off-capped to him; and, by the faith of man,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.11","kind":"speech"},"1.1.12":{"play":"IAGO: I know my price, I am worth no worse a place.","notes":["Knight: 'I know my price, I am worth no worse a place.' — On Othello's pride and self-valuation; see textual variants and metrical remarks."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.12","kind":"speech"},"1.1.13":{"play":"IAGO: But he, as loving his own pride and purposes,","notes":["Note: 'But he (as loving his owne pride, and purposes) Evades them...' — Commentary on Iago's calumnious picture of Othello as arrogant, and on the collapsed lineation in different early texts."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.13","kind":"speech"},"1.1.14":{"play":"IAGO: Evades them with a bombast circumstance,","notes":["Reed: 'bombast Circumstance' — Definition and use of 'bombast' (originally cotton stuffed; hence 'puffed language') and 'circumstance' as circumlocution."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.14","kind":"speech"},"1.1.15":{"play":"IAGO: Horribly stuffed with epithets of war,","notes":["Editor: 'Horribly stuff'd with Epithets of warre;' — On Iago's caricature of Othello's style and language."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.15","kind":"speech"},"1.1.16":{"play":"IAGO: And in conclusion,","notes":["Knight: 'Nonsuits my Mediators.' — Legal phraseology: 'nonsuiting' in the courts; explanation of the term as used by Shakespeare."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.16","kind":"speech"},"1.1.17":{"play":"IAGO: Nonsuits my mediators. For says he,","notes":["Steevens: 'For certes, saies he,' — Note on the adverb 'certes' and its scansion as disyllable in early usage."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.17","kind":"speech"},"1.1.18":{"play":"IAGO: ","notes":["Textual note: 'I haue already chose my Officer. And what was he?' — Discussion of the punctuation and quotation marks in various early copies; whether 'For' begins the quotation."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.18","kind":"speech"},"1.1.19":{"play":"IAGO: And what was he?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.19","kind":"speech"},"1.1.20":{"play":"IAGO: Forsooth, a great arithmetician,","notes":["Note: 'Forsooth, a great Arithmetician,' — On 'Arithmetician' as derisive epithet for Cassio: bookish soldier, conversant with tactics on paper but not in field."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.20","kind":"speech"},"1.1.21":{"play":"IAGO: One Michael Cassio, a Florentine,","notes":["Annotation: 'One Michael Cassio, a Florentine,' — Debate among editors whether Cassio or Iago is the Florentine; discussion of implications and textual emendations (Florentine's, Florentine, etc.)."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.21","kind":"speech"},"1.1.22":{"play":"IAGO: A fellow almost damned in a fair wife,","notes":["Critical note: '(A Fellow almost damn'd in a faire Wife)' — Long note on the difficulty of 'a fellow almost damn'd in a fair wife' — many emendations and interpretations surveyed (Theobald, Hanmer, Tyrwhitt, Malone, Theobald's 'Florentine's', Hanmer's 'fair phiz', Theobald, Steevens, Knight, Dyce, Hudson, etc.). (See especially extended commentary on the phrase's meaning: nearly damned by a fair wife, almost degraded into woman, near marrying, nearly damned in his life, or corruption of text: wife/wise/wiifte/guise/strife, with many authorities cited.)"],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.22","kind":"speech"},"1.1.23":{"play":"IAGO: That never set a squadron in the field,","notes":["Note on military phrasing: 'That neuer set a Squadron in the Field' — Explanations of 'set a squadron' and its intended scorn of Cassio's lack of active command experience."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.23","kind":"speech"},"1.1.24":{"play":"IAGO: Nor the division of a battle knows","notes":["Gloss: 'Nor the division of a Battail knowes' — On the word 'Battail' and its several senses; comparisons to Holinshed and other uses in Shakespeare."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.24","kind":"speech"},"1.1.25":{"play":"IAGO: More than a spinster—unless the bookish theoric,","notes":["Note: 'More then a Spinster. Vnlesse the Bookish Theoricke' — Explanation of 'spinster' and 'bookish theorick' as contemptuous of Cassio's theoretical knowledge."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.25","kind":"speech"},"1.1.26":{"play":"IAGO: Wherein the togèd consuls can propose","notes":["Textual/lexical note: 'Wherein the Tongued Consuls can propose As Masterly as he.' — Discussion of 'tongued', 'toged', 'toga' imagery and the contrast between senators (toga) and soldiers."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.26","kind":"speech"},"1.1.27":{"play":"IAGO: As masterly as he. Mere prattle without practice","notes":["Walker: 'Masterly' — On form and contraction '-ly' for 'like' in early texts."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.27","kind":"speech"},"1.1.28":{"play":"IAGO: Is all his soldiership. But he, sir, had th’ election;","notes":["Note on 'Meere prattle (without practise) Is all his Souldiership.' — On the sense of 'meere prattle' and the irony of a 'soldier' with only bookish talk."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.28","kind":"speech"},"1.1.29":{"play":"IAGO: And I, of whom his eyes had seen the proof","notes":["Editorial comment: 'But he (Sir) had the election;' — On the narrative point that Othello had chosen Cassio, and Iago's calumny that he did so before the mediators sued for Iago."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.29","kind":"speech"},"1.1.30":{"play":"IAGO: At Rhodes, at Cyprus, and on other grounds","notes":["Note: 'And I (blefs the marke) his Moorfhips Ancient.' — On 'Ancient' meaning ensign or standard-bearer, and its historical usages; references to Comenius, Anchoran, and antiquarian notes."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.30","kind":"speech"},"1.1.31":{"play":"IAGO: Christened and heathen, must be beleed and","notes":["Collier: 'By heaven, I rather would have bin his hangman.' — On Roderigo's hyperbole and social position."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.31","kind":"speech"},"1.1.32":{"play":"IAGO: calmed","notes":["Gloss: 'Why, there's no remedie. 'Tis the curse of Service;' — On 'curse of service' meaning the rule of preferment by favour; textual variants and punctuation noted."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.32","kind":"speech"},"1.1.33":{"play":"IAGO: By debitor and creditor. This countercaster,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.33","kind":"speech"},"1.1.34":{"play":"IAGO: He, in good time, must his lieutenant be,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.34","kind":"speech"},"1.1.35":{"play":"IAGO: And I, God bless the mark, his Moorship’s ancient.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.35","kind":"speech"},"1.1.36":{"play":"RODERIGO: By heaven, I rather would have been his hangman.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.36","kind":"speech"},"1.1.37":{"play":"IAGO: Why, there’s no remedy. ’Tis the curse of service.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.37","kind":"speech"},"1.1.38":{"play":"IAGO: Preferment goes by letter and affection,","notes":["Johnson: 'Preferment goes by Letter, and affection,' — Explanatory note on 'preferment' and recommendation by letter vs gradation."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.38","kind":"speech"},"1.1.39":{"play":"IAGO: And not by old gradation, where each second","notes":["Abbott: 'And not by old gradation, where each second Stood Heire to th'first.' — On use of 'gradation' and 'stood' as subjunctive/indicative."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.39","kind":"speech"},"1.1.40":{"play":"IAGO: Stood heir to th’ first. Now, sir, be judge yourself","notes":["Note on metre and elision in 'Now Sir, be iudge your selfe,' — Meter and address forms explained."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.40","kind":"speech"},"1.1.41":{"play":"IAGO: Whether I in any just term am affined","notes":["Lexical note: 'Whether I in any iust terme am Affin'd To loue the Moor.' — On 'affin'd' meaning bound or obliged, and moral obligation."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.41","kind":"speech"},"1.1.42":{"play":"IAGO: To love the Moor.","notes":["Fechter: 'I follow him, to serve my turne vpon him.' — Comment on Iago's candid admission of his motive.","Dramatic note: 'We cannot all be Masters...' — On Iago's rhetorical strategy of universal examples of servile knaves; discussion of 'knaue' as servitor."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.42","kind":"speech"},"1.1.43":{"play":"RODERIGO: I would not follow him, then.","notes":["Note on 'Many a dutious and knee-crooking knaue' — On 'knee-crooking' and connotations of servility."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.43","kind":"speech"},"1.1.44":{"play":"IAGO: O, sir, content you.","notes":["Gloss: 'Whip me such honest knaues.' — On use of the command as ironic."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.44","kind":"speech"},"1.1.45":{"play":"IAGO: I follow him to serve my turn upon him.","notes":["Cultural note: 'For naught but Prouender...' — On meaning 'for nothing but provender' and its implications for a servant's life."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.45","kind":"speech"},"1.1.46":{"play":"IAGO: We cannot all be masters, nor all masters","notes":["Note: 'These Fellowes haue some foule, and such a one do I professe my selfe.' — Iago's self-confession of being one of the corrupt."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.46","kind":"speech"},"1.1.47":{"play":"IAGO: Cannot be truly followed. You shall mark","notes":["Dictionary note: 'I am not what I am.' — On inversion of Exodus phrase (I am that I am) and Iago's conscious deception."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.47","kind":"speech"},"1.1.48":{"play":"IAGO: Many a duteous and knee-crooking knave","notes":["Knight: 'What a full Fortune does the Thick-lips owe' — On 'full fortune / fall' interpretations and Knight's note on prophetic foreshadowing."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.48","kind":"speech"},"1.1.49":{"play":"IAGO: That, doting on his own obsequious bondage,","notes":["Textual: 'Call vp her Father Rowse him, make after him...' — Stage-direction sense and Iago's plan to rouse Brabantio."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.49","kind":"speech"},"1.1.50":{"play":"IAGO: Wears out his time, much like his master’s ass,","notes":["Ritson/others: 'Proclaime him in the Streets. Incense her kinsmen' — On military/mob incitement language; 'incense' meaning inflame."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.50","kind":"speech"},"1.1.51":{"play":"IAGO: For naught but provender, and when he’s old,","notes":["Note on 'Plague him with Flies' — Interpretation of metaphor 'plague with flies' and chances of vexation to discolor joy."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.51","kind":"speech"},"1.1.52":{"play":"IAGO: cashiered.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.52","kind":"speech"},"1.1.53":{"play":"IAGO: Whip me such honest knaves! Others there are","notes":["Stage note: 'Here is her Father's house, He call aloud.' — On stage business and movement toward Brabantio's door."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.53","kind":"speech"},"1.1.54":{"play":"IAGO: Who, trimmed in forms and visages of duty,","notes":["Stage direction: 'Doe, with like tim'rous accent, and dire yell, As when (by Night and Negligence) the Fire Is spied in populous Cities.' — On mimicry of alarm and intended effect."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.54","kind":"speech"},"1.1.55":{"play":"IAGO: Keep yet their hearts attending on themselves,","notes":["Note: 'What hoa: Brabantio, Signior Brabantio, hoa.' — On the call and stage presence; references to acting practice."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.55","kind":"speech"},"1.1.56":{"play":"IAGO: And, throwing but shows of service on their lords,","notes":["Annotation: 'Awake: what hoa, Brabantio: Theeues, Theeues.' — On repetitive cry and terror-raising."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.56","kind":"speech"},"1.1.57":{"play":"IAGO: Do well thrive by them; and when they have lined","notes":["Gloss: 'Looke to your house, your daughter, and your Bags, Theeues, Theeues.' — On accusatory imagery: 'thieves' as rhetorical device."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.57","kind":"speech"},"1.1.58":{"play":"IAGO: their coats,","notes":["Annotation: 'Brabantio (above): What is the reason of this terrible Summons?' — On stage position 'above' (at window) and actors' movements."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.58","kind":"speech"},"1.1.59":{"play":"IAGO: Do themselves homage. These fellows have some","notes":["Text-note: 'Signior is all your Familie within?' — On the query whether household is present."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.59","kind":"speech"},"1.1.60":{"play":"IAGO: soul,","notes":["Note: 'Are your Doores lock'd?' — On urgency and domestic security, and subsequent actions."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.60","kind":"speech"},"1.1.61":{"play":"IAGO: And such a one do I profess myself. For, sir,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.61","kind":"speech"},"1.1.62":{"play":"IAGO: It is as sure as you are Roderigo,","notes":["Lexical note: 'Sir, y'are rob'd, for shame put on your Gowne,' — On 'gown' meaning Senatorial or civic robe; discuss Capell and other editors' views."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.62","kind":"speech"},"1.1.63":{"play":"IAGO: Were I the Moor I would not be Iago.","notes":["Commentary: 'Your heart is burst, you have lost half your soule' — On the hyperbolic moral collapse Brabantio imputes."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.63","kind":"speech"},"1.1.64":{"play":"IAGO: In following him, I follow but myself.","notes":["Note: 'Euen now, now, very now, an old blacke Ram Is tupping your white Ewe.' — On the crude simile and Brabantio's outrage; cultural and racial implications discussed."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.64","kind":"speech"},"1.1.65":{"play":"IAGO: Heaven is my judge, not I for love and duty,","notes":["Annotation: 'Arise, arise, Awake the snorting Citizens with the Bell' — Civic alarm and legal consequences."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.65","kind":"speech"},"1.1.66":{"play":"IAGO: But seeming so for my peculiar end.","notes":["Note: 'Beleefe of it oppresses me alreadie. Light, I say, light.' — Brabantio's sense of overwhelmed belief; superstition and dream cited in later notes."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.66","kind":"speech"},"1.1.67":{"play":"IAGO: For when my outward action doth demonstrate","notes":["Editorial: 'Farewell: for I must leaue you. It seemes not meete, nor wholesome to my place To be produced, (as if I stay, I shall,) Against the Moore.' — Iago's apparent prudence; strategic withdrawal discussed."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.67","kind":"speech"},"1.1.68":{"play":"IAGO: The native act and figure of my heart","notes":["Annotation: 'For he is embark'd With such loud reason to the Cyprus Warres' — On military movements and their urgency."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.68","kind":"speech"},"1.1.69":{"play":"IAGO: In complement extern, ’tis not long after","notes":["Note: 'Lead to the Sagittary the raised Search' — Discussion of the Sagittary (inn or arsenal?) with citations; many editors' views (Knight, Rolfe, Elze) summarized."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.69","kind":"speech"},"1.1.70":{"play":"IAGO: But I will wear my heart upon my sleeve","notes":["Stage-direction note: 'And there will I be with him. So farewell.' — Iago's exit and planning; commentators note his duplicity and plotting."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.70","kind":"speech"},"1.1.71":{"play":"IAGO: For daws to peck at. I am not what I am.","notes":["Textual note: 'On good Roderigo, I will deserve your paines. [Exeunt]' — Final business of the scene and Roderigo's promise; stage exits and scene close."],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.71","kind":"speech"},"1.1.72":{"play":"RODERIGO: What a full fortune does the thick-lips owe","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.72","kind":"speech"},"1.1.73":{"play":"RODERIGO: If he can carry ’t thus!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.73","kind":"speech"},"1.1.74":{"play":"IAGO: Call up her father.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.74","kind":"speech"},"1.1.75":{"play":"IAGO: Rouse him. Make after him, poison his delight,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.75","kind":"speech"},"1.1.76":{"play":"IAGO: Proclaim him in the streets; incense her kinsmen,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.76","kind":"speech"},"1.1.77":{"play":"IAGO: And, though he in a fertile climate dwell,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.77","kind":"speech"},"1.1.78":{"play":"IAGO: Plague him with flies. Though that his joy be joy,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.78","kind":"speech"},"1.1.79":{"play":"IAGO: Yet throw such chances of vexation on ’t","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.79","kind":"speech"},"1.1.80":{"play":"IAGO: As it may lose some color.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.80","kind":"speech"},"1.1.81":{"play":"RODERIGO: Here is her father’s house. I’ll call aloud.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.81","kind":"speech"},"1.1.82":{"play":"IAGO: Do, with like timorous accent and dire yell","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.82","kind":"speech"},"1.1.83":{"play":"IAGO: As when, by night and negligence, the fire","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.83","kind":"speech"},"1.1.84":{"play":"IAGO: Is spied in populous cities.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.84","kind":"speech"},"1.1.85":{"play":"RODERIGO: What ho, Brabantio! Signior Brabantio, ho!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.85","kind":"speech"},"1.1.86":{"play":"IAGO: Awake! What ho, Brabantio! Thieves, thieves!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.86","kind":"speech"},"1.1.87":{"play":"IAGO: Look to your house, your daughter, and your bags!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.87","kind":"speech"},"1.1.88":{"play":"IAGO: Thieves, thieves!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.88","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.1.88.1":{"play":"[Enter Brabantio, above.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.1.88.1","kind":"stage"},"1.1.89":{"play":"BRABANTIO: What is the reason of this terrible summons?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.89","kind":"speech"},"1.1.90":{"play":"BRABANTIO: What is the matter there?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.90","kind":"speech"},"1.1.91":{"play":"RODERIGO: Signior, is all your family within?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.91","kind":"speech"},"1.1.92":{"play":"IAGO: Are your doors locked?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.92","kind":"speech"},"1.1.93":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Why, wherefore ask you this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.93","kind":"speech"},"1.1.94":{"play":"IAGO: Zounds, sir, you’re robbed. For shame, put on your","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.94","kind":"speech"},"1.1.95":{"play":"IAGO: gown!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.95","kind":"speech"},"1.1.96":{"play":"IAGO: Your heart is burst. You have lost half your soul.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.96","kind":"speech"},"1.1.97":{"play":"IAGO: Even now, now, very now, an old black ram","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.97","kind":"speech"},"1.1.98":{"play":"IAGO: Is tupping your white ewe. Arise, arise!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.98","kind":"speech"},"1.1.99":{"play":"IAGO: Awake the snorting citizens with the bell,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.99","kind":"speech"},"1.1.100":{"play":"IAGO: Or else the devil will make a grandsire of you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.100","kind":"speech"},"1.1.101":{"play":"IAGO: Arise, I say!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.101","kind":"speech"},"1.1.102":{"play":"BRABANTIO: What, have you lost your wits?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.102","kind":"speech"},"1.1.103":{"play":"RODERIGO: Most reverend signior, do you know my voice?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.103","kind":"speech"},"1.1.104":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Not I. What are you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.104","kind":"speech"},"1.1.105":{"play":"RODERIGO: My name is Roderigo.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.105","kind":"speech"},"1.1.106":{"play":"BRABANTIO: The worser welcome.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.106","kind":"speech"},"1.1.107":{"play":"BRABANTIO: I have charged thee not to haunt about my doors.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.107","kind":"speech"},"1.1.108":{"play":"BRABANTIO: In honest plainness thou hast heard me say","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.108","kind":"speech"},"1.1.109":{"play":"BRABANTIO: My daughter is not for thee. And now in madness,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.109","kind":"speech"},"1.1.110":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Being full of supper and distemp’ring draughts,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.110","kind":"speech"},"1.1.111":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Upon malicious bravery dost thou come","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.111","kind":"speech"},"1.1.112":{"play":"BRABANTIO: To start my quiet.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.112","kind":"speech"},"1.1.113":{"play":"RODERIGO: Sir, sir, sir—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.113","kind":"speech"},"1.1.114":{"play":"BRABANTIO: But thou must needs be sure","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.114","kind":"speech"},"1.1.115":{"play":"BRABANTIO: My spirit and my place have in them power","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.115","kind":"speech"},"1.1.116":{"play":"BRABANTIO: To make this bitter to thee.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.116","kind":"speech"},"1.1.117":{"play":"RODERIGO: Patience, good sir.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.117","kind":"speech"},"1.1.118":{"play":"BRABANTIO: What tell’st thou me of robbing?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.118","kind":"speech"},"1.1.119":{"play":"BRABANTIO: This is Venice. My house is not a grange.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.119","kind":"speech"},"1.1.120":{"play":"RODERIGO: Most grave Brabantio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.120","kind":"speech"},"1.1.121":{"play":"RODERIGO: In simple and pure soul I come to you—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.121","kind":"speech"},"1.1.122":{"play":"IAGO: Zounds, sir, you are one of those that will not","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.122","kind":"speech"},"1.1.123":{"play":"IAGO: serve God if the devil bid you. Because we come to","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.123","kind":"speech"},"1.1.124":{"play":"IAGO: do you service and you think we are ruffians, you’ll","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.124","kind":"speech"},"1.1.125":{"play":"IAGO: have your daughter covered with a Barbary horse,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.125","kind":"speech"},"1.1.126":{"play":"IAGO: you’ll have your nephews neigh to you, you’ll have","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.126","kind":"speech"},"1.1.127":{"play":"IAGO: coursers for cousins and jennets for germans.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.127","kind":"speech"},"1.1.128":{"play":"BRABANTIO: What profane wretch art thou?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.128","kind":"speech"},"1.1.129":{"play":"IAGO: I am one, sir, that comes to tell you your daughter","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.129","kind":"speech"},"1.1.130":{"play":"IAGO: and the Moor are now making the beast with","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.130","kind":"speech"},"1.1.131":{"play":"IAGO: two backs.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.131","kind":"speech"},"1.1.132":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Thou art a villain.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.132","kind":"speech"},"1.1.133":{"play":"IAGO: You are a senator.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.133","kind":"speech"},"1.1.134":{"play":"BRABANTIO: This thou shalt answer. I know thee, Roderigo.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.134","kind":"speech"},"1.1.135":{"play":"RODERIGO: Sir, I will answer anything. But I beseech you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.135","kind":"speech"},"1.1.136":{"play":"RODERIGO: If ’t be your pleasure and most wise consent—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.136","kind":"speech"},"1.1.137":{"play":"RODERIGO: As partly I find it is—that your fair daughter,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.137","kind":"speech"},"1.1.138":{"play":"RODERIGO: At this odd-even and dull watch o’ th’ night,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.138","kind":"speech"},"1.1.139":{"play":"RODERIGO: Transported with no worse nor better guard","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.139","kind":"speech"},"1.1.140":{"play":"RODERIGO: But with a knave of common hire, a gondolier,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.140","kind":"speech"},"1.1.141":{"play":"RODERIGO: To the gross clasps of a lascivious Moor:","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.141","kind":"speech"},"1.1.142":{"play":"RODERIGO: If this be known to you, and your allowance,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.142","kind":"speech"},"1.1.143":{"play":"RODERIGO: We then have done you bold and saucy wrongs.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.143","kind":"speech"},"1.1.144":{"play":"RODERIGO: But if you know not this, my manners tell me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.144","kind":"speech"},"1.1.145":{"play":"RODERIGO: We have your wrong rebuke. Do not believe","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.145","kind":"speech"},"1.1.146":{"play":"RODERIGO: That from the sense of all civility","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.146","kind":"speech"},"1.1.147":{"play":"RODERIGO: I thus would play and trifle with your Reverence.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.147","kind":"speech"},"1.1.148":{"play":"RODERIGO: Your daughter, if you have not given her leave,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.148","kind":"speech"},"1.1.149":{"play":"RODERIGO: I say again, hath made a gross revolt,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.149","kind":"speech"},"1.1.150":{"play":"RODERIGO: Tying her duty, beauty, wit, and fortunes","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.150","kind":"speech"},"1.1.151":{"play":"RODERIGO: In an extravagant and wheeling stranger","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.151","kind":"speech"},"1.1.152":{"play":"RODERIGO: Of here and everywhere. Straight satisfy yourself.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.152","kind":"speech"},"1.1.153":{"play":"RODERIGO: If she be in her chamber or your house,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.153","kind":"speech"},"1.1.154":{"play":"RODERIGO: Let loose on me the justice of the state","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.154","kind":"speech"},"1.1.155":{"play":"RODERIGO: For thus deluding you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.155","kind":"speech"},"1.1.156":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Strike on the tinder, ho!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.156","kind":"speech"},"1.1.157":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Give me a taper. Call up all my people.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.157","kind":"speech"},"1.1.158":{"play":"BRABANTIO: This accident is not unlike my dream.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.158","kind":"speech"},"1.1.159":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Belief of it oppresses me already.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.159","kind":"speech"},"1.1.160":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Light, I say, light!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.160","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.1.160":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.1.160","kind":"stage"},"1.1.161":{"play":"IAGO: Farewell, for I must leave you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.161","kind":"speech"},"1.1.162":{"play":"IAGO: It seems not meet nor wholesome to my place","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.162","kind":"speech"},"1.1.163":{"play":"IAGO: To be producted, as if I stay I shall,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.163","kind":"speech"},"1.1.164":{"play":"IAGO: Against the Moor. For I do know the state,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.164","kind":"speech"},"1.1.165":{"play":"IAGO: However this may gall him with some check,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.165","kind":"speech"},"1.1.166":{"play":"IAGO: Cannot with safety cast him, for he’s embarked","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.166","kind":"speech"},"1.1.167":{"play":"IAGO: With such loud reason to the Cyprus wars,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.167","kind":"speech"},"1.1.168":{"play":"IAGO: Which even now stands in act, that, for their souls,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.168","kind":"speech"},"1.1.169":{"play":"IAGO: Another of his fathom they have none","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.169","kind":"speech"},"1.1.170":{"play":"IAGO: To lead their business. In which regard,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.170","kind":"speech"},"1.1.171":{"play":"IAGO: Though I do hate him as I do hell pains,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.171","kind":"speech"},"1.1.172":{"play":"IAGO: Yet, for necessity of present life,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.172","kind":"speech"},"1.1.173":{"play":"IAGO: I must show out a flag and sign of love—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.173","kind":"speech"},"1.1.174":{"play":"IAGO: Which is indeed but sign. That you shall surely find","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.174","kind":"speech"},"1.1.175":{"play":"IAGO: him,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.175","kind":"speech"},"1.1.176":{"play":"IAGO: Lead to the Sagittary the raisèd search,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.176","kind":"speech"},"1.1.177":{"play":"IAGO: And there will I be with him. So, farewell.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.177","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.1.177":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.1.177","kind":"stage"},"SD_1.1.177.1":{"play":"[Enter Brabantio in his nightgown, with Servants and Torches.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.1.177.1","kind":"stage"},"1.1.178":{"play":"BRABANTIO: It is too true an evil. Gone she is,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.178","kind":"speech"},"1.1.179":{"play":"BRABANTIO: And what’s to come of my despisèd time","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.179","kind":"speech"},"1.1.180":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Is naught but bitterness.—Now, Roderigo,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.180","kind":"speech"},"1.1.181":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Where didst thou see her?—O, unhappy girl!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.181","kind":"speech"},"1.1.182":{"play":"BRABANTIO: With the Moor, sayst thou?—Who would be a","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.182","kind":"speech"},"1.1.183":{"play":"BRABANTIO: father?—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.183","kind":"speech"},"1.1.184":{"play":"BRABANTIO: How didst thou know ’twas she?—O, she deceives","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.184","kind":"speech"},"1.1.185":{"play":"BRABANTIO: me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.185","kind":"speech"},"1.1.186":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Past thought!—What said she to you?—Get more","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.186","kind":"speech"},"1.1.187":{"play":"BRABANTIO: tapers.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.187","kind":"speech"},"1.1.188":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Raise all my kindred.—Are they married, think","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.188","kind":"speech"},"1.1.189":{"play":"BRABANTIO: you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.189","kind":"speech"},"1.1.190":{"play":"RODERIGO: Truly, I think they are.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.190","kind":"speech"},"1.1.191":{"play":"BRABANTIO: O heaven! How got she out? O treason of the blood!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.191","kind":"speech"},"1.1.192":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Fathers, from hence trust not your daughters’ minds","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.192","kind":"speech"},"1.1.193":{"play":"BRABANTIO: By what you see them act.—Is there not charms","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.193","kind":"speech"},"1.1.194":{"play":"BRABANTIO: By which the property of youth and maidhood","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.194","kind":"speech"},"1.1.195":{"play":"BRABANTIO: May be abused? Have you not read, Roderigo,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.195","kind":"speech"},"1.1.196":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Of some such thing?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.196","kind":"speech"},"1.1.197":{"play":"RODERIGO: Yes, sir, I have indeed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.197","kind":"speech"},"1.1.198":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Call up my brother.—O, would you had had her!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.198","kind":"speech"},"1.1.199":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Some one way, some another.—Do you know","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.199","kind":"speech"},"1.1.200":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Where we may apprehend her and the Moor?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.200","kind":"speech"},"1.1.201":{"play":"RODERIGO: I think I can discover him, if you please","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.201","kind":"speech"},"1.1.202":{"play":"RODERIGO: To get good guard and go along with me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.202","kind":"speech"},"1.1.203":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Pray you lead on. At every house I’ll call.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.203","kind":"speech"},"1.1.204":{"play":"BRABANTIO: I may command at most.—Get weapons, ho!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.204","kind":"speech"},"1.1.205":{"play":"BRABANTIO: And raise some special officers of night.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.205","kind":"speech"},"1.1.206":{"play":"BRABANTIO: On, good Roderigo. I will deserve your pains.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.1.206","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.1.206.1":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.1.206.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 1, SCENE 2":{"SD_1.2.0":{"play":"[Enter Othello, Iago, Attendants, with Torches.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.2.0","kind":"stage"},"1.2.1":{"play":"IAGO: Though in the trade of war I have slain men,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.1","kind":"speech"},"1.2.2":{"play":"IAGO: Yet do I hold it very stuff o’ th’ conscience","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.2","kind":"speech"},"1.2.3":{"play":"IAGO: To do no contrived murder. I lack iniquity","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.3","kind":"speech"},"1.2.4":{"play":"IAGO: Sometimes to do me service. Nine or ten times","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.4","kind":"speech"},"1.2.5":{"play":"IAGO: I had thought t’ have yerked him here under the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.5","kind":"speech"},"1.2.6":{"play":"IAGO: ribs.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.6","kind":"speech"},"1.2.7":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Tis better as it is.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.7","kind":"speech"},"1.2.8":{"play":"IAGO: Nay, but he prated","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.8","kind":"speech"},"1.2.9":{"play":"IAGO: And spoke such scurvy and provoking terms","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.9","kind":"speech"},"1.2.10":{"play":"IAGO: Against your Honor,","notes":["Gould: J. B. Booth gave this with a gravity, a weighty distinctness on the last three words, 'better—as—it—is,' which conveyed a reproof, and was intended to dismiss the subject."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.10","kind":"speech"},"1.2.11":{"play":"IAGO: That with the little godliness I have","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.11","kind":"speech"},"1.2.12":{"play":"IAGO: I did full hard forbear him. But I pray you, sir,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.12","kind":"speech"},"1.2.13":{"play":"IAGO: Are you fast married? Be assured of this,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.13","kind":"speech"},"1.2.14":{"play":"IAGO: That the magnifico is much beloved,","notes":["Steevens: Steevens asks, 'of whom is this said? Of Roderigo?' Knight answers: 'Iago is preparing Othello for the appearance of Roderigo with Brabantio, which he does by representing that Roderigo has communicated to him his intention to apprise Desdemona's father of her flight, and that he resented his expressions toward Othello.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.14","kind":"speech"},"1.2.15":{"play":"IAGO: And hath in his effect a voice potential","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.15","kind":"speech"},"1.2.16":{"play":"IAGO: As double as the Duke’s. He will divorce you","notes":["Dyce: Separate line, Dyce, Stahl. Glo. Cam. Del. Rife, Hud’s. Pope et seq. For be sure Qq et cet."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.16","kind":"speech"},"1.2.17":{"play":"IAGO: Or put upon you what restraint or grievance","notes":["Schmidt: To spare, to let alone. Conf. Ham. V, i, 261: 'For love of God, forbear him.'","Booth: Now let your manner be more serious.","Ed.: A mere enclitic in pronunciation, absorbed in the final sound of 'pray.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.17","kind":"speech"},"1.2.18":{"play":"IAGO: The law (with all his might to enforce it on)","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.18","kind":"speech"},"1.2.19":{"play":"IAGO: Will give him cable.","notes":["Tollet: 'The chief men of Venice are by a peculiar name called Magnifico, i.e. Magnificoes.'—Minshew [s. v. Magnificent. Minshew adds: Et Academia rum Rectors in Germania, modem tituli insinuator. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.19","kind":"speech"},"1.2.20":{"play":"OTHELLO: Let him do his spite.","notes":["Staunton: Here employed for the then scarce known its, and refers to 'voice.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.20","kind":"speech"},"1.2.21":{"play":"OTHELLO: My services which I have done the signiory","notes":["Warburton: Warburton, followed by Theobald (not Capell, as Knight says), interpreted this as signifying as large, as extensive, equivalent to the Greek dm7.ov£ t and cited Dioscorides and Theocritus. Whereupon Dr Johnson thus improved the occasion: All this learning, if it had even been what it endeavors to be thought, is, in this place, superfluous. There is no ground for supposing, that our author copied or knew the Greek phrase; nor does it follow, that, because a word has two senses in one language, the word which in another answers to one sense should answer to both. Afanus, in Latin, signifies both a hand and troop of soldiers, but we cannot say, that 'the captain marched at the head of his hand;' or, 'that he laid his troop upon his sword.' It is not always in books that the meaning is to be sought of this writer, who was much more acquainted with naked reason and with living manners. 'Double' has here its natural sense. The president of every deliberative assembly has a double voice. In our courts the chief justice and one of the inferior judges prevail over the other two.","[Further commentators on 'As double as the Dukes.' See main text for detailed scholarly opinions: Johnson, Steevens, Malone, Pye, Knight, Delius, Hudson, Jourdain, White.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.21","kind":"speech"},"1.2.22":{"play":"OTHELLO: Shall out-tongue his complaints. ’Tis yet to know","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.22","kind":"speech"},"1.2.23":{"play":"OTHELLO: (Which, when I know that boasting is an honor,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.23","kind":"speech"},"1.2.24":{"play":"OTHELLO: I shall promulgate) I fetch my life and being","notes":["Abbott: To smooth away this Alexandrine, Abbott (§471) scans: My services which I've done | the Sign | ivory. See also Walker, Veers., p. 243."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.24","kind":"speech"},"1.2.25":{"play":"OTHELLO: From men of royal siege, and my demerits","notes":["Booth: The keynote of his nature, a modest, simple-hearted gentleman, not a braggart as Iago would make him out."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.25","kind":"speech"},"1.2.26":{"play":"OTHELLO: May speak unbonneted to as proud a fortune","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.26","kind":"speech"},"1.2.27":{"play":"OTHELLO: As this that I have reached. For know, Iago,","notes":["Johnson: Men who have sat upon royal thrones. Clarendon: Seat, thence rank, because people sat at table and elsewhere in order of precedence. See Ham. IV, vii, 77.","Steevens: This has the same meaning, among Elizabethan writers, as merits. [Both Bullroar, 1621, and Minshew, 1617, give Demerit: A desert.] Staunton: 'Demerit' now signifies only ill desert; in Shakespeare's day it was used indiscriminately for good or ill deserving. In the present instance it is apparently employed in the good sense, for Othello could hardly mean that his blemishes might stand without concealment beside the dignity he had achieved.","Pope: It should be unbonneting, i.e. without putting off the bonnet. THEOBALD: To speak 'unbonneted' is to speak with the cap off, which is directly opposite to the poet's meaning. So in Lear, III, i, 14, 'unbonneted he runs.' Othello means to say, that his birth and services set him upon such a rank that he may speak to a Senator of Venice with his hat on, i.e. without showing any marks of deference or inequality. I, therefore, am inclined to think Shakespeare wrote: 'May speak, and bonneted; &c. Or, if any like better the change of the negative un, in the corrupted reading, into the epistatic I’m, we may thus reform it: 'May speak unbonneted; &c. [This last conjecture was withdrawn by Theobald (ed. ii), but proposed anew by Steevens, without credit.] Johnson: Pope's emendation may as well be not putting on as not putting off, the bonnet. Steevens: Bonnier, says Cotgrave, is to put off one's cap. So in Cor. II, ii, 30. Mr Fuseli explains this passage as follows: ‘I am his equal or superior in rank; and were it not so, such are my demerits, that, unbonneted, without the addition of patrician or senatorial dignity, they may speak to as proud a fortune,' &c. 'At Venice the bonnet, as well as the tongue, is a badge of aristocratic honours to this day.' A. C. (in VarJ21): 'Unbonneted' is uncovered, revealed, made known. See a similar expression in II, iii, 'you unlace your reputation.' Coleridge [Notes, &c, p. 250): Theobald's argument goes on the assumption that Shakespeare could not use the same word differently in different places; whereas I should conclude, that as in the passage in Lear the word is employed in its direct meaning, so here it is used metaphorically; and this is confirmed by what has escaped the editors, that it is not 'I' but 'my demerits' that may speak 'unbonneted,'—without the symbol of a petitioning inferior. Staunton: The import we take to be,—my services when revealed [unbonneted) may aspire or lay claim to [may speak to) as proud a fortune as this which I have attained. Even with Fuseli's interpretation it is indispensable for the integrity of the passage that 'speak to' be understood in the sense just mentioned of aspire or lay claim to. Schmidt [Lex.): Perhaps the meaning is simply: I may say so with all courtesy and humility, and Othello's words must, perhaps, be accompanied by a corresponding gesture, as the writing of F seems to imply, by placing the word 'unbonnetted' in a parenthesis. White (ed. ii): The question of manners in Shakespeare's time as to the hat seems very difficult. The remembering courtesy, the off-capping, and the unbonneting are quite incongruous. No attempt to reconcile these expressions has been at all successful."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.27","kind":"speech"},"1.2.28":{"play":"OTHELLO: But that I love the gentle Desdemona,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.28","kind":"speech"},"1.2.29":{"play":"OTHELLO: I would not my unhousèd free condition","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.29","kind":"speech"},"1.2.30":{"play":"OTHELLO: Put into circumscription and confine","notes":["Johnson: Free from domestic cares. A thought natural to an adventurer. Whalley: To Othello, talking as a soldier, 'unhoused' may signify the having no settled house or habitation. Hunter [New Illust., ii, 282): This passage affords one of the best proofs of Shakespeare's acquaintance with the Italian language. 'Un housed' conveys to English ears no idea of anything which any one would be unwilling to resign; and, in fact, it is only by recollecting the way in which the Italians use Caesar that we arrive at its true meaning, which is unmarried. A soldier was as much 'unhoused,' in the ordinary meaning of the term, after marriage as before. Othello would not resign the freedom of his bachelor estate. Knight: Othello expresses no satisfaction at having been houseless, but he simply uses 'unhoused' for unmarried. The husband is the head or band of the house,—the unmarried is the unhorse-banded—the 'unhoused.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.30","kind":"speech"},"1.2.31":{"play":"OTHELLO: For the sea’s worth. But look, what lights come","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.31","kind":"speech"},"1.2.32":{"play":"OTHELLO: yond?","notes":["Johnson: I would not marry her, though she were as rich as the Adriatic, which the Doge annually marries. Steevens: As the gold ring annually thrown by the Doge into the Adriatic cannot be said to have much enriched it, I believe the common and obvious meaning of this passage is the true one. Pye: I think Steevens indubitably right, but not for the reason he gives. I believe Johnson thought no more of the Adriatic being enriched by the annual wedding-ring, than Shakespeare did of the Adriatic at all. [Steevens refers to the occurrence of the same phrase in D'Avenant's Cruel Brother (p. 131, ed. Maidment), and adds, 'perhaps the phrase is proverbial.' A citation from D'Avenant, in a case like this, carries but little weight. I doubt if there be an Act in all D'Avenant's plays, wherein Shakespearian phrases may not be found. For instance, the sixth line of this very play of The Cruel Brother reads: 'This way to madness leads,' and 'excellent wretch,' occurs more than once farther on. With more propriety Steevens refers to Wint. Tale, IV, iv, 501, and Hen. V: I, ii, 164; but is again far afield in referring to Pliny's Chapter (IX, 34) on The Riches of the Sea, which alludes to the high prices paid by luxury 'in furnishing the table with such varietie of dishes, in pleasing and contenting the taste with so many dainty and delicate fishes.' Conf. Rich. III: I, iv, 26: 'Wedges of gold, great anchors, heaps of pearls, Inestimable stones, unvalued jewels, All scatter'd in the bottom of the sea.' Ed.] Booth: Note the frequent reference to the sea;—for the same reason, that I gave anent the 'superstition' in the play."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.32","kind":"speech"},"1.2.33":{"play":"IAGO: Those are the raisèd father and his friends.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.33","kind":"speech"},"1.2.34":{"play":"IAGO: You were best go in.","notes":["Walker: Walker [Crit. ii, 202): Thou wert (sometimes written in the old poets Th'wert), you were, I was, &c, occur frequently, both in Shakespeare and contemporary dramatists, in places where it is clear they must have been pronounced as one syllable, in whatever manner the contraction was effected. [See Ham. IV, v, 14, and Aiipott, §461.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.34","kind":"speech"},"1.2.35":{"play":"OTHELLO: Not I. I must be found.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.35","kind":"speech"},"1.2.36":{"play":"OTHELLO: My parts, my title, and my perfect soul","notes":["Schmidt and Rolfe: Schmidt and Rolfe agree in interpreting this as merits. It seems to me that it is rather the endowments of nature, his natural gifts, like 'your sum of parts in Ham. IV, vii, 74. Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.36","kind":"speech"},"1.2.37":{"play":"OTHELLO: Shall manifest me rightly. Is it they?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.37","kind":"speech"},"1.2.38":{"play":"IAGO: By Janus, I think no.","notes":["Warburton: There is great propriety in making the double Iago swear by Janus, who had two faces. The address of it likewise is as remarkable; for as the people coming up appeared at different distances to have different shapes, he might swear by Janus without suspicion of any other emblematic meaning."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.38","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.2.38.1":{"play":"[Enter Cassio, with Officers, and Torches.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.2.38.1","kind":"stage"},"1.2.39":{"play":"OTHELLO: The servants of the Duke and my lieutenant!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.39","kind":"speech"},"1.2.40":{"play":"OTHELLO: The goodness of the night upon you, friends.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.40","kind":"speech"},"1.2.41":{"play":"OTHELLO: What is the news?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.41","kind":"speech"},"1.2.42":{"play":"CASSIO: The Duke does greet you, general,","notes":["Delius: May night, usually unfriendly to everybody, show only its good side to you. [Is it not simply the ordinary salutation 'good day,' or 'Godgigoden' adapted to the hour? Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.42","kind":"speech"},"1.2.43":{"play":"CASSIO: And he requires your haste-post-haste appearance,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.43","kind":"speech"},"1.2.44":{"play":"CASSIO: Even on the instant.","notes":["Booth: Cassio alone knew where Othello was to be found. Othello says, that he knew from first to last of the secret love, &c. Remember this when Iago tells you. 'he's married,' &c."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.44","kind":"speech"},"1.2.45":{"play":"OTHELLO: What is the matter, think you?","notes":["Ritson: The comma, hitherto placed after haste,' should be a hyphen. 'Your haste-post-haste appearance' is your immediate appearance. The words 'Haste, post, haste,' were, in our author's time, usually written on the cover of packets or letters sent express."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.45","kind":"speech"},"1.2.46":{"play":"CASSIO: Something from Cyprus, as I may divine.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.46","kind":"speech"},"1.2.47":{"play":"CASSIO: It is a business of some heat. The galleys","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.47","kind":"speech"},"1.2.48":{"play":"CASSIO: Have sent a dozen sequent messengers","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.48","kind":"speech"},"1.2.49":{"play":"CASSIO: This very night at one another’s heels,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.49","kind":"speech"},"1.2.50":{"play":"CASSIO: And many of the Consuls, raised and met,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.50","kind":"speech"},"1.2.51":{"play":"CASSIO: Are at the Duke’s already. You have been hotly","notes":["Theobald: Theobald changed this to Couns'lers, for the reasons given at I, i, 27. Knight says, that in both cases senators were probably meant. Th. Elze (Sh. Jahrbuch, xiv, 179): Shakespeare has not clearly distinguished between the Col- Ugio and the Senate. Brabantio's accusation of Othello could not have been brought before the Senate, but before the Ministerial Council—the Collegio. The Third Scene of the First Act is correctly laid in the 'Council Chamber,' not in the 'Hall of the Senate.' Properly also, Shakespeare speaks of 'the Council' and the 'Consuls,' that is, the Counsellors; but improperly in the same speech of the 'Senate' and [line 255] of the 'Senators.' But, perhaps, Shakespeare purposely avoided the use of the word College, because of its ambiguity to English ears."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.51","kind":"speech"},"1.2.52":{"play":"CASSIO: called for.","notes":["Lettsom: Lettsom (ap. Dyce, ed. iii) would read 'you had been,' &c. Hudson adopted the emendation."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.52","kind":"speech"},"1.2.53":{"play":"CASSIO: When, being not at your lodging to be found,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.53","kind":"speech"},"1.2.54":{"play":"CASSIO: The Senate hath sent about three several quests","notes":["Johnson: That is, about the city. Collier (ed. i) preferred above of the Qq, because a '\"quest\" necessarily searches in various directions; and the word \"about\" may, therefore, be considered surplusage. Cassio means that more than \"three several quests\" have been sent in search of Othello.' But as his (MS) retained 'about,' Collier, in his subsequent editions, followed it.","Steevens: That is, searches. So in Heywood's Brazen Age, 1613: 'Now, if in all his quests, he be withheld.' An ancient MS. entitled The Boke of Huntyng that is cleped Mayster of Game, has the following explanation of the word 'quest': 'This word quest is a terme of herte hunters of beyonde the see; and is thus moche to say as whan the hunter goth to fynde the hert and to herborow him.' Halliwell cites Cotgrave, s. v. 'Queste: f. A quest, inquirie, search, inquisition, seeking,' &c."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.54","kind":"speech"},"1.2.55":{"play":"CASSIO: To search you out.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.55","kind":"speech"},"1.2.56":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Tis well I am found by you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.56","kind":"speech"},"1.2.57":{"play":"OTHELLO: I will but spend a word here in the house","notes":["Gerard: Gerard: Les expressions to spend et to pay sont a tout moment employees par les Anglais, peuple commercant et pratique par excellence. lis ne rendent pas, ils paient une visite; ils ne passent pas, ils depensent leur temps. En Amerique la premiere question que Ton fait sur quelqu'un, c'est: Combien vaut-il? [When Mons. Gerard enacts the 'Pow'r,' and 'wad the giftie gie us,' shall not we Americans accept it, however startling the revelation? Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.57","kind":"speech"},"1.2.58":{"play":"OTHELLO: And go with you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.58","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.2.58":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.2.58","kind":"stage"},"1.2.59":{"play":"CASSIO: Ancient, what makes he here?","notes":["Booth: Speak this with curiosity, as if to learn what Iago knows of the marriage."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.59","kind":"speech"},"1.2.60":{"play":"IAGO: Faith, he tonight hath boarded a land carrack.","notes":["Skeat: A ship of burden. (We also find carrick, which comes nearer to Low Lat. carrica, a ship of burden.) Low Lat. carra- (are, better carrienre to lade a car.—Lat. carrus, a car. Staunton: A ship of large burden, like the Spanish galleon; but the compound in the text appears to have been a dissolute expression."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.60","kind":"speech"},"1.2.61":{"play":"IAGO: If it prove lawful prize, he’s made forever.","notes":["Lord Campbell: Lord Campbell (p. 114): A very distinct proof that Shakespeare was acquainted with Admiralty law, as well as with the procedure of Westminster Hall, the trope indicating, that there would be a suit in the High Court of Admiralty to determine the validity of the capture."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.61","kind":"speech"},"1.2.62":{"play":"CASSIO: I do not understand.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.62","kind":"speech"},"1.2.63":{"play":"IAGO: He’s married.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.63","kind":"speech"},"1.2.64":{"play":"CASSIO: To who?","notes":["Theobald: Theobald (Nichols's Illust. of Lit., ii, 586): Surely, this is a terrible forgetfulness in our author. How came Cassio such a stranger to this affair, when it afterward appears he went a-wooing with Othello and took his part in the suit? [Cf. III, iii, 82.] Ritson (p. 227): It is very easy to imagine, that Cassio might wish to know if Iago were acquainted with the lady, to prevent the latter's suspecting that he was. Blackstone: Cassio's seeming ignorance might only be affected, in order to keep his friend's secret till it became publicly known. Malone: Or he might fear that Othello had proved false to the gentle Desdemona, and married another. Steevens: How far this suspicious apprehension would have become the benevolent Cassio, the intimate friend of Othello, let the reader judge. Singer: It was probably a mere oversight of the poet. Abbott, § 274, gives many instances where the inflection of who is neglected. See IV, ii, 115; Macb. III, iv, 42; Ham. II, ii, 193; Lear, IV, iii, 7 and V, iii, 249."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.64","kind":"speech"},"1.2.65":{"play":"IAGO: Marry, to—","notes":["Abbott: Abbott, § 506: It is obvious that a syllable or foot may be supplied by a gesture, a beckoning, a movement of the head to listen, or of the hand to demand attention, as here: ‘Marry | to [Enter /the//o.) | Come, cap | tain, will | you g6 ?' However, we may scan, Marry | to—Come | Cap(i) | tain will | you go,' but very harshly and improbably."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.65","kind":"speech"},"1.2.66":{"play":"IAGO: Come, captain, will you go?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.66","kind":"speech"},"1.2.67":{"play":"OTHELLO: Have with you.","notes":["Steevens: Steevens: This expression denotes readiness."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.67","kind":"speech"},"1.2.68":{"play":"CASSIO: Here comes another troop to seek for you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.68","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.2.68.1":{"play":"[Enter Brabantio, Roderigo, with Officers, and Torches.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.2.68.1","kind":"stage"},"1.2.69":{"play":"IAGO: It is Brabantio. General, be advised,","notes":["Johnson: Johnson: That is, be cool, be cautious, be discreet."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.69","kind":"speech"},"1.2.70":{"play":"IAGO: He comes to bad intent.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.70","kind":"speech"},"1.2.71":{"play":"OTHELLO: Holla, stand there!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.71","kind":"speech"},"1.2.72":{"play":"RODERIGO: Signior, it is the Moor.","notes":["Booth: Booth: This is spoken 'within.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.72","kind":"speech"},"1.2.73":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Down with him,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.73","kind":"speech"},"1.2.74":{"play":"BRABANTIO: thief!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.74","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.2.74.1":{"play":"[They draw their swords.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.2.74.1","kind":"stage"},"1.2.75":{"play":"IAGO: You, Roderigo! Come, sir, I am for you.","notes":["Booth: Booth: This is to prevent harm to Roderigo, for whose purse Iago has a tender regard. Make the audience understand this by your manner of singling him out,—look will do it. [See Textual Notes for another instance of the difference between the copy of F x, from which Lionel Booth reprinted, and that from which this edition is reprinted. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.75","kind":"speech"},"1.2.76":{"play":"OTHELLO: Keep up your bright swords, for the dew will rust","notes":["Booth: Booth: Othello's party—Cassio, Iago, and others—should motion 'to draw, when these words restrain them. Brabantio's friends enter with swords drawn. Be very respectful to Brabantio, resent his abuse, merely with a look of momentary anger.","Walker: See Walker (Crit. ii, 321), for an Article, with many examples, on the confusion in the Folio of or and for. Walker would here read or, which may be correct, but of the instances of this confusion, cited by Walker, the present is, perhaps, the least manifest. Ed.","Hudson: If I mistake not there is a sort of playful, good-humoured irony expressed in the very rhythm of this line."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.76","kind":"speech"},"1.2.77":{"play":"OTHELLO: them.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.77","kind":"speech"},"1.2.78":{"play":"OTHELLO: Good signior, you shall more command with years","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.78","kind":"speech"},"1.2.79":{"play":"OTHELLO: Than with your weapons.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.79","kind":"speech"},"1.2.80":{"play":"BRABANTIO: O, thou foul thief, where hast thou stowed my","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.80","kind":"speech"},"1.2.81":{"play":"BRABANTIO: daughter?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.81","kind":"speech"},"1.2.82":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Damned as thou art, thou hast enchanted her!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.82","kind":"speech"},"1.2.83":{"play":"BRABANTIO: For I’ll refer me to all things of sense,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.83","kind":"speech"},"1.2.84":{"play":"BRABANTIO: If she in chains of magic were not bound,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.84","kind":"speech"},"1.2.85":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Whether a maid so tender, fair, and happy,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.85","kind":"speech"},"1.2.86":{"play":"BRABANTIO: So opposite to marriage that she shunned","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.86","kind":"speech"},"1.2.87":{"play":"BRABANTIO: The wealthy curlèd darlings of our nation,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.87","kind":"speech"},"1.2.88":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Would ever have, t’ incur a general mock,","notes":["Warburton: I read culled, i.e. select, chosen. Shakespeare uses the word frequently. Cf. Hen. V: III, cho. 24. 'Curled' was an improper mark of diffr-snce between a Venetian and a Moor, which latter people are remarkably curVd by nature. Johnson: 'Curled' is elegantly and ostentatiously dressed. He had not the hair particularly in his thoughts. Steevens: Shakespeare evidently alludes to the hair in 'the curled Anthony,' Ant. & Cleo. V, ii, 304. D'Avenant uses the same expression in his Just Italian [but as was said before, parallel expressions in D'Avenant are of small avail. Ed.] Malone: In R. of L., 981, the hair is expressly mentioned, and the epithet 'curled' is added as characteristic of a person of the highest rank: 'Let him have time to tear his curled hair.' [See notes in Lear, III, iv, 84, 'A Serving-man, proud in heart and mind; that curled my hair.'—Ed.]","Knight: This Saxon word is used in a plural sense. Dyce [Remarks, p. 233): The fact is, the s has been omitted in the Folio by a mistake of the compositor. In Shakespeare's time dearling could never have been used as a plural. That even Spenser (who antiquated his language more than any of his contemporaries) did not venture to employ such an archaism, is proved by the following from his Hymne in honour of Love:— \"in a Paradize Of all delight, and ioyous happie rest, Where they doe feede on Nectar heauenly wize, With Hercules and Hebe, and the rest Of Venus dearlings, through her bountie blest.\""],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.88","kind":"speech"},"1.2.89":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Run from her guardage to the sooty bosom","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.89","kind":"speech"},"1.2.90":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Of such a thing as thou—to fear, not to delight!","notes":["Rolfe: Rolfe: Guardianship, used by Shakespeare nowhere else."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.90","kind":"speech"},"1.2.91":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Judge me the world, if ’tis not gross in sense","notes":["Steevens: To terrify, as in j Hen. VI: V, ii, 2, a bug that feared us all.' The line is redundant in measure. It might originally have ran, 'Of such as. thou: to fear, not to delight.' Malone takes 'fear' to be a substantive, and used for the object of fear; but Abbott, §405, more correctly explains the phrase as an ellipsis, common among Elizabethans, after will and is, e.g. 'I will to the weird sisters.' 'I must to Coventry.' 'I am to thank you for it,' i.e. I am bound to thank you for it; sc here 'such a thing as thou (a thing fit) to fear [act.), not to delight.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.91","kind":"speech"},"1.2.92":{"play":"BRABANTIO: That thou hast practiced on her with foul charms,","notes":["Abbott: Abbott, § 365, Let the world judge for me. This optative use of the subjunctive, dispensing with 'let,' 'may,' &c, gives great vigour to the Shakespearian line. [It is doubtful if 'me' be here the Ethical Dative, as in I, i, 53: 'Whip me such honest knaues,' or 'He plucked me open his doublet,' Jul. Cæs. Brabantio calls upon the world really to judge him and his position, which he immediately proceeds to state. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.92","kind":"speech"},"1.2.93":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Abused her delicate youth with drugs or minerals","notes":["Abbot: Very frequently used, as here, in the sense of plotting, with arts or magic. See Lear, III, ii, 57: 'Has practiced on man's life.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.93","kind":"speech"},"1.2.94":{"play":"BRABANTIO: That weakens motion. I’ll have ’t disputed on.","notes":["[See multiple commentators: Steevens, Johnson, Ritson, Staunton, Booth, Spence, Knight. All on \"That weakens Motion. He haven’t disputed on,\" and \"weakens Motion.\"] See main text for full discussion."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.94","kind":"speech"},"1.2.95":{"play":"BRABANTIO: ’Tis probable, and palpable to thinking.","notes":["Staunton: This is an allusion to the manner in which causes were debated by the judges according to the custom of Venice formerly, Aud it affords, one of many proofs that before writing Othello Shakespeare had attentively perused Lewkenor's translation of The Commonwealth and Government of Venice, written by the Cardinall Gasper Contareno, &c, 1599..."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.95","kind":"speech"},"1.2.96":{"play":"BRABANTIO: I therefore apprehend and do attach thee","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.96","kind":"speech"},"1.2.97":{"play":"BRABANTIO: For an abuser of the world, a practicer","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.97","kind":"speech"},"1.2.98":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Of arts inhibited and out of warrant.—","notes":["Booth: Othello and Cassio exchange smiles of pity for the old man's credulity."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.98","kind":"speech"},"1.2.99":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Lay hold upon him. If he do resist,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.99","kind":"speech"},"1.2.100":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Subdue him at his peril.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.100","kind":"speech"},"1.2.101":{"play":"OTHELLO: Hold your hands,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.101","kind":"speech"},"1.2.102":{"play":"OTHELLO: Both you of my inclining and the rest.","notes":["Booth: Now Othello's friends draw. Othello stands between the two parties with sheathed scimitar held up; its crescent shape lends a little Oriental atmosphere to the picture. 'Tis harmless."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.102","kind":"speech"},"1.2.103":{"play":"OTHELLO: Were it my cue to fight, I should have known it","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.103","kind":"speech"},"1.2.104":{"play":"OTHELLO: Without a prompter.—Whither will you that I go","notes":["Wedgwood: In Ham. II, ii, 534, Wedgwood's definition is quoted: 'The last words of the preceding speech, prefixed to the speech of an actor in order to let him know when he is to come on the stage. From the letter Q by which it was marked, \"because,\" says Butler, Eng. Gram., 1634, \"it is the first letter of quando, when, showing when to enter and speak.\" ’ Skeat now gives a different derivation; he says, 'that an actor's cue seems to be the same word as queue, as signifying the last words or tail-end of the speech of the preceding speaker. Oddly enough, it was, in this sense, sometimes denoted by Q; owing to the similarity of the sound.'","Walker: This passage is cited by Walker (Vers. 106) as one of the many instances in which hither, whether, &c. are printed as dissyllables, where the verse indicates that they are monosyllables. Cf. Macb. I, iii, ill; Ham. III, ii, 193; Lear, II, i, 53. also m Aubott, §466."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.104","kind":"speech"},"1.2.105":{"play":"OTHELLO: To answer this your charge?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.105","kind":"speech"},"1.2.106":{"play":"BRABANTIO: To prison, till fit time","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.106","kind":"speech"},"1.2.107":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Of law and course of direct session","notes":["Hudson: The language is rather odd, and, perhaps, somewhat obscure; but the meaning probably is, till the time prescribed by law and by the regular course of judicial procedure."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.107","kind":"speech"},"1.2.108":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Call thee to answer.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.108","kind":"speech"},"1.2.109":{"play":"OTHELLO: What if I do obey?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.109","kind":"speech"},"1.2.110":{"play":"OTHELLO: How may the Duke be therewith satisfied,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.110","kind":"speech"},"1.2.111":{"play":"OTHELLO: Whose messengers are here about my side,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.111","kind":"speech"},"1.2.112":{"play":"OTHELLO: Upon some present business of the state,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.112","kind":"speech"},"1.2.113":{"play":"OTHELLO: To bring me to him?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.113","kind":"speech"},"1.2.114":{"play":"OFFICER: ’Tis true, most worthy signior.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.114","kind":"speech"},"1.2.115":{"play":"OFFICER: The Duke’s in council, and your noble self","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.115","kind":"speech"},"1.2.116":{"play":"OFFICER: I am sure is sent for.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.116","kind":"speech"},"1.2.117":{"play":"BRABANTIO: How? The Duke in council?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.117","kind":"speech"},"1.2.118":{"play":"BRABANTIO: In this time of the night? Bring him away;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.118","kind":"speech"},"1.2.119":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Mine’s not an idle cause. The Duke himself,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.119","kind":"speech"},"1.2.120":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Or any of my brothers of the state,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.120","kind":"speech"},"1.2.121":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Cannot but feel this wrong as ’twere their own.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.121","kind":"speech"},"1.2.122":{"play":"BRABANTIO: For if such actions may have passage free,","notes":["Theobald: Would Brabantio infer, if his private injury were not redressed, the Senate should no longer pretend to call themselves Christians? But pagans are as strict and moral as the most regular Christians in the preservation of private property. Difference of faith is not concerned, but mere human policy. I therefore read pageants, i.e. if we let such injurious actions go unpunished our statesmen must be slaves, ciphers in office, and have no power of redressing, be things of mere show and gaudy appearance only. Steevens: I believe the morality of either Christians or pagans was not in our author's thoughts. He alludes to the common condition of all blacks, who come from their own country both slaves and pagans; and uses the word in contempt of Othello and his complexion. If this Moor is now suffered to escape with impunity, it will be such an encouragment to his black countrymen, that we may expect to see all the first offices of our state filled up by the pagans and bondslaves of Africa. Heath (p. 534): It is certain from this very play that the Moor had been both a bondslave and a pagan, though at that time he was neither. Malone: In Shakespeare's time page was a very common expression of contempt."],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.122","kind":"speech"},"1.2.123":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Bondslaves and pagans shall our statesmen be.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.2.123","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.2.123.1":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.2.123.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 1, SCENE 3":{"SD_1.3.0":{"play":"[Enter Duke, Senators, and Officers.]","notes":["Collier (ed. ii): Collier adopts from his (MS) 'with the same reports,' with the note that 'the clear meaning being, that even when reports of such occurrences are mainly the same, it is often with difference. It appears highly probable that the passage was misheard, as well as misprinted, and that the true text is what we have adopted.' [Nevertheless, Collier returned to F1 in the text of his ed. iii. The Cam. Ed. records 'aim besorts' and 'main accords' as anonymous conjectures. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.0","kind":"stage"},"1.3.1":{"play":"DUKE: There’s no composition in these news","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.1","kind":"speech"},"1.3.2":{"play":"DUKE: That gives them credit.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.2","kind":"speech"},"1.3.3":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: Indeed, they are disproportioned.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.3","kind":"speech"},"1.3.4":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: My letters say a hundred and seven galleys.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.4","kind":"speech"},"1.3.5":{"play":"DUKE: And mine, a hundred forty.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.5","kind":"speech"},"1.3.6":{"play":"SECOND SENATOR: And mine, two hundred.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.6","kind":"speech"},"1.3.7":{"play":"SECOND SENATOR: But though they jump not on a just account","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.7","kind":"speech"},"1.3.8":{"play":"SECOND SENATOR: (As in these cases, where the aim reports","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.8","kind":"speech"},"1.3.9":{"play":"SECOND SENATOR: ’Tis oft with difference), yet do they all confirm","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.9","kind":"speech"},"1.3.10":{"play":"SECOND SENATOR: A Turkish fleet, and bearing up to Cyprus.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.10","kind":"speech"},"1.3.11":{"play":"DUKE: Nay, it is possible enough to judgment.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.11","kind":"speech"},"1.3.12":{"play":"DUKE: I do not so secure me in the error,","notes":["Staunton: Staunton paraphrases, 'I do not so over-confidently build on the discrepancy;' but Purnell, with more fidelity to the derivation of the word, ‘‘I do not lay aside anxiety on account of the discrepancy.’’"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.12","kind":"speech"},"1.3.13":{"play":"DUKE: But the main article I do approve","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.13","kind":"speech"},"1.3.14":{"play":"DUKE: In fearful sense.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.14","kind":"speech"},"1.3.15":{"play":"SAILOR: What ho, what ho, what ho!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.15","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.3.15.1":{"play":"[Enter Sailor.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.15.1","kind":"stage"},"1.3.16":{"play":"OFFICER: A messenger from the galleys.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.16","kind":"speech"},"1.3.17":{"play":"DUKE: Now, what’s the business?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.17","kind":"speech"},"1.3.18":{"play":"SAILOR: The Turkish preparation makes for Rhodes.","notes":["See Appendix, 'Date of the Action.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.18","kind":"speech"},"1.3.19":{"play":"SAILOR: So was I bid report here to the state","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.19","kind":"speech"},"1.3.20":{"play":"SAILOR: By Signior Angelo.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.20","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.3.20":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.20","kind":"stage"},"1.3.21":{"play":"DUKE: How say you by this change?","notes":["For other instances where 'by' means about, concerning, see Abbott, § 145. Purnell refers [as does also Abbott] to '1 Corinth, iv, 4, \"I know nothing by myself\" (the Greek being, \"I am conscious of nothing against myself\"), where Alford quotes, \"I know no harm by him,\" as a midland-county current expression.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.21","kind":"speech"},"1.3.22":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: This cannot be,","notes":["For instances of double negatives, see ABBOTT, §406."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.22","kind":"speech"},"1.3.23":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: By no assay of reason. ’Tis a pageant","notes":["Johnson: Bring it to the test, examine it by reason as we examine metals by the assay, it will be found counterfeit by all trials."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.23","kind":"speech"},"1.3.24":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: To keep us in false gaze. When we consider","notes":["Rolfe: Used by Shakespeare nowhere else."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.24","kind":"speech"},"1.3.25":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: Th’ importancy of Cyprus to the Turk,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.25","kind":"speech"},"1.3.26":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: And let ourselves again but understand","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.26","kind":"speech"},"1.3.27":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: That, as it more concerns the Turk than Rhodes,","notes":["Johnson: 'Question' is for the act of seeking, with more easy endeavour. Mason: May carry it with less dispute, with less opposition. Schmidt (Lex.) from the use of 'question ' in the sense of a judicial trial, deduces the meaning here of 'a trial and decision by the force of arms as the ultima ratio regum.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.27","kind":"speech"},"1.3.28":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: So may he with more facile question bear it,","notes":["Johnson: State of defence. White (ed. ii): Warlike strain, military necessity or compulsion. [I cannot understand how White deduces this interpretation. The very point of the speech is, that Cyprus is of greater 'military necessity' to the Turk than Rhodes. 'Brace' is, I think, here equivalent to readiness; when a knight had braced on his armour he was ready. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.28","kind":"speech"},"1.3.29":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: For that it stands not in such warlike brace,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.29","kind":"speech"},"1.3.30":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: But altogether lacks th’ abilities","notes":["Steevens gives as the meaning here, to fight, to combat, and cites in proof, 'To wage against the enmity o'th'air.' Lear, II, iv, 206; but 'wage' is transitive here; accordingly, Schmidt gives the better interpretation: to hazard, to attempt."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.30","kind":"speech"},"1.3.31":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: That Rhodes is dressed in—if we make thought of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.31","kind":"speech"},"1.3.32":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: this,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.32","kind":"speech"},"1.3.33":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: We must not think the Turk is so unskillful","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.33","kind":"speech"},"1.3.34":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: To leave that latest which concerns him first,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.34","kind":"speech"},"1.3.35":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: Neglecting an attempt of ease and gain","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.35","kind":"speech"},"1.3.36":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: To wake and wage a danger profitless.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.36","kind":"speech"},"1.3.37":{"play":"DUKE: Nay, in all confidence, he’s not for Rhodes.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.37","kind":"speech"},"1.3.38":{"play":"OFFICER: Here is more news.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.38","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.3.38.1":{"play":"[Enter a Messenger.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.38.1","kind":"stage"},"1.3.39":{"play":"MESSENGER: The Ottomites, Reverend and Gracious,","notes":["Booth here begins his Scene IV, in the Council Chamber. The Duke and the Senators are discovered R. with a Messenger who is kneeling before them. Enter as the scene opens, Gra. Rod. and others. The advantage of placing the Duke at the side instead of at the back as in the old 'set' is, that the characters need not turn theii backs on the audience when addressing the Duke."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.39","kind":"speech"},"1.3.40":{"play":"MESSENGER: Steering with due course toward the isle of Rhodes,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.40","kind":"speech"},"1.3.41":{"play":"MESSENGER: Have there injointed them with an after fleet.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.41","kind":"speech"},"1.3.42":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: Ay, so I thought. How many, as you guess?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.42","kind":"speech"},"1.3.43":{"play":"MESSENGER: Of thirty sail; and now they do restem","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.43","kind":"speech"},"1.3.44":{"play":"MESSENGER: Their backward course, bearing with frank","notes":["Malone: Used by Shakespeare nowhere else."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.44","kind":"speech"},"1.3.45":{"play":"MESSENGER: appearance","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.45","kind":"speech"},"1.3.46":{"play":"MESSENGER: Their purposes toward Cyprus. Signior Montano,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.46","kind":"speech"},"1.3.47":{"play":"MESSENGER: Your trusty and most valiant servitor,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.47","kind":"speech"},"1.3.48":{"play":"MESSENGER: With his free duty recommends you thus,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.48","kind":"speech"},"1.3.49":{"play":"MESSENGER: And prays you to believe him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.49","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.3.49":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.49","kind":"stage"},"1.3.50":{"play":"DUKE: ’Tis certain, then, for Cyprus.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.50","kind":"speech"},"1.3.51":{"play":"DUKE: Marcus Luccicos, is not he in town?","notes":["Walker (Crit. iii, 285): Injoint? Ham. I, ii, 20: 'Our state to be disjoint, and out of frame.' Yet I doubt whether the cases are parallel. [For other instances of the omission, in participles, of ed after d or t, see Walker [Crit. ii, 324), and Abbott, § 342.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.51","kind":"speech"},"1.3.52":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: He’s now in Florence.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.52","kind":"speech"},"1.3.53":{"play":"DUKE: Write from us to him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.53","kind":"speech"},"1.3.54":{"play":"DUKE: Post-post-haste. Dispatch.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.54","kind":"speech"},"1.3.55":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: Here comes Brabantio and the valiant Moor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.55","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.3.55.1":{"play":"[Enter Brabantio, Othello, Cassio, Iago, Roderigo, and Officers.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.55.1","kind":"stage"},"1.3.56":{"play":"DUKE: Valiant Othello, we must straight employ you","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.56","kind":"speech"},"1.3.57":{"play":"DUKE: Against the general enemy Ottoman.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.57","kind":"speech"},"1.3.58":{"play":"DUKE: I did not see you. Welcome, gentle","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.58","kind":"speech"},"1.3.59":{"play":"DUKE: signior.","notes":["Johnson: The late learned and ingenious Mr Thomas Clark, of Lincoln's Inn, read the passage, 'relieve him.' But the present reading may stand. He entreats you not to doubt the truth of this intelligence. Capell: Montano's message to the Senate is worded with great politeness in all the parts of it; in this last relief, the thing he stood in want of and wish'd, is only insinuated; knowing it would follow from them, was belief accorded him. [This emendation of relieve for 'believe,' Collier attributed to Rev. Mr Barry. Dyce and White ascribe it to Capell; White pronounces it 'plausible;' Dyce (ed. iii) quotes Lettsom as follows: 'Believe,' I think right as Johnson takes it. Relieve would mean 'send a successor?]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.59","kind":"speech"},"1.3.60":{"play":"DUKE: We lacked your counsel and your help tonight.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.60","kind":"speech"},"1.3.61":{"play":"BRABANTIO: So did I yours. Good your Grace, pardon me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.61","kind":"speech"},"1.3.62":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Neither my place nor aught I heard of business","notes":["Capell changed this to Lucchese, and justified the change in a note in his usual style: 'The corniptions of \"Veronese\" may induce belief, that this which we are come to is no strain'd one; and the Italian will call it necessary, terminations like that below being unknown in his language.' 'But,' asks Knight, with more shrewdness than grammar, 'who is the Duke inquiring after? Most probably a Greek soldier of Cyprus, an Estradiot, one who from his local knowledge was enabled to give him information. Is it necessary that the Greek should bear an Italian name? And does not tbe termination in cos better convey the notion which we believe the poet to have h>d?'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.62","kind":"speech"},"1.3.63":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Hath raised me from my bed, nor doth the general","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.63","kind":"speech"},"1.3.64":{"play":"BRABANTIO: care","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.64","kind":"speech"},"1.3.65":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Take hold on me, for my particular grief","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.65","kind":"speech"},"1.3.66":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Is of so floodgate and o’erbearing nature","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.66","kind":"speech"},"1.3.67":{"play":"BRABANTIO: That it engluts and swallows other sorrows","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.67","kind":"speech"},"1.3.68":{"play":"BRABANTIO: And it is still itself.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.68","kind":"speech"},"1.3.69":{"play":"DUKE: Why, what’s the matter?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.69","kind":"speech"},"1.3.70":{"play":"BRABANTIO: My daughter! O, my daughter!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.70","kind":"speech"},"1.3.71":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: Dead?","notes":["Malone: It is part of the policy of the Venetian state never to entrust the command of an army to a native. ' To exclude, therefore, (says Contareno, trans, by Lewkenor, 1599) out of our estate the danger or occasion of any such ambitious enterprises, our ancestors held it a better course to defend the dominions on the continent with foreign mercenary soldiers, than with their home-bred citizens.' Again: 'alwaies they do entertain in honourable sort with great provision a captaine generally who alwaies is a stranger borne.'' Reed: So in Thomas's Hist, of Italy, p. 82: 'By lande they are served of straungers, both for generalls, for capitaines, and for all other men of warre; because theyr lawe permitteth not any Venetian to be capitaine over an armie by lande: Fearing, I thinke, Caesar's example.' Schmidt [Lex.) queries whether this be used here as an adjective or substantive; Rolfe inclines to think it is the former."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.71","kind":"speech"},"1.3.72":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Ay, to me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.72","kind":"speech"},"1.3.73":{"play":"BRABANTIO: She is abused, stol’n from me, and corrupted","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.73","kind":"speech"},"1.3.74":{"play":"BRABANTIO: By spells and medicines bought of mountebanks;","notes":["Abbott, §13: The possessive adjectives when unemphatic are sometimes transposed, being really combined with nouns (like the French monsieur milord)."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.74","kind":"speech"},"1.3.75":{"play":"BRABANTIO: For nature so prepost’rously to err—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.75","kind":"speech"},"1.3.76":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Being not deficient, blind, or lame of sense—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.76","kind":"speech"},"1.3.77":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Sans witchcraft could not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.77","kind":"speech"},"1.3.78":{"play":"DUKE: Whoe’er he be that in this foul proceeding","notes":["Johnson: Were the man exposed to your charge or accusation. Morel: C'est la un sens tout francais du mot."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.78","kind":"speech"},"1.3.79":{"play":"DUKE: Hath thus beguiled your daughter of herself","notes":["Abbott, § 160, gives instances of 'in' used for on. See note on I, i, 149."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.79","kind":"speech"},"1.3.80":{"play":"DUKE: And you of her, the bloody book of law","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.80","kind":"speech"},"1.3.81":{"play":"DUKE: You shall yourself read in the bitter letter,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.81","kind":"speech"},"1.3.82":{"play":"DUKE: After your own sense, yea, though our proper son","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.82","kind":"speech"},"1.3.83":{"play":"DUKE: Stood in your action.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.83","kind":"speech"},"1.3.84":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Humbly I thank your Grace.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.84","kind":"speech"},"1.3.85":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Here is the man—this Moor, whom now it seems","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.85","kind":"speech"},"1.3.86":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Your special mandate for the state affairs","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.86","kind":"speech"},"1.3.87":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Hath hither brought.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.87","kind":"speech"},"1.3.88":{"play":"ALL: We are very sorry for ’t.","notes":["Grey (ii, 312) cites a law of I Jac. cap. xii, to the effect: 'That if any person or persons should take upon him or them, by witchcraft, inchantment, charm or sorcery, to the intent to provoke any person to unlawful love; and being thereof lawfully convicted, should, for the first offence, suffer imprisonment for the space of one whole year,' &c. Warburton says that Rymer ridicules this accusation of charms and medicines, but the passage in Rymer has escaped me, and small wonder, in that headlong torrent of amusing abuse of Shakespeare. Warburton, however, avails himself of the chance to cite a Venetian law, Dei maleficii et herbarie, cap. xvii, of the code, entitled ' Della promission del maleficio.' Whereupon Steevens remarks 'Though I believe Shakespeare knew no more of this Venetian law than I do, yet he was well acquainted with the edicts of that sapient prince King James the First.' 'But,' says Ritson (p. 228), 'there is no doubt that Shakespeare had the substance of Brabantio's speech from Cinthio's novel, however he might come by it; and Cinthio, it may be supposed, knew something of the Venetian Statute.' At this line and at line 80, Booth says, Cassio and Othello should exchange smiles, as at I, ii, 95."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.88","kind":"speech"},"1.3.89":{"play":"DUKE: What, in your own part, can you say to this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.89","kind":"speech"},"1.3.90":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Nothing, but this is so.","notes":["Abbott cites this passage under §350, where examples are given of the use of ' to ' when the finite principal verb is an auxiliary or like an auxiliary, as in Ham. I, v, 18 and 178, and thus explains: 'Here either (1) \"to err\" depends on \"could,\" i. e. \"Nature was not able to err;\" or (2) \"could not\" might perhaps stand for \"could not be,\" \"was impossible,\" having for its subject \"Nature to err.\" In (2) \"for\" may be either (a) a conjunction, or (<£) a preposition: \" It was not possible for Nature thus to err.\" I prefer (1).'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.90","kind":"speech"},"1.3.91":{"play":"OTHELLO: Most potent, grave, and reverend signiors,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.91","kind":"speech"},"1.3.92":{"play":"OTHELLO: My very noble and approved good masters:","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.92","kind":"speech"},"1.3.93":{"play":"OTHELLO: That I have ta’en away this old man’s daughter,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.93","kind":"speech"},"1.3.94":{"play":"OTHELLO: It is most true; true I have married her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.94","kind":"speech"},"1.3.95":{"play":"OTHELLO: The very head and front of my offending","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.95","kind":"speech"},"1.3.96":{"play":"OTHELLO: Hath this extent, no more. Rude am I in my speech,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.96","kind":"speech"},"1.3.97":{"play":"OTHELLO: And little blessed with the soft phrase of peace;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.97","kind":"speech"},"1.3.98":{"play":"OTHELLO: For since these arms of mine had seven years’ pith,","notes":["Warburton: This apology, if addressed to his mistress, had been well expressed. But what he wanted, in speaking before a Venetian Senate, was not the soft blandishments of speech, but the art and method of masculine eloquence. I am persuaded, therefore, that set of the Qq is right."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.98","kind":"speech"},"1.3.99":{"play":"OTHELLO: Till now some nine moons wasted, they have used","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.99","kind":"speech"},"1.3.100":{"play":"OTHELLO: Their dearest action in the tented field,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.100","kind":"speech"},"1.3.101":{"play":"OTHELLO: And little of this great world can I speak","notes":["Forrest emphasized this word, and 'not ' myself.'—Rees's Life p. 140."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.101","kind":"speech"},"1.3.102":{"play":"OTHELLO: More than pertains to feats of broil and battle.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.102","kind":"speech"},"1.3.103":{"play":"OTHELLO: And therefore little shall I grace my cause","notes":["Rymer (p. 100): We find the Duke of Venice with his Senators in Councel at Midnight, upon advice that the Turks or Ottamites, or both together, were ready in transport Ships, put to sea, in order to make a Descent upon Cyprus. This is the posture, when we see Brabantio and Othello join them. By their Conduct and manner of talk, a body must strain hard to fancy the Scene at Venice; And not rather in some 4"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.103","kind":"speech"},"1.3.104":{"play":"OTHELLO: In speaking for myself. Yet, by your gracious","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.104","kind":"speech"},"1.3.105":{"play":"OTHELLO: patience,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.105","kind":"speech"},"1.3.106":{"play":"OTHELLO: I will a round unvarnished tale deliver","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.106","kind":"speech"},"1.3.107":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of my whole course of love—what drugs, what","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.107","kind":"speech"},"1.3.108":{"play":"OTHELLO: charms,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.108","kind":"speech"},"1.3.109":{"play":"OTHELLO: What conjuration, and what mighty magic","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.109","kind":"speech"},"1.3.110":{"play":"OTHELLO: (For such proceeding I am charged withal)","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.110","kind":"speech"},"1.3.111":{"play":"OTHELLO: I won his daughter.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.111","kind":"speech"},"1.3.112":{"play":"BRABANTIO: A maiden never bold,","notes":["Purnell; French ' engloutir,' to swallow."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.112","kind":"speech"},"1.3.113":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Of spirit so still and quiet that her motion","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.113","kind":"speech"},"1.3.114":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Blushed at herself. And she, in spite of nature,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.114","kind":"speech"},"1.3.115":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Of years, of country, credit, everything,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.115","kind":"speech"},"1.3.116":{"play":"BRABANTIO: To fall in love with what she feared to look on!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.116","kind":"speech"},"1.3.117":{"play":"BRABANTIO: It is a judgment maimed and most imperfect","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.117","kind":"speech"},"1.3.118":{"play":"BRABANTIO: That will confess perfection so could err","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.118","kind":"speech"},"1.3.119":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Against all rules of nature, and must be driven","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.119","kind":"speech"},"1.3.120":{"play":"BRABANTIO: To find out practices of cunning hell","notes":["Walker (Vers., 227): 'God be with you' is, in fact, God b' wi' you: sometimes a trisyllable, sometimes contracted into a disyllable; now Good-bye. Accordingly write: ' Due to the Moor, my lord. God b' wi' you ! I've done ' [one line. See III, iii, 433.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.120","kind":"speech"},"1.3.121":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Why this should be. I therefore vouch again","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.121","kind":"speech"},"1.3.122":{"play":"BRABANTIO: That with some mixtures powerful o’er the blood,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.122","kind":"speech"},"1.3.123":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Or with some dram conjured to this effect,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.123","kind":"speech"},"1.3.124":{"play":"BRABANTIO: He wrought upon her.","notes":["Johnson: That is, dear, for which much is paid, whether money or labour; dear action is action performed at great expense, either of ease or safety. Malone thinks it here means most important; Steevens that in modern language we should say, their best exertion; and M. Mason that it means their favourite action. [To me, Dr W. Alois Wright's definition seems exact: ' dear is used of whatever touches us nearly, either in love or hate, joy or sorrow.' See Ham. I, ii, 182. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.124","kind":"speech"},"1.3.125":{"play":"DUKE: To vouch this is no proof","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.125","kind":"speech"},"1.3.126":{"play":"DUKE: Without more wider and more overt test","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.126","kind":"speech"},"1.3.127":{"play":"DUKE: Than these thin habits and poor likelihoods","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.127","kind":"speech"},"1.3.128":{"play":"DUKE: Of modern seeming do prefer against him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.128","kind":"speech"},"1.3.129":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: But, Othello, speak:","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.129","kind":"speech"},"1.3.130":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: Did you by indirect and forcèd courses","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.130","kind":"speech"},"1.3.131":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: Subdue and poison this young maid’s affections?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.131","kind":"speech"},"1.3.132":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: Or came it by request, and such fair question","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.132","kind":"speech"},"1.3.133":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: As soul to soul affordeth?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.133","kind":"speech"},"1.3.134":{"play":"OTHELLO: I do beseech you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.134","kind":"speech"},"1.3.135":{"play":"OTHELLO: Send for the lady to the Sagittary","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.135","kind":"speech"},"1.3.136":{"play":"OTHELLO: And let her speak of me before her father.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.136","kind":"speech"},"1.3.137":{"play":"OTHELLO: If you do find me foul in her report,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.137","kind":"speech"},"1.3.138":{"play":"OTHELLO: The trust, the office I do hold of you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.138","kind":"speech"},"1.3.139":{"play":"OTHELLO: Not only take away, but let your sentence","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.139","kind":"speech"},"1.3.140":{"play":"OTHELLO: Even fall upon my life.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.140","kind":"speech"},"1.3.141":{"play":"DUKE: Fetch Desdemona hither.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.141","kind":"speech"},"1.3.142":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ancient, conduct them. You best know the place.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.142","kind":"speech"},"1.3.143":{"play":"OTHELLO: And till she come, as truly as to heaven","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.143","kind":"speech"},"1.3.144":{"play":"OTHELLO: I do confess the vices of my blood,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.144","kind":"speech"},"1.3.145":{"play":"OTHELLO: So justly to your grave ears I’ll present","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.145","kind":"speech"},"1.3.146":{"play":"OTHELLO: How I did thrive in this fair lady’s love,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.146","kind":"speech"},"1.3.147":{"play":"OTHELLO: And she in mine.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.147","kind":"speech"},"1.3.148":{"play":"DUKE: Say it, Othello.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.148","kind":"speech"},"1.3.149":{"play":"OTHELLO: Her father loved me, oft invited me,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.149","kind":"speech"},"1.3.150":{"play":"OTHELLO: Still questioned me the story of my life","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.150","kind":"speech"},"1.3.151":{"play":"OTHELLO: From year to year—the battles, sieges, fortunes","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.151","kind":"speech"},"1.3.152":{"play":"OTHELLO: That I have passed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.152","kind":"speech"},"1.3.153":{"play":"OTHELLO: I ran it through, even from my boyish days","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.153","kind":"speech"},"1.3.154":{"play":"OTHELLO: To th’ very moment that he bade me tell it,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.154","kind":"speech"},"1.3.155":{"play":"OTHELLO: Wherein I spoke of most disastrous chances:","notes":["Theobald's note on Antropophague and the headless men: Sir Walter Raleigh in his Travels [The Discoverie of Gviana, 1596, p. 85, ed. Hakluyt Soc] has given the following account: 'Next vnto Arui there are two riuers Atoica and Caora, and on that braunch which is called Caora are a nation of people, whose heades appeare not aboue their shoulders, which though it may be thought a meere fable, yet for mine owne parte I am resolued it is true … They are called Ewaipanoma: they are reported to haue their eyes in their shoulders, and their mouths in the middle of their breasts, and that a long train of haire groweth backward betwen their shoulders …' This passage and the same allusion in Temp. III, iii, 46, help us in fixing the date of these plays; neither of them could have been written before 1596."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.155","kind":"speech"},"1.3.156":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of moving accidents by flood and field,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.156","kind":"speech"},"1.3.157":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of hairbreadth ’scapes i’ th’ imminent deadly","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.157","kind":"speech"},"1.3.158":{"play":"OTHELLO: breach,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.158","kind":"speech"},"1.3.159":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of being taken by the insolent foe","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.159","kind":"speech"},"1.3.160":{"play":"OTHELLO: And sold to slavery, of my redemption thence,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.160","kind":"speech"},"1.3.161":{"play":"OTHELLO: And portance in my traveler’s history,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.161","kind":"speech"},"1.3.162":{"play":"OTHELLO: Wherein of antres vast and deserts idle,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.162","kind":"speech"},"1.3.163":{"play":"OTHELLO: Rough quarries, rocks, and hills whose heads","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.163","kind":"speech"},"1.3.164":{"play":"OTHELLO: touch heaven,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.164","kind":"speech"},"1.3.165":{"play":"OTHELLO: It was my hint to speak—such was my process—","notes":["Warburton: Discourses of this nature made the subject of the politest conversation, when voyages into, and discoveries of, the new world were all in vogue. So, when the Bastard Faulconbridge in King John, describes the behaviour of upstart greatness, he makes one of the essential circumstances of it to be this kind of table-talk.… The fashion then running altogether this way, it is no wonder a young lady of quality should be struck with the history of an adventurer. Johnson: Whoever ridicules this account of the progress of love, shows his ignorance not only of history, but also of nature and manners.… It is no wonder that, in any age or in any nation, a lady recluse, timorous, and delicate—should desire to hear of events and scenes which she could never see; and should admire the man who had endured dangers and performed actions, which, however great, were yet magnified by her timidity."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.165","kind":"speech"},"1.3.166":{"play":"OTHELLO: And of the cannibals that each other eat,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.166","kind":"speech"},"1.3.167":{"play":"OTHELLO: The Anthropophagi, and men whose heads","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.167","kind":"speech"},"1.3.168":{"play":"OTHELLO: Do grow beneath their shoulders. These things to","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.168","kind":"speech"},"1.3.169":{"play":"OTHELLO: hear","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.169","kind":"speech"},"1.3.170":{"play":"OTHELLO: Would Desdemona seriously incline.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.170","kind":"speech"},"1.3.171":{"play":"OTHELLO: But still the house affairs would draw her thence,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.171","kind":"speech"},"1.3.172":{"play":"OTHELLO: Which ever as she could with haste dispatch","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.172","kind":"speech"},"1.3.173":{"play":"OTHELLO: She’d come again, and with a greedy ear","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.173","kind":"speech"},"1.3.174":{"play":"OTHELLO: Devour up my discourse. Which I, observing,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.174","kind":"speech"},"1.3.175":{"play":"OTHELLO: Took once a pliant hour, and found good means","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.175","kind":"speech"},"1.3.176":{"play":"OTHELLO: To draw from her a prayer of earnest heart","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.176","kind":"speech"},"1.3.177":{"play":"OTHELLO: That I would all my pilgrimage dilate,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.177","kind":"speech"},"1.3.178":{"play":"OTHELLO: Whereof by parcels she had something heard,","notes":["Forrest emphasized this word—Rees's Life, p. 141."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.178","kind":"speech"},"1.3.179":{"play":"OTHELLO: But not intentively. I did consent,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.179","kind":"speech"},"1.3.180":{"play":"OTHELLO: And often did beguile her of her tears","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.180","kind":"speech"},"1.3.181":{"play":"OTHELLO: When I did speak of some distressful stroke","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.181","kind":"speech"},"1.3.182":{"play":"OTHELLO: That my youth suffered. My story being done,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.182","kind":"speech"},"1.3.183":{"play":"OTHELLO: She gave me for my pains a world of sighs.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.183","kind":"speech"},"1.3.184":{"play":"OTHELLO: She swore, in faith, ’twas strange, ’twas passing","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.184","kind":"speech"},"1.3.185":{"play":"OTHELLO: strange,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.185","kind":"speech"},"1.3.186":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Twas pitiful, ’twas wondrous pitiful.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.186","kind":"speech"},"1.3.187":{"play":"OTHELLO: She wished she had not heard it, yet she wished","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.187","kind":"speech"},"1.3.188":{"play":"OTHELLO: That heaven had made her such a man. She thanked","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.188","kind":"speech"},"1.3.189":{"play":"OTHELLO: me,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.189","kind":"speech"},"1.3.190":{"play":"OTHELLO: And bade me, if I had a friend that loved her,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.190","kind":"speech"},"1.3.191":{"play":"OTHELLO: I should but teach him how to tell my story,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.191","kind":"speech"},"1.3.192":{"play":"OTHELLO: And that would woo her. Upon this hint I spake.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.192","kind":"speech"},"1.3.193":{"play":"OTHELLO: She loved me for the dangers I had passed,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.193","kind":"speech"},"1.3.194":{"play":"OTHELLO: And I loved her that she did pity them.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.194","kind":"speech"},"1.3.195":{"play":"OTHELLO: This only is the witchcraft I have used.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.195","kind":"speech"},"1.3.196":{"play":"OTHELLO: Here comes the lady. Let her witness it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.196","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.3.196.1":{"play":"[Enter Desdemona, Iago, Attendants.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.196.1","kind":"stage"},"1.3.197":{"play":"DUKE: I think this tale would win my daughter, too.","notes":["Dyce (Remarks, p. 234): Intentively was always used as equivalent to attentively, not only by the writers of Shakespeare's time, but by those of a much earlier date. Palsgrave has ( Intentyfex hedefull.'—'Ententyfe, busy to do a thynge or to take hede to a thyng.' Singer quotes Bullokar's Expositor: 'Intentive Which listeneth well, and is earnestly bent to a thing.' Lettsom (Walker's Crit. i, 181, Foot-note): 'Distinctively 'seems a mere sophistication of F2 for instinctiuely, the nonsensical reading of F1. In this particular passage intentively seems to mean either all at a stretch, or so as to comprehend the story as a whole.…"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.197","kind":"speech"},"1.3.198":{"play":"DUKE: Good Brabantio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.198","kind":"speech"},"1.3.199":{"play":"DUKE: Take up this mangled matter at the best.","notes":["Pope: Sighs is evidently the true reading. The lady had been forward indeed, to give him a world of kisses upon the bare recital of his story, nor does it agree with the following lines. [And yet we must remember that kissing in Elizabeth's time was not as significant as it is now. See the openness with which, in II, i, Cassio kisses Emilia. Ed.]","Dyce: Desdemona's love remains, and though the did of the Qq assists the rhythm, it enfeebles the sense. Cowden-Clarke: Desdemona is gentle even to timidity; but, like many women whose gentleness has been wrought into timidity by a too rigid strictness of their elders, she is capable of singularly bold action and of self-assertion on occasion. Her independent act in leaving her father's house, and in marrying the man of her choice, is precisely characteristic of the one, and her present speech is an eminent specimen of the other."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.199","kind":"speech"},"1.3.200":{"play":"DUKE: Men do their broken weapons rather use","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.200","kind":"speech"},"1.3.201":{"play":"DUKE: Than their bare hands.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.201","kind":"speech"},"1.3.202":{"play":"BRABANTIO: I pray you hear her speak.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.202","kind":"speech"},"1.3.203":{"play":"BRABANTIO: If she confess that she was half the wooer,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.203","kind":"speech"},"1.3.204":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Destruction on my head if my bad blame","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.204","kind":"speech"},"1.3.205":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Light on the man.—Come hither, gentle mistress.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.205","kind":"speech"},"1.3.206":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Do you perceive in all this noble company","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.206","kind":"speech"},"1.3.207":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Where most you owe obedience?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.207","kind":"speech"},"1.3.208":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My noble father,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.208","kind":"speech"},"1.3.209":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I do perceive here a divided duty.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.209","kind":"speech"},"1.3.210":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To you I am bound for life and education.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.210","kind":"speech"},"1.3.211":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My life and education both do learn me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.211","kind":"speech"},"1.3.212":{"play":"DESDEMONA: How to respect you. You are the lord of duty.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.212","kind":"speech"},"1.3.213":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I am hitherto your daughter. But here’s my","notes":["Schmidt (Trans.): refers to a similar thought, amplified, in Much Ado, IV, i, 129."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.213","kind":"speech"},"1.3.214":{"play":"DESDEMONA: husband.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.214","kind":"speech"},"1.3.215":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And so much duty as my mother showed","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.215","kind":"speech"},"1.3.216":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To you, preferring you before her father,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.216","kind":"speech"},"1.3.217":{"play":"DESDEMONA: So much I challenge that I may profess","notes":["Johnson: Let your favour privilege me."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.217","kind":"speech"},"1.3.218":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Due to the Moor my lord.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.218","kind":"speech"},"1.3.219":{"play":"BRABANTIO: God be with you! I have done.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.219","kind":"speech"},"1.3.220":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Please it your Grace, on to the state affairs.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.220","kind":"speech"},"1.3.221":{"play":"BRABANTIO: I had rather to adopt a child than get it.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.221","kind":"speech"},"1.3.222":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Come hither, Moor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.222","kind":"speech"},"1.3.223":{"play":"BRABANTIO: I here do give thee that with all my heart","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.223","kind":"speech"},"1.3.224":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Which, but thou hast already, with all my heart","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.224","kind":"speech"},"1.3.225":{"play":"BRABANTIO: I would keep from thee.—For your sake, jewel,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.225","kind":"speech"},"1.3.226":{"play":"BRABANTIO: I am glad at soul I have no other child,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.226","kind":"speech"},"1.3.227":{"play":"BRABANTIO: For thy escape would teach me tyranny,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.227","kind":"speech"},"1.3.228":{"play":"BRABANTIO: To hang clogs on them.—I have done, my lord.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.228","kind":"speech"},"1.3.229":{"play":"DUKE: Let me speak like yourself and lay a sentence,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.229","kind":"speech"},"1.3.230":{"play":"DUKE: Which as a grise or step may help these lovers","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.230","kind":"speech"},"1.3.231":{"play":"DUKE: Into your favor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.231","kind":"speech"},"1.3.232":{"play":"DUKE: When remedies are past, the griefs are ended","notes":["Compare ' Past cure is still past care,' Love's Lab. V, ii, 28; ' What's gone and what's past help Should be past grief,' Wint. Tale, III, ii, 223; ' Things without all remedy Should be without regard,' Macb. III, ii, 11. Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.232","kind":"speech"},"1.3.233":{"play":"DUKE: By seeing the worst, which late on hopes depended.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.233","kind":"speech"},"1.3.234":{"play":"DUKE: To mourn a mischief that is past and gone","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.234","kind":"speech"},"1.3.235":{"play":"DUKE: Is the next way to draw new mischief on.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.235","kind":"speech"},"1.3.236":{"play":"DUKE: What cannot be preserved when fortune takes,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.236","kind":"speech"},"1.3.237":{"play":"DUKE: Patience her injury a mock’ry makes.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.237","kind":"speech"},"1.3.238":{"play":"DUKE: The robbed that smiles steals something from the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.238","kind":"speech"},"1.3.239":{"play":"DUKE: thief;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.239","kind":"speech"},"1.3.240":{"play":"DUKE: He robs himself that spends a bootless grief.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.240","kind":"speech"},"1.3.241":{"play":"BRABANTIO: So let the Turk of Cyprus us beguile,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.241","kind":"speech"},"1.3.242":{"play":"BRABANTIO: We lose it not so long as we can smile.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.242","kind":"speech"},"1.3.243":{"play":"BRABANTIO: He bears the sentence well that nothing bears","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.243","kind":"speech"},"1.3.244":{"play":"BRABANTIO: But the free comfort which from thence he hears;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.244","kind":"speech"},"1.3.245":{"play":"BRABANTIO: But he bears both the sentence and the sorrow","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.245","kind":"speech"},"1.3.246":{"play":"BRABANTIO: That, to pay grief, must of poor patience borrow.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.246","kind":"speech"},"1.3.247":{"play":"BRABANTIO: These sentences to sugar or to gall,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.247","kind":"speech"},"1.3.248":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Being strong on both sides, are equivocal.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.248","kind":"speech"},"1.3.249":{"play":"BRABANTIO: But words are words. I never yet did hear","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.249","kind":"speech"},"1.3.250":{"play":"BRABANTIO: That the bruised heart was piercèd through the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.250","kind":"speech"},"1.3.251":{"play":"BRABANTIO: ear.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.251","kind":"speech"},"1.3.252":{"play":"BRABANTIO: I humbly beseech you, proceed to th’ affairs of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.252","kind":"speech"},"1.3.253":{"play":"BRABANTIO: state.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.253","kind":"speech"},"1.3.254":{"play":"DUKE: The Turk with a most mighty preparation makes","notes":["Johnson: Let your favour privilege me."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.254","kind":"speech"},"1.3.255":{"play":"DUKE: for Cyprus. Othello, the fortitude of the place is","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.255","kind":"speech"},"1.3.256":{"play":"DUKE: best known to you. And though we have there a","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.256","kind":"speech"},"1.3.257":{"play":"DUKE: substitute of most allowed sufficiency, yet opinion, a","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.257","kind":"speech"},"1.3.258":{"play":"DUKE: sovereign mistress of effects, throws a more safer","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.258","kind":"speech"},"1.3.259":{"play":"DUKE: voice on you. You must therefore be content to","notes":["Steevens: That is, obscure. So in the First Part of Jeronimo, 1605: 'The evening, too, begins to slubber day' [p. 74, ed. Dodsley]. Rolfe: This word occurs in Shakespeare only here, and, in the sense of slighting, slurring over, in Mer. of Ven. II, viii, 39: 'slubber not business for my sake.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.259","kind":"speech"},"1.3.260":{"play":"DUKE: slubber the gloss of your new fortunes with this","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.260","kind":"speech"},"1.3.261":{"play":"DUKE: more stubborn and boist’rous expedition.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.261","kind":"speech"},"1.3.262":{"play":"OTHELLO: The tyrant custom, most grave senators,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.262","kind":"speech"},"1.3.263":{"play":"OTHELLO: Hath made the flinty and steel couch of war","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.263","kind":"speech"},"1.3.264":{"play":"OTHELLO: My thrice-driven bed of down. I do agnize","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.264","kind":"speech"},"1.3.265":{"play":"OTHELLO: A natural and prompt alacrity","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.265","kind":"speech"},"1.3.266":{"play":"OTHELLO: I find in hardness, and do undertake","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.266","kind":"speech"},"1.3.267":{"play":"OTHELLO: This present wars against the Ottomites.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.267","kind":"speech"},"1.3.268":{"play":"OTHELLO: Most humbly, therefore, bending to your state,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.268","kind":"speech"},"1.3.269":{"play":"OTHELLO: I crave fit disposition for my wife,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.269","kind":"speech"},"1.3.270":{"play":"OTHELLO: Due reference of place and exhibition,","notes":["Johnson: I desire that proper disposition be made for my wife, that she may have precedency and revenue, accommodation and company, suitable to her rank. I should read preference."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.270","kind":"speech"},"1.3.271":{"play":"OTHELLO: With such accommodation and besort","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.271","kind":"speech"},"1.3.272":{"play":"OTHELLO: As levels with her breeding.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.272","kind":"speech"},"1.3.273":{"play":"DUKE: Why, at her father’s.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.273","kind":"speech"},"1.3.274":{"play":"BRABANTIO: I will not have it so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.274","kind":"speech"},"1.3.275":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nor I.","notes":["Cowden-Clarke: Besitting attendance, proper retinue. Compare 'such men as may besort your age,' Lear, I, iv, 244."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.275","kind":"speech"},"1.3.276":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Nor would I there reside","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.276","kind":"speech"},"1.3.277":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To put my father in impatient thoughts","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.277","kind":"speech"},"1.3.278":{"play":"DESDEMONA: By being in his eye. Most gracious duke,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.278","kind":"speech"},"1.3.279":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To my unfolding lend your prosperous ear","notes":["Booth: Not harshly, but firmly."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.279","kind":"speech"},"1.3.280":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And let me find a charter in your voice","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.280","kind":"speech"},"1.3.281":{"play":"DESDEMONA: T’ assist my simpleness.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.281","kind":"speech"},"1.3.282":{"play":"DUKE: What would you, Desdemona?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.282","kind":"speech"},"1.3.283":{"play":"DESDEMONA: That I love the Moor to live with him","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.283","kind":"speech"},"1.3.284":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My downright violence and storm of fortunes","notes":["Edwards [Canons, &C., p. 144): 'Downright violence,' means the unbridled impetuosity with which her passion hurried her on to this unlawful marriage; and ' storm of fortunes ' may signify the hazard she thereby ran of making shipwreck of her worldly interest.… M. Mason cannot understand the ' storm of fortunes ' with ' fortunes ' in the plural, and asserts that we should read either ' scorn of fortunes,' or ' storm of Fortune,' the latter meaning 'not the injuries of Fortune, but Desdemona's own high-spirited braving of her.' Steevens: The same mistake of scorn for 'storm' occurs in the old copies of Tro. & Cress. I, i, 35: 'as when the sun doth light a scorn.' Dyce [Remarks, &c, p. 234) believes that scorn of the Qto was 'no doubt right;' but as an editor he preferred 'storm.' Hudson: The meaning, probably, is the state or course of life which the speaker has boldly ventured upon in forsaking the peaceful home of her father to share the storms and perils, the violences and hardships, of a warrior's career."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.284","kind":"speech"},"1.3.285":{"play":"DESDEMONA: May trumpet to the world. My heart’s subdued","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.285","kind":"speech"},"1.3.286":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Even to the very quality of my lord.","notes":["Malone: That is, profession. 'I am so much enamoured of Othello, that I am even willing to endure all the inconveniences incident to a military life and to attend him to the wars.' That this is the meaning appears not only from the reading of the Qto: 'even to the utmost pleasure of my lord, i.e. so as to prompt me to go with him wherever he wishes I should go,' but also from the whole tenour of Desdemona's speech, viz: that as she had married a soldier, so she was ready to accompany him to the wars, and to consecrate her soul and fortunes to his honours and his valiant parts; i.e. to attend him wherever his military character and his love of fame should call him."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.286","kind":"speech"},"1.3.287":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I saw Othello’s visage in his mind,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.287","kind":"speech"},"1.3.288":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And to his honors and his valiant parts","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.288","kind":"speech"},"1.3.289":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Did I my soul and fortunes consecrate.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.289","kind":"speech"},"1.3.290":{"play":"DESDEMONA: So that, dear lords, if I be left behind,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.290","kind":"speech"},"1.3.291":{"play":"DESDEMONA: A moth of peace, and he go to the war,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.291","kind":"speech"},"1.3.292":{"play":"DESDEMONA: The rites for why I love him are bereft me","notes":["Warburton: Without question Shakespeare wrote rights, i.e. the right of sharing his dangers with him. Othello tells the Senate: 'She lov'd me for the dangers I had passed,' and she was now desirous of sharing with him what were to come."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.292","kind":"speech"},"1.3.293":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And I a heavy interim shall support","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.293","kind":"speech"},"1.3.294":{"play":"DESDEMONA: By his dear absence. Let me go with him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.294","kind":"speech"},"1.3.295":{"play":"OTHELLO: Let her have your voice.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.295","kind":"speech"},"1.3.296":{"play":"OTHELLO: Vouch with me, heaven, I therefore beg it not","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.296","kind":"speech"},"1.3.297":{"play":"OTHELLO: To please the palate of my appetite,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.297","kind":"speech"},"1.3.298":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nor to comply with heat (the young affects","notes":["Theobald was the first to note the obscurity of this passage, which, as it had been theretofore printed, he pronounced a 'period of as stubborn nonsense as the editors have obtruded upon poor Shakespeare throughout his whole works;' the difficulty lay, he thought, in the word 'defunct,' which 'signifies nothing else either primitively or metaphorically ' than dead; and Othello could not mean to say that ' appetite was dead in him,' because he afterwards says, ' I am declined Into the vale of years; yet that's not much.' Wherefore Theobald changed 'defunct' to distinct, and paraphrased the passage thus: 'I do not beg her company with me, merely to please myself; nor to indulge the heat and affects (i.e. affections) of a new-married man, in my own distinct and proper satisfaction, but to comply with her in her request and desire of accompanying me.' Shakespeare, he adds, uses 'affects' for affections in several other passages which are cited."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.298","kind":"speech"},"1.3.299":{"play":"OTHELLO: In me defunct) and proper satisfaction,","notes":["RANN: disjoined from those with which they are connected in sense, as to form a most lame and impotent conclusion; to say nothing of the awkwardness of using the word 'proper' without any possessive pronoun prefixed to it. All these difficulties are done away by retaining the original word 'my,' and reading disjunct, instead of 'defunct ;' and the meaning will be, 'I ask it not for the sake of my separate and private enjoyment, oy the gratification of appetite, but that I may indulge the wishes of my wife.'","Rann (reading 'the young affect's In me defunct '): 'The tumult of such young desires is at my time of life considerably abated.' Rann here anticipates Gifford, who in his note on the passage in Massinger's Bondman, cited by Steevens, says: '\"Affects\" occurs incessantly in the sense of passions, affections: \"young affects\" are, therefore, perfectly synonymous with youthful heats. Othello was not an old man, though he had lost the fire of youth; the critics might, therefore, have dismissed that concern for the lady, which they have so delicately communicated for the edification of the rising generation. I would wish the future editors of Shakespeare to consider whether he might not have given affect in the singular (this also is used for passion) to correspond with heat.''","Knight: 'Comply' may be used in the sense of supply, 'affects' are affections, and 'defunct' does not necessarily mean dead. Tyrwhitt considers that 'defunct' may be used in the Latin sense of perfor?Tied. As function has the same Latin root, we would suggest that Shakespeare used 'defunct' for functional, and then the meaning is clear: ' nor to gratify the young affections in my official and individual satisfaction.'","Collier (ed. i): 'In my defunct and proper satisfaction' is merely 'in my own dead satisfaction' or gratification, the youthful passions or 'young affects' being comparatively 'defunct' in him. For the sense, though not for the harmony of the verse, it ought to have run 'for my proper and defunct satisfaction;' and had it so run, we doubt if so much ink would have been spilt and wasted upon it. It requires no proof that 'proper' was often used for own.","Dyce [Remarks, p. 235) apprehends that 'few persons will be satisfied with Collier's explanation; nobody, assuredly, with Knight's,' and then cites the passage already given from Massinger's Bondman, together with one from Fletcher's Fair Maid of the Inn, I, i, first cited by Gifford, to show, as Gifford had already observed, how these lines of Shakespeare were understood by his contemporaries. 'They also show,' adds Dyce, 'that Upton's alteration of \"my\" to me is absolutely necessary.' Both Dyce and Gifford approve of Johnson's explanation.","Collier (ed. ii) gives the lines as they are made to stand in his (MS), thus: ' Nor to comply wi' the young affects of heat (In me defunct) and proper satisfaction.'","Jourdain [Trans. Fhilolog. Soc, i860, p. 139) is anticipated by Tyrwhitt in suggesting that the lines should be transposed, but asserts as 'his firm persuasion that 'defunct' is a misprint for default, meaning 'in my want of appearance, in my absence, and for my own satisfaction.' For the use of default in this sense Jourdain cites several examples.","White (ed. i): Utterly unable either to explain this passage or to suggest in what particular it may be corrupted, I leave it exactly as it appears in the old copies. Of the page after page of comment which has been written upon it, and the several conjectural attempts which have been made to modify it into intelligibility, only Johnson's appears worthy of notice. That Shakespeare, although he may very probably have written 'comply with heat,' wrote 'comply with proper satisfaction,' I think almost impossible.","Bailey (ii, 102) is dissatisfied with all that has been said about this passage, and asserts that nothing can be less felicitous than Johnson's text, wherein the parenthesis and the change of * my ' to ??ie combine 'to ruin the meaning of the speaker, which yet seems plain enough.' ' The epithet \" young \" does not refer, as is generally supposed, to young people or the young, but to the recency of his marriage.'","Bailey proposes to read ' Nor to comply with heat of young affects.' ' Instead of merely \" heat,\" Wheat might be put with advantage and with the probability that it was the original reading. This slight emendation gives to the line clearness, precision, and propriety.' \"Defunct\" is used in its etymological sense to have done with, like \"defunctus laboribus\" of Horace, and by its use here Othello refers to the gratification of his moments of leisure and privacy, when he would be free from the duties of his office. Perhaps, to comprise the same meaning in another single epithet, we could not select a better than unofficial: \"In my unofficial and proper or personal satisfaction.\"'","Keightley {Expositor, p. 300) after citing Upton's reading, asks: 'But can any one produce a single instance of Shakespeare's thus interposing a parenthesis between two substantives connected by a copula, or forming a sentence like that in the parenthesis? and what can be more rugged and disjointed than the whole passage as thus arranged? Would not the following not very violent corrections make the whole more Shakespearian and more harmonious? [See Textual Notes.] \"Distinct and proper \" means separate and peculiar. Distinct, the correction of \"defunct,\" I regard as nearly certain. Its meaning here is separate. \"Sheds stuff 'd with lambs and goats, distinctly kept, Distinct the biggest, the more mean distinct, Distinct the youngest.\"—Chapman, Odyss., ix, 34.'","Daniel [Notes, &c, p. 77): Read: 'heat the young affects—In me defunct but for her satisfaction And to be,' &c.","Hudson adopts this reading with the remark that it seems to him 'one of the happiest emendations ever made of the Poet's text. Nor can the changes be justly termed violent; as forher might easily get misprinted \"proper;\" and such transpositions as and and but are among the commonest of typographical errors.' Daniel interprets 'the young affects' as that 'which affects the young,' in which interpretation he follows Delius, who conceived himself justified therein by Malone, but over which Dyce lifts his hands in wonder at 'what Gifford would have thought if he had lived to read it.","Rolfe: Othello only means that the early impetuosity of youthful passions is past—that he can control them, and is no longer controlled by them.","White (ed. ii) The parenthetic passage is in a very doubtful condition. The confession put into Othello's mouth is the last that a lover would make, and on this occasion, especially after Desdemona's foregoing speech.","Hudson: '\"Defunct\" properly goes with \"heat,\" not with \"affects.\" Othello means simply that the heat of youthful impulse has cooled down, that his passions have become tempered to the rule of judgement.' Hudson agrees with Bailey in thinking that 'with ' should be with the, regarding it as a case of absorption, as in 'Bring her to Try with Maine-course,' Temp. I, i; 'Let's all sink with King,' lb. [Cf. also 'Holds such an enmity with blood of man,' Ham. I, v, 65, and Allen's note in Rom. 6° Jul., p. 429.] Hudson adds, 'that to \"comply with one's own satisfaction\" is not and never was English, as it seems to me.' [Is not this the speech to be expected from Othello after what Desdemona had just said? As there was no alloy of passion in her love for him whose visage she saw in his mind, and to whose honours she had consecrated her soul, so Othello proclaimed that it was for the nobler intercourse of marriage that he wanted Desdemona to accompany him, to be free and bounteous to her mind, not to please the palate of his appetite; and in saying this, he wishes as delicately as possible to intimate that the 'compulsive ardour of ' flaming youth,' as Hamlet calls it, was over for him. This, I think, is the idea which, if we heard the speech on the stage only, we should all gather from it, nor do the various emendations and changes convey any very different meaning. Here then, I think, we may rest. The object of the speaker is attained; he has given us his meaning. As a mere intellectual amusement we may inquire into the passage more curiously, and rearrange the puzzle while retaining the sense; the pleasure and the profit will, by the exercise, accrue to ourselves alone, with but little likelihood of ever heading, except in imagination, a band of converts. Moreover, in the inexplicable passages in Shakespeare, like 'the runaway's eyes,' 'the dram of eale,' 'Vllorxa,' the present passage, and others, after the printers have borne all the obloquy which we can heap upon them, might we not frown a little at Shakespeare himself? He must have written rapidly. Would his fame be seriously impaired or stabbed to the centre, if we cautiously whispered among ourselves that he now and then wrote carelessly?—Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.299","kind":"speech"},"1.3.300":{"play":"OTHELLO: But to be free and bounteous to her mind.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.300","kind":"speech"},"1.3.301":{"play":"OTHELLO: And heaven defend your good souls that you think","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.301","kind":"speech"},"1.3.302":{"play":"OTHELLO: I will your serious and great business scant","notes":["Steevens says, and he has been followed by all editors who have noticed the word, that 'defend' here means to forbid, a meaning which it undoubtedly bears in many passages; but it may be doubted if it be worth while to reject here its ordinary meaning; if it has a military flavour it is certainly not inappropriate to Othello. Abbott gives prevent as its equivalent, which to me is scarcely better than forbid.—Ed. Collier (Notes, &c, p. 451): 'Good souls' become counsels in the (MS). Othello would hardly apply 'good souls' to the Duke and Senators of Venice. [Certainly a plausible emendation, which evidently gave Dyce pause; he advises [Few Notes, p. 149) 'an editor of Shakespeare to weigh it well before he adopts it.' 'What is the meaning,' he asks, 'of \"Heaven defend your counsels?\" adding in parenthesis: 'If \"defend\" be equivalent here, as Steevens supposes, to forbid, the alteration [counsels] must be decidedly wrong.' Ed.]","Abbott, § 368: 'Think' seems used subjunctively, and 'that' as a conjunction, in this passage, i. e. 'that you (should) think.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.302","kind":"speech"},"1.3.303":{"play":"OTHELLO: For she is with me. No, when light-winged toys","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.303","kind":"speech"},"1.3.304":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of feathered Cupid seel with wanton dullness","notes":["Is there any urgent reason for deserting the Ff here? For those, however, who prefer the Qq, Abbott, § 151, gives many examples where For is equivalent to because.—Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.304","kind":"speech"},"1.3.305":{"play":"OTHELLO: My speculative and officed instruments,","notes":["Harting (p. 69): 'Seeling,' consisted in sewing a thread through the upper and under eyelids of a newly-caught hawk to obscure the sight for a time, and accustom her to the hood. Turbervile, in his Booh of Falconrie, 1575, gives the following directions 'how to seele a hawke': 'Take a needle threeded with untwisted thread, and (casting your Hawke) take her by the beake and put the needle through her eye-lidde, not right against the sight of the eye, but somewhat nearer to the beake, because she may see backwards. And you must take good heede that you hurt not the webbe, which is under the eye-lidde, or on the inside thereof. Then put youi needle also through that other eye-lidde, drawing the endes of the thread together, tye them over the beake not with a straight knotte, but cut off the threedes endes neare to the knotte and twist them together in such sorte, that the eye-liddes may be raysed so upwards, that the Hawke may not see at all, and when the threed shall ware loose or untyed, then the Hawke may see somewhat backwardes, which is the cause that the threed is put nearer to the beake. For a Sparrow-hawke should see somewhat backwardes, and a Falcon forwardes. The reas5 is that if the Sparrow-hawke should see forwardes, shee would beat off her feathers or break them when she bateth upon the fist, and seeing the companie of men, or such like, she would bate too much.' Sir Emerson Tennant {Sketches of the Nat. Hist, of Ceylon, p. 246), says: 'Where it [the goshawk] is trained for hawking, it is usual, in lieu of a hood, to darken its eyes by means of a silken thread passed through holes in the eyelids.' This practice of 'seeling,' has happily given way to a great extent to the more merciful use of the hood. [See post, III, iii, 242; also notes on 'seeling night,' Alacb. Ill, ii, 46. Ed.] Wright [Bible Word-Book, s. v. Cieled): The etymology of this word is obscured by the spelling, which seems to connect it with the Fr. ciel, It. cielo, ' a canopy.' To seel or seele a room was to cover it with boards, or wainscotting, like Fr. plancher. To seel the eyes of a hawk or dove (Fr. siller les yeux) was to sew up their eyelids. 'What we now call the ceiling was formerly called the upper-seeling, Fr. sus-lambris, to distinguish it from the seeling or wainscotting on the walls.'—Wedgwood, Diet."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.305","kind":"speech"},"1.3.306":{"play":"OTHELLO: That my disports corrupt and taint my business,","notes":["Malone: 'Speculative instruments,' in Shakespeare's language, are the eyes, and 'active instruments,' the hands and feet. As ' seel ' is here metaphorically used, it applies very properly to the ' speculative instruments;' but foils, of the Qq, agrees better with 'active instruments.' Knight: The modern editors have made up a text between the Qto and Ff. They reject the foils of the Qto, and adopt the 'seel ' of the Ff, while they substitute the active of the Qto for the 'offic'd ' of the Ff. Having accomplished this hocus-pocus, they tell us that speculative instruments are the eyes, and active instruments the hands and feet; that to ' seel ' is to close the eyelids of a bird, which applies very properly to the speculative instruments, but that foils better suits the active. It is their own work they are quarrelling with, and not that of the author. Either reading is good, if they had let it alone. The speculative and active instruments, which are foiled, are the thoughts and the senses; the speculative and offic'd instrument, which is seeled, is the whole man in meditation and in action. When the poet adopted the more expressive word seel, he did not leave the ugly anomaly which the commentators have made. He took the whole man as an instrument, spiritual and material, and metaphorically seeled the perceptions of that instrument. [Cf. 'no speculation in those eyes,' Macb. Ill, iv, 95.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.306","kind":"speech"},"1.3.307":{"play":"OTHELLO: Let housewives make a skillet of my helm,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.307","kind":"speech"},"1.3.308":{"play":"OTHELLO: And all indign and base adversities","notes":["Halliwell: It is unlikely that the poet had any substantial image in his mind when penning this line; but, nevertheless, the following note, communicated by Mr. Fairholt, is an exceedingly curious one: 'The Museum of London Antiquities, formed by C. Roach Smith, F. S. A., furnishes a curious illustration of this passage, proving the custom of so turning an old helmet to use. In this instance a crested Morion of the sixteenth century has been fitted with a hook and chain, and formed into a camp-kettle. It was found in dredging the Thames near the Tower of London.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.308","kind":"speech"},"1.3.309":{"play":"OTHELLO: Make head against my estimation.","notes":["indigne] Dyce [Gloss.): Unworthy, disgraceful."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.309","kind":"speech"},"1.3.310":{"play":"DUKE: Be it as you shall privately determine,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.310","kind":"speech"},"1.3.311":{"play":"DUKE: Either for her stay or going. Th’ affair cries haste,","notes":["Booth: After consultation with the Senators."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.311","kind":"speech"},"1.3.312":{"play":"DUKE: And speed must answer it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.312","kind":"speech"},"1.3.313":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: You must away tonight.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.313","kind":"speech"},"1.3.314":{"play":"OTHELLO: With all my","notes":["Booth: Roderigo shows alarm at this, but Iago quiets him. This must not interfere with the action of the scene, but merely be suggested. In reference to the reading of the Qq, Knight says: It appears to us that the wareful rejection of the speech of Desdemona was a great improvement in the Folio. Collier (ed. ii): It is surely very natural that Desdemona should express surprise at the suddenness of the command, and our persuasion is, that the words were left out in the Folio by accident. White (ed. i): In my judgement Shakespeare probably wrote the passage originally as in the Qq, but modified it from a consciousness that Desdemona had already expressed with sufficient candour the nature of her feelings towards Othello, and that both delicacy and truth of characterization would be gained by suppressing her exclamation."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.314","kind":"speech"},"1.3.315":{"play":"OTHELLO: heart.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.315","kind":"speech"},"1.3.316":{"play":"DUKE: At nine i’ th’ morning here we’ll meet again.","notes":["Booth: Probably the hour of rehearsal in Shakespeare's time."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.316","kind":"speech"},"1.3.317":{"play":"DUKE: Othello, leave some officer behind","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.317","kind":"speech"},"1.3.318":{"play":"DUKE: And he shall our commission bring to you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.318","kind":"speech"},"1.3.319":{"play":"DUKE: With such things else of quality and respect","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.319","kind":"speech"},"1.3.320":{"play":"DUKE: As doth import you.","notes":["As doth] For other instances of singular verbs in relative sentences where the antecedents aie plural, see Abbott, §247; also, 'it is not words that shakes me thus,' IV, i, 5\"; 'they laugh, that winnes,' IV, i, 141; 'you [gods] that stirs,' Lear, II, iv, 271. 313-315: Coleridge (Notes, &c, 250): Compare this with the behaviour of Leontes to his true friend Camillo."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.320","kind":"speech"},"1.3.321":{"play":"OTHELLO: So please your Grace, my","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.321","kind":"speech"},"1.3.322":{"play":"OTHELLO: ancient.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.322","kind":"speech"},"1.3.323":{"play":"OTHELLO: A man he is of honesty and trust.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.323","kind":"speech"},"1.3.324":{"play":"OTHELLO: To his conveyance I assign my wife,","notes":["Rolfe: That is, whatever else your grace shall think needful, &c. For many similar transpositions, see Abbott, §419 a. Cf. 'whiter skin of hers then snow,' V, ii, 6."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.324","kind":"speech"},"1.3.325":{"play":"OTHELLO: With what else needful your good Grace shall think","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.325","kind":"speech"},"1.3.326":{"play":"OTHELLO: To be sent after me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.326","kind":"speech"},"1.3.327":{"play":"DUKE: Let it be so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.327","kind":"speech"},"1.3.328":{"play":"DUKE: Good night to everyone. And, noble","notes":["Warburton: This is a senseless epithet. We should read delighted, i. e. white and fair. Johnson: I should rather read delight or. Delight for delectation or power of pleasing, as it is frequently used. Steevens: The meaning is, if virtue comprehends everything in itself, then your virtuous son-in-law is, of course, beautiful; he has that beauty which delights every one. 'Delighted' for delighting, Shakespeare often uses the active and passive participles indiscriminately. The same sentiment occurs in Twelfth Night, III, iv, 403. Tyrwhitt: 'Delighted' is used for delighting ox delightful in Cymo. V, iv, 102. [In illustration of 'the delighted spirit' in Meas. for Meas. Ill, i, Ritson cites from Sir Thos. Herbert's Relation of Some Years Travels, &c, 1634, p. 104: 'Mirza .... gave a period to his miseries in this world by supping a delighted cup of extreame poyson,' which Walker (Crit., ii, 11) interprets as meaning rendered delicious by the admixture of certain ingredients. Thereupon Walker queries if 'delighted' be not used here in Othello nearly as in Herbert—that is, endowed with delights, deliciis exornata. Delius adopts this interpre* tation, and it is to me also eminently satisfactory both here and in Meas. for Meas.; 'If virtue lacks not beauty that is endowed with every delightsome quality, Then,' &c. Ed.] 323-325: Coleridge (Notes, &c, 251): In real life, how da we look back to little speeches as presentimental of, or contrasted with, an affecting event? Even so, Shakespeare, as secure of being read over and over, of becoming a family friend, provides this passage for his readers and leaves it to them."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.328","kind":"speech"},"1.3.329":{"play":"DUKE: signior,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.329","kind":"speech"},"1.3.330":{"play":"DUKE: If virtue no delighted beauty lack,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.330","kind":"speech"},"1.3.331":{"play":"DUKE: Your son-in-law is far more fair than black.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.331","kind":"speech"},"1.3.332":{"play":"FIRST SENATOR: Adieu, brave Moor, use Desdemona well.","notes":["Lloyd: Thus it is that the Venetian Senate comes to the truth of a matter, and the impression thus gained of its judiciousness gives great emphasis to the parting words of the Senator as he goes out. The words fall on the heart like an omen; it is true, then, that the Senator recognizes as no improbability the ill-treatment of Desdemona by the gallant husband she has chosen for herself at such a sacrifice. Even so, and the words strengthen the sense of separation between the Moorish and the Venetian noble; for addressed by one equal to another, they would justify an answer with the hand at the sword-hilt.","Fechter: Brabantio goes out last, disengaging himself from his daughter, who attempts to kiss his hand; and addressing Othello with threatening irony. Booth: Exeunt Duke and Senators. All bow to them as they pass. Desdemona appeals, in action, to her father."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.332","kind":"speech"},"1.3.333":{"play":"BRABANTIO: Look to her, Moor, if thou hast eyes to see.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.333","kind":"speech"},"1.3.334":{"play":"BRABANTIO: She has deceived her father, and may thee.","notes":["Lloyd: Some critics moralize the fate of Desdemona as punishment for undutiful and ill-assorted marriage, yet the punishment falls quite as severely on the severity of Brabantio,—on his cruelty, we may say, for he is the first,—and out of unnatural pique,—to belie his own daughter's chastity. Morel: Ce premier acte nous a donne jusqu'ici une exposition complete du sujet. Othello, Desdemone, Iago, Cassio, les caracteres de tous les personnages principaux nous sont deja parfaitement connus; tous les faits dont le jeu et les consequences ameneront les peripeties diverses de Taction sont indiques, toutes les donnees du probleme dramatiques sont fixees.—Les deux vers dits par Brabantio sont le prelude d'une phase nouvelle de l'intrigue: ils nous font pressentir les suites tragiques de ces amour sur lesquilles pese des la premiere heure la malediction d'un pere."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.334","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.3.334":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.334","kind":"stage"},"1.3.335":{"play":"OTHELLO: My life upon her faith!","notes":["Johnson: Fairest opportunity."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.335","kind":"speech"},"1.3.336":{"play":"OTHELLO: Honest Iago,","notes":["Guizot: C'est justement le contraire de ce que Voltaire a fait dire a Orosmane cet autre jaloux, dans Zaire: 'Je vais donner une heure aux soins de mon empire Et le reste du jour sera tout a Zaire.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.336","kind":"speech"},"1.3.337":{"play":"OTHELLO: My Desdemona must I leave to thee.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.337","kind":"speech"},"1.3.338":{"play":"OTHELLO: I prithee let thy wife attend on her,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.338","kind":"speech"},"1.3.339":{"play":"OTHELLO: And bring them after in the best advantage.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.339","kind":"speech"},"1.3.340":{"play":"OTHELLO: Come, Desdemona, I have but an hour","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.340","kind":"speech"},"1.3.341":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of love, of worldly matters, and direction","notes":["The despairing emphasis laid on this word shows, I think, why it is used* and n« * shall.—Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.341","kind":"speech"},"1.3.342":{"play":"OTHELLO: To spend with thee. We must obey the time.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.342","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.3.342.1":{"play":"[Othello and Desdemona exit.]","notes":["incontinently] Rolfe: Immediately; used by Shakespeare here only; see 'incontinent,' IV, iii, 16, in the same sense. Morel: Le mot, employe par Montaigne et Amyot, a ete introduit en anglais par les ecrivains du XVIe siecle, mais ne s'est pas impose a l'usage."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.342.1","kind":"stage"},"1.3.343":{"play":"RODERIGO: Iago—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.343","kind":"speech"},"1.3.344":{"play":"IAGO: What sayst thou, noble heart?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.344","kind":"speech"},"1.3.345":{"play":"RODERIGO: What will I do, think’st thou?","notes":["Gentleman] Booth: Tapping him playfully on the forehead. Roderigo is a gentleman, though a silly one, not a 'stage-idiot.'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.345","kind":"speech"},"1.3.346":{"play":"IAGO: Why, go to bed and sleep.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.346","kind":"speech"},"1.3.347":{"play":"RODERIGO: I will incontinently drown myself.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.347","kind":"speech"},"1.3.348":{"play":"IAGO: If thou dost, I shall never love thee after. Why,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.348","kind":"speech"},"1.3.349":{"play":"IAGO: thou silly gentleman!","notes":["Malone: From this, Iago's age may be ascertained; and it corresponds with the account in the novel on which Othello is founded, where he is described as a young, handsome man. [Le Tourneur having said in his translation: Jago pouvoit avoir environ quarante ans; les annees qu'il compte sont celles de l'experience, Malone replies:] that Iago meant to say he was but twenty-eight years old is clearly ascertained by his marking particularly, though indefinitely, a period within that time [' and since I could distinguish,' &c] when he began to make observations on the characters of men. Verplanck: The actors who have been most celebrated in the part, from Quin to Cooke, are understood to have represented Iago as at least a middle-aged man. Yet the incident of Iago's youth seems to add much to the individuality and intensity of the character. An old soldier of acknowledged merit, who, after years of service, see^ a young man like Cassio placed over his head, has not a little to plead in justification of deep resentment, and in excuse, though not in defence, of his revenge; such a man may well brood over imaginary wrongs. The caustic sarcasm and contemptuous estimate of mankind are, at least, pardonable in a soured and disappointed veteran. But in a young man the revenge is more purely gratuitous, the hypocrisy, the knowledge, and dexterous management of the worst and weakest parts of human nature, the recklessness of moral feeling,—even the stern, bitter wit, intellectual and contemptuous, without any of the gayety of youth,—are all precocious and peculiar; separating Iago from the ordinary sympathies of our nature, and investing him with higher talent and blacker guilt. Cowden-Clarke: It is remarkable that Shakespeare has here taken pains to specify the exact age of Iago, as he has specified that of Hamlet. They are, perhaps, the two most intellectual characters that our poet has drawn; and he has made them nearly of the same age, as if at that period of life a man's intellect were at the culminating point of activity and energy Iag° is a hard, cold-blooded, almost vivacious scoundrel from inherent disposition, who uses his keen intellect with the )ame fierce joy in its skill and power to destroy that he uses his sharp dagger or sword. Hudson (Introd., p. 22): Moreover Iago's youth goes far to explain the trust which othi.rs repose in him; they cannot suspect one so young of being either skilled in villainous craft or soured by hard experience of the world; while his polished manners and winning address gain him the credit of superior parts, without breeding any question of his truth."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.349","kind":"speech"},"1.3.350":{"play":"RODERIGO: It is silliness to live, when to live is torment,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.350","kind":"speech"},"1.3.351":{"play":"RODERIGO: and then have we a prescription to die when death is","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.351","kind":"speech"},"1.3.352":{"play":"RODERIGO: our physician.","notes":["Gynney Hen] Steevens: Anciently the cant term for a prostitute."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.352","kind":"speech"},"1.3.353":{"play":"IAGO: O, villainous! I have looked upon the world for","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.353","kind":"speech"},"1.3.354":{"play":"IAGO: four times seven years, and since I could distinguish","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.354","kind":"speech"},"1.3.355":{"play":"IAGO: betwixt a benefit and an injury, I never found","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.355","kind":"speech"},"1.3.356":{"play":"IAGO: man that knew how to love himself. Ere I would say","notes":["Coleridge [Notes, 251): This speech comprises the passionless character of Iago. It is all will in intellect; and therefore he is here a bold partisan of a truth, but yet of a truth converted into a falsehood by the absence of all the necessary modifications caused by the frail nature of man. And then comes the last sentiment: 'Our raging motions, our carnal stings, our unbitted lusts, whereof I take this that you call—love to be a sect or scion!' Here is the true Iagoism of, alas! how many! Note Iago's pride of mastery in the repetition of 'Go, make money!' to his anticipated dupe, even stronger than his love of lucre; and when Roderigo is completely won—'I am chang'd. I'll go sell all my land,' when the effect has been fully produced, the repetition of triumph—'Go to; farewell; put money enough in your purse!'"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.356","kind":"speech"},"1.3.357":{"play":"IAGO: I would drown myself for the love of a guinea hen, I","notes":["thus, or thus] Booth: Qy. Point up and down, to signify good or bad f","our Gardens] In his first ed. White considered 'our' an inteqiolation of the printers, due to the recurrence of the same word twice elsewhere in this clause of the sentence."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.357","kind":"speech"},"1.3.358":{"play":"IAGO: would change my humanity with a baboon.","notes":["Ellacombe (p. 136): We have two native species (Urtica urens and U. dioica). 'Nettle,' etymologically, is the same word as needle, and the plant is so named not for its stinging properties, but because at one time it supplied the chief aid to sewing; not in the little familiar instrument, but in the thread, and very good linen it made. In many parts of England the young shoots are boiled and much relished as food, and M. Soyer tried hard, but almost in vain, to introduce it as a most dainty dish. In other points the nettle is a most interesting plant. Microscopists find in it most beautiful objects; entomologists value it as a favourite of butterflies and other insects, of which in Britain alone upwards of thirty varieties feed solely on the nettle-plant, and it marks the progress of civilization by following man wherever he goes. But as a garden plant the only advice to be given is to keep it out of the garden by every means, where, if allowed, it would soon become a sad weed."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.358","kind":"speech"},"1.3.359":{"play":"RODERIGO: What should I do? I confess it is my shame","notes":["Ellacombe (p. 106): This excellent vegetable with its Latin name came to us, probably, from the Romans. It was cultivated by the Anglo-Saxons, who, in recognition of its narcotic qualities, called it ' Sleepwort.' In Shakespeare's time the sorts cultivated were very similar to ours, and probably as good.","Ellacombe (p. 97): The Hyssopus officinalis is not a British plant, but it was held in high esteem in Shakespeare's time. It is now very little cultivated it has not much beauty, and its medicinal properties are not much esteemed; yet it will always have an interest to readers of the Bible, though whether or not the hyssop of Scripture is the Hyssopus offic. is still a question. It seems likely from the following passage in Lyly's Euphues, that the plants were not named at random by Iago: 'Good gardeiners, in their curious knots, mixe Hisoppe with Time, as ayders the one to the growth of the other; the one beeing drye, the other moyst ' [p. 37, ed. Arber].","Ellacombe (p. 233): It is one of the most curious of the curiosities of English plant names that the Wild Thyme,—a plant so common and so widely distributed, and that makes itself so easily known by its fine, aromatic, pungent scent that it is almost impossible to pass it by without notice,—has yet no English name, and never seems to have had one. Thyme is the Anglicized form of the Greek and Latin Thymum, which it probably received from its use as incense in sacrifices; while its other name, serpyllum, refers to its creeping habit. It is another curious point connected with the name that thymum does not occur in the old English vocabularies. Nor is even its Latin form found, except in the Prompt. Parv., where it is ' Tyme, herbe, Tima, timum—Tyme, flowre, Titnus? It is thus a puzzle to know how it can have got naturalized among us, for in .Shakespeare's time it was completely naturalized. It is as a bee-plant especially that the thyme has always been celebrated. See Ovid's Fasti, v; Vergil, Eel. vii. The wild thyme can be scarcely considered a garden plant, except in its variegated and golden varieties; but if it ever should come naturally in the turf, it should be welcomed and cherished for its sweet scent."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.359","kind":"speech"},"1.3.360":{"play":"RODERIGO: to be so fond, but it is not in my virtue to amend it.","notes":["Bucknill [The Medical Knowledge of Shakespeare, p. 270): This word, which with a degree of probability not more overstrained than that which attributes to Shakespeare the knowledge of Harvey's great discovery, by a literal reading would lead to the conclusion that he had anticipated Linnoeus's theory of the sexes of plants. No other author I know of uses the word 'gender' in any other sense than to mark the attributes of sex; while he himself uses it in this sense in several passages, 'the 1 imbers of the genders,' Merry Wives, IV, i, 73. But he also uses it to designate a kind or species, as 'the great love the general gender bear him,' Ham. IV, vii, 18. It is probable, therefore, that it is in this sense the word is used by Iago, and that Shakespeare had not necessarily any idea of the sexual physiology of plants which the great Swedish naturalist developed into a system; and thus also when he refers, in other places, to the sex of plants, that it is merely a poetical metaphor."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.360","kind":"speech"},"1.3.361":{"play":"IAGO: Virtue? A fig! ’Tis in ourselves that we are thus or","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.361","kind":"speech"},"1.3.362":{"play":"IAGO: thus. Our bodies are our gardens, to the which our","notes":["Corrigeable: For many instances of the use of adjectives in able and ible in an active sense, see Walker, Crit., i, 183; Abbott, §3; also Ham. I, i, 57; Leary I, iv, 300. Purnell refers to Milton's use of deceivable in both an active and a passive sense, ' what not in man Deceivable and vain,' Sams. Agon. [349]; ' blind, and thereby Deceivable,' lb. [941]."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.362","kind":"speech"},"1.3.363":{"play":"IAGO: wills are gardeners. So that if we will plant nettles","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.363","kind":"speech"},"1.3.364":{"play":"IAGO: or sow lettuce, set hyssop and weed up thyme,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.364","kind":"speech"},"1.3.365":{"play":"IAGO: supply it with one gender of herbs or distract it","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.365","kind":"speech"},"1.3.366":{"play":"IAGO: with many, either to have it sterile with idleness or","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.366","kind":"speech"},"1.3.367":{"play":"IAGO: manured with industry, why the power and corrigible","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.367","kind":"speech"},"1.3.368":{"play":"IAGO: authority of this lies in our wills. If the balance","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.368","kind":"speech"},"1.3.369":{"play":"IAGO: of our lives had not one scale of reason to poise","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.369","kind":"speech"},"1.3.370":{"play":"IAGO: another of sensuality, the blood and baseness of our","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.370","kind":"speech"},"1.3.371":{"play":"IAGO: natures would conduct us to most prepost’rous","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.371","kind":"speech"},"1.3.372":{"play":"IAGO: conclusions. But we have reason to cool our raging","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.372","kind":"speech"},"1.3.373":{"play":"IAGO: motions, our carnal stings, our unbitted lusts—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.373","kind":"speech"},"1.3.374":{"play":"IAGO: whereof I take this that you call love to be a sect, or","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.374","kind":"speech"},"1.3.375":{"play":"IAGO: scion.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.375","kind":"speech"},"1.3.376":{"play":"RODERIGO: It cannot be.","notes":["Theobald rejected ballance of the Qto as 'certainly wrong,' because it is equivalent to saying, * if the scale of our lives had not one scale,' &c. ; wherefore he believed that the true word is bea?ne, inasmuch as Shakespeare 'generally distinguishes betwixt the Beam and Balance ; using the latter to signify the scales, and the former the steel bar to which they are hung and which poises them.' [Theobald's argument and the examples which he cited in support, especially one from Rich. II : III, iv, S7, where balance signifies scale and nothing else, quite converted Capell, who 'yerked out the following note]: Were beam spelt as of old with an (e) final, it's corruption into the word below is very easy and natural: consider'd then as a true Folio reading, the word beam or beame merits preference that way; and if consider'd another way, as a word absolutely unequivocal, and used often by Shakespeare in the sense that belongs to it, we shall not greatly applaud the gentlemen who discard it for balance. [Theobald overlooked, I think, a notable instance where 'balance' is used for both scales and beam in Mer. of Ven. IV, i, 255: 'Are there balance here to weigh the flesh?' Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.376","kind":"speech"},"1.3.377":{"play":"IAGO: It is merely a lust of the blood and a permission","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.377","kind":"speech"},"1.3.378":{"play":"IAGO: of the will. Come, be a man! Drown thyself? Drown","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.378","kind":"speech"},"1.3.379":{"play":"IAGO: cats and blind puppies. I have professed me thy","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.379","kind":"speech"},"1.3.380":{"play":"IAGO: friend, and I confess me knit to thy deserving","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.380","kind":"speech"},"1.3.381":{"play":"IAGO: with cables of perdurable toughness. I could never","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.381","kind":"speech"},"1.3.382":{"play":"IAGO: better stead thee than now. Put money in thy purse.","notes":["STEEVENS: By modern gardeners calle: a cutting."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.382","kind":"speech"},"1.3.383":{"play":"IAGO: Follow thou the wars; defeat thy favor with an","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.383","kind":"speech"},"1.3.384":{"play":"IAGO: usurped beard. I say, put money in thy purse. It","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.384","kind":"speech"},"1.3.385":{"play":"IAGO: cannot be that Desdemona should long continue","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.385","kind":"speech"},"1.3.386":{"play":"IAGO: her love to the Moor—put money in thy purse—","notes":["hang'd]: See Cotgrave, s. v. Couillatris.—Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.386","kind":"speech"},"1.3.387":{"play":"IAGO: nor he his to her. It was a violent commencement in","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.387","kind":"speech"},"1.3.388":{"play":"IAGO: her, and thou shalt see an answerable sequestration","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.388","kind":"speech"},"1.3.389":{"play":"IAGO: —put but money in thy purse. These Moors are","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.389","kind":"speech"},"1.3.390":{"play":"IAGO: changeable in their wills. Fill thy purse with money.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.390","kind":"speech"},"1.3.391":{"play":"IAGO: The food that to him now is as luscious as locusts","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.391","kind":"speech"},"1.3.392":{"play":"IAGO: shall be to him shortly as bitter as coloquintida.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.392","kind":"speech"},"1.3.393":{"play":"IAGO: She must change for youth. When she is sated","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.393","kind":"speech"},"1.3.394":{"play":"IAGO: with his body she will find the error of her choice.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.394","kind":"speech"},"1.3.395":{"play":"IAGO: Therefore, put money in thy purse. If thou wilt","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.395","kind":"speech"},"1.3.396":{"play":"IAGO: needs damn thyself, do it a more delicate way than","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.396","kind":"speech"},"1.3.397":{"play":"IAGO: drowning. Make all the money thou canst. If sanctimony","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.397","kind":"speech"},"1.3.398":{"play":"IAGO: and a frail vow betwixt an erring barbarian","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.398","kind":"speech"},"1.3.399":{"play":"IAGO: and a supersubtle Venetian be not too hard for my","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.399","kind":"speech"},"1.3.400":{"play":"IAGO: wits and all the tribe of hell, thou shalt enjoy her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.400","kind":"speech"},"1.3.401":{"play":"IAGO: Therefore make money. A pox of drowning thyself!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.401","kind":"speech"},"1.3.402":{"play":"IAGO: It is clean out of the way. Seek thou rather to be","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.402","kind":"speech"},"1.3.403":{"play":"IAGO: hanged in compassing thy joy than to be drowned","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.403","kind":"speech"},"1.3.404":{"play":"IAGO: and go without her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.404","kind":"speech"},"1.3.405":{"play":"RODERIGO: Wilt thou be fast to my hopes if I depend on","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.405","kind":"speech"},"1.3.406":{"play":"RODERIGO: the issue?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.406","kind":"speech"},"1.3.407":{"play":"IAGO: Thou art sure of me. Go, make money. I have","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.407","kind":"speech"},"1.3.408":{"play":"IAGO: told thee often, and I retell thee again and again, I","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.408","kind":"speech"},"1.3.409":{"play":"IAGO: hate the Moor. My cause is hearted; thine hath no","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.409","kind":"speech"},"1.3.410":{"play":"IAGO: less reason. Let us be conjunctive in our revenge","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.410","kind":"speech"},"1.3.411":{"play":"IAGO: against him. If thou canst cuckold him, thou dost","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.411","kind":"speech"},"1.3.412":{"play":"IAGO: thyself a pleasure, me a sport. There are many","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.412","kind":"speech"},"1.3.413":{"play":"IAGO: events in the womb of time which will be delivered.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.413","kind":"speech"},"1.3.414":{"play":"IAGO: Traverse, go, provide thy money. We will have more","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.414","kind":"speech"},"1.3.415":{"play":"IAGO: of this tomorrow. Adieu.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.415","kind":"speech"},"1.3.416":{"play":"RODERIGO: Where shall we meet i’ th’ morning?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.416","kind":"speech"},"1.3.417":{"play":"IAGO: At my lodging.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.417","kind":"speech"},"1.3.418":{"play":"RODERIGO: I’ll be with thee betimes.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.418","kind":"speech"},"1.3.419":{"play":"IAGO: Go to, farewell. Do you hear, Roderigo?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.419","kind":"speech"},"1.3.420":{"play":"RODERIGO: What say you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.420","kind":"speech"},"1.3.421":{"play":"IAGO: No more of drowning, do you hear?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.421","kind":"speech"},"1.3.422":{"play":"RODERIGO: I am changed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.422","kind":"speech"},"1.3.423":{"play":"IAGO: Go to, farewell. Put money enough in your","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.423","kind":"speech"},"1.3.424":{"play":"IAGO: purse.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.424","kind":"speech"},"1.3.425":{"play":"RODERIGO: I’ll sell all my land.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.425","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.3.425":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.425","kind":"stage"},"1.3.426":{"play":"IAGO: Thus do I ever make my fool my purse.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.426","kind":"speech"},"1.3.427":{"play":"IAGO: For I mine own gained knowledge should profane","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.427","kind":"speech"},"1.3.428":{"play":"IAGO: If I would time expend with such a snipe","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.428","kind":"speech"},"1.3.429":{"play":"IAGO: But for my sport and profit. I hate the Moor,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.429","kind":"speech"},"1.3.430":{"play":"IAGO: And it is thought abroad that ’twixt my sheets","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.430","kind":"speech"},"1.3.431":{"play":"IAGO: ’Has done my office. I know not if ’t be true,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.431","kind":"speech"},"1.3.432":{"play":"IAGO: But I, for mere suspicion in that kind,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.432","kind":"speech"},"1.3.433":{"play":"IAGO: Will do as if for surety. He holds me well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.433","kind":"speech"},"1.3.434":{"play":"IAGO: The better shall my purpose work on him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.434","kind":"speech"},"1.3.435":{"play":"IAGO: Cassio’s a proper man. Let me see now:","notes":["Steevens, who has, T think, been uniformly followed, says this is an 'ancient military word of command,' and cites in proof, from 2 Hen. IV: III, ii, 291, Falstaff' s command to Wart after a caliver has been put in Wart's hand, 'Hold, Wart, traverse,' which is clearly the ordinary fencing or musket-drill phrase, and is scarcely parallel with the present passage. Malone cites Bullokar (Eng. Exp., s. v.): 'Trauerse. To march vp and downe, or to moue the feete with proportion as in dancing,' which seems somewhat more appropriate here, but is not altogether satisfactory. L. Booth's Reprint gives a comma after 'Trauerfe. 'Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.435","kind":"speech"},"1.3.436":{"play":"IAGO: To get his place and to plume up my will","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.436","kind":"speech"},"1.3.437":{"play":"IAGO: In double knavery—How? how?—Let’s see.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.437","kind":"speech"},"1.3.438":{"play":"IAGO: After some time, to abuse Othello’s ear","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.438","kind":"speech"},"1.3.439":{"play":"IAGO: That he is too familiar with his wife.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.439","kind":"speech"},"1.3.440":{"play":"IAGO: He hath a person and a smooth dispose","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.440","kind":"speech"},"1.3.441":{"play":"IAGO: To be suspected, framed to make women false.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.441","kind":"speech"},"1.3.442":{"play":"IAGO: The Moor is of a free and open nature","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.442","kind":"speech"},"1.3.443":{"play":"IAGO: That thinks men honest that but seem to be so,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.443","kind":"speech"},"1.3.444":{"play":"IAGO: And will as tenderly be led by th’ nose","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.444","kind":"speech"},"1.3.445":{"play":"IAGO: As asses are.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.445","kind":"speech"},"1.3.446":{"play":"IAGO: I have ’t. It is engendered. Hell and night","notes":["W. N. {Memorials of Sh., p. 356): Shakespeare has shown great judgement in the darkness which he makes to prevail in the first counsels of Iago. To the poet himself all the succeeding events must have been clear and determined; but to bring himself again into the situation of one who sees them in embryo, to draw a mist over that which he had already cleared, must have required an exertion of genius peculiar to this author alone. In so lively a manner does he make Iago show his perplexity about the future management of his conduct, that one is almost tempted to think that the poet had determined as little himself about some of the particulars of Iago's destruction."],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.446","kind":"speech"},"1.3.447":{"play":"IAGO: Must bring this monstrous birth to the world’s light.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"1.3.447","kind":"speech"},"SD_1.3.447.1":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 1.3.447.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 2, SCENE 1":{"SD_2.1.0":{"play":"[Enter Montano and two Gentlemen.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.0","kind":"stage"},"2.1.1":{"play":"MONTANO: What from the cape can you discern at sea?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.1","kind":"speech"},"2.1.2":{"play":"FIRST GENTLEMAN: Nothing at all. It is a high-wrought flood.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.2","kind":"speech"},"2.1.3":{"play":"FIRST GENTLEMAN: I cannot ’twixt the heaven and the main","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.3","kind":"speech"},"2.1.4":{"play":"FIRST GENTLEMAN: Descry a sail.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.4","kind":"speech"},"2.1.5":{"play":"MONTANO: Methinks the wind hath spoke aloud at land.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.5","kind":"speech"},"2.1.6":{"play":"MONTANO: A fuller blast ne’er shook our battlements.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.6","kind":"speech"},"2.1.7":{"play":"MONTANO: If it hath ruffianed so upon the sea,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.7","kind":"speech"},"2.1.8":{"play":"MONTANO: What ribs of oak, when mountains melt on them,","notes":["Theobald: In adopting the Qq, Pope evidently supposed that 'mountains' here referred not to water, but, to land; Theobald showed that Shakespeare refers to 'hills of seas' in this very Scene, line 215, and 'liquid mountains' in Tro. & Cress., and that he had abundance of classical authority for the simile, in Homer, and Vergil and Ovid; and that therefore 'mountains' here refers to waves. Despite this clear exposition, JENNENS, the sturdy follower of Qx , thinks that the sense seems to require either Pope's text or his own, both founded on the Qto. In the mes It of Qx he sees, correctly, a typographical error for melts, and thus interprets the passage: ' If it hath ruffian'd so upon the sea as here at land, where the huge mountain melts away before the storm, what ribs of oak can hold the mortise? Theobald did not consider the impropriety of waves melting; clouds have been said to melt indeed, but never waves that I remember. I don't doubt that Shakespeare had the following passage of Scripture in his eye, \" The mountains melt at the presence of the Lord,\" &c.'"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.8","kind":"speech"},"2.1.9":{"play":"MONTANO: Can hold the mortise? What shall we hear of this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.9","kind":"speech"},"2.1.10":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: A segregation of the Turkish fleet.","notes":["Dyce: [Gloss.): A separation, or dispersion. White (ed. ii) The opposite of congregation; an extraordinary use of the word."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.10","kind":"speech"},"2.1.11":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: For do but stand upon the foaming shore,","notes":["Steevens: The Qto offers the bolder image, i.e. the shore that execrates the ravage of the waves. Delius: Even if banning were erased by Shakespeare and 'foaming' substituted, the former justifies 'chidden' rather than chiding."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.11","kind":"speech"},"2.1.12":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: The chidden billow seems to pelt the clouds,","notes":["Knight: How weak is the chiding billow pelting the clouds! but the billow 'chidden' by the blast is full of beauty. [Both Dyce and Schmidt give to this word in this passage the meaning of 'to sound, to resound, to echo' and 'to be noisy about,' and they refer in support to the Qto. But this definition contains, it seems to me, but a small share of the full definition of 'chidden.' I have searched in vain for a passage in Shakespeare where 'to chide' has the meaning to sound, and that meaning alone; in every instance there is, it seems to me, the essential idea of scolding, brawling, contention in all degrees, from 'chiding as loud as thunder' to 'the sweet chiding of well-tuned sounds.' The 'gallant chiding' which Hippolyta [Mid. Ar . D. IV, i, 120] heard when Hercules and Cadmus bayed the bear in a wood in Crete, applies, I think, to the hunters scolding, urging on, the hounds; which Hippolyta afterward calls a 'musical discord;' the 'discord' was the brawling of the hunters, the hounds, their followers, and the bear; the 'music' was the softened echoes of it all from ' the skies, the fountains, every region near.' The essential idea of 'chiding' is there not merely 'sound.' The 'chiding nativity' of Marina {.Per. Ill, i, 32) was the rude, brawling welcome to the world given tc her by the contest of ' fire, air, water earth, and Heaven.' Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.12","kind":"speech"},"2.1.13":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: The wind-shaked surge, with high and monstrous","notes":["Knight: What is ' high and monstrous main '? We use the word main elliptically; for the main sea, the great sea, as Shakespeare uses it, in * 'twixt the heaven and the main.' The main is the ocean. Substitute that word, and what can we make of the passage before us ? ' the wind-shak'd surge with high and monstrous ocean.' But adopt the word mane, and it appears to us we have as fine an image as any in Shakespeare. It is more striking even than the passage in Hen. IV. 1—the winds, Who take the ruffian billows by the top, Curling their monstrous heads.' In the high and monstrous mane we have a picture which was probably suggested by the noble passage in Job : ' Hast thou given the horse strength ? Hast thou clothed his neck with thunder?' One of the biblical commentators upon this passage remarks, that Homer and Vergil mention the mane of the horse; but that the sacred author, by the bold figure of thunder, expresses the shaking of the mane, and the flakes of hair which suggest the idea of lightning. The horse of Job is the war-horse, ' who swalloweth the ground with fierceness and rage ;' and when Shakespeare pictured to himself his mane wildly streaming, 'when the quiver rattleth against him, the glittering spear and the shield,' he saw an image of the fury of the ' wind-shak'd surge,' and of its very form; and he painted it with 'high and monstrous mane.'"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.13","kind":"speech"},"2.1.14":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: mane,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.14","kind":"speech"},"2.1.15":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: Seems to cast water on the burning Bear","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.15","kind":"speech"},"2.1.16":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: And quench the guards of th’ ever-fixèd pole.","notes":["Johnson: Alluding to the star Arctophylax. Steevens: I wonder that none of the advocates of Shakespeare's learning have observed that Arctophylax literally signifies 'the guard of the Bear.' J. F. Marsh (A 7 \". 6° Qu., 1877, 5th, viii, 83): Both Johnson and Steevens are in error; and Shakespeare knew better than his commentators what he was talking about when he spoke of the guards of the pole, and not of the guard of the Bear. Arctophylax is not a synonym for the star Arcturus, but for the constellation Bootes; and the Bear, of which he is the guard, or rather keeper, is not the Little Bear, of which Polaris is the lucida, but the Great Bear, as will be evident in the most cursory glance at a celestial globe. Arctophylax, whether it mean the star or the constellation, has no connection with the Polar guards. They are the two stars /3 and y Ursae Minoris, on the shoulder and foreleg of the Little Bear, as usually depicted, or sometimes on the ear and shoulder. They were more observed in Shakespeare's time than now for the purposes of navigation. Norman's Safeguard of Sailers, 1 587, has a chapter, ' Howe to knowe the houre of the night by the Guards,' &c. They were even made the subject of mechanical contrivances for facilitating calculation, one of which is described in The Arte of Navigation, trans, by Richard Eden from the Spanish of Martin Curtis (or Cortez), 1561, consisting of fixed and movable concentric circles with holes, through which to observe 'the two starres called the Guardians, or the mouth of the home.' Further details will be found in Admiral Smyth's Cycle of Celestial Objects, ii, 331, where is also cited Tap's Seaman's Grammar, 1609, 'containing still more upon the Guards;' and Hood's Use of the Celestial Globe, 1590, deriving the name 'from the Spanish word guardare, which is to beholde, because they are diligently to be looked unto, in regard of the singular use which they have in navigation.' Shakespeare probably meant to include in the Guards all the three stars [i.e. /3 and y Ursae Minoris, and Polaris] required for the observations above noticed. Otherwise in describing a tempest which seemed to cast water on one constellation, and quench two of the principal stars of another, he could scarcely have avoided mentioning the third star, the brightest and most important of the three."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.16","kind":"speech"},"2.1.17":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: I never did like molestation view","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.17","kind":"speech"},"2.1.18":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: On the enchafèd flood.","notes":["There is an unusual number, in this Scene, of words with the prefix en: enshelter'd, embay'd, ensteep'd, enclogge, enwhcele. In Scene iii, enfetterd, enmesh; in IV, i, encave. For this usage elsewhere, see Abbott, § 440."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.18","kind":"speech"},"2.1.19":{"play":"MONTANO: If that the Turkish fleet","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.19","kind":"speech"},"2.1.20":{"play":"MONTANO: Be not ensheltered and embayed, they are drowned.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.20","kind":"speech"},"2.1.21":{"play":"MONTANO: It is impossible to bear it out.","notes":["Hunter (Disq. on The Tempest, p. 134) condemns the substitution of the modern spelling in this word as a loss in melody in the lines he cites from The Tempest, and implies that we should throughout the plays retain the old word. 'These are but niceties (he says), but poetry is a luxury, and should therefore be as refined and perfect as possible.' 'The reason for the substitution is evident. \"Wrack\" has in a great measure gone out of use, though we still use the familiar phrase \" wrack and ruin.\" But \"wrack\" continued in use long after Shakespeare, and cannot have been, by any means, extinct in the days of Rowe.' [For four instances from V. &> A., A', of L., and the Sonn., where the rhyme will not permit the substitution of wreck, see Mrs Furness's Concordance, s. v. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.21","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.21.1":{"play":"[Enter a third Gentleman.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.21.1","kind":"stage"},"2.1.22":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: News, lads! Our wars are done.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.22","kind":"speech"},"2.1.23":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: The desperate tempest hath so banged the Turks","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.23","kind":"speech"},"2.1.24":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: That their designment halts. A noble ship of Venice","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.24","kind":"speech"},"2.1.25":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: Hath seen a grievous wrack and sufferance","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.25","kind":"speech"},"2.1.26":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: On most part of their fleet.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.26","kind":"speech"},"2.1.27":{"play":"MONTANO: How? Is this true?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.27","kind":"speech"},"2.1.28":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: The ship is here put in,","notes":["Theobald, by simply altering the punctuation, was the first to make this refer to the ship and not to Cassio, ' who was no Veronese,' says Theobald in his ed. i; ' but we find from other passages in the play he was of Rome ' (withdrawn in ed. ii). 'The vessel properly belonged to Verona, but was in the service of Venice.' Heath: Shakespeare had no ship in his thoughts, but intended to inform us that Cassio was of Verona, an inland city of the Venetian State. The word Veronese should be pronounced after the Italian manner as a quadrisyllable. T. Warton: It was common to introduce Italian words, and in their proper pronunciation then familiar; see Faerie Queene, III, xii, 90: 'And sleeues dependant Albanese-wyse? The ship was a Veronese, just as we now say a Hamburgher. Cassio was a Florentine. In this speech the Third Gentleman, who brings the news of the wreck of the Turkish fleet, returns to the tale, and tells the circumstances more distinctly. In his former speech he speaks of ' a noble ship of Venice,' and now he adds: ' The very ship is just now put into port, and she is a VeroneseV That is, a ship fitted out or furnished by the people of Verona, a city of the Venetian State. Steevens: I believe we are all wrong. Verona is an inland city. Every inconsistency may, however, be avoided if we read The Veronessa, i. e. the name of the ship is the Veronessa. [While all the critics thus far had stated that Verona was tributary to Venice, yet, having cited no authority, they had apparently drawn the fact from the depths of their consciousness it was reserved for Malone to justify the assertion in a note, which is the only one from the mass that Dyce quotes, as follows :] ' Besides many other towns (says Contareno), castles, and villages, they [the Venetians] possess seven faire cities ; as Trevigi, Padoua, Vicenza, Verona, Brescia, Bergamo, and Crema.' Commonwealth of Venice, 1599. Knight retains the Veronessa, because 'as a feminine it is applicable to a ship.' Collier: The Third Gentleman has already said that the ship was ' of Venice,' and it is not likely that he would assert just afterwards that she was a 'Veronese;' it seems much more probable that he would by mistake call Cassio, whom he did not know, a ' Veronese.' Singer: Whether a Veronessa signified a ship fitted out by Verona, or designated some particular kind of vessel, is not yet fully established. But as it has not hitherto been met with elsewhere, the former is most probably the true explanation. White (ed. i): There is difficulty in either reading; but of the two errors, one of which it is necessary to suppose on Shakespeare's part, a momertary forgetfulness appears the more probable. Keightley {Exp., 301): Another instance of the poet's negligence or forgetfulness Though the metre is perfect, it might be better to insert nam\" J or one. It is not likely that the ship was called 'the Veronessa? Daniel (p. 78): Read: 'The ship is here r»ut in, | \" La Veronesa:\" Michael Cassio, | Lieutenant,' &c. Hudson adopts Daniel's suggestion. Rolfe agrees with White that the confusion is perhaps due to a momentary forgetfulness on Shakespeare's part. Til. ELZE (Sh. Jahrbuch, xiv, 1 76): The word is clearly corrupt, but F x puts us on the right track. Let the true word be ' verrinessa,' and the changes, due to editorial lack of knowledge, through ' verennessa ' and * Veronessa ' to ' Veronese ' are easily understood. Now although I cannot at the moment give an Italian authority for the noun ' verinessa,' yet there is the word ' verrina ' and the verb ' verrinare,' which is an old nautical term and still in use, equivalent in meaning to tenebrare, perforare, traforare, that is, to ' cut through,' to ' cleave,' like the French percer. Wherefore the • noble ship of Venice ' was a verrinessa, * un perceflot.' [Is not this the exact equivalent of the nautical term ' cutter ' ? If only an instance of the use of the Italian word could be produced, this vexed question would be settled for ever. As it is, Th. Elze's explanation seems far more satisfactory than any other ; but if a supersubtle compositor forces us to choose between a lack of memory on Shakespeare's part and a lack of geographical information, I prefer the latter. The nationality of a chance ship, mentioned once and never again, is of less moment than the nationality of an important •cnaracter ; the same wind that can blow a ship to Aleppo can waft one from Verona. Furthermore, how in the wild excitement of the moment could the Third Gentleman find out from what city of Italy Cassio came ? That he was the lieutenant to the warlike Moor might be revealed at a glance by some distinctive decoration of his dress, such as the scarf of company, which always bore the Captain's colours. Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.28","kind":"speech"},"2.1.29":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: A Veronesa. Michael Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.29","kind":"speech"},"2.1.30":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: Lieutenant to the warlike Moor Othello,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.30","kind":"speech"},"2.1.31":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: Is come on shore; the Moor himself at sea,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.31","kind":"speech"},"2.1.32":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: And is in full commission here for Cyprus.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.32","kind":"speech"},"2.1.33":{"play":"MONTANO: I am glad on ’t. ’Tis a worthy governor.","notes":["For many other instances of the omission of the, see Abbott, § 89."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.33","kind":"speech"},"2.1.34":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: But this same Cassio, though he speak of comfort","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.34","kind":"speech"},"2.1.35":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: Touching the Turkish loss, yet he looks sadly","notes":["Theobald, by simply altering the punctuation, was the first to make this refer to the ship and not to Cassio, ' who was no Veronese,' says Theobald in his ed. i; ' but we find from other passages in the play he was of Rome ' (withdrawn in ed. ii). 'The vessel properly belonged to Verona, but was in the service of Venice.' Heath: Shakespeare had no ship in his thoughts, but intended to inform us that Cassio was of Verona, an inland city of the Venetian State. The word Veronese should be pronounced after the Italian manner as a quadrisyllable. T. Warton: It was common to introduce Italian words, and in their proper pronunciation then familiar; see Faerie Queene, III, xii, 90: 'And sleeues dependant Albanese-wyse? The ship was a Veronese, just as we now say a Hamburgher. Cassio was a Florentine. In this speech the Third Gentleman, who brings the news of the wreck of the Turkish fleet, returns to the tale, and tells the circumstances more distinctly. In his former speech he speaks of ' a noble ship of Venice,' and now he adds: ' The very ship is just now put into port, and she is a VeroneseV That is, a ship fitted out or furnished by the people of Verona, a city of the Venetian State. Steevens: I believe we are all wrong. Verona is an inland city. Every inconsistency may, however, be avoided if we read The Veronessa, i. e. the name of the ship is the Veronessa."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.35","kind":"speech"},"2.1.36":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: And prays the Moor be safe, for they were parted","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.36","kind":"speech"},"2.1.37":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: With foul and violent tempest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.37","kind":"speech"},"2.1.38":{"play":"MONTANO: Pray heaven he be;","notes":["Unless this means ‘for Cyprus, here,’ it is not easy to explain it. Daniel’s emendation perfects the sense, but the ductus literarum is against it.—Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.38","kind":"speech"},"2.1.39":{"play":"MONTANO: For I have served him, and the man commands","notes":["John Hunter: Montano would be well pleased to resign the post in a time of so great peril to such a man as Othello, under whom he had served."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.39","kind":"speech"},"2.1.40":{"play":"MONTANO: Like a full soldier. Let’s to the seaside, ho!","notes":["Walker (Crit., iii, 286): Wheel for circle is not altogether unfrequent in the old dramatists. Cf. ‘Heaven’s grace in-wheel you, And all good thoughts and prayers dwell about you.’—B. and F. The Pilgrim, I, ii, p. 17, ed. Dyce."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.40","kind":"speech"},"2.1.41":{"play":"MONTANO: As well to see the vessel that’s come in","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.41","kind":"speech"},"2.1.42":{"play":"MONTANO: As to throw out our eyes for brave Othello,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.42","kind":"speech"},"2.1.43":{"play":"MONTANO: Even till we make the main and th’ aerial blue","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.43","kind":"speech"},"2.1.44":{"play":"MONTANO: An indistinct regard.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.44","kind":"speech"},"2.1.45":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: Come, let’s do so;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.45","kind":"speech"},"2.1.46":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: For every minute is expectancy","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.46","kind":"speech"},"2.1.47":{"play":"THIRD GENTLEMAN: Of more arrivance.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.47","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.47.1":{"play":"[Enter Cassio.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.47.1","kind":"stage"},"2.1.48":{"play":"CASSIO: Thanks, you the valiant of this warlike isle,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.48","kind":"speech"},"2.1.49":{"play":"CASSIO: That so approve the Moor! O, let the heavens","notes":["A typographical error, in the omission of ‘to’, begun in Reed's Var. of 1803, was continued in the Var. of 1813, of 1821, and in Singer’s ed. i. The line thus mutilated, and almost painfully prosaic, was accepted as complete by Guest (i, 239), and thus bravely scanned: ‘As | throw out | our eyes | : for brave | Othel | lo.’ Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.49","kind":"speech"},"2.1.50":{"play":"CASSIO: Give him defense against the elements,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.50","kind":"speech"},"2.1.51":{"play":"CASSIO: For I have lost him on a dangerous sea.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.51","kind":"speech"},"2.1.52":{"play":"MONTANO: Is he well shipped?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.52","kind":"speech"},"2.1.53":{"play":"CASSIO: His bark is stoutly timbered, and his pilot","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.53","kind":"speech"},"2.1.54":{"play":"CASSIO: Of very expert and approved allowance;","notes":["Steevens: This is put for ‘allow’d and approv’d expertness.’ [For a list of similar expressions where the relations of adjectives and their nouns seem inverted, like ‘paly ashes’, ‘shady stealth,’ &c. see the excellent Grammatical Obs. on p. 1417 of Schmidt's Lex.—Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.54","kind":"speech"},"2.1.55":{"play":"CASSIO: Therefore my hopes, not surfeited to death,","notes":["Johnson: I do not understand these lines. I know not how hope can be surfeited to death, that is, can be increased, till it be destroyed; nor what it is, 'to stand in bold cure;' or why hope should be considered a disease. Shall we read: ‘Therefore my fears, not surfeited to death’ ? &c. This is better, but it is not well. Shall we strike a bolder stroke, and read thus: 'Therefore my hopes, not forfeited to death, Stand bold, not sure' ? Jennens: Wishes may be called the food upon which hope is very apt to surfeit ; and to surfeit to death too, when there is no ground or foundation to expect the thing hoped for. Hope is in perfect health where the grounds for it are equal to the wish ; but if the wish preponderate the grounds of expectation, hope is in a sickly state. This was the case with Cassio ; his wishes for Othello's safety were greater than the probability of it, for he had left him on a dangerous sea ; so his hope was sick ; but not sick to death, because the ship had a good pilot ; this thought physicked hope, and put it in a bold state of cure. Steevens: Presumptuous hopes, which have no foundation in probability, may poetically be said to surfeit themselves to death, or forward their own dissolution. 'In bold cure' means in confidence of being cured. Malone: It is not hope which is here described as the disease ; those misgiving apprehensions which diminish hope are, in fact, the disease, and hope itself is the patient. Henley: I believe that Solomon upon this occasion will be found the best interpreter: 'Hope deferred maketh the heart sick.' Knight: Hope upon hope, without realization, is- a surfeit of hope and extinguishes hope. Cassio had some reasonable facts to prevent his hope being 'surfeited to death.' Collier: The meaning seems to be, that Cassio's hopes are not destroyed by constant repetition and disappointment. Singer: Therefore my hopes, not surfeited to death by excess of apprehension, stand in confidence of being cured. Staunton (Note on Ant. & Cleo. II, i, 38): As in our early language to expect most commonly meant to stay or wait, so to hope on some occasions was used where we should now adopt to expect. (Note on present passage): 'Hopes' here are expectations or presentiments. Cowden-Clarke: My hopes, not having been utterly destroyed by reiterated false excitement and successive defeat, remain in confident expectation of being fulfilled. Hudson: Cassio, though anxious, does not despair; and the meaning of ‘stand in bold cure’ seems to be, ‘my hopes, though near dying, stay themselves upon, or are kept alive by, bold conjecture;’ or, it may be, ‘are confident of being cured.’ I was for a while in doubt whether to read ‘not suffocate to death’ or ‘not sick yet unto death;’ but on the whole preferred the former as involving somewhat less of change, and as being perhaps rather more in Shakespeare's manner. D'Hugues: Il est clair cependant que les esperances s'ajoutant aux esperances, sans etre jamais realisees, constituent un trop plein (surfeit) d'esperances, qui fait evanouir toute esperance. C'est la meme chose que Moliere a voulu dire dans le fameux sonnet d'Oronte : Belle Philis, on desespere Alors qu'on espere toujours. [These paraphrases are all of them intelligible, and would be entirely satisfactory could we only forget the text, which as it now stands is unintelligible to me, and I am willing to ' say ditto to' Dr. Johnson. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.55","kind":"speech"},"2.1.56":{"play":"CASSIO: Stand in bold cure.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.56","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.56.1":{"play":"[Voices cry within. A sail, a sail, a sail!]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.56.1","kind":"stage"},"SD_2.1.56.2":{"play":"[Enter a Messenger.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.56.2","kind":"stage"},"2.1.57":{"play":"CASSIO: What noise?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.57","kind":"speech"},"2.1.58":{"play":"MESSENGER: The town is empty; on the brow o’ th’ sea","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.58","kind":"speech"},"2.1.59":{"play":"MESSENGER: Stand ranks of people, and they cry","notes":["Steevens: I believe Qx has the true reading here, as in Love's Lab. IV, i, 127. [To the same effect, Staunton. See Bishop Percy's Folio MS., vol. iv. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.59","kind":"speech"},"2.1.60":{"play":"CASSIO: My hopes do shape him for the Governor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.60","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.60.1":{"play":"[A shot.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.60.1","kind":"stage"},"2.1.61":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: They do discharge their shot of courtesy.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.61","kind":"speech"},"2.1.62":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: Our friends, at least.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.62","kind":"speech"},"2.1.63":{"play":"CASSIO: I pray you, sir, go forth,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.63","kind":"speech"},"2.1.64":{"play":"CASSIO: And give us truth who ’tis that is arrived.","notes":["Warburton: It is plain that something very hyperbolical was here intended. But what is there as it stands? Why this, that in the essence of creation she bore all excellency. The expression is intolerable, and could never come from one who so well understood the force of words as our Poet. The essential vesture is the same as essential form. So that the expression is nonsense. For the vesture of creation signifies the forms in which created beings are cast. And essence relates not to the form, but to the matter. Shakespeare certainly wrote: 'And in terrestrial vesture,' &c. And in this lay the wonder, that all created excellence should be contained within an earthly mortal form. Heath (p. 559): I entirely agree with Warburton that the common reading is indefensible I should rather suspect that the poet wrote 'And in the sensual vesture,' &c. The sense is, And within that vesture of the human senses with which she is clothed by the Creator she is endued with every excellency. Johnson: I do not think ' essential ' inexplicable; it seems to be used for existent, real. She excels the praises of invention says he, and in real qualities with which creation has invested her bears all excellency. I explain thus: Does tire the ingenious verse. This is the best reading, and that which the author substituted in his revisal."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.64","kind":"speech"},"2.1.65":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: I shall.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.65","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.65":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.65","kind":"stage"},"2.1.66":{"play":"MONTANO: But, good lieutenant, is your general wived?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.66","kind":"speech"},"2.1.67":{"play":"CASSIO: Most fortunately. He hath achieved a maid","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.67","kind":"speech"},"2.1.68":{"play":"CASSIO: That paragons description and wild fame,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.68","kind":"speech"},"2.1.69":{"play":"CASSIO: One that excels the quirks of blazoning pens,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.69","kind":"speech"},"2.1.70":{"play":"CASSIO: And in th’ essential vesture of creation","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.70","kind":"speech"},"2.1.71":{"play":"CASSIO: Does tire the ingener.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.71","kind":"speech"},"2.1.72":{"play":"CASSIO: How now? Who has put in?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.72","kind":"speech"},"2.1.73":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: ’Tis one Iago, ancient to the General.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.73","kind":"speech"},"2.1.74":{"play":"CASSIO: ’Has had most favorable and happy speed!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.74","kind":"speech"},"2.1.75":{"play":"CASSIO: Tempests themselves, high seas, and howling winds,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.75","kind":"speech"},"2.1.76":{"play":"CASSIO: The guttered rocks and congregated sands","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.76","kind":"speech"},"2.1.77":{"play":"CASSIO: (Traitors ensteeped to clog the guiltless keel),","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.77","kind":"speech"},"2.1.78":{"play":"CASSIO: As having sense of beauty, do omit","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.78","kind":"speech"},"2.1.79":{"play":"CASSIO: Their mortal natures, letting go safely by","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.79","kind":"speech"},"2.1.80":{"play":"CASSIO: The divine Desdemona.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.80","kind":"speech"},"2.1.81":{"play":"MONTANO: What is she?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.81","kind":"speech"},"2.1.82":{"play":"CASSIO: She that I spake of, our great captain’s captain,","notes":["Ha's: An instance of the absorption of the personal pronoun, similar to that of 'it' in I, iii, 220. Dyce in his last edition has indicated this. Schmidt in his admirable translation thus renders this line: 'Er stand in eines guten Engels Schutz,' and pleads for it thus: If we consider the meaning of this line in connection with what follows it is evident that there must be some reference to Desdemona. ' Speed' in Shakespeare means not only swiftness, haste, but success, fortune, and also that propitious power, or exalted guardianship, which brings success, especially in the expression of good wishes. ' Saint Nicholas be thy speed !' Two Gent. Ill, i, 301; ' Hercules be thy speed,' As You Like It, I, ii, 222, and elsewhere; and with a comic turn in 'good manners be your speed,' 1 Hen. IV: III, i, 190. Hence, therefore, Desdemona is here the guardian angel who saves Iago's ship, and at the conclusion of the speech she is styled not without a purpose, ' the divine Desdemona.'"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.82","kind":"speech"},"2.1.83":{"play":"CASSIO: Left in the conduct of the bold Iago,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.83","kind":"speech"},"2.1.84":{"play":"CASSIO: Whose footing here anticipates our thoughts","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.84","kind":"speech"},"2.1.85":{"play":"CASSIO: A sennight’s speed. Great Jove, Othello guard,","notes":["Theobald (Sh. Rest., p. 143): That is, That Rocks and Shoals lurk under, and lye covered by the Deep, treacherously to destroy Vessels which happen to be thrown upon them. Steevens: Perhaps escerped was an old English word borrowed from the French, escarps, which Shakespeare, not finding congruous to the image of clogging the keel, afterwards changed. I once thought it might be Traitors enscarfd, i.e. muffled in their robes, as in Jul. Cats, or Ham., ' My sea-gown scarfd about me.' Henley: Steevens's difficulty would, perhaps, have been removed had he recollected Othello's speech in IV, ii, 60: ' Steep'd me in poverty to the very lips.' Boswell: Traitors ensteep'd are merely traitors concealed under the water. Knight: Rocks and sand are beneath the water, and what is beneath the water is steep'd in the water. The identical word thus applied is in the Faerit Queene, I, xi, 276: ' Now gan the goldei Phoebus for to steepe His fierie face in billowes of the west.' White (ed i) reads enscarfd and upholds the word: because Shakespeare never uses ' steep' in the sense of ' plunge' or ' submerge,' but always in that of ' lave' or ' soak,' which is almost ridiculously inappropriate here; because 'scarp' in Shakespeare's day meanl the inner slope of a ditch or intrenchment, then as now descriptive of shelving rocks: and because enscarped might be easily mistaken for ' ensteeped,' owing to the likeness between c and t in the MS. of the early seventeenth century. Dyce in his ed. ii reminded White of Henley's reference to IV, ii, 60, and White adopted ' ensteep'd ' in his ed. ii, and enscarfd was heard of no more."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.85","kind":"speech"},"2.1.86":{"play":"CASSIO: And swell his sail with thine own powerful breath,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.86","kind":"speech"},"2.1.87":{"play":"CASSIO: That he may bless this bay with his tall ship,","notes":["Reed: That is, deadly, destructive."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.87","kind":"speech"},"2.1.88":{"play":"CASSIO: Make love’s quick pants in Desdemona’s arms,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.88","kind":"speech"},"2.1.89":{"play":"CASSIO: Give renewed fire to our extincted spirits,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.89","kind":"speech"},"2.1.90":{"play":"CASSIO: And bring all Cyprus comfort!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.90","kind":"speech"},"2.1.91":{"play":"CASSIO: O, behold,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.91","kind":"speech"},"2.1.92":{"play":"CASSIO: The riches of the ship is come on shore!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.92","kind":"speech"},"2.1.93":{"play":"CASSIO: You men of Cyprus, let her have your knees.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.93","kind":"speech"},"2.1.94":{"play":"CASSIO: Hail to thee, lady, and the grace of heaven,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.94","kind":"speech"},"2.1.95":{"play":"CASSIO: Before, behind thee, and on every hand","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.95","kind":"speech"},"2.1.96":{"play":"CASSIO: Enwheel thee round.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.96","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.96":{"play":"[He rises.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.96","kind":"stage"},"2.1.97":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I thank you, valiant Cassio.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.97","kind":"speech"},"2.1.98":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What tidings can you tell of my lord?","notes":["The omission in the Folio of the phrase found in the Qto, White (ed. ii) pronounces due to 'manifest accident;' as well as me in line 104."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.98","kind":"speech"},"2.1.99":{"play":"CASSIO: He is not yet arrived, nor know I aught","notes":["Malone: For this absurdity I have not the smallest doubt that the Master of the Revels, and not our poet, is answerable. [Malone made the same remark on 2 Hen. VI: IV, x, 56, where the Ff have 'Jove,' and the Qq God. The inference is that Malone deemed God the true word here; Hudson has adopted it. Ed.] Cowden-Clarke: We believe it to have been the author's own word characteristically put into Cassio's mouth here. To this day Italians use mythological adjurations in common with Christian appeals; and in Shakespeare's time the custom was almost universal."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.99","kind":"speech"},"2.1.100":{"play":"CASSIO: But that he’s well and will be shortly here.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.100","kind":"speech"},"2.1.101":{"play":"DESDEMONA: O, but I fear—How lost you company?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.101","kind":"speech"},"2.1.102":{"play":"CASSIO: The great contention of sea and skies","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.102","kind":"speech"},"2.1.103":{"play":"CASSIO: Parted our fellowship.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.103","kind":"speech"},"2.1.104":{"play":"CASSIO: But hark, a sail!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.104","kind":"speech"},"2.1.105":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: They give their greeting to the citadel.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.105","kind":"speech"},"2.1.106":{"play":"SECOND GENTLEMAN: This likewise is a friend.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.106","kind":"speech"},"2.1.107":{"play":"CASSIO: See for the news.","notes":["Johnson: Desdemona gives her hand to Cassio, who kisses it, and rises from his knee."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.107","kind":"speech"},"2.1.108":{"play":"CASSIO: Good ancient, you are welcome. Welcome, mistress.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.108","kind":"speech"},"2.1.109":{"play":"CASSIO: Let it not gall your patience, good Iago,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.109","kind":"speech"},"2.1.110":{"play":"CASSIO: That I extend my manners. ’Tis my breeding","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.110","kind":"speech"},"2.1.111":{"play":"CASSIO: That gives me this bold show of courtesy.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.111","kind":"speech"},"2.1.112":{"play":"IAGO: Sir, would she give you so much of her lips","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.112","kind":"speech"},"2.1.113":{"play":"IAGO: As of her tongue she oft bestows on me,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.113","kind":"speech"},"2.1.114":{"play":"IAGO: You would have enough.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.114","kind":"speech"},"2.1.115":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Alas, she has no speech!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.115","kind":"speech"},"2.1.116":{"play":"IAGO: In faith, too much.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.116","kind":"speech"},"2.1.117":{"play":"IAGO: I find it still when I have list to sleep.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.117","kind":"speech"},"2.1.118":{"play":"IAGO: Marry, before your Ladyship, I grant,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.118","kind":"speech"},"2.1.119":{"play":"IAGO: She puts her tongue a little in her heart","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.119","kind":"speech"},"2.1.120":{"play":"IAGO: And chides with thinking.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.120","kind":"speech"},"2.1.121":{"play":"EMILIA: You have little cause to say so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.121","kind":"speech"},"2.1.122":{"play":"IAGO: Come on, come on! You are pictures out of door,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.122","kind":"speech"},"2.1.123":{"play":"IAGO: bells in your parlors, wildcats in your kitchens,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.123","kind":"speech"},"2.1.124":{"play":"IAGO: saints in your injuries, devils being offended, players","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.124","kind":"speech"},"2.1.125":{"play":"IAGO: in your huswifery, and huswives in your beds.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.125","kind":"speech"},"2.1.126":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Oh, fie upon thee, slanderer.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.126","kind":"speech"},"2.1.127":{"play":"IAGO: Nay, it is true, or else I am a Turk.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.127","kind":"speech"},"2.1.128":{"play":"IAGO: You rise to play, and go to bed to work.","notes":["Dyce [Remarks, &c, p. 237): When Collier adopted 'leave' of the Folio, what meaning did he attach to it ? did he suppose it to be only another form of '* leve,' ' leef,' or ' lief ' (a word which, I apprehend, was never used as a substantive) ? List is clearly the true reading. Collier (ed. ii): Lust is from the (MS.). ' Leave' merely means ' when I have permission to sleep,' and has nothing to do with ' leef,' *leve,' or 'lief.' Dyce [Strictures, p. 197): Collier's present explanation of 'leave' makes Iago talk sheer nonsense."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.128","kind":"speech"},"2.1.129":{"play":"EMILIA: You shall not write my praise.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.129","kind":"speech"},"2.1.130":{"play":"IAGO: No, let me not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.130","kind":"speech"},"2.1.131":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What wouldst write of me if thou shouldst praise","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.131","kind":"speech"},"2.1.132":{"play":"DESDEMONA: me?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.132","kind":"speech"},"2.1.133":{"play":"IAGO: O, gentle lady, do not put me to ’t,","notes":["Gerard: Nous avons en francais la meme expression:'Sagss eomme des images.' [This refers to the ' paintings ' with which Hamlet taxes women, III, i, 142: 'I have heard of your paintings too, well enough ; God has given you one face, and you make yourselves another.' Ed.] 129-133: Steevens: Almost the same thoughts are to be found in Puttenham's Arte of Poesie, 1589: 'We limit the comely parts of a woman to consist in foure points, that is to be a shrewe in the kitchin, a saint in the Church, an Angell at the bourd, and an Ape in the bed '[p. 299, ed. Arber]. See also Middleton's Blurt, Master- Constable, 1602 [III, iii], and The Miseries of Inforced Marriage, 1607 [I, i, p. 10, ed. Collier]. Puttenham, who mentions all other contemporary writers, has not once spoken of Shakespeare ; so that it is probable that he had not produced anything of so early a date. The truth is, that this book appears to have been written several years before its publication. See p. 115 [p. 152, ed. Arber], where the author refers to Sir Nicholas Bacon, who died in 1579, and recounts a circumstance, from his own knowledge, that happened in 1553. Malone: How does it appear that this book was written several years before its publication, from the circumstances mentioned ? Puttenham does not speak of Sir Nicholas Bacon as living ; but speaks of those that knew him; from which we might rather infer that it could not be written before 1578, when that lord keeper died."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.133","kind":"speech"},"2.1.134":{"play":"IAGO: For I am nothing if not critical.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.134","kind":"speech"},"2.1.135":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Come on, assay.—There’s one gone to the harbor?","notes":["Johnson: When you have a mind to do injuries, you put on an air of sanctity."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.135","kind":"speech"},"2.1.136":{"play":"IAGO: Ay, madam.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.136","kind":"speech"},"2.1.137":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I am not merry, but I do beguile","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.137","kind":"speech"},"2.1.138":{"play":"DESDEMONA: The thing I am by seeming otherwise.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.138","kind":"speech"},"2.1.139":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Come, how wouldst thou praise me?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.139","kind":"speech"},"2.1.140":{"play":"IAGO: I am about it, but indeed my invention comes","notes":["Booth: Cassio should make this reply. He has been awaiting their arrival—Iago has just landed with Desdemona."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.140","kind":"speech"},"2.1.141":{"play":"IAGO: from my pate as birdlime does from frieze: it","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.141","kind":"speech"},"2.1.142":{"play":"IAGO: plucks out brains and all. But my muse labors, and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.142","kind":"speech"},"2.1.143":{"play":"IAGO: thus she is delivered:","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.143","kind":"speech"},"2.1.146":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Well praised! How if she be black and witty?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.146","kind":"speech"},"2.1.149":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Worse and worse.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.149","kind":"speech"},"2.1.150":{"play":"EMILIA: How if fair and foolish?","notes":["Steevens: I believe Qx has the true reading here, as in Love's Lab. IV, i, 127. [To the same effect, Staunton. See Bishop Percy's Folio MS., vol. iv. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.150","kind":"speech"},"2.1.153":{"play":"DESDEMONA: These are old fond paradoxes to make","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.153","kind":"speech"},"2.1.154":{"play":"DESDEMONA: fools laugh i’ th’ alehouse. What miserable praise","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.154","kind":"speech"},"2.1.155":{"play":"DESDEMONA: hast thou for her that’s foul and foolish?","notes":["Dyce (Lex.): Foolish, simple, silly."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.155","kind":"speech"},"2.1.158":{"play":"DESDEMONA: O heavy ignorance! Thou praisest the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.158","kind":"speech"},"2.1.159":{"play":"DESDEMONA: worst best. But what praise couldst thou bestow on","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.159","kind":"speech"},"2.1.160":{"play":"DESDEMONA: a deserving woman indeed, one that in the authority","notes":["Johnson: We may read: ‘She ne'er was yet so foolish that was fair, But even,’ &c. Yet I believe the common reading to be right ; the law makes the power of cohabitation a proof that a man is not a natural ; therefore, since the foolishest woman, if pretty, may have a child, no pretty woman is ever foolish. Halliweel: To elucidate this sentence, the reader may remember, that ‘ if one have so much knowledge as to measure a yard of cloth ; number twenty pence rightly ; name the days o( the week ; or become the parent of a child ; he shall not be accounted an idiot by die laws of the realm.’ A statement of which may be seen in The Student's Companion, or the Reason of the Law, 2d ed. 1734. Anon."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.160","kind":"speech"},"2.1.161":{"play":"DESDEMONA: of her merit did justly put on the vouch of very","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.161","kind":"speech"},"2.1.162":{"play":"DESDEMONA: malice itself?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.162","kind":"speech"},"2.1.174":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To do what?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.174","kind":"speech"},"2.1.176":{"play":"DESDEMONA: O, most lame and impotent conclusion!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.176","kind":"speech"},"2.1.177":{"play":"DESDEMONA: —Do not learn of him, Emilia, though he be thy","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.177","kind":"speech"},"2.1.178":{"play":"DESDEMONA: husband.—How say you, Cassio? Is he not a most","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.178","kind":"speech"},"2.1.179":{"play":"DESDEMONA: profane and liberal counselor?","notes":["Steevens: The hint for this question, and the metrical reply of Iago, is taken from a strange pamphlet, called Choice, Chance, and Change, or Conceits in their Colours, 1606; when after Tidero has described many ridiculous characters in verse, Arnofilo asks him, ' But, I pray thee, didst thou write none in commendation of some worthy creature ?' Tidero then proceeds, like Iago, to repeat more verses. [It would not have been worth while to cite this note of Steevens, had not Singer repeated it, without acknowledgement, in both his First and Second editions. I never saw the pamphlet, and dislike to depart from the safe rule of verifying all Steevens's citations, especially those wherefrom Steevens asserts that Shakespeare ' took hints,' assertions always doubtful, frequently absurd, and here especially uncertain, in view of the date 1606. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.179","kind":"speech"},"2.1.180":{"play":"CASSIO: He speaks home, madam. You may relish him","notes":["Theobald: ‘put on’. Warburton: The sense is, one that was so conscious of her own merit, and of the authority her character had with every one, that she durst venture to call upon malice itself to vouch for her. This was some commendation. And the character only of the clearest virtue; which could force malice, even against its nature, to do justice. Johnson: To put on the vouch of malice, is to assume a character vouched by the testimony of malice itself. Capell (p. 142): ‘Put on’ is—push on, push forward the unwilling; so that the sense is—push malice on to vouch, dare it to give its testimony, say what it knows of her; this is the very force of ‘put on’ and ‘vouch,’ and their explanation combin'd; and other comment than this the passage does not require."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.180","kind":"speech"},"2.1.181":{"play":"CASSIO: more in the soldier than in the scholar.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.181","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.181.1":{"play":"[Cassio takes Desdemona’s hand.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.181.1","kind":"stage"},"2.1.182":{"play":"IAGO: He takes her by the palm. Ay, well said,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.182","kind":"speech"},"2.1.183":{"play":"IAGO: whisper. With as little a web as this will I ensnare as","notes":["Johnson: In this word Johnson discerned an allusion 'to the Roman practice of marking the jars with the name of the Consul. The appearance of such a woman would make an era, but as the merit of the best woman is but small, that era might be properly applied to the distinction of the different ages of small beer.' This note was not repeated in either of the two editions which Dr Johnson and Steevens afterwards edited. In its stead appeared the interpretation by Steevens, which has been since then generally accepted, ‘of keeping the accounts of a household’"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.183","kind":"speech"},"2.1.184":{"play":"IAGO: great a fly as Cassio. Ay, smile upon her, do. I will","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.184","kind":"speech"},"2.1.185":{"play":"IAGO: gyve thee in thine own courtship. You say true, ’tis","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.185","kind":"speech"},"2.1.186":{"play":"IAGO: so indeed. If such tricks as these strip you out of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.186","kind":"speech"},"2.1.187":{"play":"IAGO: your lieutenantry, it had been better you had not","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.187","kind":"speech"},"2.1.188":{"play":"IAGO: kissed your three fingers so oft, which now again","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.188","kind":"speech"},"2.1.189":{"play":"IAGO: you are most apt to play the sir in. Very good; well","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.189","kind":"speech"},"2.1.190":{"play":"IAGO: kissed; an excellent courtesy! ’Tis so, indeed. Yet","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.190","kind":"speech"},"2.1.191":{"play":"IAGO: again your fingers to your lips? Would they were","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.191","kind":"speech"},"2.1.192":{"play":"IAGO: clyster pipes for your sake!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.192","kind":"speech"},"2.1.193":{"play":"IAGO: The Moor. I know his trumpet.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.193","kind":"speech"},"2.1.194":{"play":"CASSIO: ’Tis truly so.","notes":["Steevens: That is, to exchange a delicacy for coarser fare. See Queen Elizabeth's Household Book for the 43d year of her Reign: ‘Item, the Mastei Cookes have to see all the salmons' tailes,’ &c, p. 296."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.194","kind":"speech"},"2.1.195":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Let’s meet him and receive him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.195","kind":"speech"},"2.1.196":{"play":"CASSIO: Lo, where he comes!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.196","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.196.1":{"play":"[Enter Othello and Attendants.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.196.1","kind":"stage"},"2.1.197":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, my fair warrior!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.197","kind":"speech"},"2.1.198":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My dear Othello!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.198","kind":"speech"},"2.1.199":{"play":"OTHELLO: It gives me wonder great as my content","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.199","kind":"speech"},"2.1.200":{"play":"OTHELLO: To see you here before me. O my soul’s joy!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.200","kind":"speech"},"2.1.201":{"play":"OTHELLO: If after every tempest come such calms,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.201","kind":"speech"},"2.1.202":{"play":"OTHELLO: May the winds blow till they have wakened death,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.202","kind":"speech"},"2.1.203":{"play":"OTHELLO: And let the laboring bark climb hills of seas","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.203","kind":"speech"},"2.1.204":{"play":"OTHELLO: Olympus high, and duck again as low","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.204","kind":"speech"},"2.1.205":{"play":"OTHELLO: As hell’s from heaven! If it were now to die,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.205","kind":"speech"},"2.1.206":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Twere now to be most happy, for I fear","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.206","kind":"speech"},"2.1.207":{"play":"OTHELLO: My soul hath her content so absolute","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.207","kind":"speech"},"2.1.208":{"play":"OTHELLO: That not another comfort like to this","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.208","kind":"speech"},"2.1.209":{"play":"OTHELLO: Succeeds in unknown fate.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.209","kind":"speech"},"2.1.210":{"play":"DESDEMONA: The heavens forbid","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.210","kind":"speech"},"2.1.211":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But that our loves and comforts should increase","notes":["Henley: That is, to show your good breeding and gallantry. Staunton: The courtier, or gallant.","Johnson: Spoken when Cassio kisses his hand, and Desdemona courtesies. Malone: We have just had 'I will catch you in your own courtesies [Qx ]. Here, therefore, he probably meant only to speak of Cassio, while kissing his hand. ‘Well kissed! an excellent courtesy!’ i.e. an excellent salute. Courtesy, in the sense of obeisance or salute, was applied to men as well as to women. ‘The homely villain court’sies to her low,’ R. of L. 1338. Rolfe: It is doubtful whether this refers to Cassio or Desdemona."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.211","kind":"speech"},"2.1.212":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Even as our days do grow!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.212","kind":"speech"},"2.1.213":{"play":"OTHELLO: Amen to that, sweet powers!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.213","kind":"speech"},"2.1.214":{"play":"OTHELLO: I cannot speak enough of this content.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.214","kind":"speech"},"2.1.215":{"play":"OTHELLO: It stops me here; it is too much of joy.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.215","kind":"speech"},"2.1.216":{"play":"OTHELLO: And this, and this, the greatest discords be","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.216","kind":"speech"},"2.1.217":{"play":"OTHELLO: That e’er our hearts shall make!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.217","kind":"speech"},"2.1.218":{"play":"IAGO: O, you are well tuned now,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.218","kind":"speech"},"2.1.219":{"play":"IAGO: But I’ll set down the pegs that make this music,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.219","kind":"speech"},"2.1.220":{"play":"IAGO: As honest as I am.","notes":["Steevens: In III, iv, 173, Desdemona calls herself an 'unhandsome Warrior.' This phrase was introduced by our copiers of the French Sonneteers. Ronsard frequently calls his mistresses guerriires ; and Southern, his imitator, is not less prodigal of the same appellation. Had I not met with the word thus fantastically applied, I should have concluded that Othello called his wife a ' warrior ' because she had embarked with him on a warlike expedition, and not in consequence of Ovid's observation: ' Militat omnis amans, et habet sua castra Cupido.' [Southern was not born until nigh a half century after Shakespeare's death. Steevens' s reading was so extensive, his memory so tenacious, and his wit so ready, that we shall always owe him gratitude for his labours, and ought not to ' mock his useful toil ' if now and then he wanders far, very far, afield. Desdemona had protested that she could not stay at home a 'moth of peace,' but must go to 'the War' with Othello; and to that, I think, is the allusion here. Ed.]."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.220","kind":"speech"},"2.1.221":{"play":"OTHELLO: Come. Let us to the castle.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.221","kind":"speech"},"2.1.222":{"play":"OTHELLO: News, friends! Our wars are done. The Turks are","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.222","kind":"speech"},"2.1.223":{"play":"OTHELLO: drowned.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.223","kind":"speech"},"2.1.224":{"play":"OTHELLO: How does my old acquaintance of this isle?—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.224","kind":"speech"},"2.1.225":{"play":"OTHELLO: Honey, you shall be well desired in Cyprus.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.225","kind":"speech"},"2.1.226":{"play":"OTHELLO: I have found great love amongst them. O, my sweet,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.226","kind":"speech"},"2.1.227":{"play":"OTHELLO: I prattle out of fashion, and I dote","notes":["Steevens: Cf. ‘The sea making mountaines of itself, over which the tossed and tottering ship should climbe, to be straight carried downe againe to a pit of hellish darknesses—Sidney's Arcadia, b. i."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.227","kind":"speech"},"2.1.228":{"play":"OTHELLO: In mine own comforts.—I prithee, good Iago,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.228","kind":"speech"},"2.1.229":{"play":"OTHELLO: Go to the bay and disembark my coffers.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.229","kind":"speech"},"2.1.230":{"play":"OTHELLO: Bring thou the master to the citadel.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.230","kind":"speech"},"2.1.231":{"play":"OTHELLO: He is a good one, and his worthiness","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.231","kind":"speech"},"2.1.232":{"play":"OTHELLO: Does challenge much respect.—Come, Desdemona.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.232","kind":"speech"},"2.1.233":{"play":"OTHELLO: Once more, well met at Cyprus.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.233","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.233.1":{"play":"[All but Iago and Roderigo exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.233.1","kind":"stage"},"2.1.234":{"play":"IAGO: Do thou meet me presently","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.234","kind":"speech"},"2.1.235":{"play":"IAGO: at the harbor. Come hither. If","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.235","kind":"speech"},"2.1.236":{"play":"IAGO: thou be’st valiant—as they say base men being in","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.236","kind":"speech"},"2.1.237":{"play":"IAGO: love have then a nobility in their natures more than","notes":["Johnson: On thy mouth, to stop it while thou art listening to a wiser man."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.237","kind":"speech"},"2.1.238":{"play":"IAGO: is native to them—list me. The Lieutenant tonight","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.238","kind":"speech"},"2.1.239":{"play":"IAGO: watches on the court of guard. First, I must tell thee","notes":["Dyce [Gloss.): A separation, or dispersion. White (ed. ii) The opposite of congregation; an extraordinary use of the word."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.239","kind":"speech"},"2.1.240":{"play":"IAGO: this: Desdemona is directly in love with him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.240","kind":"speech"},"2.1.241":{"play":"RODERIGO: With him? Why, ’tis not possible.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.241","kind":"speech"},"2.1.242":{"play":"IAGO: Lay thy finger thus, and let thy soul be instructed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.242","kind":"speech"},"2.1.243":{"play":"IAGO: Mark me with what violence she first loved the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.243","kind":"speech"},"2.1.244":{"play":"IAGO: Moor but for bragging and telling her fantastical","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.244","kind":"speech"},"2.1.245":{"play":"IAGO: lies. And will she love him still for prating? Let not","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.245","kind":"speech"},"2.1.246":{"play":"IAGO: thy discreet heart think it. Her eye must be fed. And","notes":["Warburton: 'A trifling insignificant fellow may perhaps be called Trash, but the metaphor of hunting is not preserved. I suppose therefore that the word is brack, which is a low species of hounds of the chase, and a term generally used in contempt. As to \" trace,\" crush of Qx is plainly a corruption of cherish? Warton was the first to suggest that trash should be substituted for 'trace,' but he was not strictly accurate in his definition of its technical meaning ; he supposed that it meant simply to rate, to check, and cited Caratach's reply to Nennius (Bonduca, I, i) when Nennius taunted him with flying from the Romans: 'I fled too ; But not so fast,—your jewel had been lost then, Young Hengo there ; he trashV me,' i. e., says Warton, he stopped me. At last Steevens (1793) discovered the meaning of trash which has since been generally accepted. 'To trash is still a hunter's phrase, and signifies to fasten a weight on the neck of a dog, when his speed is superior to that of his companions \" Trash \" in the first instance in this line may be used to signify a worthless hound, as the same term is afterwards employed to describe a worthless female: \"I do suspect this trash\" (V, i, 108). It is scarcely necessary to support the present jingle on the word, it is so much in our author's manner, although his worst.' Knight upholds ' trace,' but was misled in his interpretation. ' Trash ' and ' trace,' says Knight, 'are used with perfect propriety. The \"trash\" is the thing traced, put in traces—confined—as an untrained worthless dog is held, and hence the present meaning of trask.' Dyce (Remarks, p. 237): Knight's explanation of 'trash' is borrowed from Richardson's Diet., where we find: ' A trash—anything (man, dog) trashed or traced or confined in traces, that it may not, because it would, run or pursue too fast, rashly ; like an untrained dog ; a worthless hound; hence it is anything worthless,' &c. But in this explanation Richardson is undoubtedly mistaken ; he gives to trash a meaning which it never did and never could bear. When used as a huntsman vr dog-trainer's term, or metaphorically with an allusion to their practices, it invariably signifies the thing WHICH RESTRAINS: 'Above this lower roome shall be your huntsmans lodging, wherin hee shall also keep his cooples, liams, collars, trashes, boxes,' •Sec.—Markham's Conntrey Contentments, b. i. c., i, p. 15, 1615. The trash, whether a strap, a rope dragging loose on the ground, or a weight, was fastened round the neck of a too forward dog, to check his movements. Collier (ed. ii) in justification of his (MS.) says that 'trash and trace were used somewhat synonymously, as a mode of keeping back braches, i. e. dogs, who hunted too quickly. Iago speaks of Roderigo as a poor hound, who was so eager in the chase that it was necessary to restrain him.' Singer (ed. ii) thinks that Warburton's brach is correct, and that crush is a misprint for trash. * The converse has happened in the Ind. to the Tarn, cf Shr., where brach has been misprinted trash.* Roderigo is cheeked or trashed by Iago for his quick hunting ; i. e. he is in too great a hurry to come to an explanation with Desdemona.' White (ed. i): 'Whom I trash,' i. e. whom I restrain, whip in. ' Trace ' seems to have been only a varied form of trash. The misprint in the Qto is evidently due to the likeness of c and l. Staunton cannot subscribe to Warburton's emendation brach, 'although persuaded that \" trash of Venice\" is a vitiation of what the poet wrote. Trash signifying to clog, to impede, is surely the genuine word for \" trace \" of the Folio.' Bailey (ii, 108): It is plain to me that the genuine reading is leash, i. e. whom I hold in leash for the quick hunting of the Moor. Keightley [Exp. 302): ' The jingle,' Steevens says, ' being in Shakespeare's manner.' Now to this I object first, that this was not Shakespeare's manner, for the apparent instances of it are mostly printers' blunders ; and, secondly, that Roderigo did not require to be trashed or checked ' for his quick hunting,' for he was always hanging back and ready to give up the chase till urged on by Iago. This last objection also applies to ' trace ' in the sense of follow or accompany. It would apply also, though in a less degree, to train, which would yield a tolerable sense. On the whole, I think that Iago's words may have been praise, which would suit his sneering, ironical tone. As to brach, though we frequently find it used of a woman, I believe it was never applied to a man. Dyce (ed. iii): I give the reading of Steevens, but I now (1865) entertain great doubts if it be what Shakespeare wrote. [I have reserved Halliwell's note for the last, because it gives what seems to me to be the true interpretation ; the Folio needs no change ; « trace ' bears here one of its commonest meanings ; ' For his quick hunting ' does not mean, because of his quick hunting' but in order to make him, for the purpose of making him, hunt quickly, a meaning of 'for' which White (ed. ii) especially notes, and, thus noting it, it is strange that White should have missed the common meaning of the word ' trace.' Ii was Steevens who gave a bias to the word from which it never recovered until Halli well set it straight, whose note is as follows : ' The meaning seems to be—if this wietched fellow, whose steps I carefully watch in order to quicken his pace, follows my directions, I will have our Michael Cassio on the hip.' Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.246","kind":"speech"},"2.1.247":{"play":"IAGO: what delight shall she have to look on the devil?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.247","kind":"speech"},"2.1.248":{"play":"IAGO: When the blood is made dull with the act of sport,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.248","kind":"speech"},"2.1.249":{"play":"IAGO: there should be, again to inflame it and to give","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.249","kind":"speech"},"2.1.250":{"play":"IAGO: satiety a fresh appetite, loveliness in favor, sympathy","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.250","kind":"speech"},"2.1.251":{"play":"IAGO: in years, manners, and beauties, all which the Moor","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.251","kind":"speech"},"2.1.252":{"play":"IAGO: is defective in. Now, for want of these required","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.252","kind":"speech"},"2.1.253":{"play":"IAGO: conveniences, her delicate tenderness will find itself","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.253","kind":"speech"},"2.1.254":{"play":"IAGO: abused, begin to heave the gorge, disrelish and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.254","kind":"speech"},"2.1.255":{"play":"IAGO: abhor the Moor. Very nature will instruct her in it","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.255","kind":"speech"},"2.1.256":{"play":"IAGO: and compel her to some second choice. Now, sir,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.256","kind":"speech"},"2.1.257":{"play":"IAGO: this granted—as it is a most pregnant and unforced","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.257","kind":"speech"},"2.1.258":{"play":"IAGO: position—who stands so eminent in the degree of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.258","kind":"speech"},"2.1.259":{"play":"IAGO: this fortune as Cassio does? A knave very voluble, no","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.259","kind":"speech"},"2.1.260":{"play":"IAGO: further conscionable than in putting on the mere","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.260","kind":"speech"},"2.1.261":{"play":"IAGO: form of civil and humane seeming for the better","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.261","kind":"speech"},"2.1.262":{"play":"IAGO: compassing of his salt and most hidden loose","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.262","kind":"speech"},"2.1.263":{"play":"IAGO: affection. Why, none, why, none! A slipper and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.263","kind":"speech"},"2.1.264":{"play":"IAGO: subtle knave, a finder-out of occasions, that has an","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.264","kind":"speech"},"2.1.265":{"play":"IAGO: eye can stamp and counterfeit advantages, though","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.265","kind":"speech"},"2.1.266":{"play":"IAGO: true advantage never present itself; a devilish knave!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.266","kind":"speech"},"2.1.267":{"play":"IAGO: Besides, the knave is handsome, young, and hath all","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.267","kind":"speech"},"2.1.268":{"play":"IAGO: those requisites in him that folly and green minds","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.268","kind":"speech"},"2.1.269":{"play":"IAGO: look after. A pestilent complete knave, and the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.269","kind":"speech"},"2.1.270":{"play":"IAGO: woman hath found him already.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.270","kind":"speech"},"2.1.271":{"play":"RODERIGO: I cannot believe that in her. She’s full of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.271","kind":"speech"},"2.1.272":{"play":"RODERIGO: most blessed condition.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.272","kind":"speech"},"2.1.273":{"play":"IAGO: Blessed fig’s end! The wine she drinks is made of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.273","kind":"speech"},"2.1.274":{"play":"IAGO: grapes. If she had been blessed, she would never","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.274","kind":"speech"},"2.1.275":{"play":"IAGO: have loved the Moor. Blessed pudding! Didst thou","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.275","kind":"speech"},"2.1.276":{"play":"IAGO: not see her paddle with the palm of his hand? Didst","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.276","kind":"speech"},"2.1.277":{"play":"IAGO: not mark that?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.277","kind":"speech"},"2.1.278":{"play":"RODERIGO: Yes, that I did. But that was but courtesy.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.278","kind":"speech"},"2.1.279":{"play":"IAGO: Lechery, by this hand! An index and obscure","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.279","kind":"speech"},"2.1.280":{"play":"IAGO: prologue to the history of lust and foul thoughts.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.280","kind":"speech"},"2.1.281":{"play":"IAGO: They met so near with their lips that their breaths","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.281","kind":"speech"},"2.1.282":{"play":"IAGO: embraced together. Villainous thoughts, Roderigo!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.282","kind":"speech"},"2.1.283":{"play":"IAGO: When these mutualities so marshal the way, hard","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.283","kind":"speech"},"2.1.284":{"play":"IAGO: at hand comes the master and main exercise, th’","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.284","kind":"speech"},"2.1.285":{"play":"IAGO: incorporate conclusion. Pish! But, sir, be you ruled","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.285","kind":"speech"},"2.1.286":{"play":"IAGO: by me. I have brought you from Venice. Watch you","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.286","kind":"speech"},"2.1.287":{"play":"IAGO: tonight. For the command, I’ll lay ’t upon you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.287","kind":"speech"},"2.1.288":{"play":"IAGO: Cassio knows you not. I’ll not be far from you. Do","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.288","kind":"speech"},"2.1.289":{"play":"IAGO: you find some occasion to anger Cassio, either by","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.289","kind":"speech"},"2.1.290":{"play":"IAGO: speaking too loud, or tainting his discipline, or from","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.290","kind":"speech"},"2.1.291":{"play":"IAGO: what other course you please, which the time shall","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.291","kind":"speech"},"2.1.292":{"play":"IAGO: more favorably minister.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.292","kind":"speech"},"2.1.293":{"play":"RODERIGO: Well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.293","kind":"speech"},"2.1.294":{"play":"IAGO: Sir, he’s rash and very sudden in choler, and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.294","kind":"speech"},"2.1.295":{"play":"IAGO: haply may strike at you. Provoke him that he may,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.295","kind":"speech"},"2.1.296":{"play":"IAGO: for even out of that will I cause these of Cyprus to","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.296","kind":"speech"},"2.1.297":{"play":"IAGO: mutiny, whose qualification shall come into no","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.297","kind":"speech"},"2.1.298":{"play":"IAGO: true taste again but by the displanting of Cassio. So","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.298","kind":"speech"},"2.1.299":{"play":"IAGO: shall you have a shorter journey to your desires by","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.299","kind":"speech"},"2.1.300":{"play":"IAGO: the means I shall then have to prefer them, and the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.300","kind":"speech"},"2.1.301":{"play":"IAGO: impediment most profitably removed, without the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.301","kind":"speech"},"2.1.302":{"play":"IAGO: which there were no expectation of our prosperity.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.302","kind":"speech"},"2.1.303":{"play":"RODERIGO: I will do this, if you can bring it to any","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.303","kind":"speech"},"2.1.304":{"play":"RODERIGO: opportunity.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.304","kind":"speech"},"2.1.305":{"play":"IAGO: I warrant thee. Meet me by and by at the citadel. I","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.305","kind":"speech"},"2.1.306":{"play":"IAGO: must fetch his necessaries ashore. Farewell.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.306","kind":"speech"},"2.1.307":{"play":"RODERIGO: Adieu.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.307","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.307":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.307","kind":"stage"},"2.1.308":{"play":"IAGO: That Cassio loves her, I do well believe ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.308","kind":"speech"},"2.1.309":{"play":"IAGO: That she loves him, ’tis apt and of great credit.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.309","kind":"speech"},"2.1.310":{"play":"IAGO: The Moor, howbeit that I endure him not,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.310","kind":"speech"},"2.1.311":{"play":"IAGO: Is of a constant, loving, noble nature,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.311","kind":"speech"},"2.1.312":{"play":"IAGO: And I dare think he’ll prove to Desdemona","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.312","kind":"speech"},"2.1.313":{"play":"IAGO: A most dear husband. Now, I do love her too,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.313","kind":"speech"},"2.1.314":{"play":"IAGO: Not out of absolute lust (though peradventure","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.314","kind":"speech"},"2.1.315":{"play":"IAGO: I stand accountant for as great a sin)","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.315","kind":"speech"},"2.1.316":{"play":"IAGO: But partly led to diet my revenge","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.316","kind":"speech"},"2.1.317":{"play":"IAGO: For that I do suspect the lusty Moor","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.317","kind":"speech"},"2.1.318":{"play":"IAGO: Hath leaped into my seat—the thought whereof","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.318","kind":"speech"},"2.1.319":{"play":"IAGO: Doth, like a poisonous mineral, gnaw my inwards,","notes":["Johnson: A phrase from the art of wrestling."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.319","kind":"speech"},"2.1.320":{"play":"IAGO: And nothing can or shall content my soul","notes":["Hudson: This thought, originally by Iago's own confession a mere suspicion, is now ripening, and gnaws his base nature as his own ' poisonous mineral ' is about to gnaw the noble heart of his general."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.320","kind":"speech"},"2.1.321":{"play":"IAGO: Till I am evened with him, wife for wife,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.321","kind":"speech"},"2.1.322":{"play":"IAGO: Or, failing so, yet that I put the Moor","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.322","kind":"speech"},"2.1.323":{"play":"IAGO: At least into a jealousy so strong","notes":["Johnson: An honest man acts upon a plan, and forecasts his designs ; but a knave depends upon temporary and local opportunities, and never knows his own purpose but at the time of execution."],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.323","kind":"speech"},"2.1.324":{"play":"IAGO: That judgment cannot cure. Which thing to do,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.324","kind":"speech"},"2.1.325":{"play":"IAGO: If this poor trash of Venice, whom I trace","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.325","kind":"speech"},"2.1.326":{"play":"IAGO: For his quick hunting, stand the putting on,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.326","kind":"speech"},"2.1.327":{"play":"IAGO: I’ll have our Michael Cassio on the hip,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.327","kind":"speech"},"2.1.328":{"play":"IAGO: Abuse him to the Moor in the rank garb","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.328","kind":"speech"},"2.1.329":{"play":"IAGO: (For I fear Cassio with my nightcap too),","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.329","kind":"speech"},"2.1.330":{"play":"IAGO: Make the Moor thank me, love me, and reward me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.330","kind":"speech"},"2.1.331":{"play":"IAGO: For making him egregiously an ass","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.331","kind":"speech"},"2.1.332":{"play":"IAGO: And practicing upon his peace and quiet","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.332","kind":"speech"},"2.1.333":{"play":"IAGO: Even to madness. ’Tis here, but yet confused.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.333","kind":"speech"},"2.1.334":{"play":"IAGO: Knavery’s plain face is never seen till used.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.1.334","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.1.334.1":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.1.334.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 2, SCENE 2":{"SD_2.2.0":{"play":"[Enter Othello’s Herald with a proclamation.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.2.0","kind":"stage"},"2.2.1":{"play":"HERALD: It is Othello’s pleasure, our noble and valiant","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.1","kind":"speech"},"2.2.2":{"play":"HERALD: general, that upon certain tidings now arrived,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.2","kind":"speech"},"2.2.3":{"play":"HERALD: importing the mere perdition of the Turkish fleet,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.3","kind":"speech"},"2.2.4":{"play":"HERALD: every man put himself into triumph: some to","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.4","kind":"speech"},"2.2.5":{"play":"HERALD: dance, some to make bonfires, each man to what","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.5","kind":"speech"},"2.2.6":{"play":"HERALD: sport and revels his addition leads him. For besides","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.6","kind":"speech"},"2.2.7":{"play":"HERALD: these beneficial news, it is the celebration of his","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.7","kind":"speech"},"2.2.8":{"play":"HERALD: nuptial. So much was his pleasure should be proclaimed","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.8","kind":"speech"},"2.2.9":{"play":"HERALD: All offices are open, and there is full","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.9","kind":"speech"},"2.2.10":{"play":"HERALD: liberty of feasting from this present hour of five till","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.10","kind":"speech"},"2.2.11":{"play":"HERALD: the bell have told eleven. Heaven bless the isle of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.11","kind":"speech"},"2.2.12":{"play":"HERALD: Cyprus and our noble general, Othello!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.2.12","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.2.12.1":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.2.12.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 2, SCENE 3":{"SD_2.3.0":{"play":"[Enter Othello, Desdemona, Cassio, and Attendants.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.0","kind":"stage"},"2.3.1":{"play":"OTHELLO: Good Michael, look you to the guard tonight.","notes":["Good Michael] Cowden-Clarke (The Shakespeare Key, p. 91): These few words, seemingly insignificant, are of important dramatic use. They give augmented effect to Othello's subsequent anger at Cassio's being betrayed not only into neglect of duty in preserving order, but into breach of order himself; while they set well before the mind Othello's trust and confidence in Cassio as his chosen officer, and his liking for him as a personal friend, calling him by his Christian name ‘Michael,' which, after the one final impressive appeal, ‘How comes it, Michael, you are thus forgot?’ he never again uses."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.1","kind":"speech"},"2.3.2":{"play":"OTHELLO: Let’s teach ourselves that honorable stop","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.2","kind":"speech"},"2.3.3":{"play":"OTHELLO: Not to outsport discretion.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.3","kind":"speech"},"2.3.4":{"play":"CASSIO: Iago hath direction what to do,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.4","kind":"speech"},"2.3.5":{"play":"CASSIO: But notwithstanding, with my personal eye","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.5","kind":"speech"},"2.3.6":{"play":"CASSIO: Will I look to ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.6","kind":"speech"},"2.3.7":{"play":"OTHELLO: Iago is most honest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.7","kind":"speech"},"2.3.8":{"play":"OTHELLO: Michael, goodnight. Tomorrow with your earliest","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.8","kind":"speech"},"2.3.9":{"play":"OTHELLO: Let me have speech with you. Come,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.9","kind":"speech"},"2.3.10":{"play":"OTHELLO: my dear love,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.10","kind":"speech"},"2.3.11":{"play":"OTHELLO: The purchase made, the fruits are to ensue;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.11","kind":"speech"},"2.3.12":{"play":"OTHELLO: That profit’s yet to come ’tween me and you.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.12","kind":"speech"},"2.3.13":{"play":"OTHELLO: Goodnight.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.13","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.13.1":{"play":"[Othello and Desdemona exit, with Attendants.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.13.1","kind":"stage"},"SD_2.3.13.2":{"play":"[Enter Iago.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.13.2","kind":"stage"},"2.3.14":{"play":"CASSIO: Welcome, Iago. We must to the watch.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.14","kind":"speech"},"2.3.15":{"play":"IAGO: Not this hour, lieutenant. ’Tis not yet ten o’ th’","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.15","kind":"speech"},"2.3.16":{"play":"IAGO: clock. Our general cast us thus early for the love of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.16","kind":"speech"},"2.3.17":{"play":"IAGO: his Desdemona—who let us not therefore blame;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.17","kind":"speech"},"2.3.18":{"play":"IAGO: he hath not yet made wanton the night with her, and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.18","kind":"speech"},"2.3.19":{"play":"IAGO: she is sport for Jove.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.19","kind":"speech"},"2.3.20":{"play":"CASSIO: She’s a most exquisite lady.","notes":["Nuptiall] Richardson [Diet. s. v.) : The noun is usually written with the plural termination s. Shakespeare writes it without. [This assertion of Richardson is an illustration of the fact which we are all so liable to forget, viz. : that, omitting V. &* A. and Lucrece, we cannot know how Shakespeare wrote anything except through the medium of the printers, whose work, it is believed, he never corrected. In this very word we find the s of the plural in the Qq, which some editors think were fresher from Shakespeare's hand than the Folio. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.20","kind":"speech"},"2.3.21":{"play":"IAGO: And, I’ll warrant her, full of game.","notes":["offices] Halliwell: The rooms appropriated to the upper servants of great families."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.21","kind":"speech"},"2.3.22":{"play":"CASSIO: Indeed, she’s a most fresh and delicate","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.22","kind":"speech"},"2.3.23":{"play":"CASSIO: creature.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.23","kind":"speech"},"2.3.24":{"play":"IAGO: What an eye she has! Methinks it sounds a parley","notes":["Blesse] Walker (i, 215) supposes that the word God, softened in the Qq, was omitted by the editor of the Folio in deference to the well-known act of Parliament; or was, perhaps, expunged by the licenser of the press."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.24","kind":"speech"},"2.3.25":{"play":"IAGO: to provocation.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.25","kind":"speech"},"2.3.26":{"play":"CASSIO: An inviting eye, and yet methinks right","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.26","kind":"speech"},"2.3.27":{"play":"CASSIO: modest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.27","kind":"speech"},"2.3.28":{"play":"IAGO: And when she speaks, is it not an alarum to love?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.28","kind":"speech"},"2.3.29":{"play":"CASSIO: She is indeed perfection.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.29","kind":"speech"},"2.3.30":{"play":"IAGO: Well, happiness to their sheets! Come, lieutenant,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.30","kind":"speech"},"2.3.31":{"play":"IAGO: I have a stoup of wine; and here without are a","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.31","kind":"speech"},"2.3.32":{"play":"IAGO: brace of Cyprus gallants that would fain have a","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.32","kind":"speech"},"2.3.33":{"play":"IAGO: measure to the health of black Othello.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.33","kind":"speech"},"2.3.34":{"play":"CASSIO: Not tonight, good Iago. I have very poor and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.34","kind":"speech"},"2.3.35":{"play":"CASSIO: unhappy brains for drinking. I could well wish","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.35","kind":"speech"},"2.3.36":{"play":"CASSIO: courtesy would invent some other custom of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.36","kind":"speech"},"2.3.37":{"play":"CASSIO: entertainment.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.37","kind":"speech"},"2.3.38":{"play":"IAGO: O, they are our friends! But one cup; I’ll drink","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.38","kind":"speech"},"2.3.39":{"play":"IAGO: for you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.39","kind":"speech"},"2.3.40":{"play":"CASSIO: I have drunk but one cup tonight, and that was","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.40","kind":"speech"},"2.3.41":{"play":"CASSIO: craftily qualified too, and behold what innovation it","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.41","kind":"speech"},"2.3.42":{"play":"CASSIO: makes here. I am unfortunate in the infirmity and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.42","kind":"speech"},"2.3.43":{"play":"CASSIO: dare not task my weakness with any more.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.43","kind":"speech"},"2.3.44":{"play":"IAGO: What, man! ’Tis a night of revels. The gallants","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.44","kind":"speech"},"2.3.45":{"play":"IAGO: desire it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.45","kind":"speech"},"2.3.46":{"play":"CASSIO: Where are they?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.46","kind":"speech"},"2.3.47":{"play":"IAGO: Here at the door. I pray you, call them in.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.47","kind":"speech"},"2.3.48":{"play":"CASSIO: I’ll do ’t, but it dislikes me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.48","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.48":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.48","kind":"stage"},"2.3.49":{"play":"IAGO: If I can fasten but one cup upon him","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.49","kind":"speech"},"2.3.50":{"play":"IAGO: With that which he hath drunk tonight already,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.50","kind":"speech"},"2.3.51":{"play":"IAGO: He’ll be as full of quarrel and offense","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.51","kind":"speech"},"2.3.52":{"play":"IAGO: As my young mistress’ dog. Now my sick fool","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.52","kind":"speech"},"2.3.53":{"play":"IAGO: Roderigo,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.53","kind":"speech"},"2.3.54":{"play":"IAGO: Whom love hath turned almost the wrong side out,","notes":["cast] Johnson, perhaps forgetting that in I, i, 164, he had given to this word the meaning which is now generally accepted, to dismiss, here interprets it as equivalent to ‘appointed us to our stations. To cast the play' he continues, 'is to assign to every actor his proper part.’ See II, ii, 302, and V, ii, 400, where the meaning to dismiss is equally suitable. Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.54","kind":"speech"},"2.3.55":{"play":"IAGO: To Desdemona hath tonight caroused","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.55","kind":"speech"},"2.3.56":{"play":"IAGO: Potations pottle-deep; and he’s to watch.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.56","kind":"speech"},"2.3.57":{"play":"IAGO: Three else of Cyprus, noble swelling spirits","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.57","kind":"speech"},"2.3.58":{"play":"IAGO: That hold their honors in a wary distance,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.58","kind":"speech"},"2.3.59":{"play":"IAGO: The very elements of this warlike isle,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.59","kind":"speech"},"2.3.60":{"play":"IAGO: Have I tonight flustered with flowing cups;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.60","kind":"speech"},"2.3.61":{"play":"IAGO: And they watch too. Now, ’mongst this flock of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.61","kind":"speech"},"2.3.62":{"play":"IAGO: drunkards","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.62","kind":"speech"},"2.3.63":{"play":"IAGO: Am I to put our Cassio in some action","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.63","kind":"speech"},"2.3.64":{"play":"IAGO: That may offend the isle. But here they come.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.64","kind":"speech"},"2.3.65":{"play":"IAGO: If consequence do but approve my dream,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.65","kind":"speech"},"2.3.66":{"play":"IAGO: My boat sails freely both with wind and stream.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.66","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.66.1":{"play":"[Enter Cassio, Montano, and Gentlemen, followed by Servants with wine.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.66.1","kind":"stage"},"2.3.67":{"play":"CASSIO: ’Fore God, they have given me a rouse","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.67","kind":"speech"},"2.3.68":{"play":"CASSIO: already.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.68","kind":"speech"},"2.3.69":{"play":"MONTANO: Good faith, a little one; not past a pint, as I","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.69","kind":"speech"},"2.3.70":{"play":"MONTANO: am a soldier.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.70","kind":"speech"},"2.3.71":{"play":"IAGO: Some wine, ho!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.71","kind":"speech"},"2.3.77":{"play":"IAGO: Some wine, boys!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.77","kind":"speech"},"2.3.78":{"play":"CASSIO: ’Fore God, an excellent song.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.78","kind":"speech"},"2.3.79":{"play":"IAGO: I learned it in England, where indeed they are","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.79","kind":"speech"},"2.3.80":{"play":"IAGO: most potent in potting. Your Dane, your German,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.80","kind":"speech"},"2.3.81":{"play":"IAGO: and your swag-bellied Hollander—drink, ho!—are","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.81","kind":"speech"},"2.3.82":{"play":"IAGO: nothing to your English.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.82","kind":"speech"},"2.3.83":{"play":"CASSIO: Is your Englishman so exquisite in his","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.83","kind":"speech"},"2.3.84":{"play":"CASSIO: drinking?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.84","kind":"speech"},"2.3.85":{"play":"IAGO: Why, he drinks you, with facility, your Dane","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.85","kind":"speech"},"2.3.86":{"play":"IAGO: dead drunk. He sweats not to overthrow your Almain.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.86","kind":"speech"},"2.3.87":{"play":"IAGO: He gives your Hollander a vomit ere the next","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.87","kind":"speech"},"2.3.88":{"play":"IAGO: pottle can be filled.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.88","kind":"speech"},"2.3.89":{"play":"CASSIO: To the health of our general!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.89","kind":"speech"},"2.3.90":{"play":"MONTANO: I am for it, lieutenant, and I’ll do you","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.90","kind":"speech"},"2.3.91":{"play":"MONTANO: justice.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.91","kind":"speech"},"2.3.92":{"play":"IAGO: O sweet England!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.92","kind":"speech"},"2.3.101":{"play":"IAGO: Some wine, ho!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.101","kind":"speech"},"2.3.102":{"play":"CASSIO: ’Fore God, this is a more exquisite song than","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.102","kind":"speech"},"2.3.103":{"play":"CASSIO: the other!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.103","kind":"speech"},"2.3.104":{"play":"IAGO: Will you hear ’t again?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.104","kind":"speech"},"2.3.105":{"play":"CASSIO: No, for I hold him to be unworthy of his place","notes":["Booth: Iago watches Cassio intently."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.105","kind":"speech"},"2.3.106":{"play":"CASSIO: that does those things. Well, God’s above all; and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.106","kind":"speech"},"2.3.107":{"play":"CASSIO: there be souls must be saved, and there be souls","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.107","kind":"speech"},"2.3.108":{"play":"CASSIO: must not be saved.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.108","kind":"speech"},"2.3.109":{"play":"IAGO: It’s true, good lieutenant.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.109","kind":"speech"},"2.3.110":{"play":"CASSIO: For mine own part—no offense to the General,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.110","kind":"speech"},"2.3.111":{"play":"CASSIO: nor any man of quality—I hope to be saved.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.111","kind":"speech"},"2.3.112":{"play":"IAGO: And so do I too, lieutenant.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.112","kind":"speech"},"2.3.113":{"play":"CASSIO: Ay, but, by your leave, not before me. The","notes":["Alarum] Johnson: The voice may sound an alarm more properly than the eye can sound a parley. Ritson (p. 229): The eye is often said to speak. Thus we frequently hear of the language of the eye. Surely that which can talk may, without any violent stretch of the figure, be allowed to sound a parley. Steevens: So in Tro. & Cress. IV, v, 55: ‘There's language in her eye, her cheek, her lip, Nay, her foot speaks.’ Booth: So in Mer. of Ven. I, i, 164: ‘from her eyes I did receive fair speechless messages.’"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.113","kind":"speech"},"2.3.114":{"play":"CASSIO: Lieutenant is to be saved before the Ancient. Let’s","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.114","kind":"speech"},"2.3.115":{"play":"CASSIO: have no more of this. Let’s to our affairs. God","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.115","kind":"speech"},"2.3.116":{"play":"CASSIO: forgive us our sins! Gentlemen, let’s look to our","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.116","kind":"speech"},"2.3.117":{"play":"CASSIO: business. Do not think, gentlemen, I am drunk. This","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.117","kind":"speech"},"2.3.118":{"play":"CASSIO: is my ancient, this is my right hand, and this is my","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.118","kind":"speech"},"2.3.119":{"play":"CASSIO: left. I am not drunk now. I can stand well enough,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.119","kind":"speech"},"2.3.120":{"play":"CASSIO: and I speak well enough.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.120","kind":"speech"},"2.3.121":{"play":"GENTLEMEN: Excellent well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.121","kind":"speech"},"2.3.122":{"play":"CASSIO: Why, very well then. You must not think then","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.122","kind":"speech"},"2.3.123":{"play":"CASSIO: that I am drunk.","notes":["stope] It occurred to me that the uniformity of spelling in Qq and Ff might here betoken the pronunciation, especially as this form is given by Skeat as Middle English. But a comparison of the five times where the word occurs in Shakespeare shows that no such inference can be drawn. It is 'stoope' in Twelfth Night, II, iii, 14; 'stope,' lb. 129; 'stoupe,' Ham. V, i, 68; 'stopes,' lb. 278. The fact that the spelling agrees in three cases out of the five might at best indicate that the pronunciation was in the transition state from the old to the new. Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.123","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.123":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.123","kind":"stage"},"2.3.124":{"play":"MONTANO: To th’ platform, masters. Come, let’s set the watch.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.124","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.124.1":{"play":"[Gentlemen exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.124.1","kind":"stage"},"2.3.125":{"play":"IAGO: You see this fellow that is gone before?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.125","kind":"speech"},"2.3.126":{"play":"IAGO: He’s a soldier fit to stand by Caesar","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.126","kind":"speech"},"2.3.127":{"play":"IAGO: And give direction; and do but see his vice.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.127","kind":"speech"},"2.3.128":{"play":"IAGO: ’Tis to his virtue a just equinox,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.128","kind":"speech"},"2.3.129":{"play":"IAGO: The one as long as th’ other. ’Tis pity of him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.129","kind":"speech"},"2.3.130":{"play":"IAGO: I fear the trust Othello puts him in,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.130","kind":"speech"},"2.3.131":{"play":"IAGO: On some odd time of his infirmity,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.131","kind":"speech"},"2.3.132":{"play":"IAGO: Will shake this island.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.132","kind":"speech"},"2.3.133":{"play":"MONTANO: But is he often thus?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.133","kind":"speech"},"2.3.134":{"play":"IAGO: ’Tis evermore the prologue to his sleep.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.134","kind":"speech"},"2.3.135":{"play":"IAGO: He’ll watch the horologe a double set","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.135","kind":"speech"},"2.3.136":{"play":"IAGO: If drink rock not his cradle.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.136","kind":"speech"},"2.3.137":{"play":"MONTANO: It were well","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.137","kind":"speech"},"2.3.138":{"play":"MONTANO: The General were put in mind of it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.138","kind":"speech"},"2.3.139":{"play":"MONTANO: Perhaps he sees it not, or his good nature","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.139","kind":"speech"},"2.3.140":{"play":"MONTANO: Prizes the virtue that appears in Cassio","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.140","kind":"speech"},"2.3.141":{"play":"MONTANO: And looks not on his evils. Is not this true?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.141","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.141.1":{"play":"[Enter Roderigo.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.141.1","kind":"stage"},"2.3.142":{"play":"IAGO: How now, Roderigo?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.142","kind":"speech"},"2.3.143":{"play":"IAGO: I pray you, after the Lieutenant, go.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.143","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.143.1":{"play":"[Roderigo exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.143.1","kind":"stage"},"2.3.144":{"play":"MONTANO: And ’tis great pity that the noble Moor","notes":["craftily qualified] Johnson: Slyly mixed with water. [Cannot 'craftily' here mean strongly, powerfully? * I have drunk but one cup, and that was “powerful weak,” too.’ The necessity of his 'qualifying' his cup furtively is not clearly apparent to me, when he confesses the action thus freely to Iago. To be sure, Cassio may have accompanied the confession with a wink to indicate that he thought it a good joke; but this jars a little with my conception of Cassio's character. I prefer to think that he openly and freely qualified that first cup, and the innovation it wrought made him forget to qualify the second among the lads of Cyprus. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.144","kind":"speech"},"2.3.145":{"play":"MONTANO: Should hazard such a place as his own second","notes":["heere] Booth: Merely a flushed face."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.145","kind":"speech"},"2.3.146":{"play":"MONTANO: With one of an engraffed infirmity.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.146","kind":"speech"},"2.3.147":{"play":"MONTANO: It were an honest action to say so","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.147","kind":"speech"},"2.3.148":{"play":"MONTANO: To the Moor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.148","kind":"speech"},"2.3.149":{"play":"IAGO: Not I, for this fair island.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.149","kind":"speech"},"2.3.150":{"play":"IAGO: I do love Cassio well and would do much","notes":["He drink for you] What does this mean? Is it that Iago will use any and every argument, even one as ridiculous as drinking by proxy, to induce Cassio to join the revels? Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.150","kind":"speech"},"2.3.151":{"play":"IAGO: To cure him of this evil—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.151","kind":"speech"},"2.3.152":{"play":"IAGO: But hark! What noise?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.152","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.152.1":{"play":"[Enter Cassio, pursuing Roderigo.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.152.1","kind":"stage"},"2.3.153":{"play":"CASSIO: Zounds, you rogue, you rascal!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.153","kind":"speech"},"2.3.154":{"play":"MONTANO: What’s the matter, lieutenant?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.154","kind":"speech"},"2.3.155":{"play":"CASSIO: A knave teach me my duty? I’ll beat the knave","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.155","kind":"speech"},"2.3.156":{"play":"CASSIO: into a twiggen bottle.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.156","kind":"speech"},"2.3.157":{"play":"RODERIGO: Beat me?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.157","kind":"speech"},"2.3.158":{"play":"CASSIO: Dost thou prate, rogue?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.158","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.158":{"play":"[He hits Roderigo.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.158","kind":"stage"},"2.3.159":{"play":"MONTANO: Nay, good lieutenant. I pray you, sir, hold","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.159","kind":"speech"},"2.3.160":{"play":"MONTANO: your hand.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.160","kind":"speech"},"2.3.161":{"play":"CASSIO: Let me go, sir, or I’ll knock you o’er the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.161","kind":"speech"},"2.3.162":{"play":"CASSIO: mazard.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.162","kind":"speech"},"2.3.163":{"play":"MONTANO: Come, come, you’re drunk.","notes":["it dislikes] For similar instances of the use of impersonal verbs, see Abbot, §297."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.163","kind":"speech"},"2.3.164":{"play":"CASSIO: Drunk?","notes":["one Cup] Booth: This should warn Cassio against overdoing the intoxication."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.164","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.164.1":{"play":"[They fight.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.164.1","kind":"stage"},"2.3.165":{"play":"IAGO: Away, I say! Go out and cry a mutiny.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.165","kind":"speech"},"2.3.166":{"play":"IAGO: Nay, good lieutenant.—God’s will, gentlemen!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.166","kind":"speech"},"2.3.167":{"play":"IAGO: Help, ho! Lieutenant—sir—Montano—sir—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.167","kind":"speech"},"2.3.168":{"play":"IAGO: Help, masters!—Here’s a goodly watch indeed!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.168","kind":"speech"},"2.3.169":{"play":"IAGO: Who’s that which rings the bell? Diablo, ho!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.169","kind":"speech"},"2.3.170":{"play":"IAGO: The town will rise. God’s will, lieutenant, hold!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.170","kind":"speech"},"2.3.171":{"play":"IAGO: You will be shamed forever.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.171","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.171.1":{"play":"[Enter Othello and Attendants.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.171.1","kind":"stage"},"2.3.172":{"play":"OTHELLO: What is the matter here?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.172","kind":"speech"},"2.3.173":{"play":"MONTANO: Zounds, I bleed","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.173","kind":"speech"},"2.3.174":{"play":"MONTANO: still.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.174","kind":"speech"},"2.3.175":{"play":"MONTANO: I am hurt to th’ death. He dies!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.175","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.175":{"play":"[He attacks Cassio.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.175","kind":"stage"},"2.3.176":{"play":"OTHELLO: Hold, for your lives!","notes":["pottle-deepe] Dyce (Gloss.): A pottle was a measure of two quarts ('A Pottle, Quatuor libra liquidorum, congii Anglicani dimidium? Coles's Lat. and Eng. Diet.), but frequently meaning a drinking-vessel without reference to the measure."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.176","kind":"speech"},"2.3.177":{"play":"IAGO: Hold, ho! Lieutenant—sir—Montano—","notes":["else] Delius suggests, with great ingenuity, that this may have been meant for Ls, the abbreviation of Lords. Dyce (ed. iii): In my former edition I followed the Folio (comparing King John, II, i, 276: 'Bastards and else''); but I now think it safer to adhere to the lection of the Qq."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.177","kind":"speech"},"2.3.178":{"play":"IAGO: gentlemen—","notes":["Rolfe: That is, are sensitive with regard to their honour, or quick to take offence at a supposed insult."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.178","kind":"speech"},"2.3.179":{"play":"IAGO: Have you forgot all sense of place and duty?","notes":["Elements] Johnson: As quarrelsome as the discordia semina rerum; as quick in opposition as fire and water. Schmidt (Lex.): A pure extract, as it were, the very quintessence of the isle."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.179","kind":"speech"},"2.3.180":{"play":"IAGO: Hold! The General speaks to you. Hold, for shame!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.180","kind":"speech"},"2.3.181":{"play":"OTHELLO: Why, how now, ho! From whence ariseth this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.181","kind":"speech"},"2.3.182":{"play":"OTHELLO: Are we turned Turks, and to ourselves do that","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.182","kind":"speech"},"2.3.183":{"play":"OTHELLO: Which heaven hath forbid the Ottomites?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.183","kind":"speech"},"2.3.184":{"play":"OTHELLO: For Christian shame, put by this barbarous brawl!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.184","kind":"speech"},"2.3.185":{"play":"OTHELLO: He that stirs next to carve for his own rage","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.185","kind":"speech"},"2.3.186":{"play":"OTHELLO: Holds his soul light; he dies upon his motion.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.186","kind":"speech"},"2.3.187":{"play":"OTHELLO: Silence that dreadful bell. It frights the isle","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.187","kind":"speech"},"2.3.188":{"play":"OTHELLO: From her propriety. What is the matter, masters?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.188","kind":"speech"},"2.3.189":{"play":"OTHELLO: Honest Iago, that looks dead with grieving,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.189","kind":"speech"},"2.3.190":{"play":"OTHELLO: Speak. Who began this? On thy love, I charge thee.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.190","kind":"speech"},"2.3.191":{"play":"IAGO: I do not know. Friends all but now, even now,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.191","kind":"speech"},"2.3.192":{"play":"IAGO: In quarter and in terms like bride and groom","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.192","kind":"speech"},"2.3.193":{"play":"IAGO: Divesting them for bed; and then but now,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.193","kind":"speech"},"2.3.194":{"play":"IAGO: As if some planet had unwitted men,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.194","kind":"speech"},"2.3.195":{"play":"IAGO: Swords out, and tilting one at other’s breast,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.195","kind":"speech"},"2.3.196":{"play":"IAGO: In opposition bloody. I cannot speak","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.196","kind":"speech"},"2.3.197":{"play":"IAGO: Any beginning to this peevish odds,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.197","kind":"speech"},"2.3.198":{"play":"IAGO: And would in action glorious I had lost","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.198","kind":"speech"},"2.3.199":{"play":"IAGO: Those legs that brought me to a part of it!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.199","kind":"speech"},"2.3.200":{"play":"OTHELLO: How comes it, Michael, you are thus forgot?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.200","kind":"speech"},"2.3.201":{"play":"CASSIO: I pray you pardon me; I cannot speak.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.201","kind":"speech"},"2.3.202":{"play":"OTHELLO: Worthy Montano, you were wont be civil.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.202","kind":"speech"},"2.3.203":{"play":"OTHELLO: The gravity and stillness of your youth","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.203","kind":"speech"},"2.3.204":{"play":"OTHELLO: The world hath noted. And your name is great","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.204","kind":"speech"},"2.3.205":{"play":"OTHELLO: In mouths of wisest censure. What’s the matter","notes":["Consequence] An instance of the omission of the plural s in words whose termination has a plural sound. See Walker's Vers. Art. li, p. 243. This line is not there noted. Or see Abbott, §471.","dreame] Theobald suggested and adopted deem, i.e. opinion, judgement. Johnson: I rather read scheme. But why should 'dream' be rejected? Every scheme subsisting only in the imagination may be termed a 'dream.'"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.205","kind":"speech"},"2.3.206":{"play":"OTHELLO: That you unlace your reputation thus,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.206","kind":"speech"},"2.3.207":{"play":"OTHELLO: And spend your rich opinion for the name","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.207","kind":"speech"},"2.3.208":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of a night-brawler? Give me answer to it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.208","kind":"speech"},"2.3.209":{"play":"MONTANO: Worthy Othello, I am hurt to danger.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.209","kind":"speech"},"2.3.210":{"play":"MONTANO: Your officer Iago can inform you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.210","kind":"speech"},"2.3.211":{"play":"MONTANO: While I spare speech, which something now offends","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.211","kind":"speech"},"2.3.212":{"play":"MONTANO: me,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.212","kind":"speech"},"2.3.213":{"play":"MONTANO: Of all that I do know; nor know I aught","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.213","kind":"speech"},"2.3.214":{"play":"MONTANO: By me that’s said or done amiss this night,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.214","kind":"speech"},"2.3.215":{"play":"MONTANO: Unless self-charity be sometimes a vice,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.215","kind":"speech"},"2.3.216":{"play":"MONTANO: And to defend ourselves it be a sin","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.216","kind":"speech"},"2.3.217":{"play":"MONTANO: When violence assails us.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.217","kind":"speech"},"2.3.218":{"play":"OTHELLO: Now, by heaven,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.218","kind":"speech"},"2.3.219":{"play":"OTHELLO: My blood begins my safer guides to rule,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.219","kind":"speech"},"2.3.220":{"play":"OTHELLO: And passion, having my best judgment collied,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.220","kind":"speech"},"2.3.221":{"play":"OTHELLO: Assays to lead the way. Zounds, if I stir,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.221","kind":"speech"},"2.3.222":{"play":"OTHELLO: Or do but lift this arm, the best of you","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.222","kind":"speech"},"2.3.223":{"play":"OTHELLO: Shall sink in my rebuke. Give me to know","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.223","kind":"speech"},"2.3.224":{"play":"OTHELLO: How this foul rout began, who set it on;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.224","kind":"speech"},"2.3.225":{"play":"OTHELLO: And he that is approved in this offense,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.225","kind":"speech"},"2.3.226":{"play":"OTHELLO: Though he had twinned with me, both at a birth,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.226","kind":"speech"},"2.3.227":{"play":"OTHELLO: Shall lose me. What, in a town of war","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.227","kind":"speech"},"2.3.228":{"play":"OTHELLO: Yet wild, the people’s hearts brimful of fear,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.228","kind":"speech"},"2.3.229":{"play":"OTHELLO: To manage private and domestic quarrel,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.229","kind":"speech"},"2.3.230":{"play":"OTHELLO: In night, and on the court and guard of safety?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.230","kind":"speech"},"2.3.231":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Tis monstrous. Iago, who began ’t?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.231","kind":"speech"},"2.3.232":{"play":"MONTANO: If partially affined, or leagued in office,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.232","kind":"speech"},"2.3.233":{"play":"MONTANO: Thou dost deliver more or less than truth,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.233","kind":"speech"},"2.3.234":{"play":"MONTANO: Thou art no soldier.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.234","kind":"speech"},"2.3.235":{"play":"IAGO: Touch me not so near.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.235","kind":"speech"},"2.3.236":{"play":"IAGO: I had rather have this tongue cut from my mouth","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.236","kind":"speech"},"2.3.237":{"play":"IAGO: Than it should do offense to Michael Cassio.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.237","kind":"speech"},"2.3.238":{"play":"IAGO: Yet I persuade myself, to speak the truth","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.238","kind":"speech"},"2.3.239":{"play":"IAGO: Shall nothing wrong him. Thus it is, general:","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.239","kind":"speech"},"2.3.240":{"play":"IAGO: Montano and myself being in speech,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.240","kind":"speech"},"2.3.241":{"play":"IAGO: There comes a fellow crying out for help,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.241","kind":"speech"},"2.3.242":{"play":"IAGO: And Cassio following him with determined sword","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.242","kind":"speech"},"2.3.243":{"play":"IAGO: To execute upon him. Sir, this gentleman","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.243","kind":"speech"},"2.3.244":{"play":"IAGO: Steps in to Cassio and entreats his pause.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.244","kind":"speech"},"2.3.245":{"play":"IAGO: Myself the crying fellow did pursue,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.245","kind":"speech"},"2.3.246":{"play":"IAGO: Lest by his clamor—as it so fell out—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.246","kind":"speech"},"2.3.247":{"play":"IAGO: The town might fall in fright. He, swift of foot,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.247","kind":"speech"},"2.3.248":{"play":"IAGO: Outran my purpose, and I returned the rather","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.248","kind":"speech"},"2.3.249":{"play":"IAGO: For that I heard the clink and fall of swords","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.249","kind":"speech"},"2.3.250":{"play":"IAGO: And Cassio high in oath, which till tonight","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.250","kind":"speech"},"2.3.251":{"play":"IAGO: I ne’er might say before. When I came back—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.251","kind":"speech"},"2.3.252":{"play":"IAGO: For this was brief—I found them close together","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.252","kind":"speech"},"2.3.253":{"play":"IAGO: At blow and thrust, even as again they were","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.253","kind":"speech"},"2.3.254":{"play":"IAGO: When you yourself did part them.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.254","kind":"speech"},"2.3.255":{"play":"IAGO: More of this matter cannot I report.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.255","kind":"speech"},"2.3.256":{"play":"IAGO: But men are men; the best sometimes forget.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.256","kind":"speech"},"2.3.257":{"play":"IAGO: Though Cassio did some little wrong to him,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.257","kind":"speech"},"2.3.258":{"play":"IAGO: As men in rage strike those that wish them best,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.258","kind":"speech"},"2.3.259":{"play":"IAGO: Yet surely Cassio, I believe, received","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.259","kind":"speech"},"2.3.260":{"play":"IAGO: From him that fled some strange indignity","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.260","kind":"speech"},"2.3.261":{"play":"IAGO: Which patience could not pass.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.261","kind":"speech"},"2.3.262":{"play":"OTHELLO: I know, Iago,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.262","kind":"speech"},"2.3.263":{"play":"OTHELLO: Thy honesty and love doth mince this matter,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.263","kind":"speech"},"2.3.264":{"play":"OTHELLO: Making it light to Cassio.—Cassio, I love thee,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.264","kind":"speech"},"2.3.265":{"play":"OTHELLO: But nevermore be officer of mine.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.265","kind":"speech"},"2.3.266":{"play":"OTHELLO: Look if my gentle love be not raised up!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.266","kind":"speech"},"2.3.267":{"play":"OTHELLO: I’ll make thee an example.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.267","kind":"speech"},"2.3.268":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What is the matter, dear?","notes":["Souldier] Steevens: If Montano was Othello's predecessor in the government of Cyprus (as we are told in the Dramatis Personae), he is not very characteristically employed in the present scene, where he is tippling with people already flustered, and encouraging a subaltern officer, who commands a midnight guard, to drink to excess."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.268","kind":"speech"},"2.3.269":{"play":"OTHELLO: All’s well now,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.269","kind":"speech"},"2.3.270":{"play":"OTHELLO: sweeting.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.270","kind":"speech"},"2.3.271":{"play":"OTHELLO: Come away to bed. Sir, for your hurts,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.271","kind":"speech"},"2.3.272":{"play":"OTHELLO: Myself will be your surgeon.—Lead him off.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.272","kind":"speech"},"2.3.273":{"play":"OTHELLO: Iago, look with care about the town","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.273","kind":"speech"},"2.3.274":{"play":"OTHELLO: And silence those whom this vile brawl","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.274","kind":"speech"},"2.3.275":{"play":"OTHELLO: distracted.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.275","kind":"speech"},"2.3.276":{"play":"OTHELLO: Come, Desdemona. ’Tis the soldier’s life","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.276","kind":"speech"},"2.3.277":{"play":"OTHELLO: To have their balmy slumbers waked with strife.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.277","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.277.1":{"play":"[All but Iago and Cassio exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.277.1","kind":"stage"},"2.3.278":{"play":"IAGO: What, are you hurt, lieutenant?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.278","kind":"speech"},"2.3.279":{"play":"CASSIO: Ay, past all surgery.","notes":["clinke, clinke] Halliwell: This song appears to be referred to in The Knave in Grain new Vampt, 1640: 'Fub. The drawers have drawne him out, sir. Lod. Clinke, boyes.—Toma. Drinke, boys. Stult. And let the cannikin clinke, boyes.' The song itself does not appear to have been discovered. [This allusion I cannot find in Ingle-Dy's Centurie of Prayse.—Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.279","kind":"speech"},"2.3.280":{"play":"IAGO: Marry, God forbid!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.280","kind":"speech"},"2.3.281":{"play":"CASSIO: Reputation, reputation, reputation! O, I have","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.281","kind":"speech"},"2.3.282":{"play":"CASSIO: lost my reputation! I have lost the immortal part of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.282","kind":"speech"},"2.3.283":{"play":"CASSIO: myself, and what remains is bestial. My reputation,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.283","kind":"speech"},"2.3.284":{"play":"CASSIO: Iago, my reputation!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.284","kind":"speech"},"2.3.285":{"play":"IAGO: As I am an honest man, I thought you had","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.285","kind":"speech"},"2.3.286":{"play":"IAGO: received some bodily wound. There is more sense","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.286","kind":"speech"},"2.3.287":{"play":"IAGO: in that than in reputation. Reputation is an idle and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.287","kind":"speech"},"2.3.288":{"play":"IAGO: most false imposition, oft got without merit and lost","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.288","kind":"speech"},"2.3.289":{"play":"IAGO: without deserving. You have lost no reputation at","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.289","kind":"speech"},"2.3.290":{"play":"IAGO: all, unless you repute yourself such a loser. What,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.290","kind":"speech"},"2.3.291":{"play":"IAGO: man, there are ways to recover the General again!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.291","kind":"speech"},"2.3.292":{"play":"IAGO: You are but now cast in his mood—a punishment","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.292","kind":"speech"},"2.3.293":{"play":"IAGO: more in policy than in malice, even so as one would","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.293","kind":"speech"},"2.3.294":{"play":"IAGO: beat his offenseless dog to affright an imperious","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.294","kind":"speech"},"2.3.295":{"play":"IAGO: lion. Sue to him again and he’s yours.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.295","kind":"speech"},"2.3.296":{"play":"CASSIO: I will rather sue to be despised than to deceive","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.296","kind":"speech"},"2.3.297":{"play":"CASSIO: so good a commander with so slight, so drunken,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.297","kind":"speech"},"2.3.298":{"play":"CASSIO: and so indiscreet an officer. Drunk? And speak","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.298","kind":"speech"},"2.3.299":{"play":"CASSIO: parrot? And squabble? Swagger? Swear? And discourse","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.299","kind":"speech"},"2.3.300":{"play":"CASSIO: fustian with one’s own shadow? O thou","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.300","kind":"speech"},"2.3.301":{"play":"CASSIO: invisible spirit of wine, if thou hast no name to be","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.301","kind":"speech"},"2.3.302":{"play":"CASSIO: known by, let us call thee devil!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.302","kind":"speech"},"2.3.303":{"play":"IAGO: What was he that you followed with your sword?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.303","kind":"speech"},"2.3.304":{"play":"IAGO: What had he done to you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.304","kind":"speech"},"2.3.305":{"play":"CASSIO: I know not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.305","kind":"speech"},"2.3.306":{"play":"IAGO: Is ’t possible?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.306","kind":"speech"},"2.3.307":{"play":"CASSIO: I remember a mass of things, but nothing","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.307","kind":"speech"},"2.3.308":{"play":"CASSIO: distinctly; a quarrel, but nothing wherefore. O","notes":["'The habit which he [Kean] had acquired in early life, and which led to such important results, viz.: that of closely observing the expression of the human face whenever he had the opportunity, continued with him to the last. It was in a room at the Castle one night that he was asked by a friend when he studied? Indicating a man on the other side of the room, who was very much intoxicated, but who was labouring to keep up an appearance of sobriety, he replied, \"I am studying now. I wish some of my Cassios were here. They might see that, instead of rolling about in the ridiculous manner they do, the great secret of delineating intoxication is the endeavour to stand straight when it is impossible to do so. The only man who ever played the drunken scene in Othello properly was Holland.\"' Hawkins's Life of Kean, vol. ii, p. 360."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.308","kind":"speech"},"2.3.309":{"play":"CASSIO: God, that men should put an enemy in their","notes":["Englishmen] Steevens: This accomplishment in the English is likewise mentioned in B. and F.'s The Captain [III, ii, p. 267, ed. Dyce]: ‘Lod. Are the Englishmen Such stubborn drinkers? Piso. Not a leak at sea Can suck more liquor; you shall have their children Christen’d in mull’d sack, and, at five years old, Able to knock a Dane down.’ Singer (ed. ii): Peacham, in his Compleat Gentleman, [1622, p. 193,] has a section entitled, 'Drinking the Plague of our English Gentry,' in which he says, 'Within these fiftie or threescore yeares it was a rare thing with us to see a drunken man, our nation carrying the name of the most sober and temperate of any other in the world. But since we had to doe in the quarrell of the Netherlands .... the custom of drinking and pledging healthes was brought over into England; wherein let the Dutch be their owne judges, if we equall them not; yea I think rather excell them.'"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.309","kind":"speech"},"2.3.310":{"play":"CASSIO: mouths to steal away their brains! That we should","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.310","kind":"speech"},"2.3.311":{"play":"CASSIO: with joy, pleasance, revel, and applause transform","notes":["sinnes] Booth: The traditional 'business,' said to be Charles Kemble's, cannot be improved upon. Cassio drops his handkerchief, and in his effort to recover it, falls on his knees; to account for this position to his companions, he attempts to pray. His clothes being awry, his sword has slipped to his right side, and this confuses him for a moment as to which is his right or his left hand. Whatever you do here, do it delicately and with great seriousness, and show a readiness to fight any one who thinks you're drunk. The more dignified your manner, the more absurd and yet correct your performance will be."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.311","kind":"speech"},"2.3.312":{"play":"CASSIO: ourselves into beasts!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.312","kind":"speech"},"2.3.313":{"play":"IAGO: Why, but you are now well enough. How came","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.313","kind":"speech"},"2.3.314":{"play":"IAGO: you thus recovered?","notes":["Booth: Montano enters here, in time to witness Cassio's conduct as he goes off."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.314","kind":"speech"},"2.3.315":{"play":"CASSIO: It hath pleased the devil drunkenness to give","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.315","kind":"speech"},"2.3.316":{"play":"CASSIO: place to the devil wrath. One unperfectness shows","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.316","kind":"speech"},"2.3.317":{"play":"CASSIO: me another, to make me frankly despise myself.","notes":["trust] D'Hugues: On a juge avec raison qu'une pareille exhibition de crapule n'etait pas absolument necessaire a la marche ni a l'intelligence du drame, et que Shakespeare aurait aussi bien fait de supprimer toute cette scene."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.317","kind":"speech"},"2.3.318":{"play":"IAGO: Come, you are too severe a moraler. As the time,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.318","kind":"speech"},"2.3.319":{"play":"IAGO: the place, and the condition of this country stands,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.319","kind":"speech"},"2.3.320":{"play":"IAGO: I could heartily wish this had not so befallen. But","notes":["Equinox] Rolfe: Equal, counterpart; the only instance of the word in Shakespeare."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.320","kind":"speech"},"2.3.321":{"play":"IAGO: since it is as it is, mend it for your own good.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.321","kind":"speech"},"2.3.322":{"play":"CASSIO: I will ask him for my place again; he shall tell","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.322","kind":"speech"},"2.3.323":{"play":"CASSIO: me I am a drunkard! Had I as many mouths as","notes":["puts him in] Dyce (ed. iii) quotes Lettsom's approval of Capell's emendation: puts in him. [I think that change is needless and the Folio is right. The 'trust' that Othello put Cassio in was that of being Othello's 'own second,' referred to in line 159. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.323","kind":"speech"},"2.3.324":{"play":"CASSIO: Hydra, such an answer would stop them all. To be","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.324","kind":"speech"},"2.3.325":{"play":"CASSIO: now a sensible man, by and by a fool, and presently","notes":["Horologe] Johnson: If he have no drink, he'll keep awake while the clock strikes two rounds, or four and twenty hours. Halliwell quotes a description by Admiral Smyth of an ancient clock, wherein the dial is described as 'divided into 24 hours, in two portions of 12 each, as was customary on the clockfaces of those days.' [This starts the question whether a 'double set' is twice twelve or twice twenty-four; Halpin [Dram. Unities, p. 18) affirms that as 'the Italian horologe numbers upon its dial-plate twenty-four hours, a \"double set\" or round, i.e. forty-eight hours, is the true time meant.' It is, however, of small moment here; Iago is not to be taken literally as to the very hours and minutes of Cassio's watchfulness. To Halpin the term is important; on it he bases his theory as to the limit of a dramatic action. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.325","kind":"speech"},"2.3.326":{"play":"CASSIO: a beast! O, strange! Every inordinate cup is unblessed,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.326","kind":"speech"},"2.3.327":{"play":"CASSIO: and the ingredient is a devil.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.327","kind":"speech"},"2.3.328":{"play":"IAGO: Come, come, good wine is a good familiar creature,","notes":["ingraft] Johnson: An infirmity rooted, settled in his constitution. Henley: This explanation seems to fall short of the poet's meaning. The qualities of a tree are so changed by being engrafted, that its future fruits are not such as would have naturally sprung from the stock, but derive their qualities from the graft inserted in it. Conformably to this idea is the assertion of Hamlet concerning the same vice of his countrymen. Malone: Johnson's explanation is certainly just. So in Lear, I, i, 295; 'the imperfections of long-engrafted condition.' See Abbott, § 342, for other instances of tie omission of the participial -ed after t. Booth: This is not the language of one who had taken part in the carouse."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.328","kind":"speech"},"2.3.329":{"play":"IAGO: if it be well used. Exclaim no more against it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.329","kind":"speech"},"2.3.330":{"play":"IAGO: And, good lieutenant, I think you think I love you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.330","kind":"speech"},"2.3.331":{"play":"CASSIO: I have well approved it, sir.—I drunk!","notes":["Sir Montano] KNIGHT: Iago is pretending to separate the lieutenant and Montano, but he is not familiar with Montano, the ex-governor, and he gives him a title of courtesy."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.331","kind":"speech"},"2.3.332":{"play":"IAGO: You or any man living may be drunk at a time,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.332","kind":"speech"},"2.3.333":{"play":"IAGO: man. I’ll tell you what you shall do. Our general’s","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.333","kind":"speech"},"2.3.334":{"play":"IAGO: wife is now the general: I may say so in this","notes":["You'le be asham'd for euer] Dyce pronounces this line, as compared with the Qq, 'most ridiculous.' It does not make me laugh. Indeed, to me, it is as much better than the Qq as an appeal to a man's own self-respect is higher than an appeal to the opinion the world may have of him. Unfortunately, we must not forget that it is Iago who utters it. Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.334","kind":"speech"},"2.3.335":{"play":"IAGO: respect, for that he hath devoted and given up","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.335","kind":"speech"},"2.3.336":{"play":"IAGO: himself to the contemplation, mark, and denotement","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.336","kind":"speech"},"2.3.337":{"play":"IAGO: of her parts and graces. Confess yourself","notes":["He dies] Malone: The editor of the Folio, thinking it necessary to omit the first word of the line, absurdly supplied its place by adding these words at the end of the line. Tollet: Montano thinks he is mortally wounded, yet by these words he seems determined to continue the duel and to kill his antagonist, Cassio. So, when Roderigo runs at Cassio in Act V, he says: 'Villain, thou diest.' Steevens: That is, he shall die. He may be supposed to say this as he is offering to renew the fight. Thus, Othello in his very next speech: 'he dies upon his motion.' I do not therefore regard these words, when uttered by Montano, as an absurd addition in F. Knight and Delius give the same explanation as Toilet's. Collier: These words are, in fact, nothing more than a printer's blunder, which F2 corrects by making Montano say, 'I am hurt, but not to the death.' The true stage direction, for which 'He dies' was, no doubt, intended, is found in Q2, 'He faints.' [It is not easy here to decide between the rival claims. As stage directions there are objections both to 'He dies' and 'He faints.' Assuredly Montano does not die; and it is difficult to see with what propriety a man who had fainted could be adjured to stop fighting, both by Othello and Iago. If these words be not a stage direction, but a part of the text, there is to Toilet's interpretation this objection, viz.: that Montano was acting throughout in self-defence, as he himself tells Othello, line 227, which he would have scarcely presumed to assert had he renewed the attack with such bitterness before Othello's very eyes. This is one of the passages, I think, where it will not do to inquire too closely. The dramatic action demands a barbarous brawl, in which Montano shall be worsted, and latitude is given to the actors to portray the extent of his discomfiture. I am not sure that Cowden-Clarke's course of omitting the words altogether be not the wisest. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.337","kind":"speech"},"2.3.338":{"play":"IAGO: freely to her. Importune her help to put you in your","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.338","kind":"speech"},"2.3.339":{"play":"IAGO: place again. She is of so free, so kind, so apt, so","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.339","kind":"speech"},"2.3.340":{"play":"IAGO: blessed a disposition she holds it a vice in her","notes":["hold for shame] Walker's Versification, Art. ii, p. 295."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.340","kind":"speech"},"2.3.341":{"play":"IAGO: goodness not to do more than she is requested. This","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.341","kind":"speech"},"2.3.342":{"play":"IAGO: broken joint between you and her husband entreat","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.342","kind":"speech"},"2.3.343":{"play":"IAGO: her to splinter, and, my fortunes against any lay","notes":["Booth: Iago should go to assist Cassio, hoping that he is hurt. The Gentlemen enter in time to care for Montano, whom they place on the seat where Desdemona sat."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.343","kind":"speech"},"2.3.344":{"play":"IAGO: worth naming, this crack of your love shall grow","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.344","kind":"speech"},"2.3.345":{"play":"IAGO: stronger than it was before.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.345","kind":"speech"},"2.3.346":{"play":"CASSIO: You advise me well.","notes":["dreadful bell] Walker (Crit. ii, 78) cites this as an instance of the use of ‘dreadful’ in an active sense, as in Ham. I, ii, 207: ‘This to me in dreadful secrecy impart they did.’ Malone: When David Rizzio was murdered in Edinburgh, the Provost ordered the common bell to be rung, and five hundred persons were immediately assembled. So in Peacham's Valley of Varietie, where he is speaking of the use of bells, 'they call for helpe when houses in cities and townes are on fire; or when there is any mutinie or uproare.' Halliwell: At the poet's native town, Stratford-on-Avon, it has been the practice from time immemorial to ring the bell of the Guild chapel on the alarm of fire being given. Alger [Life of Forrest, i, 308): From the general group he [Forrest as Othello] turned to a single attendant who stood at his elbow, and delivered the command in a subdued tone, as though it were not intended for the ear of the multitude. Ottley (Fechter's Version, &c, p. 19): This command Fechter almost screams in passion, rushing up the stage the while. Kean gave it calmly and authoritatively, as a thing of course, and 'more in sorrow than in anger.'"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.346","kind":"speech"},"2.3.347":{"play":"IAGO: I protest, in the sincerity of love and honest","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.347","kind":"speech"},"2.3.348":{"play":"IAGO: kindness.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.348","kind":"speech"},"2.3.349":{"play":"CASSIO: I think it freely; and betimes in the morning I","notes":["propriety] Johnson: From her regular and proper state."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.349","kind":"speech"},"2.3.350":{"play":"CASSIO: will beseech the virtuous Desdemona to undertake","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.350","kind":"speech"},"2.3.351":{"play":"CASSIO: for me. I am desperate of my fortunes if they check","notes":["lookes] An instance (cited by Walker, CWL ii, 132) of s substituted for st in the second person singular of the verb. Compare IV, ii, 207; V, ii, 79; and two other striking instances: Ham. I, iv, 53: ‘That thou .... Revisits thus the glimpses,’ &c., and Lear, IV, vi, 160: ‘Thou hotly lusts to use her,’ &c. I think this usage should be observed in even modern editions, when to give the full grammatical form would result in harshness. Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.351","kind":"speech"},"2.3.352":{"play":"CASSIO: me here.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.352","kind":"speech"},"2.3.353":{"play":"IAGO: You are in the right. Good night, lieutenant. I","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.353","kind":"speech"},"2.3.354":{"play":"IAGO: must to the watch.","notes":["Quarter] Johnson: In their quarters; at their lodging. Malone: That is, on our station. So in Timon, V, iv, 60: ‘not a man Shall pass his quarter.’ Their station or 'quarter' in the present instance was the guardroom in Othello's castle. It cannot mean lodgings, for Montano and the Gentlemen had continued, from the time of their entrance, in the apartment of Othello's castle, in which the carousal had been and Cassio had only gone forth for a short time to set the watch. On his return from the platform to the apartment he meets Roderigo, and the scuffle ensues. Ritson (p. 230): Rather, at peace, quiet, or, as Johnson elsewhere explains it, 'in friendship, amity, concord.' They had been on that very spot (the court or platform before the castle) ever since Othello left them, which can scarcely be called being in their quarters or at their lodging. And, indeed, they could not have left it without being guilty of another offence, as they were directed by Othello to keep the watch. Henley denies that the phrase ever meant in quiet, at peace; it is evident, he says, that the 'quarter' referred to was that apartment of the castle assigned to the officers on guard, where Othello, after giving Cassio his orders, had, a little before, left him; and where Iago, with his companions, immediately found him. Pye (p. 331): This word, in the military language of the present day at least, seems to have no very precise meaning; but the meaning on our station seems the leading signification, for the principal camp-guard of a regiment is called the quarter guard; but a regiment in quarters has no such guard."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.354","kind":"speech"},"2.3.355":{"play":"CASSIO: Good night, honest Iago.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.355","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.355":{"play":"[Cassio exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.355","kind":"stage"},"2.3.356":{"play":"IAGO: And what’s he, then, that says I play the villain,","notes":["oddes] Staunton: Headstrong or perverse quarrel."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.356","kind":"speech"},"2.3.357":{"play":"IAGO: When this advice is free I give and honest,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.357","kind":"speech"},"2.3.358":{"play":"IAGO: Probal to thinking, and indeed the course","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.358","kind":"speech"},"2.3.359":{"play":"IAGO: To win the Moor again? For ’tis most easy","notes":["wont to be] Abbott, §349, following indirectly the text of the Qq, wont be, cites it as an instance of the omission of to of the infinitive, which, of course, it may be; but the presence of ‘to’ in the Ff shows that in the Qq it may be merely an instance of the absorption of the to in the t final of ‘wont.’ Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.359","kind":"speech"},"2.3.360":{"play":"IAGO: Th’ inclining Desdemona to subdue","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.360","kind":"speech"},"2.3.361":{"play":"IAGO: In any honest suit. She’s framed as fruitful","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.361","kind":"speech"},"2.3.362":{"play":"IAGO: As the free elements. And then for her","notes":["vnlace] Johnson: Slacken, or loosen. Put in danger of dropping; or perhaps strip off its ornaments."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.362","kind":"speech"},"2.3.363":{"play":"IAGO: To win the Moor—were ’t to renounce his baptism,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.363","kind":"speech"},"2.3.364":{"play":"IAGO: All seals and symbols of redeemèd sin—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.364","kind":"speech"},"2.3.365":{"play":"IAGO: His soul is so enfettered to her love","notes":["spend] Johnson: Throw away and squander a reputation so valuable as yours."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.365","kind":"speech"},"2.3.366":{"play":"IAGO: That she may make, unmake, do what she list,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.366","kind":"speech"},"2.3.367":{"play":"IAGO: Even as her appetite shall play the god","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.367","kind":"speech"},"2.3.368":{"play":"IAGO: With his weak function. How am I then a villain","notes":["Booth: Montano is still seated, supported by gentlemen, one of whom staunches the wound."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.368","kind":"speech"},"2.3.369":{"play":"IAGO: To counsel Cassio to this parallel course","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.369","kind":"speech"},"2.3.370":{"play":"IAGO: Directly to his good? Divinity of hell!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.370","kind":"speech"},"2.3.371":{"play":"IAGO: When devils will the blackest sins put on,","notes":["collied] Steevens: That is, passion having discoloured his judgement. To colly anciently signified to besmul, to blacken as with coal. Malone: Cole in his Diet., 1679, renders ‘collozv'd by denigratus; to colly, denigro.' Collier (ed. ii): Quelled, i.e. subdued or conquered, is precisely the word wanted, and we find it in the (MS). It is to be remarked that if short-hand were employed in obtaining the copy of Othello for the publisher, the very same letters which spell quelled would also spell 'collied,' and even coold. Singer (Sh. Vind., p. 283): To quell is never used by Shakespeare in any other sense than that of killing or exterminating. I pity the man who could for a moment think of displacing the effective, and now consecrated, word 'collied.' Its obvious meaning is darkened, obfuscated; and a more appropriate and expressive word could not have been used. Dyce (Strictures, &c, p. 199), after referring to the use of 'collied' in Mid. N. D. I, i, 145, and after citing with approval what Singer says of the uniform meaning of quell in Shakespeare, and after quoting what Collier says about short-hand spelling, goes on to say: Yet no one knows better than Mr Collier that the Othello of F, which has the reading 'collied,' was, beyond all doubt, printed from a transcript belonging to the theatre, and that in stage-copies of plays (whether intended for the use of the prompter or of the actors) short-hand was never employed. [Italics, Dyce's.] Keightley [Exp. p. 302): Quelled is not so absurd as Singer thinks it. D'Hugues: On s'etonne qu' Othello puisse trouver de si belles metaphores pour exprimer sa colere, au moment même où il commence à la ressentir."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.371","kind":"speech"},"2.3.372":{"play":"IAGO: They do suggest at first with heavenly shows,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.372","kind":"speech"},"2.3.373":{"play":"IAGO: As I do now. For whiles this honest fool","notes":["loose] Jennens: That is, be loose from me, or disjoined. Knight: The same word as lose, but differently applied. By the employment of lose we destroy the force of ‘Though he had twinn'd with me.’"],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.373","kind":"speech"},"2.3.374":{"play":"IAGO: Plies Desdemona to repair his fortune,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.374","kind":"speech"},"2.3.375":{"play":"IAGO: And she for him pleads strongly to the Moor,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.375","kind":"speech"},"2.3.376":{"play":"IAGO: I’ll pour this pestilence into his ear:","notes":["Court and Guard of safetie] Theobald: Guard of safety, though coupled with a word of synonymous construction, was never soldiers' language. I have ventured to make the conjunction and sign of the genitive case change places. So, ‘Court of Guard,’ II, i, 251; ‘look to the Guard,’ II, ii, 16, and ‘bear him to the Court of Guard,’ Ant. & Cleo. IV, ix, 32. Malone: A similar mistake occurs in 'all place of sense and duty,' line 191. 'Court of guard' is established as a technical term by the uniform usage of the poets of Shakespeare's time. The court of safety may, in a metaphorical sense, be understood; but who ever talked of the guard (i.e. the safety) of safety? Steevens: As a collocation of words, as seemingly perverse, occurs in Mid. N. D. Ill, 1, 192, 'I shall desire you of more acquaintance,' I forbear to disturb the text. If Safety, like the Roman Salus, or Recovery in Lear, be personified, where is the impropriety of saying, under the guard of Safety? Thus, Plautus, in his Captivi: 'Neque jam servare Salus, si vult, me potest.' Dyce (ed. iii): Steevens defends the old reading not very satisfactorily. Cowden-Clarke: The text of the Ff means, in the very spot and guarding-place of safety."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.376","kind":"speech"},"2.3.377":{"play":"IAGO: That she repeals him for her body’s lust;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.377","kind":"speech"},"2.3.378":{"play":"IAGO: And by how much she strives to do him good,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.378","kind":"speech"},"2.3.379":{"play":"IAGO: She shall undo her credit with the Moor.","notes":["Affin'd] Steevens: Affin'd is, bound by proximity of relationship; but here it means related by nearness of office. In I, i, 42, it is used in the former sense. Staunton: If, bound by partiality. Booth: Montano should be in total ignorance of the cause of the disturbance."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.379","kind":"speech"},"2.3.380":{"play":"IAGO: So will I turn her virtue into pitch,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.380","kind":"speech"},"2.3.381":{"play":"IAGO: And out of her own goodness make the net","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.381","kind":"speech"},"2.3.382":{"play":"IAGO: That shall enmesh them all.","notes":["tongue cut from my mouth] Steevens: See note on V, ii, 30."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.382","kind":"speech"},"2.3.383":{"play":"IAGO: How now, Roderigo?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.383","kind":"speech"},"2.3.384":{"play":"RODERIGO: I do follow here in the chase, not like a","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.384","kind":"speech"},"2.3.385":{"play":"RODERIGO: hound that hunts, but one that fills up the cry. My","notes":["sense] Knight: The sense of a wound is its sensibility."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.385","kind":"speech"},"2.3.386":{"play":"RODERIGO: money is almost spent, I have been tonight exceedingly","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.386","kind":"speech"},"2.3.387":{"play":"RODERIGO: well cudgeled, and I think the issue will be I","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.387","kind":"speech"},"2.3.388":{"play":"RODERIGO: shall have so much experience for my pains, and so,","notes":["You have lost no Reputation] DuBois (Wreath, p. 72) cites parallel passages from Menander in Plutarch: O vfiev 7ποίησας δεῖν βον, ἀν μὴ προσωπία—Thou hast suffered no wrong, unless thou dost fancy so. Also Epictetus, Enchirid., c. 31: ἐὰν φίλος οὐ βλάπῃ, ἑαυτὸν βλάπτεται.—No one will hurt thee, unless thou art willing he should. For then only wilt thou be hurt, when thou dost think thyself hurt. Also Marcus Antoninus, B. 7, § 14: Ἐγώ δέ, ἐὰν μὴ ὑπολάβω ὅτι κακόν τὸ συμβεβηκός, οὔπω βέβλαμμαι.—Unless I myself think that which happens an evil, I am still unhurt."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.388","kind":"speech"},"2.3.389":{"play":"RODERIGO: with no money at all and a little more wit, return","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.389","kind":"speech"},"2.3.390":{"play":"RODERIGO: again to Venice.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.390","kind":"speech"},"2.3.391":{"play":"IAGO: How poor are they that have not patience!","notes":["more wayes to recouer] Booth: This speech is not meant to be cold comfort; Iago shows concern."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.391","kind":"speech"},"2.3.392":{"play":"IAGO: What wound did ever heal but by degrees?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.392","kind":"speech"},"2.3.393":{"play":"IAGO: Thou know’st we work by wit and not by witchcraft,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.393","kind":"speech"},"2.3.394":{"play":"IAGO: And wit depends on dilatory time.","notes":["pleasance] Morel: Marot chez nous disait encore au seizieme siecle 'les plaisances mondaines,' et le mot nous est resté dans les expressions telles que, maison de plaisance, bateau de plaisance."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.394","kind":"speech"},"2.3.395":{"play":"IAGO: Does ’t not go well? Cassio hath beaten thee,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.395","kind":"speech"},"2.3.396":{"play":"IAGO: And thou, by that small hurt, hast cashiered Cassio.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.396","kind":"speech"},"2.3.397":{"play":"IAGO: Though other things grow fair against the sun,","notes":["Ingredient] Grant White, Studies in Shakespeare: For this, see \"ingredience\" in Macb. I, vii, II."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.397","kind":"speech"},"2.3.398":{"play":"IAGO: Yet fruits that blossom first will first be ripe.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.398","kind":"speech"},"2.3.399":{"play":"IAGO: Content thyself awhile. By th’ Mass, ’tis morning!","notes":["familiar] Morel: C'est le mot 'devil,' employé par Cassio, qui provoque cette ironique repartie."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.399","kind":"speech"},"2.3.400":{"play":"IAGO: Pleasure and action make the hours seem short.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.400","kind":"speech"},"2.3.401":{"play":"IAGO: Retire thee; go where thou art billeted.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.401","kind":"speech"},"2.3.402":{"play":"IAGO: Away, I say! Thou shalt know more hereafter.","notes":["time man Abbott: An instance of the earlier English “a time” standing for “one time”."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.402","kind":"speech"},"2.3.403":{"play":"IAGO: Nay, get thee gone.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.403","kind":"speech"},"2.3.404":{"play":"IAGO: Two things are to be done.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.404","kind":"speech"},"2.3.405":{"play":"IAGO: My wife must move for Cassio to her mistress.","notes":["devotement Theobald: I cannot persuade myself that our Poet would ever have said any one devoted himself to the devotement of anything. The mistake certainly arose from a single letter being turned upside-down at press. The three words, Contemplation, mark, and denotement, are, indeed, in some degree tautological, but the practice is allowed for the sake of energy."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.405","kind":"speech"},"2.3.406":{"play":"IAGO: I’ll set her on.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.406","kind":"speech"},"2.3.407":{"play":"IAGO: Myself the while to draw the Moor apart","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.407","kind":"speech"},"2.3.408":{"play":"IAGO: And bring him jump when he may Cassio find","notes":["splinter Dyce: To secure by splints."],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.408","kind":"speech"},"2.3.409":{"play":"IAGO: Soliciting his wife. Ay, that’s the way.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.409","kind":"speech"},"2.3.410":{"play":"IAGO: Dull not device by coldness and delay.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"2.3.410","kind":"speech"},"SD_2.3.410.1":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":["awl'd] This, the solitary indication of an unusual pronunciation, points, I imagine, to a rustic rather than to a purely Scotch origin, although Capell seems to assume that the whole ballad is Scottish. Speaking of the line in which this word occurs, Capell, in one of his characteristic notes, says that the usual version, 'something unscotifies it to it's injury: (a) in \"take\" and what is call'd the diphthong in \"auld\" should have the Scottish twang with them, namely—our [ah) sounded broader; and to make out the line's Iambi, the first syllable of \"about\" must have a small thesis, and \"thee\" a full one.'—Ed.","lay Ritson: Any bet, any wager."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 2.3.410.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 3, SCENE 1":{"SD_3.1.0":{"play":"[Enter Cassio with Musicians.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.1.0","kind":"stage"},"3.1.1":{"play":"CASSIO: Masters, play here (I will content your pains)","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.1","kind":"speech"},"3.1.2":{"play":"CASSIO: Something that’s brief; and bid","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.2","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.1.3":{"play":"[They play.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.1.3","kind":"stage"},"SD_3.1.3.1":{"play":"[Enter the Clown.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.1.3.1","kind":"stage"},"3.1.4":{"play":"CLOWN: Why masters, have your instruments been in","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.4","kind":"speech"},"3.1.5":{"play":"CLOWN: Naples, that they speak i’ th’ nose thus?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.5","kind":"speech"},"3.1.6":{"play":"MUSICIAN: How, sir, how?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.6","kind":"speech"},"3.1.7":{"play":"CLOWN: Are these, I pray you, wind instruments?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.7","kind":"speech"},"3.1.8":{"play":"MUSICIAN: Ay, marry, are they, sir.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.8","kind":"speech"},"3.1.9":{"play":"CLOWN: O, thereby hangs a tail.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.9","kind":"speech"},"3.1.10":{"play":"MUSICIAN: Whereby hangs a tale, sir?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.10","kind":"speech"},"3.1.11":{"play":"CLOWN: Marry, sir, by many a wind instrument that I","notes":["Knight: The Qto has the prettier phrase. [See Abbott, §169, for other instances where of is used in appeals.]"],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.11","kind":"speech"},"3.1.12":{"play":"CLOWN: know. But, masters, here’s money for you; and the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.12","kind":"speech"},"3.1.13":{"play":"CLOWN: General so likes your music that he desires you, for","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.13","kind":"speech"},"3.1.14":{"play":"CLOWN: love’s sake, to make no more noise with it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.14","kind":"speech"},"3.1.15":{"play":"MUSICIAN: Well, sir, we will not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.15","kind":"speech"},"3.1.16":{"play":"CLOWN: If you have any music that may not be heard, to","notes":["White: Is there a pun here? White (ed. ii) says that 'in \"the Generall\" we have a punning allusion to the indifference of the general public to music,' and I think one pun is quite as likely, or as unlikely, as the other. Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.16","kind":"speech"},"3.1.17":{"play":"CLOWN: ’t again. But, as they say, to hear music the General","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.17","kind":"speech"},"3.1.18":{"play":"CLOWN: does not greatly care.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.18","kind":"speech"},"3.1.19":{"play":"MUSICIAN: We have none such, sir.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.19","kind":"speech"},"3.1.20":{"play":"CLOWN: Then put up your pipes in your bag, for I’ll","notes":["Ritson: This must be wrong; possibly—fly away. [An unknown former owner of my copy of Jennens has here queried on the margin, fore all, away, which is both ingenious and plausible. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.20","kind":"speech"},"3.1.21":{"play":"CLOWN: away. Go, vanish into air, away!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.21","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.1.21.1":{"play":"[Musicians exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.1.21.1","kind":"stage"},"3.1.22":{"play":"CASSIO: Dost thou hear, mine honest friend?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.22","kind":"speech"},"3.1.23":{"play":"CLOWN: No, I hear not your honest friend. I hear you.","notes":["Malone: Nice and frivolous distinctions. [See Ham. V, i, 94]."],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.23","kind":"speech"},"3.1.24":{"play":"CASSIO: Prithee, keep up thy quillets.","notes":["Delius: A pedantic, affected phrase which the Clown purposely uses, and in such a way as to leave it uncertain that he himself understood it."],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.24","kind":"speech"},"3.1.25":{"play":"CASSIO: There’s a poor piece of gold for thee. If the gentlewoman","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.25","kind":"speech"},"3.1.26":{"play":"CASSIO: that attends the General’s wife be stirring,","notes":["These lines are, of course, prose. In the Globe Edition they chance to divide at 'hither.' White overlooked this, and, in printing his second edition from the Globe, has in his own text retained the division at 'hither' and printed as verse. 1 To err: ;.\" and no divineness is needed to forgive so venial a slip as this. Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.26","kind":"speech"},"3.1.27":{"play":"CASSIO: tell her there’s one Cassio entreats her a little favor","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.27","kind":"speech"},"3.1.28":{"play":"CASSIO: of speech. Wilt thou do this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.28","kind":"speech"},"3.1.29":{"play":"CLOWN: She is stirring, sir. If she will stir hither, I shall","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.29","kind":"speech"},"3.1.30":{"play":"CLOWN: seem to notify unto her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.30","kind":"speech"},"3.1.31":{"play":"CASSIO: Do, good my friend.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.31","kind":"speech"},"3.1.32":{"play":"CASSIO: In happy time, Iago.","notes":["A la bonne heure. See Rom. & Jul. III, v, 110; Ham. V, ii, 193, &c., &c."],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.32","kind":"speech"},"3.1.33":{"play":"IAGO: You have not been abed, then?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.33","kind":"speech"},"3.1.34":{"play":"CASSIO: Why, no. The day had broke","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.34","kind":"speech"},"3.1.35":{"play":"CASSIO: Before we parted. I have made bold, Iago,","notes":["For the accent, see Abbott, §490."],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.35","kind":"speech"},"3.1.36":{"play":"CASSIO: To send in to your wife. My suit to her","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.36","kind":"speech"},"3.1.37":{"play":"CASSIO: Is that she will to virtuous Desdemona","notes":["Walker (Crit. i, 89) suggests 'In view of the very frequent interpolation of a in the Folio, this division and reading: \"I humbly thank you for't | I ne'er knew | Florentine more kind and honest.\" \"Perhaps,\" he adds, \"we should arrange rather, 'I humbly thank you for't; I ne'er knew Florentine | More kind and honest.'\" [See Capell's reading and division, in Textual Notes.]","Dyce (ed. iii): 'The word \"humbly\" is constantly used with \"thank,\" \"pray,\" \"beseech,\" and the like: hence, I suppose, a transcriber inserted it here. Cassio was Iago's equal, or rather his superior, and would scarcely have used the word even in his present dejected state.'—W. N. Lettsom. Here, I apprehend, 'humbly' is no more to be taken in its literal sense than is 'humble' now-a-days when some very courteous correspondent signs himself 'Your humble servant.'","Malone: In consequence of this line, a doubt has been entertained concerning the country of Iago. Cassio was undoubtedly a Florentine, as appears by I, i, 22, where he is expressly called one. That Iago was a Venetian is proved by what he says after having stabbed Roderigo, V, i, 112. All that Cassio means to say here is, 'I never experienced more honesty and kindness even in any one of my own countrymen than in this man.' ---"],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.37","kind":"speech"},"3.1.38":{"play":"CASSIO: Procure me some access.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.38","kind":"speech"},"3.1.39":{"play":"IAGO: I’ll send her to you presently,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.39","kind":"speech"},"3.1.40":{"play":"IAGO: And I’ll devise a mean to draw the Moor","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.40","kind":"speech"},"3.1.41":{"play":"IAGO: Out of the way, that your converse and business","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.41","kind":"speech"},"3.1.42":{"play":"IAGO: May be more free.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.42","kind":"speech"},"3.1.43":{"play":"CASSIO: I humbly thank you for ’t. I never","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.43","kind":"speech"},"3.1.44":{"play":"CASSIO: knew","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.44","kind":"speech"},"3.1.45":{"play":"CASSIO: A Florentine more kind and honest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.45","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.1.45.1":{"play":"[Enter Emilia.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.1.45.1","kind":"stage"},"3.1.46":{"play":"EMILIA: Good morrow, good lieutenant. I am sorry","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.46","kind":"speech"},"3.1.47":{"play":"EMILIA: For your displeasure, but all will sure be well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.47","kind":"speech"},"3.1.48":{"play":"EMILIA: The General and his wife are talking of it,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.48","kind":"speech"},"3.1.49":{"play":"EMILIA: And she speaks for you stoutly. The Moor replies","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.49","kind":"speech"},"3.1.50":{"play":"EMILIA: That he you hurt is of great fame in Cyprus","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.50","kind":"speech"},"3.1.51":{"play":"EMILIA: And great affinity, and that in wholesome wisdom","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.51","kind":"speech"},"3.1.52":{"play":"EMILIA: He might not but refuse you. But he protests he","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.52","kind":"speech"},"3.1.53":{"play":"EMILIA: loves you","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.53","kind":"speech"},"3.1.54":{"play":"EMILIA: And needs no other suitor but his likings","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.54","kind":"speech"},"3.1.55":{"play":"EMILIA: To take the safest occasion by the front","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.55","kind":"speech"},"3.1.56":{"play":"EMILIA: To bring you in again.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.56","kind":"speech"},"3.1.57":{"play":"CASSIO: Yet I beseech you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.57","kind":"speech"},"3.1.58":{"play":"CASSIO: If you think fit, or that it may be done,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.58","kind":"speech"},"3.1.59":{"play":"CASSIO: Give me advantage of some brief discourse","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.59","kind":"speech"},"3.1.60":{"play":"CASSIO: With Desdemon alone.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.60","kind":"speech"},"3.1.61":{"play":"EMILIA: Pray you come in.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.61","kind":"speech"},"3.1.62":{"play":"EMILIA: I will bestow you where you shall have time","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.62","kind":"speech"},"3.1.63":{"play":"EMILIA: To speak your bosom freely.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.63","kind":"speech"},"3.1.64":{"play":"CASSIO: I am much bound to you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.1.64","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.1.64.1":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.1.64.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 3, SCENE 2":{"SD_3.2.0":{"play":"[Enter Othello, Iago, and Gentlemen.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.2.0","kind":"stage"},"3.2.1":{"play":"OTHELLO: These letters give, Iago, to the pilot","notes":["by him: bid him Cap. conj. (p. 28 b).","Senate: State Qq, Cap. Steev. Mai. Warb."],"folgerAnchor":"3.2.1","kind":"speech"},"3.2.2":{"play":"OTHELLO: And by him do my duties to the Senate.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.2.2","kind":"speech"},"3.2.3":{"play":"OTHELLO: That done, I will be walking on the works.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.2.3","kind":"speech"},"3.2.4":{"play":"OTHELLO: Repair there to me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.2.4","kind":"speech"},"3.2.5":{"play":"IAGO: Well, my good lord, I’ll do ’t.","notes":["Well: Om. Pope +."],"folgerAnchor":"3.2.5","kind":"speech"},"3.2.6":{"play":"OTHELLO: This fortification, gentlemen, shall we see ’t?","notes":["Well: We Qq, Jen. Coll. Wh. i. We'll FfG F4 et cet. ---"],"folgerAnchor":"3.2.6","kind":"speech"},"3.2.7":{"play":"GENTLEMEN: We wait upon your Lordship.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.2.7","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.2.7.1":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.2.7.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 3, SCENE 3":{"SD_3.3.0":{"play":"[Enter Desdemona, Cassio, and Emilia.]","notes":["Fechter: Rousing himself, and trembling with rage.","Booth: All this passage should be spoken more with anguish than with anger."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.3.0","kind":"stage"},"3.3.1":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Be thou assured, good Cassio, I will do","notes":["Harting (p. 58): These were two narrow strips of leather, fastened one to each leg, the other ends being attached to a swivel, from which depended the 'leash.' When the hawk was flown, the swivel and leash were taken off, the jesses and bells remaining on the bird.","Turbervile, in his Book of Falconrie, 1575, speaking of the trappings of a hawk, says: 'Shee must haue jesses of leather, the which must haue knottes at the ende, and they should be halfe a foote long, or there about; at the least a shaftmeete betweene the hoose of the jesse, and the knotte at the ende, whereby you tye the hauke.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.1","kind":"speech"},"3.3.2":{"play":"DESDEMONA: All my abilities in thy behalf.","notes":["Fechter: thought not on the language of falconers."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.2","kind":"speech"},"3.3.3":{"play":"EMILIA: Good madam, do. I warrant it grieves my husband","notes":["Booth: This word may bother the many, so touch your heart to signify, likings, or longings."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.3","kind":"speech"},"3.3.4":{"play":"EMILIA: As if the cause were his.","notes":["Steevens: That is, men of intrigue. So in the Countess of Pembroke's Antonius, 1590: 'Fal'n from a soldier to a chamberer.'","Henley: See Romans, xiii, 13: 'Let us walk honestly as in the day; not in rioting and drunkenness, not in chambering and wantonness.'","Wright (Bible Word-Book): Latimer, in his remarks on Rom. xiii, 13, thus explains the word: 'St. Paul useth this word chambering; for when folks will be wanton, they get themselves in corners.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.4","kind":"speech"},"3.3.5":{"play":"DESDEMONA: O, that’s an honest fellow! Do not doubt, Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.5","kind":"speech"},"3.3.6":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But I will have my lord and you again","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.6","kind":"speech"},"3.3.7":{"play":"DESDEMONA: As friendly as you were.","notes":["Walker (Vers. 176): Pronounce dissolute."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.7","kind":"speech"},"3.3.8":{"play":"CASSIO: Bounteous madam,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.8","kind":"speech"},"3.3.9":{"play":"CASSIO: Whatever shall become of Michael Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.9","kind":"speech"},"3.3.10":{"play":"CASSIO: He’s never anything but your true servant.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.10","kind":"speech"},"3.3.11":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I know ’t. I thank you. You do love my lord;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.11","kind":"speech"},"3.3.12":{"play":"DESDEMONA: You have known him long; and be you well assured","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.12","kind":"speech"},"3.3.13":{"play":"DESDEMONA: He shall in strangeness stand no farther off","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.13","kind":"speech"},"3.3.14":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Than in a politic distance.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.14","kind":"speech"},"3.3.15":{"play":"CASSIO: Ay, but, lady,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.15","kind":"speech"},"3.3.16":{"play":"CASSIO: That policy may either last so long,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.16","kind":"speech"},"3.3.17":{"play":"CASSIO: Or feed upon such nice and waterish diet,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.17","kind":"speech"},"3.3.18":{"play":"CASSIO: Or breed itself so out of circumstance,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.18","kind":"speech"},"3.3.19":{"play":"CASSIO: That, I being absent and my place supplied,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.19","kind":"speech"},"3.3.20":{"play":"CASSIO: My general will forget my love and service.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.20","kind":"speech"},"3.3.21":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Do not doubt that. Before Emilia here,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.21","kind":"speech"},"3.3.22":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I give thee warrant of thy place. Assure thee,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.22","kind":"speech"},"3.3.23":{"play":"DESDEMONA: If I do vow a friendship, I’ll perform it","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.23","kind":"speech"},"3.3.24":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To the last article. My lord shall never rest:","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.24","kind":"speech"},"3.3.25":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I’ll watch him tame and talk him out of patience;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.25","kind":"speech"},"3.3.26":{"play":"DESDEMONA: His bed shall seem a school, his board a shrift;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.26","kind":"speech"},"3.3.27":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I’ll intermingle everything he does","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.27","kind":"speech"},"3.3.28":{"play":"DESDEMONA: With Cassio’s suit. Therefore be merry, Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.28","kind":"speech"},"3.3.29":{"play":"DESDEMONA: For thy solicitor shall rather die","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.29","kind":"speech"},"3.3.30":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Than give thy cause away.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.30","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.3.30.1":{"play":"[Enter Othello and Iago.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.3.30.1","kind":"stage"},"3.3.31":{"play":"EMILIA: Madam, here comes my lord.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.31","kind":"speech"},"3.3.32":{"play":"CASSIO: Madam, I’ll take my leave.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.32","kind":"speech"},"3.3.33":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Why, stay, and hear me speak.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.33","kind":"speech"},"3.3.34":{"play":"CASSIO: Madam, not now. I am very ill at ease,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.34","kind":"speech"},"3.3.35":{"play":"CASSIO: Unfit for mine own purposes.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.35","kind":"speech"},"3.3.36":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Well, do your discretion.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.36","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.3.36":{"play":"[Cassio exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.3.36","kind":"stage"},"3.3.37":{"play":"IAGO: Ha, I like not that.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.37","kind":"speech"},"3.3.38":{"play":"OTHELLO: What dost thou say?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.38","kind":"speech"},"3.3.39":{"play":"IAGO: Nothing, my lord; or if—I know not what.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.39","kind":"speech"},"3.3.40":{"play":"OTHELLO: Was not that Cassio parted from my wife?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.40","kind":"speech"},"3.3.41":{"play":"IAGO: Cassio, my lord? No, sure, I cannot think it","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.41","kind":"speech"},"3.3.42":{"play":"IAGO: That he would steal away so guiltylike,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.42","kind":"speech"},"3.3.43":{"play":"IAGO: Seeing your coming.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.43","kind":"speech"},"3.3.44":{"play":"OTHELLO: I do believe ’twas he.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.44","kind":"speech"},"3.3.45":{"play":"DESDEMONA: How now, my lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.45","kind":"speech"},"3.3.46":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I have been talking with a suitor here,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.46","kind":"speech"},"3.3.47":{"play":"DESDEMONA: A man that languishes in your displeasure.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.47","kind":"speech"},"3.3.48":{"play":"OTHELLO: Who is ’t you mean?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.48","kind":"speech"},"3.3.49":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Why, your lieutenant, Cassio. Good my lord,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.49","kind":"speech"},"3.3.50":{"play":"DESDEMONA: If I have any grace or power to move you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.50","kind":"speech"},"3.3.51":{"play":"DESDEMONA: His present reconciliation take;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.51","kind":"speech"},"3.3.52":{"play":"DESDEMONA: For if he be not one that truly loves you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.52","kind":"speech"},"3.3.53":{"play":"DESDEMONA: That errs in ignorance and not in cunning,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.53","kind":"speech"},"3.3.54":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I have no judgment in an honest face.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.54","kind":"speech"},"3.3.55":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I prithee call him back.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.55","kind":"speech"},"3.3.56":{"play":"OTHELLO: Went he hence now?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.56","kind":"speech"},"3.3.57":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Yes, faith, so humbled","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.57","kind":"speech"},"3.3.58":{"play":"DESDEMONA: That he hath left part of his grief with me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.58","kind":"speech"},"3.3.59":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To suffer with him. Good love, call him back.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.59","kind":"speech"},"3.3.60":{"play":"OTHELLO: Not now, sweet Desdemon. Some other time.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.60","kind":"speech"},"3.3.61":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But shall ’t be shortly?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.61","kind":"speech"},"3.3.62":{"play":"OTHELLO: The sooner, sweet, for you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.62","kind":"speech"},"3.3.63":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Shall ’t be tonight at supper?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.63","kind":"speech"},"3.3.64":{"play":"OTHELLO: No, not tonight.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.64","kind":"speech"},"3.3.65":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Tomorrow dinner, then?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.65","kind":"speech"},"3.3.66":{"play":"OTHELLO: I shall not dine at home;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.66","kind":"speech"},"3.3.67":{"play":"OTHELLO: I meet the captains at the citadel.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.67","kind":"speech"},"3.3.68":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Why then tomorrow night, or Tuesday morn,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.68","kind":"speech"},"3.3.69":{"play":"DESDEMONA: On Tuesday noon or night; on Wednesday morn.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.69","kind":"speech"},"3.3.70":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I prithee name the time, but let it not","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.70","kind":"speech"},"3.3.71":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Exceed three days. In faith, he’s penitent;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.71","kind":"speech"},"3.3.72":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And yet his trespass, in our common reason—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.72","kind":"speech"},"3.3.73":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Save that, they say, the wars must make example","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.73","kind":"speech"},"3.3.74":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Out of her best—is not almost a fault","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.74","kind":"speech"},"3.3.75":{"play":"DESDEMONA: T’ incur a private check. When shall he come?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.75","kind":"speech"},"3.3.76":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Tell me, Othello. I wonder in my soul","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.76","kind":"speech"},"3.3.77":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What you would ask me that I should deny,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.77","kind":"speech"},"3.3.78":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Or stand so mamm’ring on? What? Michael Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.78","kind":"speech"},"3.3.79":{"play":"DESDEMONA: That came a-wooing with you, and so many a time,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.79","kind":"speech"},"3.3.80":{"play":"DESDEMONA: When I have spoke of you dispraisingly,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.80","kind":"speech"},"3.3.81":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Hath ta’en your part—to have so much to do","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.81","kind":"speech"},"3.3.82":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To bring him in! By ’r Lady, I could do much—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.82","kind":"speech"},"3.3.83":{"play":"OTHELLO: Prithee, no more. Let him come when he will;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.83","kind":"speech"},"3.3.84":{"play":"OTHELLO: I will deny thee nothing.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.84","kind":"speech"},"3.3.85":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Why, this is not a boon!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.85","kind":"speech"},"3.3.86":{"play":"DESDEMONA: ’Tis as I should entreat you wear your gloves,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.86","kind":"speech"},"3.3.87":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Or feed on nourishing dishes, or keep you warm,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.87","kind":"speech"},"3.3.88":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Or sue to you to do a peculiar profit","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.88","kind":"speech"},"3.3.89":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To your own person. Nay, when I have a suit","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.89","kind":"speech"},"3.3.90":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Wherein I mean to touch your love indeed,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.90","kind":"speech"},"3.3.91":{"play":"DESDEMONA: It shall be full of poise and difficult weight,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.91","kind":"speech"},"3.3.92":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And fearful to be granted.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.92","kind":"speech"},"3.3.93":{"play":"OTHELLO: I will deny thee nothing!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.93","kind":"speech"},"3.3.94":{"play":"OTHELLO: Whereon, I do beseech thee, grant me this,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.94","kind":"speech"},"3.3.95":{"play":"OTHELLO: To leave me but a little to myself.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.95","kind":"speech"},"3.3.96":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Shall I deny you? No. Farewell, my lord.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.96","kind":"speech"},"3.3.97":{"play":"OTHELLO: Farewell, my Desdemona. I’ll come to thee straight.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.97","kind":"speech"},"3.3.98":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Emilia, come.—Be as your fancies teach you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.98","kind":"speech"},"3.3.99":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Whate’er you be, I am obedient.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.99","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.3.99.1":{"play":"[Desdemona and Emilia exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.3.99.1","kind":"stage"},"3.3.100":{"play":"OTHELLO: Excellent wretch! Perdition catch my soul","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.100","kind":"speech"},"3.3.101":{"play":"OTHELLO: But I do love thee! And when I love thee not,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.101","kind":"speech"},"3.3.102":{"play":"OTHELLO: Chaos is come again.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.102","kind":"speech"},"3.3.103":{"play":"IAGO: My noble lord—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.103","kind":"speech"},"3.3.104":{"play":"OTHELLO: What dost thou say, Iago?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.104","kind":"speech"},"3.3.105":{"play":"IAGO: Did Michael Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.105","kind":"speech"},"3.3.106":{"play":"IAGO: When you wooed my lady, know of your love?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.106","kind":"speech"},"3.3.107":{"play":"OTHELLO: He did, from first to last. Why dost thou ask?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.107","kind":"speech"},"3.3.108":{"play":"IAGO: But for a satisfaction of my thought,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.108","kind":"speech"},"3.3.109":{"play":"IAGO: No further harm.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.109","kind":"speech"},"3.3.110":{"play":"OTHELLO: Why of thy thought, Iago?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.110","kind":"speech"},"3.3.111":{"play":"IAGO: I did not think he had been acquainted with her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.111","kind":"speech"},"3.3.112":{"play":"OTHELLO: O yes, and went between us very oft.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.112","kind":"speech"},"3.3.113":{"play":"IAGO: Indeed?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.113","kind":"speech"},"3.3.114":{"play":"OTHELLO: Indeed? Ay, indeed! Discern’st thou aught in that?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.114","kind":"speech"},"3.3.115":{"play":"OTHELLO: Is he not honest?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.115","kind":"speech"},"3.3.116":{"play":"IAGO: Honest, my lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.116","kind":"speech"},"3.3.117":{"play":"OTHELLO: Honest—ay, honest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.117","kind":"speech"},"3.3.118":{"play":"IAGO: My lord, for aught I know.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.118","kind":"speech"},"3.3.119":{"play":"OTHELLO: What dost thou think?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.119","kind":"speech"},"3.3.120":{"play":"IAGO: Think, my lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.120","kind":"speech"},"3.3.121":{"play":"OTHELLO: By heaven, thou echo’st me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.121","kind":"speech"},"3.3.122":{"play":"OTHELLO: As if there were some monster in thy thought","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.122","kind":"speech"},"3.3.123":{"play":"OTHELLO: Too hideous to be shown. Thou dost mean","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.123","kind":"speech"},"3.3.124":{"play":"OTHELLO: something.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.124","kind":"speech"},"3.3.125":{"play":"OTHELLO: I heard thee say even now, thou lik’st not that,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.125","kind":"speech"},"3.3.126":{"play":"OTHELLO: When Cassio left my wife. What didst not like?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.126","kind":"speech"},"3.3.127":{"play":"OTHELLO: And when I told thee he was of my counsel","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.127","kind":"speech"},"3.3.128":{"play":"OTHELLO: In my whole course of wooing, thou cried’st","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.128","kind":"speech"},"3.3.129":{"play":"OTHELLO: ","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.129","kind":"speech"},"3.3.130":{"play":"OTHELLO: And didst contract and purse thy brow together","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.130","kind":"speech"},"3.3.131":{"play":"OTHELLO: As if thou then hadst shut up in thy brain","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.131","kind":"speech"},"3.3.132":{"play":"OTHELLO: Some horrible conceit. If thou dost love me,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.132","kind":"speech"},"3.3.133":{"play":"OTHELLO: Show me thy thought.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.133","kind":"speech"},"3.3.134":{"play":"IAGO: My lord, you know I love you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.134","kind":"speech"},"3.3.135":{"play":"OTHELLO: I think thou dost;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.135","kind":"speech"},"3.3.136":{"play":"OTHELLO: And for I know thou ’rt full of love and honesty","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.136","kind":"speech"},"3.3.137":{"play":"OTHELLO: And weigh’st thy words before thou giv’st them","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.137","kind":"speech"},"3.3.138":{"play":"OTHELLO: breath,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.138","kind":"speech"},"3.3.139":{"play":"OTHELLO: Therefore these stops of thine fright me the more.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.139","kind":"speech"},"3.3.140":{"play":"OTHELLO: For such things in a false, disloyal knave","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.140","kind":"speech"},"3.3.141":{"play":"OTHELLO: Are tricks of custom; but in a man that’s just,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.141","kind":"speech"},"3.3.142":{"play":"OTHELLO: They’re close dilations working from the heart","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.142","kind":"speech"},"3.3.143":{"play":"OTHELLO: That passion cannot rule.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.143","kind":"speech"},"3.3.144":{"play":"IAGO: For Michael Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.144","kind":"speech"},"3.3.145":{"play":"IAGO: I dare be sworn I think that he is honest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.145","kind":"speech"},"3.3.146":{"play":"OTHELLO: I think so too.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.146","kind":"speech"},"3.3.147":{"play":"IAGO: Men should be what they seem;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.147","kind":"speech"},"3.3.148":{"play":"IAGO: Or those that be not, would they might seem none!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.148","kind":"speech"},"3.3.149":{"play":"OTHELLO: Certain, men should be what they seem.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.149","kind":"speech"},"3.3.150":{"play":"IAGO: Why then, I think Cassio’s an honest man.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.150","kind":"speech"},"3.3.151":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nay, yet there’s more in this.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.151","kind":"speech"},"3.3.152":{"play":"OTHELLO: I prithee speak to me as to thy thinkings,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.152","kind":"speech"},"3.3.153":{"play":"OTHELLO: As thou dost ruminate, and give thy worst of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.153","kind":"speech"},"3.3.154":{"play":"OTHELLO: thoughts","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.154","kind":"speech"},"3.3.155":{"play":"OTHELLO: The worst of words.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.155","kind":"speech"},"3.3.156":{"play":"IAGO: Good my lord, pardon me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.156","kind":"speech"},"3.3.157":{"play":"IAGO: Though I am bound to every act of duty,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.157","kind":"speech"},"3.3.158":{"play":"IAGO: I am not bound to that all slaves are free to.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.158","kind":"speech"},"3.3.159":{"play":"IAGO: Utter my thoughts? Why, say they are vile and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.159","kind":"speech"},"3.3.160":{"play":"IAGO: false—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.160","kind":"speech"},"3.3.161":{"play":"IAGO: As where’s that palace whereinto foul things","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.161","kind":"speech"},"3.3.162":{"play":"IAGO: Sometimes intrude not? Who has that breast so","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.162","kind":"speech"},"3.3.163":{"play":"IAGO: pure","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.163","kind":"speech"},"3.3.164":{"play":"IAGO: But some uncleanly apprehensions","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.164","kind":"speech"},"3.3.165":{"play":"IAGO: Keep leets and law days and in sessions sit","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.165","kind":"speech"},"3.3.166":{"play":"IAGO: With meditations lawful?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.166","kind":"speech"},"3.3.167":{"play":"OTHELLO: Thou dost conspire against thy friend, Iago,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.167","kind":"speech"},"3.3.168":{"play":"OTHELLO: If thou but think’st him wronged and mak’st his ear","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.168","kind":"speech"},"3.3.169":{"play":"OTHELLO: A stranger to thy thoughts.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.169","kind":"speech"},"3.3.170":{"play":"IAGO: I do beseech you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.170","kind":"speech"},"3.3.171":{"play":"IAGO: Though I perchance am vicious in my guess—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.171","kind":"speech"},"3.3.172":{"play":"IAGO: As, I confess, it is my nature’s plague","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.172","kind":"speech"},"3.3.173":{"play":"IAGO: To spy into abuses, and oft my jealousy","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.173","kind":"speech"},"3.3.174":{"play":"IAGO: Shapes faults that are not—that your wisdom","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.174","kind":"speech"},"3.3.175":{"play":"IAGO: From one that so imperfectly conceits","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.175","kind":"speech"},"3.3.176":{"play":"IAGO: Would take no notice, nor build yourself a trouble","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.176","kind":"speech"},"3.3.177":{"play":"IAGO: Out of his scattering and unsure observance.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.177","kind":"speech"},"3.3.178":{"play":"IAGO: It were not for your quiet nor your good,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.178","kind":"speech"},"3.3.179":{"play":"IAGO: Nor for my manhood, honesty, and wisdom,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.179","kind":"speech"},"3.3.180":{"play":"IAGO: To let you know my thoughts.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.180","kind":"speech"},"3.3.181":{"play":"OTHELLO: What dost thou mean?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.181","kind":"speech"},"3.3.182":{"play":"IAGO: Good name in man and woman, dear my lord,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.182","kind":"speech"},"3.3.183":{"play":"IAGO: Is the immediate jewel of their souls.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.183","kind":"speech"},"3.3.184":{"play":"IAGO: Who steals my purse steals trash. ’Tis something,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.184","kind":"speech"},"3.3.185":{"play":"IAGO: nothing;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.185","kind":"speech"},"3.3.186":{"play":"IAGO: ’Twas mine, ’tis his, and has been slave to","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.186","kind":"speech"},"3.3.187":{"play":"IAGO: thousands.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.187","kind":"speech"},"3.3.188":{"play":"IAGO: But he that filches from me my good name","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.188","kind":"speech"},"3.3.189":{"play":"IAGO: Robs me of that which not enriches him","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.189","kind":"speech"},"3.3.190":{"play":"IAGO: And makes me poor indeed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.190","kind":"speech"},"3.3.191":{"play":"OTHELLO: By heaven, I’ll know thy thoughts.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.191","kind":"speech"},"3.3.192":{"play":"IAGO: You cannot, if my heart were in your hand,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.192","kind":"speech"},"3.3.193":{"play":"IAGO: Nor shall not, whilst ’tis in my custody.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.193","kind":"speech"},"3.3.194":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ha?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.194","kind":"speech"},"3.3.195":{"play":"IAGO: O, beware, my lord, of jealousy!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.195","kind":"speech"},"3.3.196":{"play":"IAGO: It is the green-eyed monster which doth mock","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.196","kind":"speech"},"3.3.197":{"play":"IAGO: The meat it feeds on. That cuckold lives in bliss","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.197","kind":"speech"},"3.3.198":{"play":"IAGO: Who, certain of his fate, loves not his wronger;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.198","kind":"speech"},"3.3.199":{"play":"IAGO: But O, what damnèd minutes tells he o’er","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.199","kind":"speech"},"3.3.200":{"play":"IAGO: Who dotes, yet doubts; suspects, yet strongly loves!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.200","kind":"speech"},"3.3.201":{"play":"OTHELLO: O misery!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.201","kind":"speech"},"3.3.202":{"play":"IAGO: Poor and content is rich, and rich enough;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.202","kind":"speech"},"3.3.203":{"play":"IAGO: But riches fineless is as poor as winter","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.203","kind":"speech"},"3.3.204":{"play":"IAGO: To him that ever fears he shall be poor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.204","kind":"speech"},"3.3.205":{"play":"IAGO: Good God, the souls of all my tribe defend","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.205","kind":"speech"},"3.3.206":{"play":"IAGO: From jealousy!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.206","kind":"speech"},"3.3.207":{"play":"OTHELLO: Why, why is this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.207","kind":"speech"},"3.3.208":{"play":"OTHELLO: Think’st thou I’d make a life of jealousy,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.208","kind":"speech"},"3.3.209":{"play":"OTHELLO: To follow still the changes of the moon","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.209","kind":"speech"},"3.3.210":{"play":"OTHELLO: With fresh suspicions? No. To be once in doubt","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.210","kind":"speech"},"3.3.211":{"play":"OTHELLO: Is once to be resolved. Exchange me for a goat","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.211","kind":"speech"},"3.3.212":{"play":"OTHELLO: When I shall turn the business of my soul","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.212","kind":"speech"},"3.3.213":{"play":"OTHELLO: To such exsufflicate and blown surmises,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.213","kind":"speech"},"3.3.214":{"play":"OTHELLO: Matching thy inference. ’Tis not to make me jealous","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.214","kind":"speech"},"3.3.215":{"play":"OTHELLO: To say my wife is fair, feeds well, loves company,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.215","kind":"speech"},"3.3.216":{"play":"OTHELLO: Is free of speech, sings, plays, and dances well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.216","kind":"speech"},"3.3.217":{"play":"OTHELLO: Where virtue is, these are more virtuous.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.217","kind":"speech"},"3.3.218":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nor from mine own weak merits will I draw","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.218","kind":"speech"},"3.3.219":{"play":"OTHELLO: The smallest fear or doubt of her revolt,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.219","kind":"speech"},"3.3.220":{"play":"OTHELLO: For she had eyes, and chose me. No, Iago,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.220","kind":"speech"},"3.3.221":{"play":"OTHELLO: I’ll see before I doubt; when I doubt, prove;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.221","kind":"speech"},"3.3.222":{"play":"OTHELLO: And on the proof, there is no more but this:","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.222","kind":"speech"},"3.3.223":{"play":"OTHELLO: Away at once with love or jealousy.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.223","kind":"speech"},"3.3.224":{"play":"IAGO: I am glad of this, for now I shall have reason","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.224","kind":"speech"},"3.3.225":{"play":"IAGO: To show the love and duty that I bear you","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.225","kind":"speech"},"3.3.226":{"play":"IAGO: With franker spirit. Therefore, as I am bound,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.226","kind":"speech"},"3.3.227":{"play":"IAGO: Receive it from me. I speak not yet of proof.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.227","kind":"speech"},"3.3.228":{"play":"IAGO: Look to your wife; observe her well with Cassio;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.228","kind":"speech"},"3.3.229":{"play":"IAGO: Wear your eyes thus, not jealous nor secure.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.229","kind":"speech"},"3.3.230":{"play":"IAGO: I would not have your free and noble nature,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.230","kind":"speech"},"3.3.231":{"play":"IAGO: Out of self-bounty, be abused. Look to ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.231","kind":"speech"},"3.3.232":{"play":"IAGO: I know our country disposition well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.232","kind":"speech"},"3.3.233":{"play":"IAGO: In Venice they do let God see the pranks","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.233","kind":"speech"},"3.3.234":{"play":"IAGO: They dare not show their husbands. Their best","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.234","kind":"speech"},"3.3.235":{"play":"IAGO: conscience","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.235","kind":"speech"},"3.3.236":{"play":"IAGO: Is not to leave ’t undone, but keep ’t unknown.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.236","kind":"speech"},"3.3.237":{"play":"OTHELLO: Dost thou say so?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.237","kind":"speech"},"3.3.238":{"play":"IAGO: She did deceive her father, marrying you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.238","kind":"speech"},"3.3.239":{"play":"IAGO: And when she seemed to shake and fear your looks,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.239","kind":"speech"},"3.3.240":{"play":"IAGO: She loved them most.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.240","kind":"speech"},"3.3.241":{"play":"OTHELLO: And so she did.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.241","kind":"speech"},"3.3.242":{"play":"IAGO: Why, go to, then!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.242","kind":"speech"},"3.3.243":{"play":"IAGO: She that, so young, could give out such a seeming,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.243","kind":"speech"},"3.3.244":{"play":"IAGO: To seel her father’s eyes up close as oak,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.244","kind":"speech"},"3.3.245":{"play":"IAGO: He thought ’twas witchcraft! But I am much to","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.245","kind":"speech"},"3.3.246":{"play":"IAGO: blame.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.246","kind":"speech"},"3.3.247":{"play":"IAGO: I humbly do beseech you of your pardon","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.247","kind":"speech"},"3.3.248":{"play":"IAGO: For too much loving you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.248","kind":"speech"},"3.3.249":{"play":"OTHELLO: I am bound to thee forever.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.249","kind":"speech"},"3.3.250":{"play":"IAGO: I see this hath a little dashed your spirits.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.250","kind":"speech"},"3.3.251":{"play":"OTHELLO: Not a jot, not a jot.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.251","kind":"speech"},"3.3.252":{"play":"IAGO: I’ faith, I fear it has.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.252","kind":"speech"},"3.3.253":{"play":"IAGO: I hope you will consider what is spoke","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.253","kind":"speech"},"3.3.254":{"play":"IAGO: Comes from my love. But I do see you’re moved.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.254","kind":"speech"},"3.3.255":{"play":"IAGO: I am to pray you not to strain my speech","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.255","kind":"speech"},"3.3.256":{"play":"IAGO: To grosser issues nor to larger reach","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.256","kind":"speech"},"3.3.257":{"play":"IAGO: Than to suspicion.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.257","kind":"speech"},"3.3.258":{"play":"OTHELLO: I will not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.258","kind":"speech"},"3.3.259":{"play":"IAGO: Should you do so, my lord,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.259","kind":"speech"},"3.3.260":{"play":"IAGO: My speech should fall into such vile success","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.260","kind":"speech"},"3.3.261":{"play":"IAGO: As my thoughts aim not at. Cassio’s my worthy","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.261","kind":"speech"},"3.3.262":{"play":"IAGO: friend.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.262","kind":"speech"},"3.3.263":{"play":"IAGO: My lord, I see you’re moved.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.263","kind":"speech"},"3.3.264":{"play":"OTHELLO: No, not much moved.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.264","kind":"speech"},"3.3.265":{"play":"OTHELLO: I do not think but Desdemona’s honest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.265","kind":"speech"},"3.3.266":{"play":"IAGO: Long live she so! And long live you to think so!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.266","kind":"speech"},"3.3.267":{"play":"OTHELLO: And yet, how nature erring from itself—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.267","kind":"speech"},"3.3.268":{"play":"IAGO: Ay, there’s the point. As, to be bold with you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.268","kind":"speech"},"3.3.269":{"play":"IAGO: Not to affect many proposèd matches","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.269","kind":"speech"},"3.3.270":{"play":"IAGO: Of her own clime, complexion, and degree,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.270","kind":"speech"},"3.3.271":{"play":"IAGO: Whereto we see in all things nature tends—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.271","kind":"speech"},"3.3.272":{"play":"IAGO: Foh! One may smell in such a will most rank,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.272","kind":"speech"},"3.3.273":{"play":"IAGO: Foul disproportion, thoughts unnatural—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.273","kind":"speech"},"3.3.274":{"play":"IAGO: But pardon me—I do not in position","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.274","kind":"speech"},"3.3.275":{"play":"IAGO: Distinctly speak of her, though I may fear","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.275","kind":"speech"},"3.3.276":{"play":"IAGO: Her will, recoiling to her better judgment,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.276","kind":"speech"},"3.3.277":{"play":"IAGO: May fall to match you with her country forms","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.277","kind":"speech"},"3.3.278":{"play":"IAGO: And happily repent.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.278","kind":"speech"},"3.3.279":{"play":"OTHELLO: Farewell, farewell!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.279","kind":"speech"},"3.3.280":{"play":"OTHELLO: If more thou dost perceive, let me know more.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.280","kind":"speech"},"3.3.281":{"play":"OTHELLO: Set on thy wife to observe. Leave me, Iago.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.281","kind":"speech"},"3.3.282":{"play":"IAGO: My lord, I take my leave.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.282","kind":"speech"},"3.3.283":{"play":"OTHELLO: Why did I marry? This honest creature doubtless","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.283","kind":"speech"},"3.3.284":{"play":"OTHELLO: Sees and knows more, much more, than he unfolds.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.284","kind":"speech"},"3.3.285":{"play":"IAGO: My lord, I would I might entreat your Honor","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.285","kind":"speech"},"3.3.286":{"play":"IAGO: To scan this thing no farther. Leave it to time.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.286","kind":"speech"},"3.3.287":{"play":"IAGO: Although ’tis fit that Cassio have his place—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.287","kind":"speech"},"3.3.288":{"play":"IAGO: For sure he fills it up with great ability—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.288","kind":"speech"},"3.3.289":{"play":"IAGO: Yet, if you please to hold him off awhile,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.289","kind":"speech"},"3.3.290":{"play":"IAGO: You shall by that perceive him and his means.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.290","kind":"speech"},"3.3.291":{"play":"IAGO: Note if your lady strain his entertainment","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.291","kind":"speech"},"3.3.292":{"play":"IAGO: With any strong or vehement importunity.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.292","kind":"speech"},"3.3.293":{"play":"IAGO: Much will be seen in that. In the meantime,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.293","kind":"speech"},"3.3.294":{"play":"IAGO: Let me be thought too busy in my fears—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.294","kind":"speech"},"3.3.295":{"play":"IAGO: As worthy cause I have to fear I am—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.295","kind":"speech"},"3.3.296":{"play":"IAGO: And hold her free, I do beseech your Honor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.296","kind":"speech"},"3.3.297":{"play":"OTHELLO: Fear not my government.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.297","kind":"speech"},"3.3.298":{"play":"IAGO: I once more take my leave.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.298","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.3.298":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.3.298","kind":"stage"},"3.3.299":{"play":"OTHELLO: This fellow’s of exceeding honesty,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.299","kind":"speech"},"3.3.300":{"play":"OTHELLO: And knows all qualities with a learnèd spirit","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.300","kind":"speech"},"3.3.301":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of human dealings. If I do prove her haggard,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.301","kind":"speech"},"3.3.302":{"play":"OTHELLO: Though that her jesses were my dear heartstrings,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.302","kind":"speech"},"3.3.303":{"play":"OTHELLO: I’d whistle her off and let her down the wind","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.303","kind":"speech"},"3.3.304":{"play":"OTHELLO: To prey at fortune. Haply, for I am black","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.304","kind":"speech"},"3.3.305":{"play":"OTHELLO: And have not those soft parts of conversation","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.305","kind":"speech"},"3.3.306":{"play":"OTHELLO: That chamberers have, or for I am declined","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.306","kind":"speech"},"3.3.307":{"play":"OTHELLO: Into the vale of years—yet that’s not much—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.307","kind":"speech"},"3.3.308":{"play":"OTHELLO: She’s gone, I am abused, and my relief","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.308","kind":"speech"},"3.3.309":{"play":"OTHELLO: Must be to loathe her. O curse of marriage,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.309","kind":"speech"},"3.3.310":{"play":"OTHELLO: That we can call these delicate creatures ours","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.310","kind":"speech"},"3.3.311":{"play":"OTHELLO: And not their appetites! I had rather be a toad","notes":["Booth: She kneels to do so,—he is sitting."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.311","kind":"speech"},"3.3.312":{"play":"OTHELLO: And live upon the vapor of a dungeon","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.312","kind":"speech"},"3.3.313":{"play":"OTHELLO: Than keep a corner in the thing I love","notes":["Warner (Letter to Garrick, p. 35): This word is still used to signify a Handkerchief in Scotland and in the North of England, especially about Sheffield in Yorkshire.","We meet with it in that sense in the Proceedings in Scotland in the Douglass cause: 'Lady Jane never admitted any person to see her till she was fully dress'd.... with a large Napkin on her breast.' ['Oft did she heave her napkin to her eyne.' Lover's Complaint, 21.]"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.313","kind":"speech"},"3.3.314":{"play":"OTHELLO: For others’ uses. Yet ’tis the plague of great ones;","notes":["Collier (ed. i): We take this necessary stage direction ['Lets fall her Napkin'] from a MS. note, in a hand-writing of the time, in the Duke of Devonshire's Qr.","Dyce (Remarks, p. 239): The stage direction inserted by other modern editors is far better, viz. ['He puts the handkerchieffrom him, and it drops'].","There can be no doubt that, while Othello pushes away the handkerchief, Desdemona lets it fall: Emilia (who is now on the stage) says presently: 'she let it drop by negligence; And I,' &c.","Collier (ed. ii): This stage direction ['The napkin falls to the ground'] and others ['Offering to bind his head, after line 29] are from the (MS.)","[Where stage directions occur in the Qq or Ff they are to be reverently accepted, and they are also respectable in Rowe, as indications of stage tradition, but in other cases, where they are devised by editors, they are apt to be intrusive and are mostly superfluous.]","The stage directions of actors stand on a different footing. Here lies the actor's true province, and to his interpretations must be applied the supreme test of public judgement, wherein we, as a part of that public, have a right to give our voice.","Here Fechter decides that it is Othello who throws down the handkerchief, and does it in a rage; but Booth, with finer insight, lets Othello gently push the handkerchief aside and Desdemona drop it."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.314","kind":"speech"},"3.3.315":{"play":"OTHELLO: Prerogatived are they less than the base.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.315","kind":"speech"},"3.3.316":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Tis destiny unshunnable, like death.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.316","kind":"speech"},"3.3.317":{"play":"OTHELLO: Even then this forkèd plague is fated to us","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.317","kind":"speech"},"3.3.318":{"play":"OTHELLO: When we do quicken. Look where she comes.","notes":["Percy: That is, the horns of the cuckold.","Malone: See, in proof, Tro. & Cress. I, ii, 178; and Wint. Tale, I, ii, 186.","One of Harrington's Epigrams contains the very expression: 'Actaeon.... Was plagu'd with homes;.... Wherefore take heed, ye that are curious, prying, With some such forked plague you be not smitten,' &c."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.318","kind":"speech"},"3.3.319":{"play":"OTHELLO: If she be false, heaven mocks itself!","notes":["'The burst of mixed passions with which Forrest uttered the first part of this speech was terrific.","His voice then sank into tones the most touching, expressive of complaining regret.","The conclusion seemed to have excited him to the utmost pitch of loathing and disgust, and, as he sees Desdemona advancing, he, for a few moments, gazed upon her with horror. The feeling gave way, and all his former tenderness seemed to return as he exclaimed, \"If she be false,\" &c.'—Alger's Life of Forrest, 1,308."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.319","kind":"speech"},"3.3.320":{"play":"OTHELLO: I’ll not believe ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.320","kind":"speech"},"3.3.321":{"play":"DESDEMONA: How now, my dear Othello?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.321","kind":"speech"},"3.3.322":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Your dinner, and the generous islanders","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.322","kind":"speech"},"3.3.323":{"play":"DESDEMONA: By you invited, do attend your presence.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.323","kind":"speech"},"3.3.324":{"play":"OTHELLO: I am to blame.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.324","kind":"speech"},"3.3.325":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Why do you speak so faintly? Are you not well?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.325","kind":"speech"},"3.3.326":{"play":"OTHELLO: I have a pain upon my forehead, here.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.326","kind":"speech"},"3.3.327":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Faith, that’s with watching. ’Twill away again.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.327","kind":"speech"},"3.3.328":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Let me but bind it hard; within this hour","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.328","kind":"speech"},"3.3.329":{"play":"DESDEMONA: It will be well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.329","kind":"speech"},"3.3.330":{"play":"OTHELLO: Your napkin is too little.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.330","kind":"speech"},"3.3.331":{"play":"OTHELLO: Let it alone.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.331","kind":"speech"},"3.3.332":{"play":"OTHELLO: Come, I’ll go in with you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.332","kind":"speech"},"3.3.333":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I am very sorry that you are not well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.333","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.3.333.1":{"play":"[Othello and Desdemona exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.3.333.1","kind":"stage"},"3.3.334":{"play":"EMILIA: I am glad I have found this napkin.","notes":["Malone: That is [see Text. Notes], renders its own labours fruitless, by forming so beautiful a creature as Desdemona, and suffering the elegance of her person to be disgraced and sullied by the impurity of her mind,—such, I think, is the meaning,—the construction, however, may be different.","If she be false, Oh, then, even heaven itself cheats us with 'unreal mockery,' with false and specious appearances, intended only to deceive.","Steevens: The first of the foregoing explanations is, I believe, the true one. If she be false, heaven disgraces itself by creating woman after its own image. To have made the resemblance perfect, she should have been good as well as beautiful.","Knight: By the reading of the Folio we may understand that, if Desdemona be false,—be not what she appears to be,—heaven, at her creation, instead of giving an image of itself, mocked itself,—gave a false image.","Booth: Note this. Iago's manner is brusque,—disappointed at not finding Othello here; he had come to drive the dagger deeper in his heart.","RYMER (p. 121): Michael Cassio came not from Venice in the ship with Desdemona, nor till this morning could be suspected of an opportunity with her. And 'tis now but dinner time; yet the Moor complains of his forehead. He might have set a guard on Cassio, or have lockt up Desdemona, or have observ'd their carriage a day or two longer. He is on other occasions phlegmatic enough: this is very hasty. [Rymer's innuendo that in the pain upon his forehead Othello here covertly alludes to the forked plague is, I am afraid, only too correct. Delius, also, thus interprets it. Note the use of 'upon.' If this reference was understood by Shakespeare's auditors,—and it seems as though it were scarcely possible in those days to refer to the forehead other than as a groundwork for this plague,—then, in Desdemona's tender response they perceived a proof of her unconscious innocence which is otherwise lost on us.—Ed.]","Booth: She kneels to do so,—he is sitting.","Booth: Take time, gently push the handkerchief from her hand as she is in the act of binding it on your forehead. Pass her, while on her knees, with forced indifference, but turn lovingly, and holding your arms for her to enter them, say 'Come, I'll go in with thee.' Then with a long soulful look into her eyes, fold her tenderly to your heart and go slowly off. Keep time. Don't drawl in either speech or movement, yet be not abrupt nor rapid. Every movement, gesture, look, and tone should be in harmony.","Fechter: Comes forward with caution, and seizes the handkerchief, which she has watched narrowly since Othello threw it down.","Booth: Emilia, by chance, sees the handkerchief and picks it up."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.334","kind":"speech"},"3.3.335":{"play":"EMILIA: This was her first remembrance from the Moor.","notes":["Steevens: The islanders of rank, distinction. So, in Meas. for Meas. IV, vi, 13, 'The generous and gravest citizens.' See also Ham. I, iii, 74, 'select and generous.'","Staunton: That is, memorial, or forget-me-not."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.335","kind":"speech"},"3.3.336":{"play":"EMILIA: My wayward husband hath a hundred times","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.336","kind":"speech"},"3.3.337":{"play":"EMILIA: Wooed me to steal it. But she so loves the token","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.337","kind":"speech"},"3.3.338":{"play":"EMILIA: (For he conjured her she should ever keep it)","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.338","kind":"speech"},"3.3.339":{"play":"EMILIA: That she reserves it evermore about her","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.339","kind":"speech"},"3.3.340":{"play":"EMILIA: To kiss and talk to. I’ll have the work ta’en out","notes":["Johnson: The meaning is not, to have the work picked out and leave the ground plain, but to have this work copied in another handkerchief.","Steevens: So in Middleton's Women Beware Women, I, i, 'she intends To take out other works in a new sampler.' Again, in the Preface to Holland's Pliny: 'Thus Nicophanes (a famous painter in his time) gave his mind wholly to antique pictures, partly to exemplifie and take out their patternes.'","Blackstone: Her first thoughts are to have a copy made of it for her husband, and to restore the original to Desdemona. But the sudden coming in of Iago, in a surly humour, makes her alter her resolution, to please him.","Malone: This scheme of having the work copied was to render Emilia less unamiable. It is remarkable that when she perceives Othello's fury on the loss of this token, though she is represented as affectionate to her mistress, she never attempts to relieve her of her distress, which she might easily have done. Shakespeare fell into this incongruity by departing from Cinthio's novel."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.340","kind":"speech"},"3.3.341":{"play":"EMILIA: And give ’t Iago. What he will do with it","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.341","kind":"speech"},"3.3.342":{"play":"EMILIA: Heaven knows, not I.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.342","kind":"speech"},"3.3.343":{"play":"EMILIA: I nothing but to please his fantasy.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.343","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.3.343.1":{"play":"[Enter Iago.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.3.343.1","kind":"stage"},"3.3.344":{"play":"IAGO: How now? What do you here alone?","notes":["Walker (Crit. iii, 287): Arrange, perhaps,—How now! | What do you here alone? Emilia. Do not you chide; | I have a thing for you. Iago. A thing for me? | It is a common thing."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.344","kind":"speech"},"3.3.345":{"play":"EMILIA: Do not you chide. I have a thing for you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.345","kind":"speech"},"3.3.346":{"play":"IAGO: You have a thing for me? It is a common thing—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.346","kind":"speech"},"3.3.347":{"play":"EMILIA: Ha?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.347","kind":"speech"},"3.3.348":{"play":"IAGO: To have a foolish wife.","notes":["Fechter: Earnestly.","Booth: Indifferently. Up stage."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.348","kind":"speech"},"3.3.349":{"play":"EMILIA: O, is that all? What will you give me now","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.349","kind":"speech"},"3.3.350":{"play":"EMILIA: For that same handkerchief?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.350","kind":"speech"},"3.3.351":{"play":"IAGO: What handkerchief?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.351","kind":"speech"},"3.3.352":{"play":"EMILIA: What handkerchief?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.352","kind":"speech"},"3.3.353":{"play":"EMILIA: Why, that the Moor first gave to Desdemona,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.353","kind":"speech"},"3.3.354":{"play":"EMILIA: That which so often you did bid me steal.","notes":["Booth: Turn quickly, with delighted expectancy."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.354","kind":"speech"},"3.3.355":{"play":"IAGO: Hast stol’n it from her?","notes":["Collier (ed. i): The Master of the Revels seems to have been capriciously scrupulous in this play; here, according to the Folio, ' 'faith ' was erased as an oath, and this not for the first time. In line 28 the same thing occurs."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.355","kind":"speech"},"3.3.356":{"play":"EMILIA: No, faith, she let it drop by negligence,","notes":["Johnson: I, being opportunely here, took it up."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.356","kind":"speech"},"3.3.357":{"play":"EMILIA: And to th’ advantage I, being here, took ’t up.","notes":["Booth: Snatch at it eagerly."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.357","kind":"speech"},"3.3.358":{"play":"EMILIA: Look, here ’tis.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.358","kind":"speech"},"3.3.359":{"play":"IAGO: A good wench! Give it me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.359","kind":"speech"},"3.3.360":{"play":"EMILIA: What will you do with ’t, that you have been so","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.360","kind":"speech"},"3.3.361":{"play":"EMILIA: earnest","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.361","kind":"speech"},"3.3.362":{"play":"EMILIA: To have me filch it?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.362","kind":"speech"},"3.3.363":{"play":"IAGO: Why, what is that to you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.363","kind":"speech"},"3.3.364":{"play":"EMILIA: If it be not for some purpose of import,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.364","kind":"speech"},"3.3.365":{"play":"EMILIA: Give ’t me again. Poor lady, she’ll run mad","notes":["Steevens: That is, do not acknowledge anything of the matter. The word occurs in Golding's Ovid: 'Howbeit I durst not be so bolde of hope acknowne to bee' [p. 91, Lib. vii, 632, 'nee me sperare fatebar']. Again in Puttenham's Arte of Poesie [p. 260, ed. Arber]: 'so would I not haue a translatour to be ashamed to be acknowen of his translation.'","Porson: Again in The Life of Ariosto, in Harrington's translation of Orlando, ed. 1607: 'Some say, he was married to her privily, but durst not be acknowne of it.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.365","kind":"speech"},"3.3.366":{"play":"EMILIA: When she shall lack it.","notes":["Booth: Many 'Iagos' kiss her, and coax her to leave him,—he is given rather to chiding than to caressing."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.366","kind":"speech"},"3.3.367":{"play":"IAGO: Be not acknown on ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.367","kind":"speech"},"3.3.368":{"play":"IAGO: I have use for it. Go, leave me.","notes":["Booth: Why may not Cassio bind this about his wounded leg at close of the next Act? 'Tis traditional, and reasonable,—do it."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.368","kind":"speech"},"3.3.369":{"play":"IAGO: I will in Cassio’s lodging lose this napkin","notes":["Hunter (ii, 281): Compare V. 60 A. 1023: 'Trifles unwitnessed with eye or ear Thy coward heart with false bethinking grieves.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.369","kind":"speech"},"3.3.370":{"play":"IAGO: And let him find it. Trifles light as air","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.370","kind":"speech"},"3.3.371":{"play":"IAGO: Are to the jealous confirmations strong","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.371","kind":"speech"},"3.3.372":{"play":"IAGO: As proofs of holy writ. This may do something.","notes":["Staunton: The repetition of 'poison' here is so inelegant that we may well suspect the word in one line was caught by the compositor's eye from the other, but it is hard to say in which the corruption lies."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.372","kind":"speech"},"3.3.373":{"play":"IAGO: The Moor already changes with my poison;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.373","kind":"speech"},"3.3.374":{"play":"IAGO: Dangerous conceits are in their natures poisons,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.374","kind":"speech"},"3.3.375":{"play":"IAGO: Which at the first are scarce found to distaste,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.375","kind":"speech"},"3.3.376":{"play":"IAGO: But with a little act upon the blood","notes":["Booth's dramatic instinct clears any difficulty by a stage direction—'Othello groans.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.376","kind":"speech"},"3.3.377":{"play":"IAGO: Burn like the mines of sulfur.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.377","kind":"speech"},"3.3.378":{"play":"IAGO: I did say so.","notes":["Staunton quotes from Holland's Pliny, Bk. xxv, ch. 13: 'This herbe Mandragoras, some writers cal Circeium; and two kinds there be .... It may be used safely enough for to procure sleep, if there be good regard Had in the dose.... Also it is an ordinarie thing to drink it ... before the cutting or cauterizing, pricking or launcing of any member to take away the sence and feeling of such extreme cures. And sufficient it is in some bodies to cast them into a sleep with the smell of Mandrage, against the time of such Chirurgery.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.378","kind":"speech"},"3.3.379":{"play":"IAGO: Look where he comes. Not poppy nor mandragora","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.379","kind":"speech"},"3.3.380":{"play":"IAGO: Nor all the drowsy syrups of the world","notes":["Steevens reads and divides: Which thou ow'dst yesterday. Oth. Ha ha! false to me? | To me? Iago. Why, how now, general? no more of that."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.380","kind":"speech"},"3.3.381":{"play":"IAGO: Shall ever medicine thee to that sweet sleep","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.381","kind":"speech"},"3.3.382":{"play":"IAGO: Which thou owedst yesterday.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.382","kind":"speech"},"3.3.383":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ha, ha, false to me?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.383","kind":"speech"},"3.3.384":{"play":"IAGO: Why, how now, general? No more of that!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.384","kind":"speech"},"3.3.385":{"play":"OTHELLO: Avaunt! Begone! Thou hast set me on the rack.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.385","kind":"speech"},"3.3.386":{"play":"OTHELLO: I swear ’tis better to be much abused","notes":["Warburton: See supra, III, iii, 244."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.386","kind":"speech"},"3.3.387":{"play":"OTHELLO: Than but to know ’t a little.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.387","kind":"speech"},"3.3.388":{"play":"IAGO: How now, my lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.388","kind":"speech"},"3.3.389":{"play":"OTHELLO: What sense had I of her stol’n hours of lust?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.389","kind":"speech"},"3.3.390":{"play":"OTHELLO: I saw ’t not, thought it not; it harmed not me.","notes":["Knight: Sense of is the modern use of the term knowledge of; 'sense in' is the more proper and peculiarly Shakespearian use, which implies the impression upon the senses, and not upon the understanding. The difference is the same as between a sensible man and a man sensible to pain."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.390","kind":"speech"},"3.3.391":{"play":"OTHELLO: I slept the next night well, fed well, was free and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.391","kind":"speech"},"3.3.392":{"play":"OTHELLO: merry.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.392","kind":"speech"},"3.3.393":{"play":"OTHELLO: I found not Cassio’s kisses on her lips.","notes":["Booth: I prefer knowing, for surely Othello did 'want' Desdemona's love at all times and forever. [But 'wanting' is here used not in the sense of needing, but of missing,—and yet even in this sense it has a lack of tenderness.—Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.393","kind":"speech"},"3.3.394":{"play":"OTHELLO: He that is robbed, not wanting what is stol’n,","notes":["Halliwell quotes Milton, ix, 756: 'For good unknown sure is not had; or had And yet unknown, is as not had at all.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.394","kind":"speech"},"3.3.395":{"play":"OTHELLO: Let him not know ’t, and he’s not robbed at all.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.395","kind":"speech"},"3.3.396":{"play":"IAGO: I am sorry to hear this.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.396","kind":"speech"},"3.3.397":{"play":"OTHELLO: I had been happy if the general camp,","notes":["Grose: 'A soldier ought ever to retaine and keepe his arms in safetie and forth comming, for he is more to be detested than a coward, that will lose or play away any part thereof, or refuse it for his ease, or to avoid paines; wherefore such a one is to be dismissed with punishment, or to be made some abject pioner.' Davies's Art of War and England Trainings, 1619.","So, in The Laws and Ordinances of War, established by the Earl of Essex, printed in 1640: 'If a trooper shall loose his horse or hackney, or a footman any part of his arms, by negligence or lewdnesse, by dice or cardes; he or they shall remain in qualitie of pioners, or scavengers, till they be furnished with as good as were lost, at their own charge.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.397","kind":"speech"},"3.3.398":{"play":"OTHELLO: Pioners and all, had tasted her sweet body,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.398","kind":"speech"},"3.3.399":{"play":"OTHELLO: So I had nothing known. O, now, forever","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.399","kind":"speech"},"3.3.400":{"play":"OTHELLO: Farewell the tranquil mind! Farewell content!","notes":["Booth: Utter this, looking off,—towards Desdemona.","My Father once said to me, 'No human voice could surpass, if equal, Edmund Kean's in his delivery of this passage.'","Begin slowly, with suppressed emotion; gradually increase the volume and intensity of voice,—never loud, nor let your tones be too tearful or tremulous,—it becomes monotonous.","Every movement, gesture, look, and tone should be in harmony."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.400","kind":"speech"},"3.3.401":{"play":"OTHELLO: Farewell the plumèd troops and the big wars","notes":["Daniel (Athenaeum, 14 Jan. 1871) calls attention to the change of this word to plumped, in a quotation of these two lines in Suckling's Goblins, 1696, and queries whether it be a misprint, or a misquotation, or the reading of some copy of Othello now lost."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.401","kind":"speech"},"3.3.402":{"play":"OTHELLO: That makes ambition virtue! O, farewell!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.402","kind":"speech"},"3.3.403":{"play":"OTHELLO: Farewell the neighing steed and the shrill trump,","notes":["Warton: In mentioning the fife joined with the drum, Shakespeare, as usual, paints from the life; those instruments accompanying each other being used in his age by the English soldiery.","The fife, however, as a martial instrument, was afterwards entirely discontinued among our troops for many years. It was first used within the memory of man, among our troops, by the British guards, by order of the Duke of Cumberland, when they were encamped at Maestricht, in the year 1747.","Among the French regiments the fife is not found, and is so completely unknown to the French in the present day, that M. Alfred de Vigny, in his translation of this passage of Othello, gives us only the drum."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.403","kind":"speech"},"3.3.404":{"play":"OTHELLO: The spirit-stirring drum, th’ ear-piercing fife,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.404","kind":"speech"},"3.3.405":{"play":"OTHELLO: The royal banner, and all quality,","notes":["Hunter (ii, 286): So singular a use of this word requires something to show that it was not without precedent. Take the following from Langley's Translation of Polydore Virgil, where we find that the Romans celebrated their dead 'with great pomp and circumstance.'—Fol. 122,^."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.405","kind":"speech"},"3.3.406":{"play":"OTHELLO: Pride, pomp, and circumstance of glorious war!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.406","kind":"speech"},"3.3.407":{"play":"OTHELLO: And O you mortal engines, whose rude throats","notes":["Giles (p. 227): Othello does not here allude once to his real grief, or to his recent happiness; but, with a terrible spring of the mind, he leaps the chasm of affliction into which he cannot dare to look, and alights on the other side, amidst the turmoils of his youth, amidst the noise and glories of his soldiership.","This is the instinct of the mind to save itself from madness.","Othello, in this passage, reveals the casuistry with which the mind blinds itself to ruin; the sophistry in which it quibbles with despair; the maniac strength with which it wrestles against fate and fact. It is as when we fall asleep with a heavy trouble on the soul; the soul takes advantage of this silent hour to escape from its bondage; again it is on the sunny hills; the strength of youth comes back, with the gladness of love and the hopes of life; not once does the spectre of ill throw its shadow on the dream; the vision is bright while the eyes are shut; but no sooner do they open than the dismal reality is present, and it cannot be dismissed."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.407","kind":"speech"},"3.3.408":{"play":"OTHELLO: Th’ immortal Jove’s dread clamors counterfeit,","notes":["Lewes (p. 4): Kean's range of expression was very limited. His physical aptitudes were such as confined him to the strictly tragic passions; and for these he was magnificently endowed.","Small and insignificant in figure, he could at times become impressively commanding by the lion-like power and grace of his bearing.","I remember the last time I saw him play Othello, how puny he appeared beside Macready, until in the Third Act, when, roused by Iago's taunts and insinuations, he moved towards him with a gouty hobble, seized him by the throat, and, in a well-known explosion, 'Villain! be sure,' &c, he seemed to swell into a stature which made Macready appear small.","On that very evening, when gout made it difficult for him to display his accustomed grace, when a drunken hoarseness had ruined that once matchless voice, such was the irresistible pathos,—manly, not tearful,—which vibrated in his tones and expressed itself in looks and gestures, that old men leaned their heads upon their arms and fairly sobbed.","It was, one must confess, a patchy performance considered as a whole; some parts were miserably tricky, others misconceived, others gabbled over in haste to reach the points; but it was irradiated with such flashes that I would again risk broken ribs for the chance of a good place in the pit to see anything like it."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.408","kind":"speech"},"3.3.409":{"play":"OTHELLO: Farewell! Othello’s occupation’s gone!","notes":["Booth: As before, with smothered intensity, not loud, gradually increasing, till 'If thou dost slander her'—when the full force of Othello's wrath breaks forth in violent tones and he seizes Iago, who cowers."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.409","kind":"speech"},"3.3.410":{"play":"IAGO: Is ’t possible, my lord?","notes":["Maginn (p. 273): We may observe that he still, though his suspicions are so fiercely aroused, calls her his 'love.' It is for the last time before her death. After her guilt is, as he thinks, proved, he has no word of affection for her. She is a convicted culprit, to be sacrificed to his sense of justice."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.410","kind":"speech"},"3.3.411":{"play":"OTHELLO: Villain, be sure thou prove my love a whore!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.411","kind":"speech"},"3.3.412":{"play":"OTHELLO: Be sure of it. Give me the ocular proof,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.412","kind":"speech"},"3.3.413":{"play":"OTHELLO: Or, by the worth of mine eternal soul,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.413","kind":"speech"},"3.3.414":{"play":"OTHELLO: Thou hadst been better have been born a dog","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.414","kind":"speech"},"3.3.415":{"play":"OTHELLO: Than answer my waked wrath.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.415","kind":"speech"},"3.3.416":{"play":"IAGO: Is ’t come to this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.416","kind":"speech"},"3.3.417":{"play":"OTHELLO: Make me to see ’t, or at the least so prove it","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.417","kind":"speech"},"3.3.418":{"play":"OTHELLO: That the probation bear no hinge nor loop","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.418","kind":"speech"},"3.3.419":{"play":"OTHELLO: To hang a doubt on, or woe upon thy life!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.419","kind":"speech"},"3.3.420":{"play":"IAGO: My noble lord—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.420","kind":"speech"},"3.3.421":{"play":"OTHELLO: If thou dost slander her and torture me,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.421","kind":"speech"},"3.3.422":{"play":"OTHELLO: Never pray more. Abandon all remorse;","notes":["Malone: All tenderness of nature, all pity. [See post, line 185.]"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.422","kind":"speech"},"3.3.423":{"play":"OTHELLO: On horror’s head horrors accumulate;","notes":["Hudson: That is, apparently here, conscience; 'Cast off the restraints and regards of conscience altogether.' The sense of pity, however, is included and interfused with it.","What an appalling disclosure this speech is, of Othello's excruciating agony of mind!"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.423","kind":"speech"},"3.3.424":{"play":"OTHELLO: Do deeds to make heaven weep, all Earth amazed;","notes":["Steevens: Compare Meas. for Meas. II, ii, 121: 'Plays such fantastic tricks before high Heaven, As make the angels weep.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.424","kind":"speech"},"3.3.425":{"play":"OTHELLO: For nothing canst thou to damnation add","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.425","kind":"speech"},"3.3.426":{"play":"OTHELLO: Greater than that.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.426","kind":"speech"},"3.3.427":{"play":"IAGO: O grace! O heaven forgive me!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.427","kind":"speech"},"3.3.428":{"play":"IAGO: Are you a man? Have you a soul or sense?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.428","kind":"speech"},"3.3.429":{"play":"IAGO: God b’ wi’ you. Take mine office.—O wretched fool,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.429","kind":"speech"},"3.3.430":{"play":"IAGO: That liv’st to make thine honesty a vice!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.430","kind":"speech"},"3.3.431":{"play":"IAGO: O monstrous world! Take note, take note, O world:","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.431","kind":"speech"},"3.3.432":{"play":"IAGO: To be direct and honest is not safe.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.432","kind":"speech"},"3.3.433":{"play":"IAGO: I thank you for this profit, and from hence","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.433","kind":"speech"},"3.3.434":{"play":"IAGO: I’ll love no friend, sith love breeds such offense.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.434","kind":"speech"},"3.3.435":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nay, stay. Thou shouldst be honest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.435","kind":"speech"},"3.3.436":{"play":"IAGO: I should be wise; for honesty’s a fool","notes":["Abbott, § 299: Be expresses more doubt than is after a verb of thinking. Very significant is this difference in this line of the doubtful Othello where is is the emphatic word and the line contains the extra dramatic syllable."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.436","kind":"speech"},"3.3.437":{"play":"IAGO: And loses that it works for.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.437","kind":"speech"},"3.3.438":{"play":"OTHELLO: By the world,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.438","kind":"speech"},"3.3.439":{"play":"OTHELLO: I think my wife be honest and think she is not.","notes":["Knight: There is probably not a more fatal corruption of the meaning of the poet [than her of Q2] amongst the thousand corruptions for which his editors are answerable. It destroys the master-key to Othello's character. It is his intense feeling of honour that makes his wife's supposed fault so terrific to him.","It is not that Desdemona's name is begrimed and black, but that his own name is degraded. This one thought, here for the first time exhibited, pervades all the rest of the play; and when we understand how the poison operates upon Othello's mind, we are quite prepared fully to believe him when he says, in conclusion,—'For naught I did in hate, but all in honour.'","The thought that his own name is now tarnished drives him at once into a phrenzy. He has said, ‘I'll have some proof;’ but the moment that the idea of dishonour comes across his sensitive nature he bursts into uncontrolled fury: 'If there be cords,.... I'll not endure it.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.439","kind":"speech"},"3.3.440":{"play":"OTHELLO: I think that thou art just and think thou art not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.440","kind":"speech"},"3.3.441":{"play":"OTHELLO: I’ll have some proof! Her name, that was as fresh","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.441","kind":"speech"},"3.3.442":{"play":"OTHELLO: As Dian’s visage, is now begrimed and black","notes":["Walker (Crit. iii, 287) prefers this to the I see, sir of the Qq, and contracts 'you are' to yare. See line 27 above."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.442","kind":"speech"},"3.3.443":{"play":"OTHELLO: As mine own face. If there be cords, or knives,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.443","kind":"speech"},"3.3.444":{"play":"OTHELLO: Poison, or fire, or suffocating streams,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.444","kind":"speech"},"3.3.445":{"play":"OTHELLO: I’ll not endure it. Would I were satisfied!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.445","kind":"speech"},"3.3.446":{"play":"IAGO: I see you are eaten up with passion.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.446","kind":"speech"},"3.3.447":{"play":"IAGO: I do repent me that I put it to you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.447","kind":"speech"},"3.3.448":{"play":"IAGO: You would be satisfied?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.448","kind":"speech"},"3.3.449":{"play":"OTHELLO: Would? Nay, and I will.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.449","kind":"speech"},"3.3.450":{"play":"IAGO: And may; but how? How satisfied, my lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.450","kind":"speech"},"3.3.451":{"play":"IAGO: Would you, the supervisor, grossly gape on,","notes":["Warburton: I would read fear-dispersing, i.e. fear-dispersing; whereupon Edwards (p. 34) suspects a misprint, and that Warburton intended to say, 'I would write; for no man living can read such a cluster of consonants.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.451","kind":"speech"},"3.3.452":{"play":"IAGO: Behold her topped?","notes":["Hazlitt (Hawkins's Life of Kean, ii, 209): Kean was great, as we expected, surpassingly great. In the Third Act he let himself loose on the ocean of his passion, and drove on in darkness and in tempest, like an abandoned barque.","The agony of his heart was the fiery Moorish agony, not cramped in within an actor's or a schoolman's confines, but fierce, ungovernable, dangerous.","You knew not what he would do next in the madness of his spirit,—he knew not himself what he should do.","One of the finest instantaneous actions of Kean was his clutching his black hand slowly round his head as though his brain were turning, and then writhing round and standing in dull agony with his back to the audience,—what other performer would so have forgotten himself?"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.452","kind":"speech"},"3.3.453":{"play":"OTHELLO: Death and damnation! O!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.453","kind":"speech"},"3.3.454":{"play":"IAGO: It were a tedious difficulty, I think,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.454","kind":"speech"},"3.3.455":{"play":"IAGO: To bring them to that prospect. Damn them then","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.455","kind":"speech"},"3.3.456":{"play":"IAGO: If ever mortal eyes do see them bolster","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.456","kind":"speech"},"3.3.457":{"play":"IAGO: More than their own! What then? How then?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.457","kind":"speech"},"3.3.458":{"play":"IAGO: What shall I say? Where’s satisfaction?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.458","kind":"speech"},"3.3.459":{"play":"IAGO: It is impossible you should see this,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.459","kind":"speech"},"3.3.460":{"play":"IAGO: Were they as prime as goats, as hot as monkeys,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.460","kind":"speech"},"3.3.461":{"play":"IAGO: As salt as wolves in pride, and fools as gross","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.461","kind":"speech"},"3.3.462":{"play":"IAGO: As ignorance made drunk. But yet I say,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.462","kind":"speech"},"3.3.463":{"play":"IAGO: If imputation and strong circumstances","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.463","kind":"speech"},"3.3.464":{"play":"IAGO: Which lead directly to the door of truth","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.464","kind":"speech"},"3.3.465":{"play":"IAGO: Will give you satisfaction, you might have ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.465","kind":"speech"},"3.3.466":{"play":"OTHELLO: Give me a living reason she’s disloyal.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.466","kind":"speech"},"3.3.467":{"play":"IAGO: I do not like the office,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.467","kind":"speech"},"3.3.468":{"play":"IAGO: But sith I am entered in this cause so far,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.468","kind":"speech"},"3.3.469":{"play":"IAGO: Pricked to ’t by foolish honesty and love,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.469","kind":"speech"},"3.3.470":{"play":"IAGO: I will go on. I lay with Cassio lately,","notes":["Booth: Iago affects remorse for having 'put this to him,' &c."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.470","kind":"speech"},"3.3.471":{"play":"IAGO: And being troubled with a raging tooth","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.471","kind":"speech"},"3.3.472":{"play":"IAGO: I could not sleep. There are a kind of men","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.472","kind":"speech"},"3.3.473":{"play":"IAGO: So loose of soul that in their sleeps will mutter","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.473","kind":"speech"},"3.3.474":{"play":"IAGO: Their affairs. One of this kind is Cassio.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.474","kind":"speech"},"3.3.475":{"play":"IAGO: In sleep I heard him say","notes":["Booth: Holds Othello's hand, which Othello draws with disgust from his grasp."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.475","kind":"speech"},"3.3.477":{"play":"IAGO: And then, sir, would he gripe and wring my hand,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.477","kind":"speech"},"3.3.478":{"play":"IAGO: Cry then kiss me hard,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.478","kind":"speech"},"3.3.479":{"play":"IAGO: As if he plucked up kisses by the roots","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.479","kind":"speech"},"3.3.480":{"play":"IAGO: That grew upon my lips; then laid his leg","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.480","kind":"speech"},"3.3.481":{"play":"IAGO: O’er my thigh, and sighed, and kissed, and then","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.481","kind":"speech"},"3.3.482":{"play":"IAGO: Cried","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.482","kind":"speech"},"3.3.483":{"play":"OTHELLO: O monstrous! Monstrous!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.483","kind":"speech"},"3.3.484":{"play":"IAGO: Nay, this was but his","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.484","kind":"speech"},"3.3.485":{"play":"IAGO: dream.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.485","kind":"speech"},"3.3.486":{"play":"OTHELLO: But this denoted a foregone conclusion.","notes":["Booth: Here you may let the savage have vent,—but for a moment only; when Othello next speaks he is tame again and speaks sadly. Iago has caught and held him as he was about to rush off to 'tear her all to pieces.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.486","kind":"speech"},"3.3.487":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Tis a shrewd doubt, though it be but a dream.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.487","kind":"speech"},"3.3.488":{"play":"IAGO: And this may help to thicken other proofs","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.488","kind":"speech"},"3.3.489":{"play":"IAGO: That do demonstrate thinly.","notes":["Halliwell: Mr Fairholt sends me the following curious note: 'The ladies of the Shakespearian era were great adepts in the use of the needle; the designs they made use of were consequently conventional like those worked by our grandmothers in the school sampler. Flowers and fruits were depicted in a sort of heraldic fashion, and repeated mechanically over the surface to be ornamented.'","'The habit of wearing curiously wrought handkerchiefs, which prevailed in our author's day, was derived from the East, where it was customary for both sexes to carry them.'—Nott."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.489","kind":"speech"},"3.3.490":{"play":"OTHELLO: I’ll tear her all to pieces.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.490","kind":"speech"},"3.3.491":{"play":"IAGO: Nay, but be wise. Yet we see nothing done.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.491","kind":"speech"},"3.3.492":{"play":"IAGO: She may be honest yet. Tell me but this:","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.492","kind":"speech"},"3.3.493":{"play":"IAGO: Have you not sometimes seen a handkerchief","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.493","kind":"speech"},"3.3.494":{"play":"IAGO: Spotted with strawberries in your wife’s hand?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.494","kind":"speech"},"3.3.495":{"play":"OTHELLO: I gave her such a one. ’Twas my first gift.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.495","kind":"speech"},"3.3.496":{"play":"IAGO: I know not that; but such a handkerchief—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.496","kind":"speech"},"3.3.497":{"play":"IAGO: I am sure it was your wife’s—did I today","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.497","kind":"speech"},"3.3.498":{"play":"IAGO: See Cassio wipe his beard with.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.498","kind":"speech"},"3.3.499":{"play":"OTHELLO: If it be that—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.499","kind":"speech"},"3.3.500":{"play":"IAGO: If it be that, or any that was hers,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.500","kind":"speech"},"3.3.501":{"play":"IAGO: It speaks against her with the other proofs.","notes":["Elze (Note on Ham. V, i, 257): Shakespeare's fondness for this number as an expression of indefiniteness."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.501","kind":"speech"},"3.3.502":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, that the slave had forty thousand lives!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.502","kind":"speech"},"3.3.503":{"play":"OTHELLO: One is too poor, too weak for my revenge.","notes":["Booth: Although the savage blood is up, let a wave of humanity weep over his heart at these words. Breathe out ''Tis gone' with a sigh of agony which seems to exhale love to heaven.","Fechter: Othello falls back on his seat, quite humbled."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.503","kind":"speech"},"3.3.504":{"play":"OTHELLO: Now do I see ’tis true. Look here, Iago,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.504","kind":"speech"},"3.3.505":{"play":"OTHELLO: All my fond love thus do I blow to heaven.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.505","kind":"speech"},"3.3.506":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Tis gone.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.506","kind":"speech"},"3.3.507":{"play":"OTHELLO: Arise, black vengeance, from the hollow hell!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.507","kind":"speech"},"3.3.508":{"play":"OTHELLO: Yield up, O love, thy crown and hearted throne","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.508","kind":"speech"},"3.3.509":{"play":"OTHELLO: To tyrannous hate! Swell, bosom, with thy fraught,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.509","kind":"speech"},"3.3.510":{"play":"OTHELLO: For ’tis of aspics’ tongues!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.510","kind":"speech"},"3.3.511":{"play":"IAGO: Yet be content.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.511","kind":"speech"},"3.3.512":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, blood, blood, blood!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.512","kind":"speech"},"3.3.513":{"play":"IAGO: Patience, I say. Your mind perhaps may change.","notes":["Fechter: Exciting him."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.513","kind":"speech"},"3.3.514":{"play":"OTHELLO: Never, Iago. Like to the Pontic Sea,","notes":["Pope: This simile is omitted in the first edition; I think it should be so, as an unnatural excursion in this place.","Steevens: Every reader will, I durst say, abide by Mr Pope's censure on this passage. When Shakespeare grew acquainted with such particulars of knowledge, he made a display of them as soon as opportunity offered."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.514","kind":"speech"},"3.3.515":{"play":"OTHELLO: Whose icy current and compulsive course","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.515","kind":"speech"},"3.3.516":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ne’er feels retiring ebb, but keeps due on","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.516","kind":"speech"},"3.3.517":{"play":"OTHELLO: To the Propontic and the Hellespont,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.517","kind":"speech"},"3.3.518":{"play":"OTHELLO: Even so my bloody thoughts, with violent pace","notes":["Hazlitt: If this passage in Othello were the only instance in Shakespeare where 'marble' is applied to the 'heavens,' this fine interpretation might stand without question....","But let us only mark the opposition of the two lines: 'All my fond love thus do I blow to heaven. Arise, black vengeance, from the hollow hell.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.518","kind":"speech"},"3.3.519":{"play":"OTHELLO: Shall ne’er look back, ne’er ebb to humble love,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.519","kind":"speech"},"3.3.520":{"play":"OTHELLO: Till that a capable and wide revenge","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.520","kind":"speech"},"3.3.521":{"play":"OTHELLO: Swallow them up. Now by yond marble","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.521","kind":"speech"},"3.3.522":{"play":"OTHELLO: heaven,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.522","kind":"speech"},"3.3.523":{"play":"OTHELLO: In the due reverence of a sacred vow,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.523","kind":"speech"},"3.3.524":{"play":"OTHELLO: I here engage my words.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.524","kind":"speech"},"3.3.525":{"play":"IAGO: Do not rise yet.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.525","kind":"speech"},"3.3.526":{"play":"IAGO: Witness, you ever-burning lights above,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.526","kind":"speech"},"3.3.527":{"play":"IAGO: You elements that clip us round about,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.527","kind":"speech"},"3.3.528":{"play":"IAGO: Witness that here Iago doth give up","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.528","kind":"speech"},"3.3.529":{"play":"IAGO: The execution of his wit, hands, heart","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.529","kind":"speech"},"3.3.530":{"play":"IAGO: To wronged Othello’s service! Let him command,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.530","kind":"speech"},"3.3.531":{"play":"IAGO: And to obey shall be in me remorse,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.531","kind":"speech"},"3.3.532":{"play":"IAGO: What bloody business ever.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.532","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.3.532":{"play":"[They rise.]","notes":["Booth: Kneels. Both hands above the head, with upturned palms and fingers towards the back. I used this gesture impulsively, in England first, and it was spoken of as suggestive of the Orient."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.3.532","kind":"stage"},"3.3.533":{"play":"OTHELLO: I greet thy love","notes":["Booth: Iago watches Othello keenly—sidewise—during his next speech; while Othello seems absorbed and with upturned eyes."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.533","kind":"speech"},"3.3.534":{"play":"OTHELLO: Not with vain thanks but with acceptance","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.534","kind":"speech"},"3.3.535":{"play":"OTHELLO: bounteous,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.535","kind":"speech"},"3.3.536":{"play":"OTHELLO: And will upon the instant put thee to ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.536","kind":"speech"},"3.3.537":{"play":"OTHELLO: Within these three days let me hear thee say","notes":["Johnson: Iago devotes himself to wronged Othello, and says, 'Let him command whatever bloody business, and in me it shall be an act, not of cruelty, but of tenderness, to obey him; not of malice to others, but of tenderness to him.'"],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.537","kind":"speech"},"3.3.538":{"play":"OTHELLO: That Cassio’s not alive.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.538","kind":"speech"},"3.3.539":{"play":"IAGO: My friend is dead.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.539","kind":"speech"},"3.3.540":{"play":"IAGO: ’Tis done at your request. But let her live.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.540","kind":"speech"},"3.3.541":{"play":"OTHELLO: Damn her, lewd minx! O, damn her, damn","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.541","kind":"speech"},"3.3.542":{"play":"OTHELLO: her!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.542","kind":"speech"},"3.3.543":{"play":"OTHELLO: Come, go with me apart. I will withdraw","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.543","kind":"speech"},"3.3.544":{"play":"OTHELLO: To furnish me with some swift means of death","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.544","kind":"speech"},"3.3.545":{"play":"OTHELLO: For the fair devil. Now art thou my lieutenant.","notes":["Booth: Iago shows deep grief till 'Now art thou my lieutenant,' then, quickly kneeling, he kisses Othello's hand, and his face reveals his triumph."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.545","kind":"speech"},"3.3.546":{"play":"IAGO: I am your own forever.","notes":["Booth: To portray Iago properly you must seem to be what all the characters think, and say, you are, not what the spectators know you to be; try to win even them by your sincerity. Don't act the villain, don't look it or speak it (by scowling and growling, I mean), but think it all the time. Be genial, sometimes jovial, always gentlemanly. Quick in motion as in thought; lithe and sinuous as a snake. A certain bluffness (which my temperament does not afford) should be added to preserve the military flavor of the character; in this particular I fail utterly, my Iago lacks the soldierly quality. My consolation is that we know him more as a courtier than as a soldier."],"folgerAnchor":"3.3.546","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.3.546.1":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.3.546.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 3, SCENE 4":{"SD_3.4.0":{"play":"[Enter Desdemona, Emilia, and Clown.]","notes":["Om.: Qq, Rowe. Scene IX. Pope +, Jen. Another Apartment in the Palace. Theob. Before the Castle. Dyce."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.4.0","kind":"stage"},"3.4.1":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Do you know, sirrah, where Lieutenant","notes":["Clown: Douce (ii, 272): He appears but twice in the play, and was certainly intended to be an allowed, or domestic, fool in the service of Othello and Desdemona."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.1","kind":"speech"},"3.4.2":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Cassio lies?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.2","kind":"speech"},"3.4.3":{"play":"CLOWN: I dare not say he lies anywhere.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.3","kind":"speech"},"3.4.4":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Why, man?","notes":["lies: Shakespeare was not above sharing the weakness of his contemporaries in making puns on this word. See also Ham. V, i, 116."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.4","kind":"speech"},"3.4.5":{"play":"CLOWN: He’s a soldier, and for me to say a soldier lies,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.5","kind":"speech"},"3.4.6":{"play":"CLOWN: ’tis stabbing.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.6","kind":"speech"},"3.4.7":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Go to! Where lodges he?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.7","kind":"speech"},"3.4.8":{"play":"CLOWN: To tell you where he lodges is to tell you","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.8","kind":"speech"},"3.4.9":{"play":"CLOWN: where I lie.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.9","kind":"speech"},"3.4.10":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Can anything be made of this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.10","kind":"speech"},"3.4.11":{"play":"CLOWN: I know not where he lodges; and for me to","notes":["throat: John Hunter: This meant, to utter a wilful lie. \"To lie in the teeth\" was less intentional, and gave less offence."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.11","kind":"speech"},"3.4.12":{"play":"CLOWN: devise a lodging and say he lies here, or he lies","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.12","kind":"speech"},"3.4.13":{"play":"CLOWN: there, were to lie in mine own throat.","notes":["by them: Warburton: The Clown was to go seek for one; he says he will ask for him, and by his own questions make answer. Without doubt we should read, \"and bid them answer;\" i.e., the world; those whom he questions. Henley: His design was to propose such questions as might elicit the information sought for from him, and, therefore, by his questions he might be enabled to answer. Malone: That is, and by them, when answered, form my own answer to you. Rolfe states it clearly By them be enabled to answer, or get the information to use in my answer."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.13","kind":"speech"},"3.4.14":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Can you inquire him out, and be edified","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.14","kind":"speech"},"3.4.15":{"play":"DESDEMONA: by report?","notes":["doing it: For a full exposition of verbals, followed by an object, see Abbott, § 93, or Macb. I, iv, 8."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.15","kind":"speech"},"3.4.16":{"play":"CLOWN: I will catechize the world for him—that is,","notes":["should I lose: Abbott, §325: \"Should,\" in a direct question about the past, seems to increase the emphasis of the interrogation, since a doubt about the past (time having been given for investigation) implies more perplexity than a doubt about the future.","the: White (ed. i): That of the Qq has a loss of significance. To Desdemona this handkerchief was at any time the handkerchief, and now more so than ever."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.16","kind":"speech"},"3.4.17":{"play":"CLOWN: make questions, and by them answer.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.17","kind":"speech"},"3.4.18":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Seek him, bid him come hither. Tell him I","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.18","kind":"speech"},"3.4.19":{"play":"DESDEMONA: have moved my lord on his behalf and hope all will","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.19","kind":"speech"},"3.4.20":{"play":"DESDEMONA: be well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.20","kind":"speech"},"3.4.21":{"play":"CLOWN: To do this is within the compass of man’s wit,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.21","kind":"speech"},"3.4.22":{"play":"CLOWN: and therefore I will attempt the doing it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.22","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.4.22.1":{"play":"[Clown exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.4.22.1","kind":"stage"},"3.4.23":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Where should I lose that handkerchief, Emilia?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.23","kind":"speech"},"3.4.24":{"play":"EMILIA: I know not, madam.","notes":["Hudson: Objection has been made to the conduct of Emilia in this scene as inconsistent with the spirit she afterwards shows. I can discover no such inconsistency. Want of principle and strength of attachment are often thus seen united. Emilia loves her mistress deeply, but she has no moral repugnance to theft and falsehood, apprehends no fatal consequences from the Moor's passion, and has no soul to conceive the agony her mistress must suffer by the charge of infidelity; and it is but natural that when the result comes she should be the more spirited for the very remembrance of her own guilty part in the process. Booth: Emilia speaks with slight embarrassment."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.24","kind":"speech"},"3.4.25":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Believe me, I had rather have lost my purse","notes":["rather: Cited by Walker (Vers. 108) as an instance of its contraction into a monosyllable. See also, to the same purpose, Abbott, § 466."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.25","kind":"speech"},"3.4.26":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Full of crusadoes. And but my noble Moor","notes":["Cruzadoes: Grey: A Portuguese coin, in value three shillings. Johnson: So called from the cross stamped on it. Fechter: Desdemona turns over her work and materials to find the handkerchief."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.26","kind":"speech"},"3.4.27":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Is true of mind and made of no such baseness","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.27","kind":"speech"},"3.4.28":{"play":"DESDEMONA: As jealous creatures are, it were enough","notes":["as jealous creatures are: Rymer (p. 126): By this manner of speech one would gather the couple had been yoked together a competent while, what might she say more, had they been man and wife seven years?"],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.28","kind":"speech"},"3.4.29":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To put him to ill thinking.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.29","kind":"speech"},"3.4.30":{"play":"EMILIA: Is he not jealous?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.30","kind":"speech"},"3.4.31":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Who, he? I think the sun where he was born","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.31","kind":"speech"},"3.4.32":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Drew all such humors from him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.32","kind":"speech"},"3.4.33":{"play":"EMILIA: Look where he","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.33","kind":"speech"},"3.4.34":{"play":"EMILIA: comes.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.34","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.4.34.1":{"play":"[Enter Othello.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.4.34.1","kind":"stage"},"3.4.35":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I will not leave him now till Cassio","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.35","kind":"speech"},"3.4.36":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Be called to him.—How is ’t with you, my lord?","notes":["to him: Fechter: Exit Emilia R. at the moment when Othello appears at the terrace. He observes them an instant; then comes down, straight to where Desdemona has been deranging her work and materials, looking at them with mistrust; when he speaks he represses his anger. Booth: Othello addresses Desdemona as he passes her, then he suddenly changes his tone and manner from indifference to sadness."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.36","kind":"speech"},"3.4.37":{"play":"OTHELLO: Well, my good lady. O, hardness to","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.37","kind":"speech"},"3.4.38":{"play":"OTHELLO: dissemble!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.38","kind":"speech"},"3.4.39":{"play":"OTHELLO: How do you, Desdemona?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.39","kind":"speech"},"3.4.40":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Well, my good lord.","notes":["sorrow: Booth: At the word \"sorrow\" he looks anxiously into her eyes, and with a sigh proceeds."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.40","kind":"speech"},"3.4.41":{"play":"OTHELLO: Give me your hand. This hand","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.41","kind":"speech"},"3.4.42":{"play":"OTHELLO: is moist, my lady.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.42","kind":"speech"},"3.4.43":{"play":"DESDEMONA: It yet has felt no age nor known no sorrow.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.43","kind":"speech"},"3.4.44":{"play":"OTHELLO: This argues fruitfulness and liberal heart.","notes":["fruitfulness: Delius: That is, liberal, bountiful, as \"fruitful\" is used in II, ii, 372."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.44","kind":"speech"},"3.4.45":{"play":"OTHELLO: Hot, hot, and moist. This hand of yours requires","notes":["moist: Bucknill (Med Knowledge of Sh. p. 273): This appears to express an old opinion that \"a moist palm indicates a hot liver,\" one, however, which Primrose considered a vulgar error, and to the refutation of which he devoted a chapter. Booth: Examining its lines as in palmistry."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.45","kind":"speech"},"3.4.46":{"play":"OTHELLO: A sequester from liberty, fasting and prayer,","notes":["Exercise: Malone: This was the term for religious duties. \"Henry VII,\" says Bacon, \"had the fortune of a true Christian as well as of a great king, in living exercised, and dying repentant.\""],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.46","kind":"speech"},"3.4.47":{"play":"OTHELLO: Much castigation, exercise devout;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.47","kind":"speech"},"3.4.48":{"play":"OTHELLO: For here’s a young and sweating devil here","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.48","kind":"speech"},"3.4.49":{"play":"OTHELLO: That commonly rebels. ’Tis a good hand,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.49","kind":"speech"},"3.4.50":{"play":"OTHELLO: A frank one.","notes":["hand, ... one.: Walker (iii, 288): Arrange, perhaps,—'\"Tis a good hand, a frank one. Desd. You may indeed say so; for 'twas that hand that gave away my heart.\" [I record this note, like many another of Walker, simply because I lack the moral courage to omit it. When Walker spends his time and ours in cutting up verses, and fragments of verses spoken by different characters, into lines, what else is it but scanning by the eye and for the eye? If the words do not flow musically, cutting them into lines will not make them musical. If they do flow musically, the lines will take care of themselves. Is it to be imagined that Shakespeare ever followed any guide but his ear? What does the ear know of lines? recurrent or uncurrent rhythm is all that ever it can note. Ed.]","frank one: Keightley (Exp. 304): I have given in my edition \"A frank one too,\" but no addition was necessary. I made an error for the sake of metre, and, I think, weakened the passage. [And was anticipated by Capell, after all. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.50","kind":"speech"},"3.4.51":{"play":"DESDEMONA: You may indeed say so,","notes":["Boaden (Life of Kemble, i, 259): During this speech of Othello, Mrs Siddons's face had a beauty of expression that offered one of the most striking and varying pictures ever contemplated. The surprise, arising to astonishment, a sort of doubt if she heard aright, and that being admitted, what it could mean; a hope that it would end in nothing so unusual from him as an offensive meaning; and the slight relief upon Othello's adding—\"'Tis a good hand, a frank one\"; all this commentary was quite as legible as the text."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.51","kind":"speech"},"3.4.52":{"play":"DESDEMONA: For ’twas that hand that gave away my heart.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.52","kind":"speech"},"3.4.53":{"play":"OTHELLO: A liberal hand! The hearts of old gave hands,","notes":["you: Abbott, §483: Emphasized pronouns sometimes dispense with the unaccented syllable. Here you is emphatic."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.53","kind":"speech"},"3.4.54":{"play":"OTHELLO: But our new heraldry is hands, not hearts.","notes":["In these lines Warburton discerned a satirical allusion to the creation of baronets by James the First, and founded on it the date of the composition of the play. For his arguments in this regard and Malone's reply to them, see Appendix, Date of the Composition. Warburton also asserted that \"it is evident that line 55 should be read: 'The hands of old gave hearts'; otherwise it would be no reply to 'For 'twas that hand that gave away my heart.' Not so, says her husband, 'The hands of old indeed gave hearts; but the custom now is to give hands without hearts.'\" Johnson: Of emendation there is no need. She says that her hand gave away her heart. He goes on with his suspicion, and the hand which he had before called frank, he now terms liberal; then proceeds to remark that the hand was formerly given by the heart; but now it neither gives it, nor is given by it. Steevens: The phrase \"our new heraldry\" is only figurative, without the least reference to James's creation of baronets. The absurdity of making Othello so familiar with British heraldry, the utter want of consistency as well as policy in any sneer of Shakespeare at the badge of honours instituted by a Prince whom, on all other occasions, he was solicitous to flatter, and at whose court this very piece was acted in 1613, most strongly incline me to question the propriety of Warburton's historical explanation. Malone: The hearts of old, says Othello, dictated the union of hands, which formerly were joined with the hearts of the parties in them; but in our modern marriages, hands alone are united, without hearts. Such is the plain meaning of the words. I do not, however, undertake to maintain that the poet, when he used the word \"heraldry,\" had not the new order of baronets in his thoughts, without intending any satirical allusion. Knight: We do not think that Shakespeare would have gone out of his way to introduce a covert sarcasm at a passing event, offensive as it must have been if understood, and perfectly useless if not understood. The obvious meaning of the words, without any allusion, is plain enough; and \"our new heraldry,\" if it be any more than a figurative expression, may be easily referred to the practice of quartering or joining the arms of husband and wife. Dyce (Remarks, p. 241): The reader will probably recollect with dismay the immense mass of annotation which this passage has called forth in consequence of Warburton's ridiculous idea that the poet alluded here to the new order of baronets created by King James. I have only to observe: first,—that the word \"heraldry\" (which the commentators are surprised at finding here) was evidently suggested to Shakespeare by the words in the preceding line, \"gave hands\" (to \"give arms\" being a heraldic term); secondly, that Warner, in his Albion's England, p. 282, ed. 1596, has, \"My hand shall never give my heart, my heart shall give my hand.\" White (ed. i and ed. ii) adopts Warburton's idea. In his ed. ii he says: \"This seems to be the new heraldry Othello speaks of; but in that case, the passage was probably added after the first production of the play.\""],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.54","kind":"speech"},"3.4.55":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I cannot speak of this. Come now, your promise.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.55","kind":"speech"},"3.4.56":{"play":"OTHELLO: What promise, chuck?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.56","kind":"speech"},"3.4.57":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I have sent to bid Cassio come speak with you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.57","kind":"speech"},"3.4.58":{"play":"OTHELLO: I have a salt and sorry rheum offends me.","notes":["sorry: Johnson's interpretation of sullen of the Qq is \"a rheum obstinately troublesome.\" Collier (ed. ii): Perhaps the word is sudden, to which it is altered in the (MS.)."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.58","kind":"speech"},"3.4.59":{"play":"OTHELLO: Lend me thy handkerchief.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.59","kind":"speech"},"3.4.60":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Here, my lord.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.60","kind":"speech"},"3.4.61":{"play":"OTHELLO: That which I gave you.","notes":["Booth: Quickly—hoping to see the one he gave her."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.61","kind":"speech"},"3.4.62":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I have it not about me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.62","kind":"speech"},"3.4.63":{"play":"OTHELLO: Not?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.63","kind":"speech"},"3.4.64":{"play":"DESDEMONA: No, faith, my lord.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.64","kind":"speech"},"3.4.65":{"play":"OTHELLO: That’s a fault. That handkerchief","notes":["Handkerchief: Theobald: Cinthio Giraldi only says it was the Moor's gift upon his wedding to Desdemona; that it was most curiously wrought after the Moorish Fashion, and very dear both to him and his wife, \"il qual pannicello era lavorato alla moresca sottilissimamente, & era carissimo alia Donna & parimente al Moro.\" Booth: All this description of the Handkerchief should be told with an air of intense and earnest mystery. Desdemona should listen in wonder and speak like a frightened child."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.65","kind":"speech"},"3.4.66":{"play":"OTHELLO: Did an Egyptian to my mother give.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.66","kind":"speech"},"3.4.67":{"play":"OTHELLO: She was a charmer, and could almost read","notes":["Egyptian: Hunter (ii, 284): By this, Shakespeare may mean either an Egyptian properly so called, or a Gypsy or Bohemian, as the same people are called in many parts of the continent. Presents of this kind from Gypsies proper occur in Italian Poetry; thus Ariosto: \"About her neck a jewel rich she ware, A cross all set with stones in gold well tried; This relick late a Boem pilgrim bare, And gave her father other things beside,\" &c. But the mention of \"mummy,\" and other points in the passage, seem to guide us to the true Egyptians, neighbours of the Moors. Elze [Sh. Jahrbuch, xi, 299) calls attention to Maudlin's description of her \"browder'd belt,\" which \"A Gypsan lady, and a right beldame Wrought by moonlight,\" in Jonson's Sad Shepherd, II, i. Elze finds a noteworthy similarity therein with this passage in Othello."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.67","kind":"speech"},"3.4.68":{"play":"OTHELLO: The thoughts of people. She told her, while she kept","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.68","kind":"speech"},"3.4.69":{"play":"OTHELLO: it,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.69","kind":"speech"},"3.4.70":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Twould make her amiable and subdue my father","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.70","kind":"speech"},"3.4.71":{"play":"OTHELLO: Entirely to her love. But if she lost it,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.71","kind":"speech"},"3.4.72":{"play":"OTHELLO: Or made a gift of it, my father’s eye","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.72","kind":"speech"},"3.4.73":{"play":"OTHELLO: Should hold her loathèd, and his spirits should hunt","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.73","kind":"speech"},"3.4.74":{"play":"OTHELLO: After new fancies. She, dying, gave it me,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.74","kind":"speech"},"3.4.75":{"play":"OTHELLO: And bid me, when my fate would have me wived,","notes":["Wived: It is not necessary to adopt the Qq here. Wived is in the same construction as \"loathed,\" line 65. Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.75","kind":"speech"},"3.4.76":{"play":"OTHELLO: To give it her. I did so; and take heed on ’t,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.76","kind":"speech"},"3.4.77":{"play":"OTHELLO: Make it a darling like your precious eye.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.77","kind":"speech"},"3.4.78":{"play":"OTHELLO: To lose ’t or give ’t away were such perdition","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.78","kind":"speech"},"3.4.79":{"play":"OTHELLO: As nothing else could match.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.79","kind":"speech"},"3.4.80":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Is ’t possible?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.80","kind":"speech"},"3.4.81":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Tis true. There’s magic in the web of it.","notes":["Mummy: Steevens: The balsamic liquor running from mummies was formerly celebrated for its anti-epileptic virtues. This fanciful medicine still holds a place in the principal shops where drugs are sold. Dyce: A preparation for magical purposes, made from dead bodies. Steevens's note seems irrelevant. [I doubt if the word conveyed, of necessity, any reference to Egyptian mummies; that reference was perhaps restricted to mummia. Falstaff refers to himself as being turned by drowning into a \"mountain of mummy,\" and we have \"Witches' mummy\" in Macb. IV, i, 23, which see with the notes. In Johnson's Did. s. v. there is a full account of the medicinal preparation, from Dr Hill's Materia Medica, and in Latham's Johnson a passage is given from Sir T. Herbert's Travels, &c. 1677, which shows that that traveler not only did not associate \"mummy\" with Egypt, but not even with dead bodies:—\"In or near this place is a precious liquor or mummy growing; .... a moist, redolent gum it is, sovereign against poisons.\" Steevens cites from The Microcosmos of John Davies of Hereford (1603, p. 77, ed. Grosart): \"That's Mummey made of the meere Hart of Love?\" That Davies was well read in Shakespeare's Sonnets is felt throughout the Microcosm, but the date of the latter is rather too early to permit the supposition that it had been influenced by Othello.—Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.81","kind":"speech"},"3.4.82":{"play":"OTHELLO: A sybil that had numbered in the world","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.82","kind":"speech"},"3.4.83":{"play":"OTHELLO: The sun to course two hundred compasses,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.83","kind":"speech"},"3.4.84":{"play":"OTHELLO: In her prophetic fury sewed the work.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.84","kind":"speech"},"3.4.85":{"play":"OTHELLO: The worms were hallowed that did breed the silk,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.85","kind":"speech"},"3.4.86":{"play":"OTHELLO: And it was dyed in mummy, which the skillful","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.86","kind":"speech"},"3.4.87":{"play":"OTHELLO: Conserved of maidens’ hearts.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.87","kind":"speech"},"3.4.88":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I’ faith, is ’t true?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.88","kind":"speech"},"3.4.89":{"play":"OTHELLO: Most veritable. Therefore, look to ’t well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.89","kind":"speech"},"3.4.90":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Then would to God that I had never seen ’t!","notes":["Mrs. Jameson (ii, 38): Desdemona, whose soft credulity, whose turn for the marvellous, whose susceptible imagination had first directed her thoughts and affections to Othello, is precisely the woman to be frightened out of her senses by such a tale as this, and betrayed by her fears into a momentary tergiversation. It is most natural in such a being, and shows us that even in the sweetest natures there can be no completeness and consistency without moral energy. There is an incident in the original tale which could not well be transferred to the drama, but which is very effective, and adds, I think, to the circumstantial horrors of the story. Desdemona does not accidentally drop the handkerchief; it is stolen from her by Iago's little child, an infant of three years old, whom he trains or bribes to the theft. The love of Desdemona for this child, her little playfellow,—the pretty description of her taking it in her arms and caressing it, while it profits by its situation to steal the handkerchief from her bosom, are well imagined, and beautifully told; and the circumstance of Iago employing his own innocent child as the instrument of his infernal villainy adds a deeper, and, in truth, an unnecessary touch of the fiend, to his fiendish character. [It is so common among the critics to accuse Desdemona of telling a falsehood here, that gratitude is due to Mrs Jameson for the milder term \"tergiversation.\" Although Desdemona herself says, \"where should I lose the handkerchief?\" she did not believe it to be actually lost, irrecoverably gone; it was merely mislaid, and a further search would reward her with discovery. If she had not been terrified she might have told all this to Othello (and we should not have had the tragedy, which would be a relief), but, as it is, I think in her soul she believed she was telling the truth. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.90","kind":"speech"},"3.4.91":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ha? Wherefore?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.91","kind":"speech"},"3.4.92":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Why do you speak so startingly and rash?","notes":["startingly and rash: Walker (Crit. i, 220) cites this, among others, as an instance of the termination -ly attached to one adjective and affecting others. See also Abbott, §397, or Schmidt, p. 1419. 105-115: Booth: This little \"bit\" is difficult to act without being tame, or too violent. I have never hit it. [At line 114, FECHTER actually directs Othello to seize Desdemona violently, and raise his hand as if to strike her! Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.92","kind":"speech"},"3.4.93":{"play":"OTHELLO: Is ’t lost? Is ’t gone? Speak, is ’t out o’ th’ way?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.93","kind":"speech"},"3.4.94":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Heaven bless us!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.94","kind":"speech"},"3.4.95":{"play":"OTHELLO: Say you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.95","kind":"speech"},"3.4.96":{"play":"DESDEMONA: It is not lost, but what an if it were?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.96","kind":"speech"},"3.4.97":{"play":"OTHELLO: How?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.97","kind":"speech"},"3.4.98":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I say it is not lost.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.98","kind":"speech"},"3.4.99":{"play":"OTHELLO: Fetch ’t. Let me see ’t!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.99","kind":"speech"},"3.4.100":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Why, so I can. But I will not now.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.100","kind":"speech"},"3.4.101":{"play":"DESDEMONA: This is a trick to put me from my suit.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.101","kind":"speech"},"3.4.102":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Pray you, let Cassio be received again.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.102","kind":"speech"},"3.4.103":{"play":"OTHELLO: Fetch me the handkerchief! My mind","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.103","kind":"speech"},"3.4.104":{"play":"OTHELLO: misgives.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.104","kind":"speech"},"3.4.105":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Come, come.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.105","kind":"speech"},"3.4.106":{"play":"DESDEMONA: You’ll never meet a more sufficient man.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.106","kind":"speech"},"3.4.107":{"play":"OTHELLO: The handkerchief!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.107","kind":"speech"},"3.4.108":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I pray, talk me of Cassio.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.108","kind":"speech"},"3.4.109":{"play":"OTHELLO: The handkerchief!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.109","kind":"speech"},"3.4.110":{"play":"DESDEMONA: A man that all his time","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.110","kind":"speech"},"3.4.111":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Hath founded his good fortunes on your love;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.111","kind":"speech"},"3.4.112":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Shared dangers with you—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.112","kind":"speech"},"3.4.113":{"play":"OTHELLO: The handkerchief!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.113","kind":"speech"},"3.4.114":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I’ faith, you are to blame.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.114","kind":"speech"},"3.4.115":{"play":"OTHELLO: Zounds!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.115","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.4.115":{"play":"[Othello exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.4.115","kind":"stage"},"3.4.116":{"play":"EMILIA: Is not this man jealous?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.116","kind":"speech"},"3.4.117":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I ne’er saw this before.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.117","kind":"speech"},"3.4.118":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Sure, there’s some wonder in this handkerchief!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.118","kind":"speech"},"3.4.119":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I am most unhappy in the loss of it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.119","kind":"speech"},"3.4.120":{"play":"EMILIA: ’Tis not a year or two shows us a man.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.120","kind":"speech"},"3.4.121":{"play":"EMILIA: They are all but stomachs, and we all but food;","notes":["week: Hudson: It would seem by this that seven days at least have elapsed since Cassio was cashiered; perhaps much more, as the \"leaden thoughts\" may have been kept off for some time by the thoughts of Desdemona's promise of intercession, and brought on again by the unexpected delay."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.121","kind":"speech"},"3.4.122":{"play":"EMILIA: They eat us hungerly, and when they are full","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.122","kind":"speech"},"3.4.123":{"play":"EMILIA: They belch us.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.123","kind":"speech"},"3.4.124":{"play":"EMILIA: Look you—Cassio and my husband.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.124","kind":"speech"},"3.4.125":{"play":"IAGO: There is no other way; ’tis she must do ’t,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.125","kind":"speech"},"3.4.126":{"play":"IAGO: And, lo, the happiness! Go and importune her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.126","kind":"speech"},"3.4.127":{"play":"DESDEMONA: How now, good Cassio, what’s the news with you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.127","kind":"speech"},"3.4.128":{"play":"CASSIO: Madam, my former suit. I do beseech you","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.128","kind":"speech"},"3.4.129":{"play":"CASSIO: That by your virtuous means I may again","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.129","kind":"speech"},"3.4.130":{"play":"CASSIO: Exist, and be a member of his love","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.130","kind":"speech"},"3.4.131":{"play":"CASSIO: Whom I with all the office of my heart","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.131","kind":"speech"},"3.4.132":{"play":"CASSIO: Entirely honor. I would not be delayed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.132","kind":"speech"},"3.4.133":{"play":"CASSIO: If my offense be of such mortal kind","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.133","kind":"speech"},"3.4.134":{"play":"CASSIO: That nor my service past nor present sorrows","notes":["score: Delius finds here a punning allusion to Bianca's \"eight score\""],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.134","kind":"speech"},"3.4.135":{"play":"CASSIO: Nor purposed merit in futurity","notes":["take me this work out: See \"coppied\" line 219, and III, iii, 344."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.135","kind":"speech"},"3.4.136":{"play":"CASSIO: Can ransom me into his love again,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.136","kind":"speech"},"3.4.137":{"play":"CASSIO: But to know so must be my benefit.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.137","kind":"speech"},"3.4.138":{"play":"CASSIO: So shall I clothe me in a forced content,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.138","kind":"speech"},"3.4.139":{"play":"CASSIO: And shut myself up in some other course","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.139","kind":"speech"},"3.4.140":{"play":"CASSIO: To fortune’s alms.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.140","kind":"speech"},"3.4.141":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Alas, thrice-gentle Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.141","kind":"speech"},"3.4.142":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My advocation is not now in tune.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.142","kind":"speech"},"3.4.143":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My lord is not my lord; nor should I know him","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.143","kind":"speech"},"3.4.144":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Were he in favor as in humor altered.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.144","kind":"speech"},"3.4.145":{"play":"DESDEMONA: So help me every spirit sanctified","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.145","kind":"speech"},"3.4.146":{"play":"DESDEMONA: As I have spoken for you all my best,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.146","kind":"speech"},"3.4.147":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And stood within the blank of his displeasure","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.147","kind":"speech"},"3.4.148":{"play":"DESDEMONA: For my free speech! You must awhile be patient.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.148","kind":"speech"},"3.4.149":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What I can do I will; and more I will","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.149","kind":"speech"},"3.4.150":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Than for myself I dare. Let that suffice you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.150","kind":"speech"},"3.4.151":{"play":"IAGO: Is my lord angry?","notes":["angry: Fielding: Nothing can be more provoking to the human temper, nor more dangerous to that cardinal virtue, Patience, than solicitations of extraordinary offices of kindness in behalf of those very persons with whom we are highly incensed. For this reason Shakespeare hath artfully introduced his Desdemona soliciting favours for Cassio of her husband, as the means of inflaming not only his jealousy, but his rage, to the highest pitch of madness; and we find the unfortunate Moor less able to command his passion on this occasion than even when he beheld his valued present to his wife in the hands of his supposed rival. In fact, we regard these efforts as insults to our understanding; and to such the pride of man is with great difficulty brought to submit.—Tom Jones, ix, 3, quoted by Halliwell."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.151","kind":"speech"},"3.4.152":{"play":"EMILIA: He went hence but now,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.152","kind":"speech"},"3.4.153":{"play":"EMILIA: And certainly in strange unquietness.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.153","kind":"speech"},"3.4.154":{"play":"IAGO: Can he be angry? I have seen the cannon","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.154","kind":"speech"},"3.4.155":{"play":"IAGO: When it hath blown his ranks into the air","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.155","kind":"speech"},"3.4.156":{"play":"IAGO: And, like the devil, from his very arm","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.156","kind":"speech"},"3.4.157":{"play":"IAGO: Puffed his own brother—and is he angry?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.157","kind":"speech"},"3.4.158":{"play":"IAGO: Something of moment then. I will go meet him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.158","kind":"speech"},"3.4.159":{"play":"IAGO: There’s matter in ’t indeed if he be angry.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.159","kind":"speech"},"3.4.160":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I prithee do so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.160","kind":"speech"},"3.4.161":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Something, sure, of state,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.161","kind":"speech"},"3.4.162":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Either from Venice, or some unhatched practice","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.162","kind":"speech"},"3.4.163":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Made demonstrable here in Cyprus to him,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.163","kind":"speech"},"3.4.164":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Hath puddled his clear spirit; and in such cases","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.164","kind":"speech"},"3.4.165":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Men’s natures wrangle with inferior things,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.165","kind":"speech"},"3.4.166":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Though great ones are their object. ’Tis even so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.166","kind":"speech"},"3.4.167":{"play":"DESDEMONA: For let our finger ache, and it endues","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.167","kind":"speech"},"3.4.168":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Our other healthful members even to a sense","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.168","kind":"speech"},"3.4.169":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Of pain. Nay, we must think men are not gods,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.169","kind":"speech"},"3.4.170":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Nor of them look for such observancy","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.170","kind":"speech"},"3.4.171":{"play":"DESDEMONA: As fits the bridal. Beshrew me much, Emilia,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.171","kind":"speech"},"3.4.172":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I was—unhandsome warrior as I am!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.172","kind":"speech"},"3.4.173":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Arraigning his unkindness with my soul.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.173","kind":"speech"},"3.4.174":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But now I find I had suborned the witness,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.174","kind":"speech"},"3.4.175":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And he’s indicted falsely.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.175","kind":"speech"},"3.4.176":{"play":"EMILIA: Pray heaven it be","notes":["a year or two: Rymer (p. 126): As if for the first year or two Othello had not been jealous? This Third Act begins in the morning, at noon she drops the Handkerchief, after dinner she misses it, and then follows all this outrage and horrible clutter about it. If we believe a small Damosel, in the last scene of this Act, this day is effectually seven days. Our Poet is at this plunge, that whether this Act contains the compass of one day, of seven days, or of seven years, or of all together, the repugnance and the absurdity would be the same. For Othello, all the while, has nothing to say or to do, but what loudly proclaim him jealous; her friend and confidant Emilia again and again rounds her in the ear that the Man is jealous; yet this Venetian dame is neither to see, nor to hear; nor to have any sense or understanding, nor to strike any other note but Cassio, Cassio. Steevens: This line has no reference to the duration of the action, or to the length of time that Desdemona had been married. What Emilia says is a sort of proverbial remark, of general application, where a definite time is put for an indefinite.  Besides, this \"year or two\" may refer to the beginning of the acquaintance and intimacy between the couple. Pye (p. 342): Emilia's saying, \"it is not a year or two shews us a man,\" may be well supposed to insinuate, how then should a month or two, or even a day or two?"],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.176","kind":"speech"},"3.4.177":{"play":"EMILIA: State matters, as you think, and no conception","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.177","kind":"speech"},"3.4.178":{"play":"EMILIA: Nor no jealous toy concerning you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.178","kind":"speech"},"3.4.179":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Alas the day, I never gave him cause!","notes":["They are all but Stomachs: White (ed. ii): Emilia means, They are nought but stomachs, and we nought but food. The obscurity results from an inversion of, They are but all stomach, and we but all food. [There may be an inversion here, but I do not think that it is the inversion which White points out. \"All\" does not qualify \"stomachs,\" or \"food,\" but \"They\" and \"we.\" The meaning is that they, every one of them, are merely stomachs for which we, every one of us, are merely food. When White represents Shakespeare as making man revert to the Gasteropods or to the Amoebas, his admiration and exaltation of our demi-god go one step farther than mine. \"We know what we are, but we know not what we may be,\" as Ophelia says, so that I may even yet be brought to believe that Shakespeare anticipated Darwin,—but not from this passage. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.179","kind":"speech"},"3.4.180":{"play":"EMILIA: But jealous souls will not be answered so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.180","kind":"speech"},"3.4.181":{"play":"EMILIA: They are not ever jealous for the cause,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.181","kind":"speech"},"3.4.182":{"play":"EMILIA: But jealous for they’re jealous. It is a monster","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.182","kind":"speech"},"3.4.183":{"play":"EMILIA: Begot upon itself, born on itself.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.183","kind":"speech"},"3.4.184":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Heaven keep that monster from Othello’s mind!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.184","kind":"speech"},"3.4.185":{"play":"EMILIA: Lady, amen.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.185","kind":"speech"},"3.4.186":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I will go seek him.—Cassio, walk hereabout.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.186","kind":"speech"},"3.4.187":{"play":"DESDEMONA: If I do find him fit, I’ll move your suit","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.187","kind":"speech"},"3.4.188":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And seek to effect it to my uttermost.","notes":["Booth: As if glad to change the subject."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.188","kind":"speech"},"3.4.189":{"play":"CASSIO: I humbly thank your Ladyship.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.189","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.4.189.1":{"play":"[Desdemona and Emilia exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.4.189.1","kind":"stage"},"SD_3.4.189.2":{"play":"[Enter Bianca.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.4.189.2","kind":"stage"},"3.4.190":{"play":"BIANCA: ’Save you, friend Cassio!","notes":["make: Collier (eds. i and ii): A Saxon idiom, which Malone destroyed by printing makes."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.190","kind":"speech"},"3.4.191":{"play":"CASSIO: What make you from","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.191","kind":"speech"},"3.4.192":{"play":"CASSIO: home?","notes":["I was: Walker (Crit. ii, 202) cites this instance, with others, as a proof that I was, from its position in the line, must have been pronounced as one syllable, in whatever manner the contraction was effected. See also Ham. IV, v, 14."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.192","kind":"speech"},"3.4.193":{"play":"CASSIO: How is ’t with you, my most fair Bianca?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.193","kind":"speech"},"3.4.194":{"play":"CASSIO: I’ faith, sweet love, I was coming to your house.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.194","kind":"speech"},"3.4.195":{"play":"BIANCA: And I was going to your lodging, Cassio.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.195","kind":"speech"},"3.4.196":{"play":"BIANCA: What, keep a week away? Seven days and nights,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.196","kind":"speech"},"3.4.197":{"play":"BIANCA: Eightscore eight hours, and lovers’ absent hours","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.197","kind":"speech"},"3.4.198":{"play":"BIANCA: More tedious than the dial eightscore times?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.198","kind":"speech"},"3.4.199":{"play":"BIANCA: O weary reck’ning!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.199","kind":"speech"},"3.4.200":{"play":"CASSIO: Pardon me, Bianca.","notes":["continuate: Johnson: That is, less interrupted, time which I can call more my own."],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.200","kind":"speech"},"3.4.201":{"play":"CASSIO: I have this while with leaden thoughts been pressed,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.201","kind":"speech"},"3.4.202":{"play":"CASSIO: But I shall in a more continuate time","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.202","kind":"speech"},"3.4.203":{"play":"CASSIO: Strike off this score of absence. Sweet Bianca,","notes":["score: Delius finds here a punning allusion to Bianca's \"eight score\""],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.203","kind":"speech"},"3.4.204":{"play":"CASSIO: Take me this work out.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.204","kind":"speech"},"3.4.205":{"play":"BIANCA: O, Cassio, whence came this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.205","kind":"speech"},"3.4.206":{"play":"BIANCA: This is some token from a newer friend.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.206","kind":"speech"},"3.4.207":{"play":"BIANCA: To the felt absence now I feel a cause.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.207","kind":"speech"},"3.4.208":{"play":"BIANCA: Is ’t come to this? Well, well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.208","kind":"speech"},"3.4.209":{"play":"CASSIO: Go to, woman!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.209","kind":"speech"},"3.4.210":{"play":"CASSIO: Throw your vile guesses in the devil’s teeth,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.210","kind":"speech"},"3.4.211":{"play":"CASSIO: From whence you have them. You are jealous now","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.211","kind":"speech"},"3.4.212":{"play":"CASSIO: That this is from some mistress, some","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.212","kind":"speech"},"3.4.213":{"play":"CASSIO: remembrance.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.213","kind":"speech"},"3.4.214":{"play":"CASSIO: No, by my faith, Bianca.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.214","kind":"speech"},"3.4.215":{"play":"BIANCA: Why, whose is it?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.215","kind":"speech"},"3.4.216":{"play":"CASSIO: I know not neither. I found it in my chamber.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.216","kind":"speech"},"3.4.217":{"play":"CASSIO: I like the work well. Ere it be demanded,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.217","kind":"speech"},"3.4.218":{"play":"CASSIO: As like enough it will, I would have it copied.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.218","kind":"speech"},"3.4.219":{"play":"CASSIO: Take it, and do ’t, and leave me for this time.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.219","kind":"speech"},"3.4.220":{"play":"BIANCA: Leave you? Wherefore?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.220","kind":"speech"},"3.4.221":{"play":"CASSIO: I do attend here on the General,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.221","kind":"speech"},"3.4.222":{"play":"CASSIO: And think it no addition, nor my wish,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.222","kind":"speech"},"3.4.223":{"play":"CASSIO: To have him see me womaned.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.223","kind":"speech"},"3.4.224":{"play":"BIANCA: Why, I pray you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.224","kind":"speech"},"3.4.225":{"play":"CASSIO: Not that I love you not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.225","kind":"speech"},"3.4.226":{"play":"BIANCA: But that you do not love me!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.226","kind":"speech"},"3.4.227":{"play":"BIANCA: I pray you bring me on the way a little,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.227","kind":"speech"},"3.4.228":{"play":"BIANCA: And say if I shall see you soon at night.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.228","kind":"speech"},"3.4.229":{"play":"CASSIO: ’Tis but a little way that I can bring you,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.229","kind":"speech"},"3.4.230":{"play":"CASSIO: For I attend here. But I’ll see you soon.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.230","kind":"speech"},"3.4.231":{"play":"BIANCA: ’Tis very good. I must be circumstanced.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"3.4.231","kind":"speech"},"SD_3.4.231.1":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 3.4.231.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 4, SCENE 1":{"SD_4.1.0":{"play":"[Enter Othello and Iago.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.1.0","kind":"stage"},"4.1.1":{"play":"IAGO: Will you think so?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.1","kind":"speech"},"4.1.2":{"play":"OTHELLO: Think so, Iago?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.2","kind":"speech"},"4.1.3":{"play":"IAGO: What,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.3","kind":"speech"},"4.1.4":{"play":"OTHELLO: An unauthorized kiss!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.4","kind":"speech"},"4.1.5":{"play":"IAGO: Or to be naked with her friend in bed","notes":["Friend] Friends Ff. Sing. Sta. Wh. i, Ktly, Del. So thy Qq 2, 4: in bed] Ff, Rowe +, Cap. Knt, Dyce, Sta. Glo. Cam. Coll. in, Wh. ii."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.5","kind":"speech"},"4.1.6":{"play":"IAGO: An hour or more, not meaning any harm?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.6","kind":"speech"},"4.1.7":{"play":"OTHELLO: Naked in bed, Iago, and not mean harm?","notes":["Divell] Johnson: This means, hypocrisy to cheat the devil. As common hypocrites cheat men by seeming good, and yet living wickedly, these men would cheat the devil, by giving him flattering hopes, and at last avoiding the crime which he thinks them ready to commit. Rymer (p. 128): At this gross rate of trifling, our General and his Auncient March on most heroically; till the jealous Booby has his Brains turn'd; and falls in a Trance. Would any imagine this to be the Language of Venetians, of Souldiers, and mighty Captains? no Bartholomew Droll cou'd subsist upon such trash. [According to Allibone (Diet.), Pope considered Rymer, 'on the whole, one of the best critics we ever had'; Dryden and Sir Walter Scott quote him with respect; Dr Johnson was disgusted at his 'ferocity'; Sergeant Talfourd praises his acuteness at the expense of his judgement, and Lord Macaulay deems him 'the worst critic that ever lived.' Ed.]","harme?] harme. Q1. Q1."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.7","kind":"speech"},"4.1.8":{"play":"OTHELLO: It is hypocrisy against the devil!","notes":["tempts; and] tempts not; Warb. Rowe et seq. Han.","Heaven] Henley; The true key to the explanation of this passage may be found in St. Matthew, iv, 7. The poet's idea is, that the devil tempts their virtues by stirring up their passions, and they tempt heaven by placing themselves in such a situation as makes it scarcely possible to avoid falling, by the gratification of them."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.8","kind":"speech"},"4.1.9":{"play":"OTHELLO: They that mean virtuously, and yet do so,","notes":["But if I] But I Q1. abed Qq et cet. 8, 16. Handkerchiefe.] handkercher. Q1. Handkerchiffe. F. handkerchief—"],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.9","kind":"speech"},"4.1.10":{"play":"OTHELLO: The devil their virtue tempts, and they tempt","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.10","kind":"speech"},"4.1.11":{"play":"OTHELLO: heaven.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.11","kind":"speech"},"4.1.12":{"play":"IAGO: If they do nothing, ’tis a venial slip.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.12","kind":"speech"},"4.1.13":{"play":"IAGO: But if I give my wife a handkerchief—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.13","kind":"speech"},"4.1.14":{"play":"OTHELLO: What then?","notes":["What then?] what then Q1."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.14","kind":"speech"},"4.1.15":{"play":"IAGO: Why then, ’tis hers, my lord, and being hers,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.15","kind":"speech"},"4.1.16":{"play":"IAGO: She may, I think, bestow ’t on any man.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.16","kind":"speech"},"4.1.17":{"play":"OTHELLO: She is protectress of her honor, too.","notes":["Protectresse] proprietor Warb. conj. propertied Warb. proprietress Cap.","too:] to, Q1. 7 and 9. naked] Dyce, in both his Second and his Third Edition, prints these words with an accent, thus: 'naked.' I wish I knew why; especially since a similar forethought for heedless readers of this word is not extended by Dyce elsewhere; after having learned to lean on our accented /s, we are liable to read, in his edition, that Emilia wishes rascals to be lashed 'nak'd through the world,' and that Othello threatens Gratiano that he will assault him 'nak'd as he was.' Ed."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.17","kind":"speech"},"4.1.18":{"play":"OTHELLO: May she give that?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.18","kind":"speech"},"4.1.19":{"play":"IAGO: Her honor is an essence that’s not seen;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.19","kind":"speech"},"4.1.20":{"play":"IAGO: They have it very oft that have it not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.20","kind":"speech"},"4.1.21":{"play":"IAGO: But for the handkerchief—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.21","kind":"speech"},"4.1.22":{"play":"OTHELLO: By heaven, I would most gladly have forgot it.","notes":["Handkerchiefe.] handkercher. Q1. hankerchief Warb."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.22","kind":"speech"},"4.1.23":{"play":"OTHELLO: Thou saidst—O, it comes o’er my memory","notes":["infectious'] Ff, Rowe, Cap. Knt, Sta. infected Qq et cet. 22-24. That's...wrong] Walker (Crit. iii, 288): Arrange, perhaps,—That's not so good now. What if I had said I had seen him do you wrong?"],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.23","kind":"speech"},"4.1.24":{"play":"OTHELLO: As doth the raven o’er the infectious house,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.24","kind":"speech"},"4.1.25":{"play":"OTHELLO: Boding to all—he had my handkerchief.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.25","kind":"speech"},"4.1.26":{"play":"IAGO: Ay, what of that?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.26","kind":"speech"},"4.1.27":{"play":"OTHELLO: That’s not so good now.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.27","kind":"speech"},"4.1.28":{"play":"IAGO: What","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.28","kind":"speech"},"4.1.29":{"play":"IAGO: Or heard him say (as knaves be such abroad,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.29","kind":"speech"},"4.1.30":{"play":"IAGO: Who having, by their own importunate suit","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.30","kind":"speech"},"4.1.31":{"play":"IAGO: Or voluntary dotage of some mistress,","notes":["Convinced or]Coniured or Q2. Conjured or Q1. convinced or Theob. Han. Warb. Johns. Cap. convinct her and Ktly.","supply'd]suppled Theob. Han.Warb. Johns. supplied Cap. supplied Qq et cet."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.31","kind":"speech"},"4.1.32":{"play":"IAGO: Convincèd or supplied them, cannot choose","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.32","kind":"speech"},"4.1.33":{"play":"IAGO: But they must blab)—","notes":["cannot chuse] they cannot Theob. Warb. Johns, then cannot Han. straight cannot Cap."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.33","kind":"speech"},"4.1.34":{"play":"OTHELLO: Hath he said anything?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.34","kind":"speech"},"4.1.35":{"play":"IAGO: He hath, my lord, but be you well assured,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.35","kind":"speech"},"4.1.36":{"play":"IAGO: No more than he’ll unswear.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.36","kind":"speech"},"4.1.37":{"play":"OTHELLO: What hath he said?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.37","kind":"speech"},"4.1.38":{"play":"IAGO: Faith, that he did—I know not what he did.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.38","kind":"speech"},"4.1.39":{"play":"OTHELLO: What? What?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.39","kind":"speech"},"4.1.40":{"play":"IAGO: Lie—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.40","kind":"speech"},"4.1.41":{"play":"OTHELLO: With her?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.41","kind":"speech"},"4.1.42":{"play":"IAGO: With her—on her—what you will.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.42","kind":"speech"},"4.1.43":{"play":"OTHELLO: Lie with her? Lie on her? We say","notes":["To confesse...confesse] Om. Pope, Han."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.43","kind":"speech"},"4.1.44":{"play":"OTHELLO: when they belie her. Lie with her—Zounds, that’s","notes":["workes] An interpolated s, according to Walker. See I, i, 31."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.44","kind":"speech"},"4.1.45":{"play":"OTHELLO: fulsome! Handkerchief—confessions—handkerchief.","notes":["Handkerchiefe: Confessions: Handkerchiefe.] handkerchers, Confession, hankerchers. Q1. handkerchiefs, confession, handkerchiefs Q2Q3. handkerchief—confessions—handkerchief—handkerchief—Theob. Warb. Johns."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.45","kind":"speech"},"4.1.46":{"play":"OTHELLO: To confess and be hanged for his labor.","notes":["Instruction] Warburton: The starts and broken reflections in this speech have something very terrible, and show the mind of the speaker to be in inexpressible agonies. But the words we are upon have a sublime in them that can never be enough admired. The ridiculous blunder of writing 'instruction' for induction (for so it should be read) has, indeed, sunk it into arrant nonsense. Othello is just going to fall into a swoon; and, as is common for people in that circumstance, feels an unusual mist and darkness, accompanied with horror, coming upon him. This, with vast sublimity of thought, is compared to the season of the sun's eclipse, at which time the earth becomes shadowed by the induction or bringing over of the moon between it and the sun. This being the allusion, the reasoning stands thus, My nature could never be thus overshadowed, and falling, as it were, into dissolution for no cause. There must be an induction of something; there must be a real cause. My jealousy cannot be merely imaginary. Ideas, words only, could not shake me thus, and raise all this disorder. My jealousy must be grounded, therefore, on matter of fact. This word is used in this sense in Rich. III: IV, iv, 5. Johnson: This is a noble conjecture, and, whether right or wrong, does honour to its author. Yet I am in doubt whether there is any necessity of emendation. There has always prevailed in the world an opinion that, when any great calamity happens at a distance, notice is given of it to the sufferer by some dejection or perturbation of mind, of which he discovers no external cause. This is ascribed to that general communication of one part of the universe with another, which is called sympathy and antipathy; or to the secret monition, instruction, and influence of a Superior Being, which superintends the order of nature and of life. Othello says, Nature could not invest herself in such shadowing passion without instruction. It is not words that shake me thus. This passion which spreads its clouds over me is the effect of some agency, more than the operation of words; it is one of those notices which men have of unseen calamities."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.46","kind":"speech"},"4.1.47":{"play":"OTHELLO: First to be hanged and then to confess—I tremble","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.47","kind":"speech"},"4.1.48":{"play":"OTHELLO: at it. Nature would not invest herself in such shadowing","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.48","kind":"speech"},"4.1.49":{"play":"OTHELLO: passion without some instruction. It is not","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.49","kind":"speech"},"4.1.50":{"play":"OTHELLO: words that shakes me thus. Pish! Noses, ears, and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.50","kind":"speech"},"4.1.51":{"play":"OTHELLO: lips—is ’t possible? Confess—handkerchief—O,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.51","kind":"speech"},"4.1.52":{"play":"OTHELLO: devil!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.52","kind":"speech"},"4.1.53":{"play":"IAGO: Work on,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.53","kind":"speech"},"4.1.54":{"play":"IAGO: My medicine, work! Thus credulous fools are","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.54","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.1.54":{"play":"[He falls in a trance.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.1.54","kind":"stage"},"4.1.55":{"play":"IAGO: caught,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.55","kind":"speech"},"4.1.56":{"play":"IAGO: And many worthy and chaste dames even thus,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.56","kind":"speech"},"4.1.57":{"play":"IAGO: All guiltless, meet reproach.—What ho! My lord!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.57","kind":"speech"},"4.1.58":{"play":"IAGO: My lord, I say. Othello!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.58","kind":"speech"},"4.1.59":{"play":"IAGO: How now, Cassio?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.59","kind":"speech"},"4.1.60":{"play":"CASSIO: What’s the matter?","notes":["Epilepsie] Bucknill (Med. Knowledge of Sh. p. 274): This designation appears a mere falsehood. It is to be observed, however, that Shakespeare's knowledge of epilepsy here goes farther than mjul. Cæs. I, ii, 256, since he describes the maniacal excitement which so often follows the fit. When Cassio has been persuaded to withdraw, Iago applies to the patient himself the truthful and correct designation of his morbid state."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.60","kind":"speech"},"4.1.61":{"play":"IAGO: My lord is fall’n into an epilepsy.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.61","kind":"speech"},"4.1.62":{"play":"IAGO: This is his second fit. He had one yesterday.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.62","kind":"speech"},"4.1.63":{"play":"CASSIO: Rub him about the temples.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.63","kind":"speech"},"4.1.64":{"play":"IAGO: No, forbear.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.64","kind":"speech"},"4.1.65":{"play":"IAGO: The lethargy must have his quiet course.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.65","kind":"speech"},"4.1.66":{"play":"IAGO: If not, he foams at mouth, and by and by","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.66","kind":"speech"},"4.1.67":{"play":"IAGO: Breaks out to savage madness. Look, he stirs.","notes":["mocke] John Hunter: As if Iago had meant the hurt done to the head when one is made a horned monster.","peculiar] White (ed. ii): Equivalent to belonging to one; that is, to each one of them (the millions) respectively."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.67","kind":"speech"},"4.1.68":{"play":"IAGO: Do you withdraw yourself a little while.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.68","kind":"speech"},"4.1.69":{"play":"IAGO: He will recover straight. When he is gone,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.69","kind":"speech"},"4.1.70":{"play":"IAGO: I would on great occasion speak with you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.70","kind":"speech"},"4.1.71":{"play":"IAGO: How is it, general? Have you not hurt your head?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.71","kind":"speech"},"4.1.72":{"play":"OTHELLO: Dost thou mock me?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.72","kind":"speech"},"4.1.73":{"play":"IAGO: I mock you not, by heaven!","notes":["unbookish] Whiter (p. 112), after citing many instances where Shakespeare has used the imagery of a book in connection with love, ends with the celebrated description of Cressida (Tro. & Cress. IV, v, 54) wherein Ulysses speaks of 'unclasping the tables of their thoughts To every ticklish reader;' and the same metaphor, Whiter is persuaded, Iago uses here. 'The \"unbookish\" jealousy of Othello,' says Whiter, 'is that which confounds his knowledge in the Books of Love, and blinds his discernment respecting the language of Lovers. It will cause him to mistake the artless smiles and gestures of Cassio for the significant expressions of amorous parley. Whether our Poet intended to comprehend the whole of this meaning, I am not able to decide: I am convinced, however, that this remote epithet \"unbookish,\" as applied to jealousy, was suggested to his mind by the above very singular imagery of the Lover and the Book.'"],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.73","kind":"speech"},"4.1.74":{"play":"IAGO: Would you would bear your fortune like a man!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.74","kind":"speech"},"4.1.75":{"play":"OTHELLO: A hornèd man’s a monster and a beast.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.75","kind":"speech"},"4.1.76":{"play":"IAGO: There’s many a beast, then, in a populous city,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.76","kind":"speech"},"4.1.77":{"play":"IAGO: And many a civil monster.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.77","kind":"speech"},"4.1.78":{"play":"OTHELLO: Did he confess it?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.78","kind":"speech"},"4.1.79":{"play":"IAGO: Good sir, be a man!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.79","kind":"speech"},"4.1.80":{"play":"IAGO: Think every bearded fellow that’s but yoked","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.80","kind":"speech"},"4.1.81":{"play":"IAGO: May draw with you. There’s millions now alive","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.81","kind":"speech"},"4.1.82":{"play":"IAGO: That nightly lie in those unproper beds","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.82","kind":"speech"},"4.1.83":{"play":"IAGO: Which they dare swear peculiar. Your case is better.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.83","kind":"speech"},"4.1.84":{"play":"IAGO: O, ’tis the spite of hell, the fiend’s arch-mock,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.84","kind":"speech"},"4.1.85":{"play":"IAGO: To lip a wanton in a secure couch","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.85","kind":"speech"},"4.1.86":{"play":"IAGO: And to suppose her chaste! No, let me know,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.86","kind":"speech"},"4.1.87":{"play":"IAGO: And knowing what I am, I know what she shall be.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.87","kind":"speech"},"4.1.88":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, thou art wise, ’tis certain.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.88","kind":"speech"},"4.1.89":{"play":"IAGO: Stand you awhile apart.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.89","kind":"speech"},"4.1.90":{"play":"IAGO: Confine yourself but in a patient list.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.90","kind":"speech"},"4.1.91":{"play":"IAGO: Whilst you were here, o’erwhelmèd with your grief—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.91","kind":"speech"},"4.1.92":{"play":"IAGO: A passion most unsuiting such a man—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.92","kind":"speech"},"4.1.93":{"play":"IAGO: Cassio came hither. I shifted him away","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.93","kind":"speech"},"4.1.94":{"play":"IAGO: And laid good ’scuses upon your ecstasy,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.94","kind":"speech"},"4.1.95":{"play":"IAGO: Bade him anon return and here speak with me,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.95","kind":"speech"},"4.1.96":{"play":"IAGO: The which he promised. Do but encave yourself,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.96","kind":"speech"},"4.1.97":{"play":"IAGO: And mark the fleers, the gibes, and notable scorns","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.97","kind":"speech"},"4.1.98":{"play":"IAGO: That dwell in every region of his face.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.98","kind":"speech"},"4.1.99":{"play":"IAGO: For I will make him tell the tale anew—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.99","kind":"speech"},"4.1.100":{"play":"IAGO: Where, how, how oft, how long ago, and when","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.100","kind":"speech"},"4.1.101":{"play":"IAGO: He hath and is again to cope your wife.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.101","kind":"speech"},"4.1.102":{"play":"IAGO: I say but mark his gesture. Marry, patience,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.102","kind":"speech"},"4.1.103":{"play":"IAGO: Or I shall say you’re all in all in spleen,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.103","kind":"speech"},"4.1.104":{"play":"IAGO: And nothing of a man.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.104","kind":"speech"},"4.1.105":{"play":"OTHELLO: Dost thou hear, Iago,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.105","kind":"speech"},"4.1.106":{"play":"OTHELLO: I will be found most cunning in my patience,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.106","kind":"speech"},"4.1.107":{"play":"OTHELLO: But (dost thou hear?) most bloody.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.107","kind":"speech"},"4.1.108":{"play":"IAGO: That’s not amiss.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.108","kind":"speech"},"4.1.109":{"play":"IAGO: But yet keep time in all. Will you withdraw?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.109","kind":"speech"},"4.1.110":{"play":"IAGO: Now will I question Cassio of Bianca,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.110","kind":"speech"},"4.1.111":{"play":"IAGO: A huswife that by selling her desires","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.111","kind":"speech"},"4.1.112":{"play":"IAGO: Buys herself bread and clothes. It is a creature","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.112","kind":"speech"},"4.1.113":{"play":"IAGO: That dotes on Cassio—as ’tis the strumpet’s plague","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.113","kind":"speech"},"4.1.114":{"play":"IAGO: To beguile many and be beguiled by one.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.114","kind":"speech"},"4.1.115":{"play":"IAGO: He, when he hears of her, cannot restrain","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.115","kind":"speech"},"4.1.116":{"play":"IAGO: From the excess of laughter. Here he comes.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.116","kind":"speech"},"4.1.117":{"play":"IAGO: As he shall smile, Othello shall go mad,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.117","kind":"speech"},"4.1.118":{"play":"IAGO: And his unbookish jealousy must construe","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.118","kind":"speech"},"4.1.119":{"play":"IAGO: Poor Cassio’s smiles, gestures, and light behaviors","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.119","kind":"speech"},"4.1.120":{"play":"IAGO: Quite in the wrong.—How do you, lieutenant?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.120","kind":"speech"},"4.1.121":{"play":"CASSIO: The worser that you give me the addition","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.121","kind":"speech"},"4.1.122":{"play":"CASSIO: Whose want even kills me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.122","kind":"speech"},"4.1.123":{"play":"IAGO: Ply Desdemona well, and you are sure on ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.123","kind":"speech"},"4.1.124":{"play":"IAGO: Now, if this suit lay in Bianca’s power,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.124","kind":"speech"},"4.1.125":{"play":"IAGO: How quickly should you speed!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.125","kind":"speech"},"4.1.126":{"play":"CASSIO: Alas, poor caitiff!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.126","kind":"speech"},"4.1.127":{"play":"OTHELLO: Look how he laughs already!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.127","kind":"speech"},"4.1.128":{"play":"IAGO: I never knew woman love man so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.128","kind":"speech"},"4.1.129":{"play":"CASSIO: Alas, poor rogue, I think i’ faith she loves me.","notes":["well said] See II, i, 192."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.129","kind":"speech"},"4.1.130":{"play":"OTHELLO: Now he denies it faintly and laughs it out.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.130","kind":"speech"},"4.1.131":{"play":"IAGO: Do you hear, Cassio?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.131","kind":"speech"},"4.1.132":{"play":"OTHELLO: Now he importunes him","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.132","kind":"speech"},"4.1.133":{"play":"OTHELLO: To tell it o’er. Go to, well said, well said.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.133","kind":"speech"},"4.1.134":{"play":"IAGO: She gives it out that you shall marry her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.134","kind":"speech"},"4.1.135":{"play":"IAGO: Do you intend it?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.135","kind":"speech"},"4.1.136":{"play":"CASSIO: Ha, ha, ha!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.136","kind":"speech"},"4.1.137":{"play":"OTHELLO: Do you triumph, Roman? Do you triumph?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.137","kind":"speech"},"4.1.138":{"play":"CASSIO: I marry her? What, a customer? Prithee bear","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.138","kind":"speech"},"4.1.139":{"play":"CASSIO: some charity to my wit! Do not think it so unwholesome.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.139","kind":"speech"},"4.1.140":{"play":"CASSIO: Ha, ha, ha!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.140","kind":"speech"},"4.1.141":{"play":"OTHELLO: So, so, so, so. They laugh that wins.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.141","kind":"speech"},"4.1.142":{"play":"IAGO: Faith, the cry goes that you marry her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.142","kind":"speech"},"4.1.143":{"play":"CASSIO: Prithee say true!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.143","kind":"speech"},"4.1.144":{"play":"IAGO: I am a very villain else.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.144","kind":"speech"},"4.1.145":{"play":"OTHELLO: Have you scored me? Well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.145","kind":"speech"},"4.1.146":{"play":"CASSIO: This is the monkey’s own giving out. She is","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.146","kind":"speech"},"4.1.147":{"play":"CASSIO: persuaded I will marry her out of her own love and","notes":["Fitchew] Dyce (Gloss.): A polecat, and the cant term for a strumpet."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.147","kind":"speech"},"4.1.148":{"play":"CASSIO: flattery, not out of my promise.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.148","kind":"speech"},"4.1.149":{"play":"OTHELLO: Iago beckons me. Now he begins the story.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.149","kind":"speech"},"4.1.150":{"play":"CASSIO: She was here even now. She haunts me in","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.150","kind":"speech"},"4.1.151":{"play":"CASSIO: every place. I was the other day talking on the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.151","kind":"speech"},"4.1.152":{"play":"CASSIO: sea-bank with certain Venetians, and thither comes","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.152","kind":"speech"},"4.1.153":{"play":"CASSIO: the bauble. By this hand, she falls thus about my","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.153","kind":"speech"},"4.1.154":{"play":"CASSIO: neck!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.154","kind":"speech"},"4.1.155":{"play":"OTHELLO: Crying, as it were; his","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.155","kind":"speech"},"4.1.156":{"play":"OTHELLO: gesture imports it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.156","kind":"speech"},"4.1.157":{"play":"CASSIO: So hangs and lolls and weeps upon me, so","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.157","kind":"speech"},"4.1.158":{"play":"CASSIO: shakes and pulls me. Ha, ha, ha!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.158","kind":"speech"},"4.1.159":{"play":"OTHELLO: Now he tells how she plucked him to my","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.159","kind":"speech"},"4.1.160":{"play":"OTHELLO: chamber.—O, I see that nose of yours, but not that","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.160","kind":"speech"},"4.1.161":{"play":"OTHELLO: dog I shall throw it to.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.161","kind":"speech"},"4.1.162":{"play":"CASSIO: Well, I must leave her company.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.162","kind":"speech"},"4.1.163":{"play":"IAGO: Before me, look where she comes.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.163","kind":"speech"},"4.1.164":{"play":"CASSIO: ’Tis such another fitchew—marry, a perfumed","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.164","kind":"speech"},"4.1.165":{"play":"CASSIO: one!—What do you mean by this haunting","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.165","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.1.165.1":{"play":"[Enter Bianca.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.1.165.1","kind":"stage"},"4.1.166":{"play":"CASSIO: of me?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.166","kind":"speech"},"4.1.167":{"play":"BIANCA: Let the devil and his dam haunt you! What did","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.167","kind":"speech"},"4.1.168":{"play":"BIANCA: you mean by that same handkerchief you gave me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.168","kind":"speech"},"4.1.169":{"play":"BIANCA: even now? I was a fine fool to take it! I must take","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.169","kind":"speech"},"4.1.170":{"play":"BIANCA: out the work? A likely piece of work, that you","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.170","kind":"speech"},"4.1.171":{"play":"BIANCA: should find it in your chamber and know not who","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.171","kind":"speech"},"4.1.172":{"play":"BIANCA: left it there! This is some minx’s token, and I must","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.172","kind":"speech"},"4.1.173":{"play":"BIANCA: take out the work! There, give it your hobbyhorse.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.173","kind":"speech"},"4.1.174":{"play":"BIANCA: Wheresoever you had it, I’ll take out no work on ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.174","kind":"speech"},"4.1.175":{"play":"CASSIO: How now, my sweet Bianca? How now? How now?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.175","kind":"speech"},"4.1.176":{"play":"OTHELLO: By heaven, that should be my handkerchief!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.176","kind":"speech"},"4.1.177":{"play":"BIANCA: If you’ll come to supper tonight you may. If","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.177","kind":"speech"},"4.1.178":{"play":"BIANCA: you will not, come when you are next prepared","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.178","kind":"speech"},"4.1.179":{"play":"BIANCA: for.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.179","kind":"speech"},"4.1.180":{"play":"IAGO: After her, after her!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.180","kind":"speech"},"4.1.181":{"play":"CASSIO: Faith, I must. She’ll rail in the streets else.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.181","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.1.181":{"play":"[She exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.1.181","kind":"stage"},"4.1.182":{"play":"IAGO: Will you sup there?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.182","kind":"speech"},"4.1.183":{"play":"CASSIO: Faith, I intend so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.183","kind":"speech"},"4.1.184":{"play":"IAGO: Well, I may chance to see you, for I would very","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.184","kind":"speech"},"4.1.185":{"play":"IAGO: fain speak with you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.185","kind":"speech"},"4.1.186":{"play":"CASSIO: Prithee come. Will you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.186","kind":"speech"},"4.1.187":{"play":"IAGO: Go to; say no more.","notes":["How shall...Iago.] This speech is often divided differently in modern editions, but transcribed here as in the edition."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.187","kind":"speech"},"4.1.188":{"play":"OTHELLO: How shall I murder him,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.188","kind":"speech"},"4.1.189":{"play":"OTHELLO: Iago?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.189","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.1.189":{"play":"[Cassio exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.1.189","kind":"stage"},"4.1.190":{"play":"IAGO: Did you perceive how he laughed at his vice?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.190","kind":"speech"},"4.1.191":{"play":"OTHELLO: O Iago!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.191","kind":"speech"},"4.1.192":{"play":"IAGO: And did you see the handkerchief?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.192","kind":"speech"},"4.1.193":{"play":"OTHELLO: Was that mine?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.193","kind":"speech"},"4.1.194":{"play":"IAGO: Yours, by this hand! And to see how he prizes","notes":["a killing:] Abbott, §24, for instances of a- before verbal nouns where it represents on; as here, 'nine years on, or in the act of killing.'"],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.194","kind":"speech"},"4.1.195":{"play":"IAGO: the foolish woman your wife! She gave it him, and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.195","kind":"speech"},"4.1.196":{"play":"IAGO: he hath giv’n it his whore.","notes":["she gave it him, and he hath giv'n it his whore.] Q1 has: she gaue him it, and he hath giu'n it his whore."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.196","kind":"speech"},"4.1.197":{"play":"OTHELLO: I would have him nine years a-killing! A fine","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.197","kind":"speech"},"4.1.198":{"play":"OTHELLO: woman, a fair woman, a sweet woman!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.198","kind":"speech"},"4.1.199":{"play":"IAGO: Nay, you must forget that.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.199","kind":"speech"},"4.1.200":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ay, let her rot and perish and be damned","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.200","kind":"speech"},"4.1.201":{"play":"OTHELLO: tonight, for she shall not live. No, my heart is turned","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.201","kind":"speech"},"4.1.202":{"play":"OTHELLO: to stone. I strike it, and it hurts my hand. O, the","notes":["Oh, the world hath not a sweeter Creature:] Fechter: Here Othello exclaims the exceeding softness of Desdemona's temper.","too gentle.] In Ff, I too gentle."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.202","kind":"speech"},"4.1.203":{"play":"OTHELLO: world hath not a sweeter creature! She might lie by","notes":["pattent] See Chalmers, on Date of Composition, in Appendix."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.203","kind":"speech"},"4.1.204":{"play":"OTHELLO: an emperor’s side and command him tasks.","notes":["condition?] See II, i, 282."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.204","kind":"speech"},"4.1.205":{"play":"IAGO: Nay, that’s not your way.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.205","kind":"speech"},"4.1.206":{"play":"OTHELLO: Hang her, I do but say what she is! So","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.206","kind":"speech"},"4.1.207":{"play":"OTHELLO: delicate with her needle, an admirable musician—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.207","kind":"speech"},"4.1.208":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, she will sing the savageness out of a bear!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.208","kind":"speech"},"4.1.209":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of so high and plenteous wit and invention!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.209","kind":"speech"},"4.1.210":{"play":"IAGO: She’s the worse for all this.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.210","kind":"speech"},"4.1.211":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, a thousand, a thousand times!—And then","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.211","kind":"speech"},"4.1.212":{"play":"OTHELLO: of so gentle a condition!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.212","kind":"speech"},"4.1.213":{"play":"IAGO: Ay, too gentle.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.213","kind":"speech"},"4.1.214":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nay, that’s certain. But yet the pity of it,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.214","kind":"speech"},"4.1.215":{"play":"OTHELLO: Iago! O, Iago, the pity of it, Iago!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.215","kind":"speech"},"4.1.216":{"play":"IAGO: If you are so fond over her iniquity, give her","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.216","kind":"speech"},"4.1.217":{"play":"IAGO: patent to offend, for if it touch not you, it comes","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.217","kind":"speech"},"4.1.218":{"play":"IAGO: near nobody.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.218","kind":"speech"},"4.1.219":{"play":"OTHELLO: I will chop her into messes! Cuckold me?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.219","kind":"speech"},"4.1.220":{"play":"IAGO: O, ’tis foul in her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.220","kind":"speech"},"4.1.221":{"play":"OTHELLO: With mine officer!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.221","kind":"speech"},"4.1.222":{"play":"IAGO: That’s fouler.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.222","kind":"speech"},"4.1.223":{"play":"OTHELLO: Get me some poison, Iago, this night. I’ll not","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.223","kind":"speech"},"4.1.224":{"play":"OTHELLO: expostulate with her lest her body and beauty","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.224","kind":"speech"},"4.1.225":{"play":"OTHELLO: unprovide my mind again. This night, Iago.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.225","kind":"speech"},"4.1.226":{"play":"IAGO: Do it not with poison. Strangle her in her bed,","notes":["midnight.] midnight. A Trumpet. Qq."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.226","kind":"speech"},"4.1.227":{"play":"IAGO: even the bed she hath contaminated.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.227","kind":"speech"},"4.1.228":{"play":"OTHELLO: Good, good. The justice of it pleases. Very","notes":["Enter...] After line 130."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.228","kind":"speech"},"4.1.229":{"play":"OTHELLO: good.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.229","kind":"speech"},"4.1.230":{"play":"IAGO: And for Cassio, let me be his undertaker. You","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.230","kind":"speech"},"4.1.231":{"play":"IAGO: shall hear more by midnight.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.231","kind":"speech"},"4.1.232":{"play":"OTHELLO: Excellent good.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.232","kind":"speech"},"4.1.233":{"play":"OTHELLO: What trumpet is that same?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.233","kind":"speech"},"4.1.234":{"play":"IAGO: I warrant something from Venice.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.234","kind":"speech"},"4.1.235":{"play":"IAGO: ’Tis Lodovico. This comes from the Duke.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.235","kind":"speech"},"4.1.236":{"play":"IAGO: See, your wife’s with him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.236","kind":"speech"},"4.1.237":{"play":"LODOVICO: God save you, worthy general.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.237","kind":"speech"},"4.1.238":{"play":"OTHELLO: With all my heart, sir.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.238","kind":"speech"},"4.1.239":{"play":"LODOVICO: The Duke and the Senators of Venice greet you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.239","kind":"speech"},"4.1.240":{"play":"OTHELLO: I kiss the instrument of their pleasures.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.240","kind":"speech"},"4.1.241":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And what’s the news, good cousin Lodovico?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.241","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.1.241.1":{"play":"[He hands Othello a paper.]","notes":["Othello: I kisse the Instrument of their pleasures.] Fechter: This response is part of Othello's distracted reply."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.1.241.1","kind":"stage"},"4.1.242":{"play":"IAGO: I am very glad to see you, signior.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.242","kind":"speech"},"4.1.243":{"play":"IAGO: Welcome to Cyprus.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.243","kind":"speech"},"4.1.244":{"play":"LODOVICO: I thank you. How does Lieutenant Cassio?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.244","kind":"speech"},"4.1.245":{"play":"IAGO: Lives, sir.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.245","kind":"speech"},"4.1.246":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Cousin, there’s fall’n between him and my lord","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.246","kind":"speech"},"4.1.247":{"play":"DESDEMONA: An unkind breach, but you shall make all well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.247","kind":"speech"},"4.1.248":{"play":"OTHELLO: Are you sure of that?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.248","kind":"speech"},"4.1.249":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.249","kind":"speech"},"4.1.250":{"play":"OTHELLO: —","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.250","kind":"speech"},"4.1.251":{"play":"DESDEMONA: ","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.251","kind":"speech"},"4.1.252":{"play":"LODOVICO: He did not call; he’s busy in the paper.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.252","kind":"speech"},"4.1.254":{"play":"DESDEMONA: A most unhappy one. I would do much","notes":["attone] Johnson: Make them one; reconcile them. Henley: The verb is formed by the coalescence of the words at one."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.254","kind":"speech"},"4.1.255":{"play":"DESDEMONA: T’ atone them, for the love I bear to Cassio.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.255","kind":"speech"},"4.1.253":{"play":"LODOVICO: Is there division ’twixt my lord and Cassio?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.253","kind":"speech"},"4.1.256":{"play":"OTHELLO: Fire and brimstone!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.256","kind":"speech"},"4.1.257":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.257","kind":"speech"},"4.1.258":{"play":"OTHELLO: Are you wise?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.258","kind":"speech"},"4.1.259":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What, is he angry?","notes":["Maybe the Letter mov'd him.] For as Q1."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.259","kind":"speech"},"4.1.260":{"play":"LODOVICO: May be the letter moved him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.260","kind":"speech"},"4.1.261":{"play":"LODOVICO: For, as I think, they do command him home,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.261","kind":"speech"},"4.1.262":{"play":"LODOVICO: Deputing Cassio in his government.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.262","kind":"speech"},"4.1.263":{"play":"DESDEMONA: By my troth, I am glad on ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.263","kind":"speech"},"4.1.264":{"play":"OTHELLO: Indeed?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.264","kind":"speech"},"4.1.265":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.265","kind":"speech"},"4.1.266":{"play":"OTHELLO: I am glad to see you mad.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.266","kind":"speech"},"4.1.267":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Why, sweet Othello!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.267","kind":"speech"},"4.1.268":{"play":"OTHELLO: Devil!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.268","kind":"speech"},"4.1.269":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I have not deserved this.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.269","kind":"speech"},"4.1.270":{"play":"LODOVICO: My lord, this would not be believed in Venice,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.270","kind":"speech"},"4.1.271":{"play":"LODOVICO: Though I should swear I saw ’t. ’Tis very much.","notes":["teeme] Johnson: If women's tears could impregnate the earth. By the doctrine of equivocal generation, new animals were supposed producible by new combinations of matter. See Bacon, vol. iii, p. 70, ed. 1740. Malone: 'It is written,' says Bullokar, 'that the crocodile will weepe ouer a man's head when he hath devoured the body, and then will eate up the head too. Wherefore in Latine there is a proverbe, Crocodili Lachrymce, crocodiles teares, to signifie such teares as are fained, and spent onely with intent to deceive or doe harme.' Expositor, 1621."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.271","kind":"speech"},"4.1.272":{"play":"LODOVICO: Make her amends. She weeps.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.272","kind":"speech"},"4.1.273":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, devil, devil!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.273","kind":"speech"},"4.1.274":{"play":"OTHELLO: If that the Earth could teem with woman’s tears,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.274","kind":"speech"},"4.1.275":{"play":"OTHELLO: Each drop she falls would prove a crocodile.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.275","kind":"speech"},"4.1.276":{"play":"OTHELLO: Out of my sight!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.276","kind":"speech"},"4.1.277":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I will not stay to offend you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.277","kind":"speech"},"4.1.278":{"play":"LODOVICO: Truly an obedient lady.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.278","kind":"speech"},"4.1.279":{"play":"LODOVICO: I do beseech your Lordship call her back.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.279","kind":"speech"},"4.1.280":{"play":"OTHELLO: Mistress.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.280","kind":"speech"},"4.1.281":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.281","kind":"speech"},"4.1.282":{"play":"OTHELLO: What would you with her, sir?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.282","kind":"speech"},"4.1.283":{"play":"LODOVICO: Who, I, my lord?","notes":["Who I, my Lord?] In F1: Which I, my Lord."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.283","kind":"speech"},"4.1.284":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ay, you did wish that I would make her turn.","notes":["all in all] all-in-all Sta. Huds."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.284","kind":"speech"},"4.1.285":{"play":"OTHELLO: Sir, she can turn, and turn, and yet go on,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.285","kind":"speech"},"4.1.286":{"play":"OTHELLO: And turn again. And she can weep, sir, weep.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.286","kind":"speech"},"4.1.287":{"play":"OTHELLO: And she’s obedient, as you say, obedient.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.287","kind":"speech"},"4.1.288":{"play":"OTHELLO: Very obedient.—Proceed you in your tears.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.288","kind":"speech"},"4.1.289":{"play":"OTHELLO: Concerning this, sir—O, well-painted passion!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.289","kind":"speech"},"4.1.290":{"play":"OTHELLO: I am commanded home.—Get you away.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.290","kind":"speech"},"4.1.291":{"play":"OTHELLO: I’ll send for you anon.—Sir, I obey the mandate","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.291","kind":"speech"},"4.1.292":{"play":"OTHELLO: And will return to Venice.—Hence, avaunt!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.292","kind":"speech"},"4.1.293":{"play":"OTHELLO: Cassio shall have my place. And, sir, tonight","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.293","kind":"speech"},"4.1.294":{"play":"OTHELLO: I do entreat that we may sup together.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.294","kind":"speech"},"4.1.295":{"play":"OTHELLO: You are welcome, sir, to Cyprus. Goats and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.295","kind":"speech"},"4.1.296":{"play":"OTHELLO: monkeys!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.296","kind":"speech"},"4.1.297":{"play":"LODOVICO: Is this the noble Moor, whom our full senate","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.297","kind":"speech"},"4.1.298":{"play":"LODOVICO: Call all in all sufficient? Is this the nature","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.298","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.1.298":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.1.298","kind":"stage"},"4.1.299":{"play":"LODOVICO: Whom passion could not shake, whose solid virtue","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.299","kind":"speech"},"4.1.300":{"play":"LODOVICO: The shot of accident nor dart of chance","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.300","kind":"speech"},"4.1.301":{"play":"LODOVICO: Could neither graze nor pierce?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.301","kind":"speech"},"4.1.302":{"play":"IAGO: He is much","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.302","kind":"speech"},"4.1.303":{"play":"IAGO: changed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.303","kind":"speech"},"4.1.304":{"play":"LODOVICO: Are his wits safe? Is he not light of brain?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.304","kind":"speech"},"4.1.305":{"play":"IAGO: He’s that he is. I may not breathe my censure","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.305","kind":"speech"},"4.1.306":{"play":"IAGO: What he might be. If what he might he is not,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.306","kind":"speech"},"4.1.307":{"play":"IAGO: I would to heaven he were.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.307","kind":"speech"},"4.1.308":{"play":"LODOVICO: What? Strike his wife?","notes":["What? Strike his wife?] Purnell: Probably this is an aside."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.308","kind":"speech"},"4.1.309":{"play":"IAGO: ’Faith, that was not so well. Yet would I knew","notes":["Letters, worke upon his blood, And new create his fault?] See commentary on 'worke upon his blood'—Steevens."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.309","kind":"speech"},"4.1.310":{"play":"IAGO: That stroke would prove the worst.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.310","kind":"speech"},"4.1.311":{"play":"LODOVICO: Is it his use?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.311","kind":"speech"},"4.1.312":{"play":"LODOVICO: Or did the letters work upon his blood","notes":["It is not honestie in me to speake] The commentary: Iago says he must not speak fully."],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.312","kind":"speech"},"4.1.313":{"play":"LODOVICO: And new-create this fault?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.313","kind":"speech"},"4.1.314":{"play":"IAGO: Alas, alas!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.314","kind":"speech"},"4.1.315":{"play":"IAGO: It is not honesty in me to speak","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.315","kind":"speech"},"4.1.316":{"play":"IAGO: What I have seen and known. You shall observe","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.316","kind":"speech"},"4.1.317":{"play":"IAGO: him,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.317","kind":"speech"},"4.1.318":{"play":"IAGO: And his own courses will denote him so","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.318","kind":"speech"},"4.1.319":{"play":"IAGO: That I may save my speech. Do but go after","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.319","kind":"speech"},"4.1.320":{"play":"IAGO: And mark how he continues.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.320","kind":"speech"},"4.1.321":{"play":"LODOVICO: I am sorry that I am deceived in him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.321","kind":"speech"},"4.1.322":{"play":"IAGO: ","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.322","kind":"speech"},"4.1.323":{"play":"LODOVICO: ","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.1.323","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.1.323.1":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.1.323.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 4, SCENE 2":{"SD_4.2.0":{"play":"[Enter Othello and Emilia.]","notes":["Abbott: See Abbott, §211, and to the instances there given of this use of 'she' for her, add: 'the earth hath swallow'd all my hopes but she' Rom. & Jul. I, ii, 14. Schmidt also gives, 'she that was thy Lucrece,' R. of L. 1682; 'I will detest myself also as well as she,' Meas. for Meas. II, i, 76; 'She should this Angelo have married,' lb. III, i, 221; 'but she I can hook to me,' Wint. Tale, II, iii, 6; 'for she that scorned at me, now scorned of me,' Rich. III: IV, iv, 102. White (ed. ii): Mere carelessness; not the 'grammar' of Shakespeare's time."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.2.0","kind":"stage"},"4.2.1":{"play":"OTHELLO: You have seen nothing then?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.1","kind":"speech"},"4.2.2":{"play":"EMILIA: Nor ever heard, nor ever did suspect.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.2","kind":"speech"},"4.2.3":{"play":"OTHELLO: Yes, you have seen Cassio and she together.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.3","kind":"speech"},"4.2.4":{"play":"EMILIA: But then I saw no harm, and then I heard","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.4","kind":"speech"},"4.2.5":{"play":"EMILIA: Each syllable that breath made up between them.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.5","kind":"speech"},"4.2.6":{"play":"OTHELLO: What, did they never whisper?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.6","kind":"speech"},"4.2.7":{"play":"EMILIA: Never, my lord.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.7","kind":"speech"},"4.2.8":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nor send you out o’ th’ way?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.8","kind":"speech"},"4.2.9":{"play":"EMILIA: Never.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.9","kind":"speech"},"4.2.10":{"play":"OTHELLO: To fetch her fan, her gloves, her mask, nor nothing?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.10","kind":"speech"},"4.2.11":{"play":"EMILIA: Never, my lord.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.11","kind":"speech"},"4.2.12":{"play":"OTHELLO: That’s strange.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.12","kind":"speech"},"4.2.13":{"play":"EMILIA: I durst, my lord, to wager she is honest,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.13","kind":"speech"},"4.2.14":{"play":"EMILIA: Lay down my soul at stake. If you think other,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.14","kind":"speech"},"4.2.15":{"play":"EMILIA: Remove your thought. It doth abuse your bosom.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.15","kind":"speech"},"4.2.16":{"play":"EMILIA: If any wretch have put this in your head,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.16","kind":"speech"},"4.2.17":{"play":"EMILIA: Let heaven requite it with the serpent’s curse,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.17","kind":"speech"},"4.2.18":{"play":"EMILIA: For if she be not honest, chaste, and true,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.18","kind":"speech"},"4.2.19":{"play":"EMILIA: There’s no man happy. The purest of their wives","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.19","kind":"speech"},"4.2.20":{"play":"EMILIA: Is foul as slander.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.20","kind":"speech"},"4.2.21":{"play":"OTHELLO: Bid her come hither. Go.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.21","kind":"speech"},"4.2.22":{"play":"OTHELLO: She says enough. Yet she’s a simple bawd","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.22","kind":"speech"},"4.2.23":{"play":"OTHELLO: That cannot say as much. This is a subtle whore,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.23","kind":"speech"},"4.2.24":{"play":"OTHELLO: A closet lock and key of villainous secrets.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.24","kind":"speech"},"4.2.25":{"play":"OTHELLO: And yet she’ll kneel and pray. I have seen her do ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.25","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.2.25.1":{"play":"[Enter Desdemona and Emilia.]","notes":["Halliwell: Halliwell quotes from Fairholt that the most ordinary fan used by Venetian ladies was the flag or vane-shaped fan, moving round an upright handle.","Elze: Although this line, as far as my knowledge goes, has never been queried, yet I cannot but think it faulty; I feel certain that Shakespeare wrote, 'her mask, her nothing.' Compare Cor. II, ii, 81: 'To hear my nothings monster'd,' although it seems doubtful whether nothing is to be understood in the same sense in these two passages. Wint. Tale, I, ii, 295: 'nor nothing have these nothings, If this be nothing.'"],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.2.25.1","kind":"stage"},"4.2.26":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My lord, what is your will?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.26","kind":"speech"},"4.2.27":{"play":"OTHELLO: Pray you, chuck, come hither.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.27","kind":"speech"},"4.2.28":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What is your","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.28","kind":"speech"},"4.2.29":{"play":"DESDEMONA: pleasure?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.29","kind":"speech"},"4.2.30":{"play":"OTHELLO: Let me see your eyes. Look in my face.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.30","kind":"speech"},"4.2.31":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What horrible fancy’s this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.31","kind":"speech"},"4.2.32":{"play":"OTHELLO: Some of your function,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.32","kind":"speech"},"4.2.33":{"play":"OTHELLO: mistress.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.33","kind":"speech"},"4.2.34":{"play":"OTHELLO: Leave procreants alone, and shut the door.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.34","kind":"speech"},"4.2.35":{"play":"OTHELLO: Cough, or cry if anybody come.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.35","kind":"speech"},"4.2.36":{"play":"OTHELLO: Your mystery, your mystery! Nay, dispatch.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.36","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.2.36.1":{"play":"[Emilia exits.]","notes":["Abbott: For other instances of the insertion and omission of to before the infinitive, see Abbott, § 349.","Booth: During this Othello is a little moved. He takes a chair from behind the arras and sits."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.2.36.1","kind":"stage"},"4.2.37":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Upon my knees, what doth your speech import?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.37","kind":"speech"},"4.2.38":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I understand a fury in your words,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.38","kind":"speech"},"4.2.39":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But not the words.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.39","kind":"speech"},"4.2.40":{"play":"OTHELLO: Why? What art thou?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.40","kind":"speech"},"4.2.41":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Your wife, my lord, your true and loyal wife.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.41","kind":"speech"},"4.2.42":{"play":"OTHELLO: Come, swear it. Damn thyself,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.42","kind":"speech"},"4.2.43":{"play":"OTHELLO: Lest, being like one of heaven, the devils themselves","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.43","kind":"speech"},"4.2.44":{"play":"OTHELLO: Should fear to seize thee. Therefore be double","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.44","kind":"speech"},"4.2.45":{"play":"OTHELLO: damned.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.45","kind":"speech"},"4.2.46":{"play":"OTHELLO: Swear thou art honest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.46","kind":"speech"},"4.2.47":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Heaven doth truly know it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.47","kind":"speech"},"4.2.48":{"play":"OTHELLO: Heaven truly knows that thou art false as hell.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.48","kind":"speech"},"4.2.49":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To whom, my lord? With whom? How am I false?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.49","kind":"speech"},"4.2.50":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ah, Desdemon, away, away, away!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.50","kind":"speech"},"4.2.51":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Alas the heavy day, why do you weep?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.51","kind":"speech"},"4.2.52":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Am I the motive of these tears, my lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.52","kind":"speech"},"4.2.53":{"play":"DESDEMONA: If haply you my father do suspect","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.53","kind":"speech"},"4.2.54":{"play":"DESDEMONA: An instrument of this your calling back,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.54","kind":"speech"},"4.2.55":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Lay not your blame on me. If you have lost him,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.55","kind":"speech"},"4.2.56":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I have lost him too.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.56","kind":"speech"},"4.2.57":{"play":"OTHELLO: Had it pleased heaven","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.57","kind":"speech"},"4.2.58":{"play":"OTHELLO: To try me with affliction, had they rained","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.58","kind":"speech"},"4.2.59":{"play":"OTHELLO: All kind of sores and shames on my bare head,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.59","kind":"speech"},"4.2.60":{"play":"OTHELLO: Steeped me in poverty to the very lips,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.60","kind":"speech"},"4.2.61":{"play":"OTHELLO: Given to captivity me and my utmost hopes,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.61","kind":"speech"},"4.2.62":{"play":"OTHELLO: I should have found in some place of my soul","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.62","kind":"speech"},"4.2.63":{"play":"OTHELLO: A drop of patience. But alas, to make me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.63","kind":"speech"},"4.2.64":{"play":"OTHELLO: A fixèd figure for the time of scorn","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.64","kind":"speech"},"4.2.65":{"play":"OTHELLO: To point his slow unmoving finger at—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.65","kind":"speech"},"4.2.66":{"play":"OTHELLO: Yet could I bear that too, well, very well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.66","kind":"speech"},"4.2.67":{"play":"OTHELLO: But there where I have garnered up my heart,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.67","kind":"speech"},"4.2.68":{"play":"OTHELLO: Where either I must live or bear no life,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.68","kind":"speech"},"4.2.69":{"play":"OTHELLO: The fountain from the which my current runs","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.69","kind":"speech"},"4.2.70":{"play":"OTHELLO: Or else dries up—to be discarded thence,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.70","kind":"speech"},"4.2.71":{"play":"OTHELLO: Or keep it as a cistern for foul toads","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.71","kind":"speech"},"4.2.72":{"play":"OTHELLO: To knot and gender in—turn thy complexion there,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.72","kind":"speech"},"4.2.73":{"play":"OTHELLO: Patience, thou young and rose-lipped cherubin,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.73","kind":"speech"},"4.2.74":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ay, there look grim as hell.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.74","kind":"speech"},"4.2.75":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I hope my noble lord esteems me honest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.75","kind":"speech"},"4.2.76":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, ay, as summer flies are in the shambles,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.76","kind":"speech"},"4.2.77":{"play":"OTHELLO: That quicken even with blowing! O thou weed,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.77","kind":"speech"},"4.2.78":{"play":"OTHELLO: Who art so lovely fair, and smell’st so sweet","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.78","kind":"speech"},"4.2.79":{"play":"OTHELLO: That the sense aches at thee, would thou hadst","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.79","kind":"speech"},"4.2.80":{"play":"OTHELLO: ne’er been born!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.80","kind":"speech"},"4.2.81":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Alas, what ignorant sin have I committed?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.81","kind":"speech"},"4.2.82":{"play":"OTHELLO: Was this fair paper, this most goodly book,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.82","kind":"speech"},"4.2.83":{"play":"OTHELLO: Made to write upon? What committed?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.83","kind":"speech"},"4.2.84":{"play":"OTHELLO: Committed? O thou public commoner,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.84","kind":"speech"},"4.2.85":{"play":"OTHELLO: I should make very forges of my cheeks","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.85","kind":"speech"},"4.2.86":{"play":"OTHELLO: That would to cinders burn up modesty,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.86","kind":"speech"},"4.2.87":{"play":"OTHELLO: Did I but speak thy deeds. What committed?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.87","kind":"speech"},"4.2.88":{"play":"OTHELLO: Heaven stops the nose at it, and the moon winks;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.88","kind":"speech"},"4.2.89":{"play":"OTHELLO: The bawdy wind that kisses all it meets","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.89","kind":"speech"},"4.2.90":{"play":"OTHELLO: Is hushed within the hollow mine of earth","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.90","kind":"speech"},"4.2.91":{"play":"OTHELLO: And will not hear ’t. What committed?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.91","kind":"speech"},"4.2.92":{"play":"OTHELLO: Impudent strumpet!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.92","kind":"speech"},"4.2.93":{"play":"DESDEMONA: By heaven, you do me wrong!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.93","kind":"speech"},"4.2.94":{"play":"OTHELLO: Are not you a strumpet?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.94","kind":"speech"},"4.2.95":{"play":"DESDEMONA: No, as I am a Christian!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.95","kind":"speech"},"4.2.96":{"play":"DESDEMONA: If to preserve this vessel for my lord","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.96","kind":"speech"},"4.2.97":{"play":"DESDEMONA: From any other foul unlawful touch","notes":["Rymer: Here follows another storm of horror and outrage against the poor Chicken, his Wife. Some Drayman or drunken Tinker might possibly treat his drab at this sort of rate, and mean no harm by it; but for his excellency, a My Lord General, to serenade a Senator's Daughter with such a volley of scoundrel filthy Language, is sure the most absurd Maggot that ever bred from any Poets addle brain."],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.97","kind":"speech"},"4.2.98":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Be not to be a strumpet, I am none.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.98","kind":"speech"},"4.2.99":{"play":"OTHELLO: What, not a whore?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.99","kind":"speech"},"4.2.100":{"play":"DESDEMONA: No, as I shall be saved.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.100","kind":"speech"},"4.2.101":{"play":"OTHELLO: Is ’t possible?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.101","kind":"speech"},"4.2.102":{"play":"DESDEMONA: O, heaven forgive us!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.102","kind":"speech"},"4.2.103":{"play":"OTHELLO: I cry you mercy, then.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.103","kind":"speech"},"4.2.104":{"play":"OTHELLO: I took you for that cunning whore of Venice","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.104","kind":"speech"},"4.2.105":{"play":"OTHELLO: That married with Othello.—You, mistress,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.105","kind":"speech"},"4.2.106":{"play":"OTHELLO: That have the office opposite to Saint Peter","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.106","kind":"speech"},"4.2.107":{"play":"OTHELLO: And keeps the gate of hell—you, you, ay, you!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.107","kind":"speech"},"4.2.108":{"play":"OTHELLO: We have done our course. There’s money for your","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.108","kind":"speech"},"4.2.109":{"play":"OTHELLO: pains.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.109","kind":"speech"},"4.2.110":{"play":"OTHELLO: I pray you turn the key and keep our counsel.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.110","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.2.110.1":{"play":"[He exits.]","notes":["Abbott: For this adverbial use, equivalent to otherwise, see Abbott, § 12, p. 24.","Cowden-Clarke: These few words serve to paint Desdemona's look of angelic purity, as well as the impression it creates, even on her husband's jaundiced sight."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.2.110.1","kind":"stage"},"4.2.111":{"play":"EMILIA: Alas, what does this gentleman conceive?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.111","kind":"speech"},"4.2.112":{"play":"EMILIA: How do you, madam? How do you, my good lady?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.112","kind":"speech"},"4.2.113":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Faith, half asleep.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.113","kind":"speech"},"4.2.114":{"play":"EMILIA: Good madam, what’s the matter with my lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.114","kind":"speech"},"4.2.115":{"play":"DESDEMONA: With who?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.115","kind":"speech"},"4.2.116":{"play":"EMILIA: Why, with my lord, madam.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.116","kind":"speech"},"4.2.117":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Who is thy lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.117","kind":"speech"},"4.2.118":{"play":"EMILIA: He that is yours, sweet lady.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.118","kind":"speech"},"4.2.119":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I have none. Do not talk to me, Emilia.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.119","kind":"speech"},"4.2.120":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I cannot weep, nor answers have I none","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.120","kind":"speech"},"4.2.121":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But what should go by water. Prithee, tonight","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.121","kind":"speech"},"4.2.122":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Lay on my bed my wedding sheets. Remember.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.122","kind":"speech"},"4.2.123":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And call thy husband hither.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.123","kind":"speech"},"4.2.124":{"play":"EMILIA: Here’s a change indeed.","notes":["Booth: See III, i, 58."],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.124","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.2.124":{"play":"[She exits.]","notes":["Heraud: Emilia's supposed hypocrisy embitters Othello both against her and her calumniated mistress. Perhaps, too, the poet intended his free-thoughted and noble Moor to entertain a customary protest against superstitious ceremonies; and here we have a glimpse vouchsafed of his religious tendency. It is in this furtive manner that Shakespeare always alludes to the theological aspects of his theme. Never will he altogether neglect them; but nowhere will he thoroughly unveil them. Both political and religious prudence are evidently observed by Shakespeare in the treatment of all his subjects. The spirit of the time compelled him to this reticence."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.2.124","kind":"stage"},"4.2.125":{"play":"DESDEMONA: ’Tis meet I should be used so, very meet.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.125","kind":"speech"},"4.2.126":{"play":"DESDEMONA: How have I been behaved that he might stick","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.126","kind":"speech"},"4.2.127":{"play":"DESDEMONA: The small’st opinion on my least misuse?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.127","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.2.127.1":{"play":"[Enter Iago and Emilia.]","notes":["Booth: She looks up, but, frightened by his piercing glare, drops her eyes again."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.2.127.1","kind":"stage"},"4.2.128":{"play":"IAGO: What is your pleasure, madam? How is ’t with you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.128","kind":"speech"},"4.2.129":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I cannot tell. Those that do teach young babes","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.129","kind":"speech"},"4.2.130":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Do it with gentle means and easy tasks.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.130","kind":"speech"},"4.2.131":{"play":"DESDEMONA: He might have chid me so, for, in good faith,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.131","kind":"speech"},"4.2.132":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I am a child to chiding.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.132","kind":"speech"},"4.2.133":{"play":"IAGO: What is the matter, lady?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.133","kind":"speech"},"4.2.134":{"play":"EMILIA: Alas, Iago, my lord hath so bewhored her,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.134","kind":"speech"},"4.2.135":{"play":"EMILIA: Thrown such despite and heavy terms upon her","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.135","kind":"speech"},"4.2.136":{"play":"EMILIA: As true hearts cannot bear.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.136","kind":"speech"},"4.2.137":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Am I that name, Iago?","notes":["Steevens: We call the hour in which we are to die, 'the hour of death,'—the time when we are to be judged, 'the day of judgement,'—the instant when we suffer calamity, 'the moment of evil'; and why may we not distinguish the time which brings contempt along with it by the title of 'the time of scorn'? Othello takes his idea from a clock. 'To make me (says he) a fixed figure (on the dial of the world) for the hour of scorn to point and make a full stop at!' By 'slow unmoving finger our poet could have meant only 'so slow that its motion was imperceptible.' Thus, in Ant. & Cleo. III, iii, 22, the messenger, describing the gait of the demure Octavia, says, she creeps; Her motion and her station are as one,' i. e., she moved so slowly that she appeared as if she stood still.","Malone: Might not Shakespeare have written 'for the scorn of time,' &c, i.e., the marked object for the contempt of all ages and all time? So in Ham. III, i, 70, 'the whips and scorns of time.' However, in support of the old copies it may be observed that 'scorn' is personified in the 88th Sonnet: 'And place my merit in the eye of scorn.' The epithet unmoving may likewise derive some support from the 104th Sonnet, in which this very thought is expressed: 'Ah yet doth beauty, like a dial-hand, Steal from his figure, and no pace perceiv'd; So your sweet hue, which methinks still doth stand, Hath motion, and mine eye may be deceiv'd.' In the clocks of the last age there was, I think, in the middle of the dial-plate, a figure of Time, which, I believe, was in our poet's thoughts when he wrote the passage in the text. The finger of the dial was the technical phrase. So in Albovine, by D'Avenant, 1629: 'Even as the slow finger of the dial Doth in its motion circular remove To distant figures.' The reading of Ff, 'and moving,' certainly agrees with the image presented, and its counterpart, better than unmoving, which can be applied to a clock only by license of poetry {not appearing to move), and as applied to 'scorn' has but little force, to say nothing of the superfluous epithet 'slow'; there needs no ghost to tell us that that which is unmoving is 'slow.' 'Slow' implies some sort of motion, however little it may be, and therefore appears to me to favour the reading of Ff.","M. Mason: Perhaps we should read, 'slowly moving finger at.'","Hunter: I have little doubt that the particles 'of and 'for' have changed places; and that, on the whole, the true reading is, 'The fixed figure of the time, for Scorn To point his slow and moving finger at.' It is of the nature of that feeling which leads a person to suppose himself an object of scorn and derision, to think of himself also as an object of universal attention. Thus, Othello represents to himself that he shall be 'the fixed figure of the time,' the one object of public attention, every passer-by pointing at him the finger of scorn.","Knight: There is certainly the most extraordinary confusion in Malone's interpretation; if the figure of Time be in the middle, the dial-hand points from it, and not at it, and there is nothing more remarkable in one numeral of a clock than in another. But why are we to have the notion of a clock at all? There is nothing whatever in the passage to warrant us in believing that the poet meant such a metaphor. By the 'fixed figure' we understand, literally, a living man exposed to public shame; or an effigy exhibited to a multitude, as Butler has it, 'To punish in effigie criminals.'"],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.137","kind":"speech"},"4.2.138":{"play":"IAGO: What name, fair","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.138","kind":"speech"},"4.2.139":{"play":"IAGO: lady?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.139","kind":"speech"},"4.2.140":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Such as she said my lord did say I was.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.140","kind":"speech"},"4.2.141":{"play":"EMILIA: He called her A beggar in his drink","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.141","kind":"speech"},"4.2.142":{"play":"EMILIA: Could not have laid such terms upon his callet.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.142","kind":"speech"},"4.2.143":{"play":"IAGO: Why did he so?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.143","kind":"speech"},"4.2.144":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I do not know. I am sure I am none such.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.144","kind":"speech"},"4.2.145":{"play":"IAGO: Do not weep, do not weep! Alas the day!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.145","kind":"speech"},"4.2.146":{"play":"EMILIA: Hath she forsook so many noble matches,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.146","kind":"speech"},"4.2.147":{"play":"EMILIA: Her father and her country and her friends,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.147","kind":"speech"},"4.2.148":{"play":"EMILIA: To be called ? Would it not make one","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.148","kind":"speech"},"4.2.149":{"play":"EMILIA: weep?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.149","kind":"speech"},"4.2.150":{"play":"DESDEMONA: It is my wretched fortune.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.150","kind":"speech"},"4.2.151":{"play":"IAGO: Beshrew him for ’t! How comes this trick upon him?","notes":["Johnson: The 'garner' and the 'fountain' are improperly conjoined.","Rolfe: But a succession of metaphors is not a fault, like the mixing of them.","Delius: The word is finely chosen; to 'garner' is to store that on which life depends.","Salvini: This passage Salvini adduces as proof that Othello was not jealous, but that his love was of a purely poetic nature, untainted with passion."],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.151","kind":"speech"},"4.2.152":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Nay, heaven doth know.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.152","kind":"speech"},"4.2.153":{"play":"EMILIA: I will be hanged if some eternal villain,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.153","kind":"speech"},"4.2.154":{"play":"EMILIA: Some busy and insinuating rogue,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.154","kind":"speech"},"4.2.155":{"play":"EMILIA: Some cogging, cozening slave, to get some office,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.155","kind":"speech"},"4.2.156":{"play":"EMILIA: Have not devised this slander. I will be hanged else.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.156","kind":"speech"},"4.2.157":{"play":"IAGO: Fie, there is no such man. It is impossible.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.157","kind":"speech"},"4.2.158":{"play":"DESDEMONA: If any such there be, heaven pardon him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.158","kind":"speech"},"4.2.159":{"play":"EMILIA: A halter pardon him, and hell gnaw his bones!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.159","kind":"speech"},"4.2.160":{"play":"EMILIA: Why should he call her ? Who keeps her","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.160","kind":"speech"},"4.2.161":{"play":"EMILIA: company?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.161","kind":"speech"},"4.2.162":{"play":"EMILIA: What place? What time? What form? What","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.162","kind":"speech"},"4.2.163":{"play":"EMILIA: likelihood?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.163","kind":"speech"},"4.2.164":{"play":"EMILIA: The Moor’s abused by some most villainous knave,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.164","kind":"speech"},"4.2.165":{"play":"EMILIA: Some base notorious knave, some scurvy fellow.","notes":["Johnson: At such an object do thou, Patience, thyself change colour; at this do thou, even thou, rosy cherub as thou art, look grim as hell. The old editions and the new have it: \"I here look grim as hell.\" / was written for ay, and not since corrected."],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.165","kind":"speech"},"4.2.166":{"play":"EMILIA: O heaven, that such companions thou ’dst unfold,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.166","kind":"speech"},"4.2.167":{"play":"EMILIA: And put in every honest hand a whip","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.167","kind":"speech"},"4.2.168":{"play":"EMILIA: To lash the rascals naked through the world,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.168","kind":"speech"},"4.2.169":{"play":"EMILIA: Even from the east to th’ west!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.169","kind":"speech"},"4.2.170":{"play":"IAGO: Speak within door.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.170","kind":"speech"},"4.2.171":{"play":"EMILIA: O, fie upon them! Some such squire he was","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.171","kind":"speech"},"4.2.172":{"play":"EMILIA: That turned your wit the seamy side without","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.172","kind":"speech"},"4.2.173":{"play":"EMILIA: And made you to suspect me with the Moor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.173","kind":"speech"},"4.2.174":{"play":"IAGO: You are a fool. Go to!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.174","kind":"speech"},"4.2.175":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Alas, Iago,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.175","kind":"speech"},"4.2.176":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What shall I do to win my lord again?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.176","kind":"speech"},"4.2.177":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Good friend, go to him. For by this light of heaven,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.177","kind":"speech"},"4.2.178":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I know not how I lost him. Here I","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.178","kind":"speech"},"4.2.179":{"play":"DESDEMONA: kneel.","notes":["Cherubin: It is not to be supposed that either Shakespeare, or his contemporaries, knew or cared that this is a Chaldee Plural. Cotgrave translates 'Cherubin, a cherubin,' and it is probably through the French that the word was introduced into English."],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.179","kind":"speech"},"4.2.180":{"play":"DESDEMONA: If e’er my will did trespass ’gainst his love,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.180","kind":"speech"},"4.2.181":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Either in discourse of thought or actual deed,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.181","kind":"speech"},"4.2.182":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Or that mine eyes, mine ears, or any sense","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.182","kind":"speech"},"4.2.183":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Delighted them in any other form,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.183","kind":"speech"},"4.2.184":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Or that I do not yet, and ever did,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.184","kind":"speech"},"4.2.185":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And ever will—though he do shake me off","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.185","kind":"speech"},"4.2.186":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To beggarly divorcement—love him dearly,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.186","kind":"speech"},"4.2.187":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Comfort forswear me! Unkindness may","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.187","kind":"speech"},"4.2.188":{"play":"DESDEMONA: do much,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.188","kind":"speech"},"4.2.189":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And his unkindness may defeat my life,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.189","kind":"speech"},"4.2.190":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But never taint my love. I cannot say —","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.190","kind":"speech"},"4.2.191":{"play":"DESDEMONA: It does abhor me now I speak the word.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.191","kind":"speech"},"4.2.192":{"play":"DESDEMONA: To do the act that might the addition earn,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.192","kind":"speech"},"4.2.193":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Not the world’s mass of vanity could make me.","notes":["Johnson: For gross, not in its proper meaning for known."],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.193","kind":"speech"},"4.2.194":{"play":"IAGO: I pray you be content. ’Tis but his humor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.194","kind":"speech"},"4.2.195":{"play":"IAGO: The business of the state does him offense,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.195","kind":"speech"},"4.2.196":{"play":"IAGO: And he does chide with you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.196","kind":"speech"},"4.2.197":{"play":"DESDEMONA: If ’twere no other—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.197","kind":"speech"},"4.2.198":{"play":"IAGO: It is but so, I warrant.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.198","kind":"speech"},"4.2.199":{"play":"IAGO: Hark how these instruments summon to supper.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.199","kind":"speech"},"4.2.200":{"play":"IAGO: The messengers of Venice stays the meat.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.200","kind":"speech"},"4.2.201":{"play":"IAGO: Go in and weep not. All things shall be well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.201","kind":"speech"},"4.2.202":{"play":"IAGO: How now, Roderigo?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.202","kind":"speech"},"4.2.203":{"play":"RODERIGO: I do not find","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.203","kind":"speech"},"4.2.204":{"play":"RODERIGO: That thou deal’st justly with me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.204","kind":"speech"},"4.2.205":{"play":"IAGO: What in the contrary?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.205","kind":"speech"},"4.2.206":{"play":"RODERIGO: Every day thou daff’st me with some device,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.206","kind":"speech"},"4.2.207":{"play":"RODERIGO: Iago, and rather, as it seems to me now,","notes":["Walker: Does 'slave' here mean anything more than villain, abandoned wretch? This use of 'slave' (compare the Italian cattivo, whence our caitiff) is frequent in old plays."],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.207","kind":"speech"},"4.2.208":{"play":"RODERIGO: keep’st from me all conveniency than suppliest me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.208","kind":"speech"},"4.2.209":{"play":"RODERIGO: with the least advantage of hope. I will indeed no","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.209","kind":"speech"},"4.2.210":{"play":"RODERIGO: longer endure it. Nor am I yet persuaded to put up","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.210","kind":"speech"},"4.2.211":{"play":"RODERIGO: in peace what already I have foolishly suffered.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.211","kind":"speech"},"4.2.212":{"play":"IAGO: Will you hear me, Roderigo?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.212","kind":"speech"},"4.2.213":{"play":"RODERIGO: Faith, I have heard too much, and your","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.213","kind":"speech"},"4.2.214":{"play":"RODERIGO: words and performances are no kin together.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.214","kind":"speech"},"4.2.215":{"play":"IAGO: You charge me most unjustly.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.215","kind":"speech"},"4.2.216":{"play":"RODERIGO: With naught but truth. I have wasted myself","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.216","kind":"speech"},"4.2.217":{"play":"RODERIGO: out of my means. The jewels you have had","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.217","kind":"speech"},"4.2.218":{"play":"RODERIGO: from me to deliver to Desdemona would half have","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.218","kind":"speech"},"4.2.219":{"play":"RODERIGO: corrupted a votaress. You have told me she hath","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.219","kind":"speech"},"4.2.220":{"play":"RODERIGO: received them, and returned me expectations and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.220","kind":"speech"},"4.2.221":{"play":"RODERIGO: comforts of sudden respect and acquaintance, but I","notes":["Collier: Here we meet with an extraordinary variation in copies of F. in that belonging to the Duke of Devonshire has the following at the top of the page: 'I have heard too much: And hell gnaw his bones Performances.'"],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.221","kind":"speech"},"4.2.222":{"play":"RODERIGO: find none.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.222","kind":"speech"},"4.2.223":{"play":"IAGO: Well, go to! Very well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.223","kind":"speech"},"4.2.224":{"play":"RODERIGO: I cannot go to, man,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.224","kind":"speech"},"4.2.225":{"play":"RODERIGO: nor ’tis not very well! By this hand, I say ’tis very","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.225","kind":"speech"},"4.2.226":{"play":"RODERIGO: scurvy, and begin to find myself fopped in it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.226","kind":"speech"},"4.2.227":{"play":"IAGO: Very well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.227","kind":"speech"},"4.2.228":{"play":"RODERIGO: I tell you ’tis not very well! I will make","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.228","kind":"speech"},"4.2.229":{"play":"RODERIGO: myself known to Desdemona. If she will return me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.229","kind":"speech"},"4.2.230":{"play":"RODERIGO: my jewels, I will give over my suit and repent my","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.230","kind":"speech"},"4.2.231":{"play":"RODERIGO: unlawful solicitation. If not, assure yourself I will","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.231","kind":"speech"},"4.2.232":{"play":"RODERIGO: seek satisfaction of you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.232","kind":"speech"},"4.2.233":{"play":"IAGO: You have said now.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.233","kind":"speech"},"4.2.234":{"play":"RODERIGO: Ay, and said nothing but what I protest","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.234","kind":"speech"},"4.2.235":{"play":"RODERIGO: intendment of doing.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.235","kind":"speech"},"4.2.236":{"play":"IAGO: Why, now I see there’s mettle in thee, and even","notes":["Knight: Steevens calls the reading of the Folio 'poor,' but its precision and familiarity make it more dramatic and characteristic."],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.236","kind":"speech"},"4.2.237":{"play":"IAGO: from this instant do build on thee a better opinion","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.237","kind":"speech"},"4.2.238":{"play":"IAGO: than ever before. Give me thy hand, Roderigo.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.238","kind":"speech"},"4.2.239":{"play":"IAGO: Thou hast taken against me a most just exception,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.239","kind":"speech"},"4.2.240":{"play":"IAGO: but yet I protest I have dealt most directly in thy","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.240","kind":"speech"},"4.2.241":{"play":"IAGO: affair.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.241","kind":"speech"},"4.2.242":{"play":"RODERIGO: It hath not appeared.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.242","kind":"speech"},"4.2.243":{"play":"IAGO: I grant indeed it hath not appeared, and your","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.243","kind":"speech"},"4.2.244":{"play":"IAGO: suspicion is not without wit and judgment. But,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.244","kind":"speech"},"4.2.245":{"play":"IAGO: Roderigo, if thou hast that in thee indeed which I","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.245","kind":"speech"},"4.2.246":{"play":"IAGO: have greater reason to believe now than ever—I","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.246","kind":"speech"},"4.2.247":{"play":"IAGO: mean purpose, courage, and valor—this night show","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.247","kind":"speech"},"4.2.248":{"play":"IAGO: it. If thou the next night following enjoy not Desdemona,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.248","kind":"speech"},"4.2.249":{"play":"IAGO: take me from this world with treachery and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.249","kind":"speech"},"4.2.250":{"play":"IAGO: devise engines for my life.","notes":["Booth: Roderigo does not, but Iago wheedles, and gets his hand laughingly."],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.250","kind":"speech"},"4.2.251":{"play":"RODERIGO: Well, what is it? Is it within reason and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.251","kind":"speech"},"4.2.252":{"play":"RODERIGO: compass?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.252","kind":"speech"},"4.2.253":{"play":"IAGO: Sir, there is especial commission come from","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.253","kind":"speech"},"4.2.254":{"play":"IAGO: Venice to depute Cassio in Othello’s place.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.254","kind":"speech"},"4.2.255":{"play":"RODERIGO: Is that true? Why, then, Othello and Desdemona","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.255","kind":"speech"},"4.2.256":{"play":"RODERIGO: return again to Venice.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.256","kind":"speech"},"4.2.257":{"play":"IAGO: O, no. He goes into Mauritania and takes away","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.257","kind":"speech"},"4.2.258":{"play":"IAGO: with him the fair Desdemona, unless his abode be","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.258","kind":"speech"},"4.2.259":{"play":"IAGO: lingered here by some accident—wherein none","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.259","kind":"speech"},"4.2.260":{"play":"IAGO: can be so determinate as the removing of Cassio.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.260","kind":"speech"},"4.2.261":{"play":"RODERIGO: How do you mean, removing him?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.261","kind":"speech"},"4.2.262":{"play":"IAGO: Why, by making him uncapable of Othello’s","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.262","kind":"speech"},"4.2.263":{"play":"IAGO: place: knocking out his brains.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.263","kind":"speech"},"4.2.264":{"play":"RODERIGO: And that you would have me to do?","notes":["Booth: With nonchalance, walking up and down, both here and at 107, but Roderigo’s threat to make himself known to Desdemona arrests Iago, and he instantly plans the removal of Roderigo as well as Cassio."],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.264","kind":"speech"},"4.2.265":{"play":"IAGO: Ay, if you dare do yourself a profit and a right. He","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.265","kind":"speech"},"4.2.266":{"play":"IAGO: sups tonight with a harlotry, and thither will I go to","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.266","kind":"speech"},"4.2.267":{"play":"IAGO: him. He knows not yet of his honorable fortune. If","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.267","kind":"speech"},"4.2.268":{"play":"IAGO: you will watch his going thence (which I will","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.268","kind":"speech"},"4.2.269":{"play":"IAGO: fashion to fall out between twelve and one), you may","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.269","kind":"speech"},"4.2.270":{"play":"IAGO: take him at your pleasure. I will be near to second","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.270","kind":"speech"},"4.2.271":{"play":"IAGO: your attempt, and he shall fall between us. Come,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.271","kind":"speech"},"4.2.272":{"play":"IAGO: stand not amazed at it, but go along with me. I will","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.272","kind":"speech"},"4.2.273":{"play":"IAGO: show you such a necessity in his death that you shall","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.273","kind":"speech"},"4.2.274":{"play":"IAGO: think yourself bound to put it on him. It is now high","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.274","kind":"speech"},"4.2.275":{"play":"IAGO: supper time, and the night grows to waste. About it!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.275","kind":"speech"},"4.2.276":{"play":"RODERIGO: I will hear further reason for this.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.276","kind":"speech"},"4.2.277":{"play":"IAGO: And you shall be satisfied.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.2.277","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.2.277.1":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":["Cowden-Clarke: Othello taunts Emilia with having made a traffic in connivance at stolen meetings between Cassio and Desdemona, and now bids her give a specimen of her proficiency in her avocation.","Hudson: As in mere wantonness of self-torture, Othello here fondles the most agonizing conceptions, and seeks a morbid relief in thinking of Emilia as doing the office or mystery of a procuress. A masterstroke of delineation.","Theobald: This is only a lie, of Iago's own invention, to carry a point with Roderigo. ---"],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.2.277.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 4, SCENE 3":{"SD_4.3.0":{"play":"[Enter Othello, Lodovico, Desdemona, Emilia, and Attendants.]","notes":["Booth: This shows that Emilia, among her other objectionable characteristics, is a listener—a mean listener at doors. She has before told the Moor, 'If any wretch have put this in your head, let Heaven requite it with the serpent's curse.' Her suspicion never for an instant falls on her own husband."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.3.0","kind":"stage"},"4.3.1":{"play":"LODOVICO: I do beseech you, sir, trouble yourself no further.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.1","kind":"speech"},"4.3.2":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, pardon me, ’twill do me good to walk.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.2","kind":"speech"},"4.3.3":{"play":"LODOVICO: Madam, good night. I humbly thank your Ladyship.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.3","kind":"speech"},"4.3.4":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Your Honor is most welcome.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.4","kind":"speech"},"4.3.5":{"play":"OTHELLO: Will you walk, sir?—O, Desdemona—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.5","kind":"speech"},"4.3.6":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.6","kind":"speech"},"4.3.7":{"play":"OTHELLO: Get you to bed on th’ instant. I will be","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.7","kind":"speech"},"4.3.8":{"play":"OTHELLO: returned forthwith. Dismiss your attendant there.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.8","kind":"speech"},"4.3.9":{"play":"OTHELLO: Look ’t be done.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.9","kind":"speech"},"4.3.10":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I will, my lord.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.10","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.3.10.1":{"play":"[All but Desdemona and Emilia exit.]","notes":["Cornhill Magazine (Oct. 1866): This presentiment of Desdemona does not bear the same tests as that of Romeo [see note ad loc. V, i, 1], nor Hamlet [V, ii, 207]. She had no reason to apprehend a violent death, but she had enough to apprehend from Othello's anger. He had struck her and called her the vilest names. Naturally, these unkindnesses would throw her into a deep state of depression. 'A sort of gain-giving' would naturally trouble her and exclude every chance of a real presentiment, the essence of which is, that it shall be spontaneous, at a time when you have no reason to look for it, when you are not under the influence of any fear or anxiety from known causes, and when, perhaps, you have some difficulty in its interpretation."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.3.10.1","kind":"stage"},"4.3.11":{"play":"EMILIA: How goes it now? He looks gentler than he did.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.11","kind":"speech"},"4.3.12":{"play":"DESDEMONA: He says he will return incontinent,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.12","kind":"speech"},"4.3.13":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And hath commanded me to go to bed,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.13","kind":"speech"},"4.3.14":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And bade me to dismiss you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.14","kind":"speech"},"4.3.15":{"play":"EMILIA: Dismiss me?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.15","kind":"speech"},"4.3.16":{"play":"DESDEMONA: It was his bidding. Therefore, good Emilia,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.16","kind":"speech"},"4.3.17":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Give me my nightly wearing, and adieu.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.17","kind":"speech"},"4.3.18":{"play":"DESDEMONA: We must not now displease him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.18","kind":"speech"},"4.3.19":{"play":"EMILIA: I would you had never seen him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.19","kind":"speech"},"4.3.20":{"play":"DESDEMONA: So would not I. My love doth so approve him","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.20","kind":"speech"},"4.3.21":{"play":"DESDEMONA: That even his stubbornness, his checks, his frowns—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.21","kind":"speech"},"4.3.22":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Prithee, unpin me—have grace and favor in them.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.22","kind":"speech"},"4.3.23":{"play":"EMILIA: I have laid those sheets you bade me on the bed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.23","kind":"speech"},"4.3.24":{"play":"DESDEMONA: All’s one. Good faith, how foolish are our minds!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.24","kind":"speech"},"4.3.25":{"play":"DESDEMONA: If I do die before thee, prithee, shroud me","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.25","kind":"speech"},"4.3.26":{"play":"DESDEMONA: In one of those same sheets.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.26","kind":"speech"},"4.3.27":{"play":"EMILIA: Come, come, you talk!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.27","kind":"speech"},"4.3.28":{"play":"DESDEMONA: My mother had a maid called Barbary.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.28","kind":"speech"},"4.3.29":{"play":"DESDEMONA: She was in love, and he she loved proved mad","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.29","kind":"speech"},"4.3.30":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And did forsake her. She had a song of willow,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.30","kind":"speech"},"4.3.31":{"play":"DESDEMONA: An old thing ’twas, but it expressed her fortune,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.31","kind":"speech"},"4.3.32":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And she died singing it. That song tonight","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.32","kind":"speech"},"4.3.33":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Will not go from my mind. I have much to do","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.33","kind":"speech"},"4.3.34":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But to go hang my head all at one side","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.34","kind":"speech"},"4.3.35":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And sing it like poor Barbary. Prithee, dispatch.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.35","kind":"speech"},"4.3.36":{"play":"EMILIA: Shall I go fetch your nightgown?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.36","kind":"speech"},"4.3.37":{"play":"DESDEMONA: No, unpin me here.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.37","kind":"speech"},"4.3.38":{"play":"DESDEMONA: This Lodovico is a proper man.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.38","kind":"speech"},"4.3.39":{"play":"EMILIA: A very handsome man.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.39","kind":"speech"},"4.3.40":{"play":"DESDEMONA: He speaks well.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.40","kind":"speech"},"4.3.41":{"play":"EMILIA: I know a lady in Venice would have walked","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.41","kind":"speech"},"4.3.42":{"play":"EMILIA: barefoot to Palestine for a touch of his nether lip.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.42","kind":"speech"},"4.3.52":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Lay by these.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.52","kind":"speech"},"4.3.54":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Prithee hie thee! He’ll come anon.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.54","kind":"speech"},"4.3.57":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Nay, that’s not next. Hark, who is ’t that knocks?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.57","kind":"speech"},"4.3.58":{"play":"EMILIA: It’s the wind.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.58","kind":"speech"},"4.3.63":{"play":"DESDEMONA: So, get thee gone. Good night. Mine eyes do itch;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.63","kind":"speech"},"4.3.64":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Doth that bode weeping?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.64","kind":"speech"},"4.3.65":{"play":"EMILIA: ’Tis neither here nor there.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.65","kind":"speech"},"4.3.66":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I have heard it said so. O these men, these men!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.66","kind":"speech"},"4.3.67":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Dost thou in conscience think—tell me, Emilia—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.67","kind":"speech"},"4.3.68":{"play":"DESDEMONA: That there be women do abuse their husbands","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.68","kind":"speech"},"4.3.69":{"play":"DESDEMONA: In such gross kind?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.69","kind":"speech"},"4.3.70":{"play":"EMILIA: There be some such, no","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.70","kind":"speech"},"4.3.71":{"play":"EMILIA: question.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.71","kind":"speech"},"4.3.72":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Wouldst thou do such a deed for all the world?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.72","kind":"speech"},"4.3.73":{"play":"EMILIA: Why, would not you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.73","kind":"speech"},"4.3.74":{"play":"DESDEMONA: No, by this heavenly light!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.74","kind":"speech"},"4.3.75":{"play":"EMILIA: Nor I neither, by this heavenly light.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.75","kind":"speech"},"4.3.76":{"play":"EMILIA: I might do ’t as well i’ th’ dark.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.76","kind":"speech"},"4.3.77":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Wouldst thou do such a deed for all the world?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.77","kind":"speech"},"4.3.78":{"play":"EMILIA: The world’s a huge thing. It is a great price","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.78","kind":"speech"},"4.3.79":{"play":"EMILIA: for a small vice.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.79","kind":"speech"},"4.3.80":{"play":"DESDEMONA: In troth, I think thou wouldst not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.80","kind":"speech"},"4.3.81":{"play":"EMILIA: In troth, I think I should, and undo ’t when I","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.81","kind":"speech"},"4.3.82":{"play":"EMILIA: had done it. Marry, I would not do such a thing for","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.82","kind":"speech"},"4.3.83":{"play":"EMILIA: a joint ring, nor for measures of lawn, nor for","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.83","kind":"speech"},"4.3.84":{"play":"EMILIA: gowns, petticoats, nor caps, nor any petty exhibition.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.84","kind":"speech"},"4.3.85":{"play":"EMILIA: But for the whole world—’Uds pity! Who","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.85","kind":"speech"},"4.3.86":{"play":"EMILIA: would not make her husband a cuckold to make","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.86","kind":"speech"},"4.3.87":{"play":"EMILIA: him a monarch? I should venture purgatory for ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.87","kind":"speech"},"4.3.88":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Beshrew me if I would do such a wrong","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.88","kind":"speech"},"4.3.89":{"play":"DESDEMONA: for the whole world!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.89","kind":"speech"},"4.3.90":{"play":"EMILIA: Why, the wrong is but a wrong i’ th’ world;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.90","kind":"speech"},"4.3.91":{"play":"EMILIA: and, having the world for your labor, ’tis a wrong in","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.91","kind":"speech"},"4.3.92":{"play":"EMILIA: your own world, and you might quickly make it","notes":["Hunter: Shakespeare having remarked in King John, 'How oft the sight of means to do ill deeds Makes ill deeds done,' we may probably take these words of Desdemona as, beside their purpose in the drama itself, intended as a hint and warning to the audience not to be infected by the fearful instance, about to be presented, of the higher paroxysms of passion. We have noticed similar cautions on other occasions."],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.92","kind":"speech"},"4.3.93":{"play":"EMILIA: right.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.93","kind":"speech"},"4.3.94":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I do not think there is any such woman.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.94","kind":"speech"},"4.3.95":{"play":"EMILIA: Yes, a dozen; and as many to th’ vantage as","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.95","kind":"speech"},"4.3.96":{"play":"EMILIA: would store the world they played for.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.96","kind":"speech"},"4.3.97":{"play":"EMILIA: But I do think it is their husbands’ faults","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.97","kind":"speech"},"4.3.98":{"play":"EMILIA: If wives do fall. Say that they slack their duties,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.98","kind":"speech"},"4.3.99":{"play":"EMILIA: And pour our treasures into foreign laps;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.99","kind":"speech"},"4.3.100":{"play":"EMILIA: Or else break out in peevish jealousies,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.100","kind":"speech"},"4.3.101":{"play":"EMILIA: Throwing restraint upon us. Or say they strike us,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.101","kind":"speech"},"4.3.102":{"play":"EMILIA: Or scant our former having in despite.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.102","kind":"speech"},"4.3.103":{"play":"EMILIA: Why, we have galls, and though we have some grace,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.103","kind":"speech"},"4.3.104":{"play":"EMILIA: Yet have we some revenge. Let husbands know","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.104","kind":"speech"},"4.3.105":{"play":"EMILIA: Their wives have sense like them. They see, and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.105","kind":"speech"},"4.3.106":{"play":"EMILIA: smell,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.106","kind":"speech"},"4.3.107":{"play":"EMILIA: And have their palates both for sweet and sour,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.107","kind":"speech"},"4.3.108":{"play":"EMILIA: As husbands have. What is it that they do","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.108","kind":"speech"},"4.3.109":{"play":"EMILIA: When they change us for others? Is it sport?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.109","kind":"speech"},"4.3.110":{"play":"EMILIA: I think it is. And doth affection breed it?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.110","kind":"speech"},"4.3.111":{"play":"EMILIA: I think it doth. Is ’t frailty that thus errs?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.111","kind":"speech"},"4.3.112":{"play":"EMILIA: It is so too. And have not we affections,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.112","kind":"speech"},"4.3.113":{"play":"EMILIA: Desires for sport, and frailty, as men have?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.113","kind":"speech"},"4.3.114":{"play":"EMILIA: Then let them use us well. Else let them know,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.114","kind":"speech"},"4.3.115":{"play":"EMILIA: The ills we do, their ills instruct us so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.115","kind":"speech"},"4.3.116":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Good night, good night. God me such uses send,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.116","kind":"speech"},"4.3.117":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Not to pick bad from bad, but by bad mend.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"4.3.117","kind":"speech"},"SD_4.3.117.1":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":["Chappell: The song, which Desdemona sings, is contained in a MS. volume, with accompaniment for the lute, in the British Museum (Addit. MSS. 15,117). Mr Halliwell considers the transcript to have been made about the year 1633; Mr Oliphant (who catalogued the Musical MSS.) dates it about 1600; but the manuscript undoubtedly contains songs of an earlier time, such as,—'O death! rock me asleep, Bring me to quiet rest,' &c, attributed to Anne Boleyn, and which Sir John Hawkins found in a MS. of the reign of Henry VIII. ['The music is older than 1600. It is found in Thomas Dallis's MS. \"Lute Book,\" with the title, \"All a greane willow.\" Dallis taught music at Cambridge; and his book, dated 1583, is now in the Library of Trinity College, Dublin.' Shakspere's Songs, p. 50, New Sh. Soc. 1884.] In this same excellent publication of The New Shakspeare Society ten compositions of this song are enumerated.","Johnson: Usage is an old word for custom, and, I think, better than 'uses.'","Collier: We may almost suspect that neither 'uses' nor usage is correct; perhaps 'uses' ought to be issues, i.e., results; in Tim. I, i, 23, we have seen 'issues' misprinted uses.","Staunton: It may be doubted whether either 'uses' or usage is the poet's word.","Ed.: 'Uses' is emphatically right. It is merely a repetition of Emilia's own word. Emilia has threatened that if 'husbands do not \"use us well,\"' it will be their fault if we follow their example.' Desdemona prays that she may receive such 'uses' that, instead of imitating the bad by bad, she may be able even to mend and become better thereby."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 4.3.117.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 5, SCENE 1":{"SD_5.1.0":{"play":"[Enter Iago and Roderigo.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.0","kind":"stage"},"5.1.1":{"play":"IAGO: Here, stand behind this bulk. Straight will he","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.1","kind":"speech"},"5.1.2":{"play":"IAGO: come.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.2","kind":"speech"},"5.1.3":{"play":"IAGO: Wear thy good rapier bare, and put it home.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.3","kind":"speech"},"5.1.4":{"play":"IAGO: Quick, quick! Fear nothing. I’ll be at thy elbow.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.4","kind":"speech"},"5.1.5":{"play":"IAGO: It makes us or it mars us—think on that,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.5","kind":"speech"},"5.1.6":{"play":"IAGO: And fix most firm thy resolution.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.6","kind":"speech"},"5.1.7":{"play":"RODERIGO: Be near at hand. I may miscarry in ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.7","kind":"speech"},"5.1.8":{"play":"IAGO: Here, at thy hand. Be bold and take thy stand.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.8","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.8.1":{"play":"[He moves aside.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.8.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.9":{"play":"RODERIGO: I have no great devotion to the deed,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.9","kind":"speech"},"5.1.10":{"play":"RODERIGO: And yet he hath given me satisfying reasons.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.10","kind":"speech"},"5.1.11":{"play":"RODERIGO: ’Tis but a man gone. Forth, my sword! He dies.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.11","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.11.1":{"play":"[He draws his sword.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.11.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.12":{"play":"IAGO: I have rubbed this young quat almost to the sense,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.12","kind":"speech"},"5.1.13":{"play":"IAGO: And he grows angry. Now, whether he kill Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.13","kind":"speech"},"5.1.14":{"play":"IAGO: Or Cassio him, or each do kill the other,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.14","kind":"speech"},"5.1.15":{"play":"IAGO: Every way makes my gain. Live Roderigo,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.15","kind":"speech"},"5.1.16":{"play":"IAGO: He calls me to a restitution large","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.16","kind":"speech"},"5.1.17":{"play":"IAGO: Of gold and jewels that I bobbed from him","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.17","kind":"speech"},"5.1.18":{"play":"IAGO: As gifts to Desdemona.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.18","kind":"speech"},"5.1.19":{"play":"IAGO: It must not be. If Cassio do remain,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.19","kind":"speech"},"5.1.20":{"play":"IAGO: He hath a daily beauty in his life","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.20","kind":"speech"},"5.1.21":{"play":"IAGO: That makes me ugly. And besides, the Moor","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.21","kind":"speech"},"5.1.22":{"play":"IAGO: May unfold me to him. There stand I in much peril.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.22","kind":"speech"},"5.1.23":{"play":"IAGO: No, he must die. Be ’t so. I hear him coming.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.23","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.23.1":{"play":"[Enter Cassio.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.23.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.24":{"play":"RODERIGO: I know his gait. ’Tis he!—Villain, thou diest!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.24","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.24.1":{"play":"[He thrusts at Cassio.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.24.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.25":{"play":"CASSIO: That thrust had been mine enemy indeed","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.25","kind":"speech"},"5.1.26":{"play":"CASSIO: But that my coat is better than thou know’st.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.26","kind":"speech"},"5.1.27":{"play":"CASSIO: I will make proof of thine.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.27","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.27.1":{"play":"[He draws, and stabs Roderigo.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.27.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.28":{"play":"RODERIGO: O, I am slain!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.28","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.28.1":{"play":"[Roderigo falls.]","notes":["Barke] Knight: We prefer the more intelligible reading bulke, although we have little doubt that 'bark' was correctly used by Shakespeare in this instance as a projecting part of the fortification,—a buttress. Singer: I feel assured that balke was intended, and not bulk. Palsgrave renders that word by pouste, and Huloet defines it. *the chief beame or piller of a house.*"],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.28.1","kind":"stage"},"SD_5.1.28.2":{"play":"[Iago stabs Cassio in the leg, and exits.]","notes":["Resolution] White (ed. ii): Five syllables."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.28.2","kind":"stage"},"5.1.29":{"play":"CASSIO: I am maimed forever! Help, ho! Murder, murder!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.29","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.29.1":{"play":"[Enter Othello.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.29.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.30":{"play":"OTHELLO: The voice of Cassio! Iago keeps his word.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.30","kind":"speech"},"5.1.31":{"play":"RODERIGO: O, villain that I am!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.31","kind":"speech"},"5.1.32":{"play":"OTHELLO: It is even so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.32","kind":"speech"},"5.1.33":{"play":"CASSIO: O, help ho! Light! A surgeon!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.33","kind":"speech"},"5.1.34":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Tis he! O brave Iago, honest and just,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.34","kind":"speech"},"5.1.35":{"play":"OTHELLO: That hast such noble sense of thy friend’s wrong!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.35","kind":"speech"},"5.1.36":{"play":"OTHELLO: Thou teachest me.—Minion, your dear lies dead,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.36","kind":"speech"},"5.1.37":{"play":"OTHELLO: And your unblest fate hies. Strumpet, I come.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.37","kind":"speech"},"5.1.38":{"play":"OTHELLO: Forth of my heart those charms, thine eyes, are","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.38","kind":"speech"},"5.1.39":{"play":"OTHELLO: blotted.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.39","kind":"speech"},"5.1.40":{"play":"OTHELLO: Thy bed, lust-stained, shall with lust’s blood be","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.40","kind":"speech"},"5.1.41":{"play":"OTHELLO: spotted.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.41","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.41":{"play":"[Othello exits.]","notes":["Quat] JOHNSON: Hanmer reads quab, a gudgeon; not that a gudgeon can be rubbed to much sense, but that a man grossly deceived is often called a gudgeon. Upton reads quail, which he proves, by much learning, to be a very cholerick bird. Theobald would introduce knot, a small bird of that name. A 'quat' in the midland counties is a pimple, which by rubbing is made to smart, or is rubbed to sense. Roderigo is called a 'quat' by the same mode of speech as a low fellow is now termed in low language a scab. [Dr Johnson forgot that Shakespeare uses this word too. Ed.] To rub to the sense is to rub to the quick. Steevens cites several instances of the use of 'quat' in Dekker and others, but more to the purpose is it that Wise (p. 156) gives it in his Glossary of Warwickshire Words, as in use at this day, in the same sense as here."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.41","kind":"stage"},"SD_5.1.41.1":{"play":"[Enter Lodovico and Gratiano.]","notes":["Liue] For instances where the subjunctive may be indicated by placing the verb before the subject, see Abbott, §361."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.41.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.42":{"play":"CASSIO: What ho! No watch? No passage? Murder, murder!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.42","kind":"speech"},"5.1.43":{"play":"GRATIANO: ’Tis some mischance. The voice is very direful.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.43","kind":"speech"},"5.1.44":{"play":"CASSIO: O, help!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.44","kind":"speech"},"5.1.45":{"play":"LODOVICO: Hark!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.45","kind":"speech"},"5.1.46":{"play":"RODERIGO: O wretched villain!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.46","kind":"speech"},"5.1.47":{"play":"LODOVICO: Two or three groan. ’Tis heavy night.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.47","kind":"speech"},"5.1.48":{"play":"LODOVICO: These may be counterfeits. Let’s think ’t unsafe","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.48","kind":"speech"},"5.1.49":{"play":"LODOVICO: To come in to the cry without more help.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.49","kind":"speech"},"5.1.50":{"play":"RODERIGO: Nobody come? Then shall I bleed to death.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.50","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.50.1":{"play":"[Enter Iago with a light.]","notes":["bob'd] Malone: That I fool'd him out of. [Both Malone and Dyce cite Coles's Latin Did., 1679, as an authority for this word; but Rider's Latin Diet, of 1626, half a century earlier, gives 'A bob or mocke, sanna? It is still current slang here in America. Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.50.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.51":{"play":"LODOVICO: Hark!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.51","kind":"speech"},"5.1.52":{"play":"GRATIANO: Here’s one comes in his shirt, with light and","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.52","kind":"speech"},"5.1.53":{"play":"GRATIANO: weapons.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.53","kind":"speech"},"5.1.54":{"play":"IAGO: Who’s there? Whose noise is this that cries on","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.54","kind":"speech"},"5.1.55":{"play":"IAGO: murder?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.55","kind":"speech"},"5.1.56":{"play":"LODOVICO: We do not know.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.56","kind":"speech"},"5.1.57":{"play":"IAGO: Did not you hear a cry?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.57","kind":"speech"},"5.1.58":{"play":"CASSIO: Here, here! For heaven’s sake, help me!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.58","kind":"speech"},"5.1.59":{"play":"IAGO: What’s the matter?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.59","kind":"speech"},"5.1.60":{"play":"GRATIANO: This is Othello’s ancient, as I take it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.60","kind":"speech"},"5.1.61":{"play":"LODOVICO: The same indeed, a very valiant fellow.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.61","kind":"speech"},"5.1.62":{"play":"IAGO: What are you here that cry so grievously?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.62","kind":"speech"},"5.1.63":{"play":"CASSIO: Iago? O, I am spoiled, undone by villains.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.63","kind":"speech"},"5.1.64":{"play":"CASSIO: Give me some help!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.64","kind":"speech"},"5.1.65":{"play":"IAGO: O me, lieutenant! What villains have done this?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.65","kind":"speech"},"5.1.66":{"play":"CASSIO: I think that one of them is hereabout","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.66","kind":"speech"},"5.1.67":{"play":"CASSIO: And cannot make away.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.67","kind":"speech"},"5.1.68":{"play":"IAGO: O treacherous villains!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.68","kind":"speech"},"5.1.69":{"play":"IAGO: What are you there?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.69","kind":"speech"},"5.1.70":{"play":"IAGO: Come in, and give some help.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.70","kind":"speech"},"5.1.71":{"play":"RODERIGO: O, help me here!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.71","kind":"speech"},"5.1.72":{"play":"CASSIO: That’s one of them.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.72","kind":"speech"},"5.1.73":{"play":"IAGO: O murd’rous slave! O villain!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.73","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.73.1":{"play":"[He stabs Roderigo.]","notes":["But so] Dyce (ed. iii): Qy. if intended for 'But, soft'? Hudson: And so I suspect it should be."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.73.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.74":{"play":"RODERIGO: O damned Iago! O inhuman dog!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.74","kind":"speech"},"5.1.75":{"play":"IAGO: Kill men i’ th’ dark?—Where be these bloody","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.75","kind":"speech"},"5.1.76":{"play":"IAGO: thieves?","notes":["passage] Johnson: No passengers? nobody going by? Singer: A passenger anciently signified a passage-boat or vessel, and could not, therefore, be used in its modern sense without an equivoque."],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.76","kind":"speech"},"5.1.77":{"play":"IAGO: How silent is this town! Ho, murder, murder!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.77","kind":"speech"},"5.1.78":{"play":"IAGO: What may you be? Are you of good or evil?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.78","kind":"speech"},"5.1.79":{"play":"LODOVICO: As you shall prove us, praise us.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.79","kind":"speech"},"5.1.80":{"play":"IAGO: Signior Lodovico?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.80","kind":"speech"},"5.1.81":{"play":"LODOVICO: He, sir.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.81","kind":"speech"},"5.1.82":{"play":"IAGO: I cry you mercy. Here’s Cassio hurt by villains.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.82","kind":"speech"},"5.1.83":{"play":"GRATIANO: Cassio?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.83","kind":"speech"},"5.1.84":{"play":"IAGO: How is ’t, brother?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.84","kind":"speech"},"5.1.85":{"play":"CASSIO: My leg is cut in two.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.85","kind":"speech"},"5.1.86":{"play":"IAGO: Marry, heaven forbid!","notes":["groane] Knight: Lodovico does not merely say that there are two or three groans from one man, but that two or three men groan; and he adds, 'these may be counterfeits.' Lettsom (Walker, Crit. iii, 290, foot-note): How could people at a distance distinguish whether groans proceeded from one person or from more, when the groaners were lying close together? [Probably they did not both groan in the same key. Ed.]","heauy] Johnson: A thick, cloudy night, in which an ambush may be commodiously laid. Purnell: 'Gloomy.' Used elsewhere only of the eye in this sense."],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.86","kind":"speech"},"5.1.87":{"play":"IAGO: Light, gentlemen. I’ll bind it with my shirt.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.87","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.87.1":{"play":"[Enter Bianca.]","notes":["Coate] Malone supposes that Iago overhearing this, and inferring from it that Cassio wears secret armour, afterwards wounds Cassio in the leg. Knight says that the characteristics, according to Vecellio, of the costume of a 'soldato disarmato,' which would be that of Cassio and Iago when off guard, were the 'buff jerkin and the scarf of company,' and that it is to this 'buff jerkin' that Cassio refers, and not to any secret armour. Theobald asserts, however, that Shakespeare 'copied his Italian Novelist in this incident,' wherein it is stated that the Ancient 'dirrizzd un colpo alle gambe, per farlo cadere.'"],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.87.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.88":{"play":"BIANCA: What is the matter, ho? Who is ’t that cried?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.88","kind":"speech"},"5.1.89":{"play":"IAGO: Who is ’t that cried?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.89","kind":"speech"},"5.1.90":{"play":"BIANCA: O, my dear Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.90","kind":"speech"},"5.1.91":{"play":"BIANCA: My sweet Cassio! O Cassio, Cassio, Cassio!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.91","kind":"speech"},"5.1.92":{"play":"IAGO: O notable strumpet! Cassio, may you suspect","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.92","kind":"speech"},"5.1.93":{"play":"IAGO: Who they should be that have thus mangled you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.93","kind":"speech"},"5.1.94":{"play":"CASSIO: No.","notes":["cries on] Malone: So in Eastward Hoe, 1605: 'Who cries on murder? Lady, was it you?' That line is a parody on a line in The Spanish Tragedy. See also Ham. V, ii, 351. White (ed. i): That is, cries continually murder."],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.94","kind":"speech"},"5.1.95":{"play":"GRATIANO: I am sorry to find you thus; I have been to seek you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.95","kind":"speech"},"5.1.96":{"play":"IAGO: Lend me a garter. So.—O for a chair","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.96","kind":"speech"},"5.1.97":{"play":"IAGO: To bear him easily hence!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.97","kind":"speech"},"5.1.98":{"play":"BIANCA: Alas, he faints. O, Cassio, Cassio, Cassio!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.98","kind":"speech"},"5.1.99":{"play":"IAGO: Gentlemen all, I do suspect this trash","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.99","kind":"speech"},"5.1.100":{"play":"IAGO: To be a party in this injury.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.100","kind":"speech"},"5.1.101":{"play":"IAGO: Patience awhile, good Cassio.—Come, come;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.101","kind":"speech"},"5.1.102":{"play":"IAGO: Lend me a light. Know we this","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.102","kind":"speech"},"5.1.103":{"play":"IAGO: face or no?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.103","kind":"speech"},"5.1.104":{"play":"IAGO: Alas, my friend and my dear countryman","notes":["Booth: Cassio takes Desdemona's handkerchief,—the gift of Othello,—from his pocket and binds his leg."],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.104","kind":"speech"},"5.1.105":{"play":"IAGO: Roderigo? No! Yes, sure. O heaven, Roderigo!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.105","kind":"speech"},"5.1.106":{"play":"GRATIANO: What, of Venice?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.106","kind":"speech"},"5.1.107":{"play":"IAGO: Even he, sir. Did you know him?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.107","kind":"speech"},"5.1.108":{"play":"GRATIANO: Know him? Ay.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.108","kind":"speech"},"5.1.109":{"play":"IAGO: Signior Gratiano? I cry your gentle pardon.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.109","kind":"speech"},"5.1.110":{"play":"IAGO: These bloody accidents must excuse my manners","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.110","kind":"speech"},"5.1.111":{"play":"IAGO: That so neglected you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.111","kind":"speech"},"5.1.112":{"play":"GRATIANO: I am glad to see you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.112","kind":"speech"},"5.1.113":{"play":"IAGO: How do you, Cassio?—O, a chair, a chair!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.113","kind":"speech"},"5.1.114":{"play":"GRATIANO: Roderigo?","notes":["Hawkins [Life of Kean, i, 253]: Previous actors of Iago did not appear to have remembered that the whole fortune of the Ancient hinged upon this event; they stabbed Roderigo, and then walked away with perfect ease and satisfaction. Not so Kean. He gave and repeated the murderous thrust till no life could be supposed to remain; but feeling this to be too important a matter to be left in doubt, he, though conversing coolly with those about him, threw his eye continually towards the prostrate body, with an intensity as if he would pierce its vital recesses to ascertain the important fact Sometimes he walked by it carelessly and surveyed it with a glance too rapid to be observed; sometimes he deliberately approached it and looked at it with his candle, as if to satisfy the spectators that it was the villain who had attacked his friend Cassio, and thus he continued to watch and hover over it until he left the stage, his manner perfectly cool, while his eye expressed the most restless anxiety."],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.114","kind":"speech"},"5.1.115":{"play":"IAGO: He, he, ’tis he! O, that’s well","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.115","kind":"speech"},"5.1.116":{"play":"IAGO: said; the chair.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.116","kind":"speech"},"5.1.117":{"play":"IAGO: Some good man bear him carefully from hence.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.117","kind":"speech"},"5.1.118":{"play":"IAGO: I’ll fetch the General’s surgeon.— For you, mistress,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.118","kind":"speech"},"5.1.119":{"play":"IAGO: Save you your labor.—He that lies slain here,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.119","kind":"speech"},"5.1.120":{"play":"IAGO: Cassio,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.120","kind":"speech"},"5.1.121":{"play":"IAGO: Was my dear friend. What malice was between you?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.121","kind":"speech"},"5.1.122":{"play":"CASSIO: None in the world. Nor do I know the man.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.122","kind":"speech"},"5.1.123":{"play":"IAGO: What, look you pale?—O, bear him out o’ th’ air.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.123","kind":"speech"},"5.1.124":{"play":"IAGO: Stay you, good","notes":["be] Abbott, § 299: Be is used in questions implying doubt: 'where can they be?'"],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.124","kind":"speech"},"5.1.125":{"play":"IAGO: gentlemen.—Look you pale, mistress?—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.125","kind":"speech"},"5.1.126":{"play":"IAGO: Do you perceive the gastness of her eye?—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.126","kind":"speech"},"5.1.127":{"play":"IAGO: Nay, if you stare, we shall hear more anon.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.127","kind":"speech"},"5.1.128":{"play":"IAGO: Behold her well. I pray you, look upon her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.128","kind":"speech"},"5.1.129":{"play":"IAGO: Do you see, gentlemen? Nay, guiltiness will speak","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.129","kind":"speech"},"5.1.130":{"play":"IAGO: Though tongues were out of use.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.130","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.130.1":{"play":"[Enter Emilia.]","notes":["Ingleby [Shakespeare, the Man, &c. ii, 192], believing that Shakespeare did not intend Othello to speak at all in this Scene, denies that Shakespeare wrote these lines, which he calls 'atrocious stuff.'"],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.130.1","kind":"stage"},"5.1.131":{"play":"EMILIA: Alas, what is the matter? What is the matter,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.131","kind":"speech"},"5.1.132":{"play":"EMILIA: husband?","notes":["Booth: As Iago is about to stab Cassio, he sees Lodovico and Gratiano approaching with servants and torches."],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.132","kind":"speech"},"5.1.133":{"play":"IAGO: Cassio hath here been set on in the dark","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.133","kind":"speech"},"5.1.134":{"play":"IAGO: By Roderigo and fellows that are scaped.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.134","kind":"speech"},"5.1.135":{"play":"IAGO: He’s almost slain, and Roderigo dead.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.135","kind":"speech"},"5.1.136":{"play":"EMILIA: Alas, good gentleman! Alas, good Cassio!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.136","kind":"speech"},"5.1.137":{"play":"IAGO: This is the fruits of whoring. Prithee, Emilia,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.137","kind":"speech"},"5.1.138":{"play":"IAGO: Go know of Cassio where he supped tonight.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.138","kind":"speech"},"5.1.139":{"play":"IAGO: What, do you shake at that?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.139","kind":"speech"},"5.1.140":{"play":"BIANCA: He supped at my house, but I therefore shake not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.140","kind":"speech"},"5.1.141":{"play":"IAGO: O, did he so? I charge you go with me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.141","kind":"speech"},"5.1.142":{"play":"EMILIA: O fie upon thee, strumpet!","notes":["Countryman] Steevens: This passage incontestably proves that Iago was meant for a Venetian. Booth: Iago is very much overcome."],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.142","kind":"speech"},"5.1.143":{"play":"BIANCA: I am no strumpet, but of life as honest","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.143","kind":"speech"},"5.1.144":{"play":"BIANCA: As you that thus abuse me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.144","kind":"speech"},"5.1.145":{"play":"EMILIA: As I? Faugh! Fie upon thee!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.145","kind":"speech"},"5.1.146":{"play":"IAGO: Kind gentlemen, let’s go see poor Cassio dressed.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.146","kind":"speech"},"5.1.147":{"play":"IAGO: Come, mistress, you must tell ’s another tale.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.147","kind":"speech"},"5.1.148":{"play":"IAGO: Emilia, run you to the citadel","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.148","kind":"speech"},"5.1.149":{"play":"IAGO: And tell my lord and lady what hath happed.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.149","kind":"speech"},"5.1.150":{"play":"IAGO: Will you go on afore? This is the night","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.150","kind":"speech"},"5.1.151":{"play":"IAGO: That either makes me or fordoes me quite.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.1.151","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.1.151.1":{"play":"[They exit in different directions.]","notes":["For of] Unquestionably a misprint for Forth of, of which form see other instances in Abbott, § 156.","foredoes] See Ham. II, i, 103."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.1.151.1","kind":"stage"}},"ACT 5, SCENE 2":{"SD_5.2.0":{"play":"[Enter Othello with a light, and Desdemona in her bed.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.0","kind":"stage"},"5.2.1":{"play":"OTHELLO: It is the cause, it is the cause, my soul.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.1","kind":"speech"},"5.2.2":{"play":"OTHELLO: Let me not name it to you, you chaste stars.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.2","kind":"speech"},"5.2.3":{"play":"OTHELLO: It is the cause. Yet I’ll not shed her blood,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.3","kind":"speech"},"5.2.4":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nor scar that whiter skin of hers than snow,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.4","kind":"speech"},"5.2.5":{"play":"OTHELLO: And smooth as monumental alabaster.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.5","kind":"speech"},"5.2.6":{"play":"OTHELLO: Yet she must die, else she’ll betray more men.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.6","kind":"speech"},"5.2.7":{"play":"OTHELLO: Put out the light, and then put out the light.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.7","kind":"speech"},"5.2.8":{"play":"OTHELLO: If I quench thee, thou flaming minister,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.8","kind":"speech"},"5.2.9":{"play":"OTHELLO: I can again thy former light restore","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.9","kind":"speech"},"5.2.10":{"play":"OTHELLO: Should I repent me. But once put out thy light,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.10","kind":"speech"},"5.2.11":{"play":"OTHELLO: Thou cunning’st pattern of excelling nature,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.11","kind":"speech"},"5.2.12":{"play":"OTHELLO: I know not where is that Promethean heat","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.12","kind":"speech"},"5.2.13":{"play":"OTHELLO: That can thy light relume. When I have plucked the","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.13","kind":"speech"},"5.2.14":{"play":"OTHELLO: rose,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.14","kind":"speech"},"5.2.15":{"play":"OTHELLO: I cannot give it vital growth again.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.15","kind":"speech"},"5.2.16":{"play":"OTHELLO: It needs must wither. I’ll smell it on the tree.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.16","kind":"speech"},"5.2.17":{"play":"OTHELLO: O balmy breath, that dost almost persuade","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.17","kind":"speech"},"5.2.18":{"play":"OTHELLO: Justice to break her sword! One","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.18","kind":"speech"},"5.2.19":{"play":"OTHELLO: more, one more.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.19","kind":"speech"},"5.2.20":{"play":"OTHELLO: Be thus when thou art dead, and I will kill thee","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.20","kind":"speech"},"5.2.21":{"play":"OTHELLO: And love thee after. One more, and this the last.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.21","kind":"speech"},"5.2.22":{"play":"OTHELLO: So sweet was ne’er so fatal. I must weep,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.22","kind":"speech"},"5.2.23":{"play":"OTHELLO: But they are cruel tears. This sorrow’s heavenly:","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.23","kind":"speech"},"5.2.24":{"play":"OTHELLO: It strikes where it doth love. She wakes.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.24","kind":"speech"},"5.2.25":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Who’s there? Othello?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.25","kind":"speech"},"5.2.26":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ay, Desdemona.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.26","kind":"speech"},"5.2.27":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Will you come to bed, my lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.27","kind":"speech"},"5.2.28":{"play":"OTHELLO: Have you prayed tonight, Desdemon?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.28","kind":"speech"},"5.2.29":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Ay, my lord.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.29","kind":"speech"},"5.2.30":{"play":"OTHELLO: If you bethink yourself of any crime","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.30","kind":"speech"},"5.2.31":{"play":"OTHELLO: Unreconciled as yet to heaven and grace,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.31","kind":"speech"},"5.2.32":{"play":"OTHELLO: Solicit for it straight.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.32","kind":"speech"},"5.2.33":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Alack, my lord,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.33","kind":"speech"},"5.2.34":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What may you mean by that?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.34","kind":"speech"},"5.2.35":{"play":"OTHELLO: Well, do it, and be brief. I will walk by.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.35","kind":"speech"},"5.2.36":{"play":"OTHELLO: I would not kill thy unpreparèd spirit.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.36","kind":"speech"},"5.2.37":{"play":"OTHELLO: No, heaven forfend! I would not kill thy soul.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.37","kind":"speech"},"5.2.38":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Talk you of killing?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.38","kind":"speech"},"5.2.39":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ay, I do.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.39","kind":"speech"},"5.2.40":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Then heaven have mercy on me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.40","kind":"speech"},"5.2.41":{"play":"OTHELLO: Amen, with all my heart.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.41","kind":"speech"},"5.2.42":{"play":"DESDEMONA: If you say so, I hope you will not kill me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.42","kind":"speech"},"5.2.43":{"play":"OTHELLO: Humh.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.43","kind":"speech"},"5.2.44":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And yet I fear you, for you’re fatal then","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.44","kind":"speech"},"5.2.45":{"play":"DESDEMONA: When your eyes roll so. Why I should fear I know","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.45","kind":"speech"},"5.2.46":{"play":"DESDEMONA: not,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.46","kind":"speech"},"5.2.47":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Since guiltiness I know not, but yet I feel I fear.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.47","kind":"speech"},"5.2.48":{"play":"OTHELLO: Think on thy sins.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.48","kind":"speech"},"5.2.49":{"play":"DESDEMONA: They are loves I bear to you.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.49","kind":"speech"},"5.2.50":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ay, and for that thou diest.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.50","kind":"speech"},"5.2.51":{"play":"DESDEMONA: That death’s unnatural that kills for loving.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.51","kind":"speech"},"5.2.52":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Alas, why gnaw you so your nether lip?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.52","kind":"speech"},"5.2.53":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Some bloody passion shakes your very frame.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.53","kind":"speech"},"5.2.54":{"play":"DESDEMONA: These are portents, but yet I hope, I hope","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.54","kind":"speech"},"5.2.55":{"play":"DESDEMONA: They do not point on me.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.55","kind":"speech"},"5.2.56":{"play":"OTHELLO: Peace, and be still.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.56","kind":"speech"},"5.2.57":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I will so. What’s the matter?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.57","kind":"speech"},"5.2.58":{"play":"OTHELLO: That handkerchief","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.58","kind":"speech"},"5.2.59":{"play":"OTHELLO: Which I so loved, and gave thee, thou gav’st to","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.59","kind":"speech"},"5.2.60":{"play":"OTHELLO: Cassio.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.60","kind":"speech"},"5.2.61":{"play":"DESDEMONA: No, by my life and soul! Send for the man","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.61","kind":"speech"},"5.2.62":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And ask him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.62","kind":"speech"},"5.2.63":{"play":"OTHELLO: Sweet soul, take heed, take heed of perjury.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.63","kind":"speech"},"5.2.64":{"play":"OTHELLO: Thou art on thy deathbed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.64","kind":"speech"},"5.2.65":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Ay, but not yet to die.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.65","kind":"speech"},"5.2.66":{"play":"OTHELLO: Yes, presently.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.66","kind":"speech"},"5.2.67":{"play":"OTHELLO: Therefore confess thee freely of thy sin.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.67","kind":"speech"},"5.2.68":{"play":"OTHELLO: For to deny each article with oath","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.68","kind":"speech"},"5.2.69":{"play":"OTHELLO: Cannot remove nor choke the strong conception","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.69","kind":"speech"},"5.2.70":{"play":"OTHELLO: That I do groan withal. Thou art to die.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.70","kind":"speech"},"5.2.71":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Then Lord have mercy on me!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.71","kind":"speech"},"5.2.72":{"play":"OTHELLO: I say","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.72","kind":"speech"},"5.2.73":{"play":"DESDEMONA: And have you mercy, too. I never did","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.73","kind":"speech"},"5.2.74":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Offend you in my life, never loved Cassio","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.74","kind":"speech"},"5.2.75":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But with such general warranty of heaven","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.75","kind":"speech"},"5.2.76":{"play":"DESDEMONA: As I might love. I never gave him token.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.76","kind":"speech"},"5.2.77":{"play":"OTHELLO: By heaven, I saw my handkerchief in ’s hand!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.77","kind":"speech"},"5.2.78":{"play":"OTHELLO: O perjured woman, thou dost stone my heart","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.78","kind":"speech"},"5.2.79":{"play":"OTHELLO: And mak’st me call what I intend to do","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.79","kind":"speech"},"5.2.80":{"play":"OTHELLO: A murder, which I thought a sacrifice!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.80","kind":"speech"},"5.2.81":{"play":"OTHELLO: I saw the handkerchief!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.81","kind":"speech"},"5.2.82":{"play":"DESDEMONA: He found it, then.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.82","kind":"speech"},"5.2.83":{"play":"DESDEMONA: I never gave it him. Send for him hither.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.83","kind":"speech"},"5.2.84":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Let him confess a truth.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.84","kind":"speech"},"5.2.85":{"play":"OTHELLO: He hath confessed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.85","kind":"speech"},"5.2.86":{"play":"DESDEMONA: What, my lord?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.86","kind":"speech"},"5.2.87":{"play":"OTHELLO: That he hath used thee.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.87","kind":"speech"},"5.2.88":{"play":"DESDEMONA: How? Unlawfully?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.88","kind":"speech"},"5.2.89":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ay.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.89","kind":"speech"},"5.2.90":{"play":"DESDEMONA: He will not say so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.90","kind":"speech"},"5.2.91":{"play":"OTHELLO: No. His mouth is stopped.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.91","kind":"speech"},"5.2.92":{"play":"OTHELLO: Honest Iago hath ta’en order for ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.92","kind":"speech"},"5.2.93":{"play":"DESDEMONA: O, my fear interprets. What, is he dead?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.93","kind":"speech"},"5.2.94":{"play":"OTHELLO: Had all his hairs been lives, my great revenge","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.94","kind":"speech"},"5.2.95":{"play":"OTHELLO: Had stomach for them all.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.95","kind":"speech"},"5.2.96":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Alas, he is betrayed, and I undone.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.96","kind":"speech"},"5.2.97":{"play":"OTHELLO: Out, strumpet! Weep’st thou for him to my face?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.97","kind":"speech"},"5.2.98":{"play":"DESDEMONA: O banish me, my lord, but kill me not!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.98","kind":"speech"},"5.2.99":{"play":"OTHELLO: Down, strumpet!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.99","kind":"speech"},"5.2.100":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Kill me tomorrow, let me live tonight.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.100","kind":"speech"},"5.2.101":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nay, if you strive—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.101","kind":"speech"},"5.2.102":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But half an hour!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.102","kind":"speech"},"5.2.103":{"play":"OTHELLO: Being done, there is no pause.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.103","kind":"speech"},"5.2.104":{"play":"DESDEMONA: But while I say one prayer!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.104","kind":"speech"},"5.2.105":{"play":"OTHELLO: It is too late.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.105","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.105.1":{"play":"[He smothers her.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.105.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.106":{"play":"EMILIA: My lord, my lord? What ho! My lord, my lord!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.106","kind":"speech"},"5.2.107":{"play":"OTHELLO: What noise is this?—Not dead? Not yet quite dead?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.107","kind":"speech"},"5.2.108":{"play":"OTHELLO: I that am cruel am yet merciful.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.108","kind":"speech"},"5.2.109":{"play":"OTHELLO: I would not have thee linger in thy pain.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.109","kind":"speech"},"5.2.110":{"play":"OTHELLO: So, so.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.110","kind":"speech"},"5.2.111":{"play":"EMILIA: What, ho! My lord, my lord!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.111","kind":"speech"},"5.2.112":{"play":"OTHELLO: Who’s","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.112","kind":"speech"},"5.2.113":{"play":"OTHELLO: there?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.113","kind":"speech"},"5.2.114":{"play":"EMILIA: O, good my lord, I would speak a word with you.","notes":["Malone: Compare Rich. III: I, ii, 134, 'It is a quarrel most unnatural, To be revenged on him that loveth you.'"],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.114","kind":"speech"},"5.2.115":{"play":"OTHELLO: Yes. ’Tis Emilia.—By and by.—She’s dead.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.115","kind":"speech"},"5.2.116":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Tis like she comes to speak of Cassio’s death.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.116","kind":"speech"},"5.2.117":{"play":"OTHELLO: The noise was here. Ha, no more moving?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.117","kind":"speech"},"5.2.118":{"play":"OTHELLO: Still as the grave. Shall she come in? Were ’t good?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.118","kind":"speech"},"5.2.119":{"play":"OTHELLO: I think she stirs again. No. What’s best to do?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.119","kind":"speech"},"5.2.120":{"play":"OTHELLO: If she come in, she’ll sure speak to my wife.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.120","kind":"speech"},"5.2.121":{"play":"OTHELLO: My wife, my wife! What wife? I have no wife.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.121","kind":"speech"},"5.2.122":{"play":"OTHELLO: O insupportable! O heavy hour!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.122","kind":"speech"},"5.2.123":{"play":"OTHELLO: Methinks it should be now a huge eclipse","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.123","kind":"speech"},"5.2.124":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of sun and moon, and that th’ affrighted globe","notes":["Fechter: She throws back the coverlet, rises, and sits on the bed."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.124","kind":"speech"},"5.2.125":{"play":"OTHELLO: Should yawn at alteration.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.125","kind":"speech"},"5.2.126":{"play":"EMILIA: I do beseech you","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.126","kind":"speech"},"5.2.127":{"play":"EMILIA: That I may speak with you. O, good my lord—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.127","kind":"speech"},"5.2.128":{"play":"OTHELLO: I had forgot thee. O, come in, Emilia.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.128","kind":"speech"},"5.2.129":{"play":"OTHELLO: Soft, by and by, let me the curtains draw.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.129","kind":"speech"},"5.2.130":{"play":"OTHELLO: Where art thou?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.130","kind":"speech"},"5.2.131":{"play":"OTHELLO: What’s the matter with thee now?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.131","kind":"speech"},"5.2.132":{"play":"EMILIA: O, my good lord, yonder’s foul murders done.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.132","kind":"speech"},"5.2.133":{"play":"OTHELLO: What? Now?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.133","kind":"speech"},"5.2.134":{"play":"EMILIA: But now, my lord.","notes":["Abbott, §190: For other instances of 'portent' thus accented on the last syllable see Abbott."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.134","kind":"speech"},"5.2.135":{"play":"OTHELLO: It is the very error of the moon.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.135","kind":"speech"},"5.2.136":{"play":"OTHELLO: She comes more nearer Earth than she was wont","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.136","kind":"speech"},"5.2.137":{"play":"OTHELLO: And makes men mad.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.137","kind":"speech"},"5.2.138":{"play":"EMILIA: Cassio, my lord, hath killed","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.138","kind":"speech"},"5.2.139":{"play":"EMILIA: A young Venetian called Roderigo.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.139","kind":"speech"},"5.2.140":{"play":"OTHELLO: Roderigo killed? And Cassio killed?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.140","kind":"speech"},"5.2.141":{"play":"EMILIA: No, Cassio is not killed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.141","kind":"speech"},"5.2.142":{"play":"OTHELLO: Not Cassio killed? Then murder’s out of tune,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.142","kind":"speech"},"5.2.143":{"play":"OTHELLO: And sweet revenge grows harsh.","notes":["Booth: Desdemona comes from her bed, and rests tremblingly against it."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.143","kind":"speech"},"5.2.144":{"play":"DESDEMONA: O falsely, falsely murdered.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.144","kind":"speech"},"5.2.145":{"play":"EMILIA: O Lord, what cry is that?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.145","kind":"speech"},"5.2.146":{"play":"OTHELLO: That? What?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.146","kind":"speech"},"5.2.147":{"play":"EMILIA: Out, and alas, that was my lady’s voice!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.147","kind":"speech"},"5.2.148":{"play":"EMILIA: Help! Help ho! Help! O lady, speak again!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.148","kind":"speech"},"5.2.149":{"play":"EMILIA: Sweet Desdemona, O sweet mistress, speak!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.149","kind":"speech"},"5.2.150":{"play":"DESDEMONA: A guiltless death I die.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.150","kind":"speech"},"5.2.151":{"play":"EMILIA: O, who hath done this deed?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.151","kind":"speech"},"5.2.152":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Nobody. I myself. Farewell.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.152","kind":"speech"},"5.2.153":{"play":"DESDEMONA: Commend me to my kind lord. O, farewell.","notes":["Abbott, §59: That is, 'at the present time,' 'at once,' instead of, as now, 'soon, but not at once.'"],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.153","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.153.1":{"play":"[She dies.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.153.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.154":{"play":"OTHELLO: Why, how should she be murdered?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.154","kind":"speech"},"5.2.155":{"play":"EMILIA: Alas, who","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.155","kind":"speech"},"5.2.156":{"play":"EMILIA: knows?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.156","kind":"speech"},"5.2.157":{"play":"OTHELLO: You heard her say herself, it was not I.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.157","kind":"speech"},"5.2.158":{"play":"EMILIA: She said so. I must needs report the truth.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.158","kind":"speech"},"5.2.159":{"play":"OTHELLO: She’s like a liar gone to burning hell!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.159","kind":"speech"},"5.2.160":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Twas I that killed her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.160","kind":"speech"},"5.2.161":{"play":"EMILIA: O, the more angel she, and you the blacker devil!","notes":["Booth: Sinking on her knees. During the rest of this, down to line 98, she is half reclining on the steps and dais of the bed."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.161","kind":"speech"},"5.2.162":{"play":"OTHELLO: She turned to folly, and she was a whore.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.162","kind":"speech"},"5.2.163":{"play":"EMILIA: Thou dost belie her, and thou art a devil!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.163","kind":"speech"},"5.2.164":{"play":"OTHELLO: She was false as water.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.164","kind":"speech"},"5.2.165":{"play":"EMILIA: Thou art rash as fire to say","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.165","kind":"speech"},"5.2.166":{"play":"EMILIA: That she was false. O, she was heavenly true!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.166","kind":"speech"},"5.2.167":{"play":"OTHELLO: Cassio did top her. Ask thy husband else.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.167","kind":"speech"},"5.2.168":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, I were damned beneath all depth in hell","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.168","kind":"speech"},"5.2.169":{"play":"OTHELLO: But that I did proceed upon just grounds","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.169","kind":"speech"},"5.2.170":{"play":"OTHELLO: To this extremity. Thy husband knew it all.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.170","kind":"speech"},"5.2.171":{"play":"EMILIA: My husband?","notes":["Steevens: After this speech, Q1 adds an invocation from Desdemona, consisting only of the sacred name thrice repeated. As this must be supposed to have been uttered while she is yet struggling with death, I think an editor may be excused from inserting such a circumstance of supererogatory horror."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.171","kind":"speech"},"5.2.172":{"play":"OTHELLO: Thy husband.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.172","kind":"speech"},"5.2.173":{"play":"EMILIA: That she was false to wedlock?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.173","kind":"speech"},"5.2.174":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ay, with Cassio. Had she been true,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.174","kind":"speech"},"5.2.175":{"play":"OTHELLO: If heaven would make me such another world","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.175","kind":"speech"},"5.2.176":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of one entire and perfect chrysolite,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.176","kind":"speech"},"5.2.177":{"play":"OTHELLO: I’d not have sold her for it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.177","kind":"speech"},"5.2.178":{"play":"EMILIA: My husband?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.178","kind":"speech"},"5.2.179":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ay, ’twas he that told me on her first.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.179","kind":"speech"},"5.2.180":{"play":"OTHELLO: An honest man he is, and hates the slime","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.180","kind":"speech"},"5.2.181":{"play":"OTHELLO: That sticks on filthy deeds.","notes":["Booth: Long pause. Emilia's rap must not be loud."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.181","kind":"speech"},"5.2.182":{"play":"EMILIA: My husband?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.182","kind":"speech"},"5.2.183":{"play":"OTHELLO: What needs this iterance, woman? I say, thy","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.183","kind":"speech"},"5.2.184":{"play":"OTHELLO: husband.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.184","kind":"speech"},"5.2.185":{"play":"EMILIA: O mistress, villainy hath made mocks with love!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.185","kind":"speech"},"5.2.186":{"play":"EMILIA: My husband say she was false?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.186","kind":"speech"},"5.2.187":{"play":"OTHELLO: He, woman.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.187","kind":"speech"},"5.2.188":{"play":"OTHELLO: I say thy husband. Dost understand the word?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.188","kind":"speech"},"5.2.189":{"play":"OTHELLO: My friend, thy husband; honest, honest Iago.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.189","kind":"speech"},"5.2.190":{"play":"EMILIA: If he say so, may his pernicious soul","notes":["Booth: At this word he pauses as if stunned, or, rather, puzzled by so strange a word, and mutters it twice inquiringly, then, under the full force of the horror, he almost screams, 'I have no wife!' and falls prostrate on the divan in centre of the stage, where he writhes while speaking the lines that follow."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.190","kind":"speech"},"5.2.191":{"play":"EMILIA: Rot half a grain a day! He lies to th’ heart!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.191","kind":"speech"},"5.2.192":{"play":"EMILIA: She was too fond of her most filthy bargain.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.192","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.192.1":{"play":"[He draws his sword.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.192.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.193":{"play":"OTHELLO: Hah?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.193","kind":"speech"},"5.2.194":{"play":"EMILIA: Do thy worst!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.194","kind":"speech"},"5.2.195":{"play":"EMILIA: This deed of thine is no more worthy heaven","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.195","kind":"speech"},"5.2.196":{"play":"EMILIA: Than thou wast worthy her.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.196","kind":"speech"},"5.2.197":{"play":"OTHELLO: Peace, you were best!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.197","kind":"speech"},"5.2.198":{"play":"EMILIA: Thou hast not half that power to do me harm","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.198","kind":"speech"},"5.2.199":{"play":"EMILIA: As I have to be hurt. O gull! O dolt,","notes":["Booth: Iago, who has turned aside, now faces them as all look towards him."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.199","kind":"speech"},"5.2.200":{"play":"EMILIA: As ignorant as dirt! Thou hast done a deed—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.200","kind":"speech"},"5.2.201":{"play":"EMILIA: I care not for thy sword. I’ll make thee known,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.201","kind":"speech"},"5.2.202":{"play":"EMILIA: Though I lost twenty lives. Help! Help, ho! Help!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.202","kind":"speech"},"5.2.203":{"play":"EMILIA: The Moor hath killed my mistress! Murder, murder!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.203","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.203.1":{"play":"[Enter Montano, Gratiano, and Iago.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.203.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.204":{"play":"MONTANO: What is the matter? How now, general?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.204","kind":"speech"},"5.2.205":{"play":"EMILIA: O, are you come, Iago? You have done well,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.205","kind":"speech"},"5.2.206":{"play":"EMILIA: That men must lay their murders on your neck.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.206","kind":"speech"},"5.2.207":{"play":"GRATIANO: What is the matter?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.207","kind":"speech"},"5.2.208":{"play":"EMILIA: Disprove this villain, if thou be’st a man.","notes":["Booth: Othello goes to the bed, and lies moaning there, not loudly."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.208","kind":"speech"},"5.2.209":{"play":"EMILIA: He says thou told’st him that his wife was false.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.209","kind":"speech"},"5.2.210":{"play":"EMILIA: I know thou didst not. Thou ’rt not such a villain.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.210","kind":"speech"},"5.2.211":{"play":"EMILIA: Speak, for my heart is full.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.211","kind":"speech"},"5.2.212":{"play":"IAGO: I told him what I thought, and told no more","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.212","kind":"speech"},"5.2.213":{"play":"IAGO: Than what he found himself was apt and true.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.213","kind":"speech"},"5.2.214":{"play":"EMILIA: But did you ever tell him she was false?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.214","kind":"speech"},"5.2.215":{"play":"IAGO: I did.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.215","kind":"speech"},"5.2.216":{"play":"EMILIA: You told a lie, an odious, damnèd lie!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.216","kind":"speech"},"5.2.217":{"play":"EMILIA: Upon my soul, a lie, a wicked lie!","notes":["Booth: Iago hardens himself, as it were, looking straight before him; immovable,—and answers after a pause, and doggedly."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.217","kind":"speech"},"5.2.218":{"play":"EMILIA: She false with Cassio? Did you say with Cassio?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.218","kind":"speech"},"5.2.219":{"play":"IAGO: With Cassio, mistress. Go to! Charm your tongue.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.219","kind":"speech"},"5.2.220":{"play":"EMILIA: I will not charm my tongue. I am bound to speak.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.220","kind":"speech"},"5.2.221":{"play":"EMILIA: My mistress here lies murdered in her bed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.221","kind":"speech"},"5.2.222":{"play":"ALL: O heavens forfend!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.222","kind":"speech"},"5.2.223":{"play":"EMILIA: And your reports have set the murder on!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.223","kind":"speech"},"5.2.224":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nay, stare not, masters; it is true indeed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.224","kind":"speech"},"5.2.225":{"play":"GRATIANO: ’Tis a strange truth.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.225","kind":"speech"},"5.2.226":{"play":"MONTANO: O monstrous act!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.226","kind":"speech"},"5.2.227":{"play":"EMILIA: Villainy, villainy, villainy!","notes":["Booth: This should affect Othello; he believes her dying with a lie on her lips, and he shows how it pains him. His next speech is in half-choked utterances."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.227","kind":"speech"},"5.2.228":{"play":"EMILIA: I think upon ’t, I think! I smell ’t! O villainy!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.228","kind":"speech"},"5.2.229":{"play":"EMILIA: I thought so then. I’ll kill myself for grief!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.229","kind":"speech"},"5.2.230":{"play":"EMILIA: O villainy! Villainy!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.230","kind":"speech"},"5.2.231":{"play":"IAGO: What, are you mad? I charge you get you home.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.231","kind":"speech"},"5.2.232":{"play":"EMILIA: Good gentlemen, let me have leave to speak.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.232","kind":"speech"},"5.2.233":{"play":"EMILIA: ’Tis proper I obey him, but not now.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.233","kind":"speech"},"5.2.234":{"play":"EMILIA: Perchance, Iago, I will ne’er go home.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.234","kind":"speech"},"5.2.235":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, O, O!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.235","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.235":{"play":"[Othello falls on the bed.]","notes":["Elze (Notes, &c., 2d Ser. p. 157): [re division of line, as two lines at 'me.' Ed.]"],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.235","kind":"stage"},"5.2.236":{"play":"EMILIA: Nay, lay thee down, and roar!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.236","kind":"speech"},"5.2.237":{"play":"EMILIA: For thou hast killed the sweetest innocent","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.237","kind":"speech"},"5.2.238":{"play":"EMILIA: That e’er did lift up eye.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.238","kind":"speech"},"5.2.239":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, she was foul!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.239","kind":"speech"},"5.2.240":{"play":"OTHELLO: I scarce did know you, uncle. There lies your niece,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.240","kind":"speech"},"5.2.241":{"play":"OTHELLO: Whose breath indeed these hands have newly","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.241","kind":"speech"},"5.2.242":{"play":"OTHELLO: stopped.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.242","kind":"speech"},"5.2.243":{"play":"OTHELLO: I know this act shows horrible and grim.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.243","kind":"speech"},"5.2.244":{"play":"GRATIANO: Poor Desdemon, I am glad thy father’s dead.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.244","kind":"speech"},"5.2.245":{"play":"GRATIANO: Thy match was mortal to him, and pure grief","notes":["Hudson: Emilia evidently means that Desdemona is the more angel for having spoken the falsehood in question. And surely all well-ordered minds must agree with her; at all events, I, for one, cannot choose but love and honour Desdemona the more for that lie. For, indeed, the sweet, dear sufferer knows that Othello is driven onward by some monstrous delusion; that some hideous inspiration has put him clean out of his native self; that he is sure to have the worst of it, and so is even more an object of compassion than herself; and the unspeakable agony legible in his features wrings her pure soul with a pity so intense as to take from her all sense of the pangs of death; and so her last breath is hallowed with a tender yearning to shield him, as far as she possibly can, from the dreadful retributions which await him, both from without and from within, when the truth shall be known."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.245","kind":"speech"},"5.2.246":{"play":"GRATIANO: Shore his old thread in twain. Did he live now,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.246","kind":"speech"},"5.2.247":{"play":"GRATIANO: This sight would make him do a desperate turn,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.247","kind":"speech"},"5.2.248":{"play":"GRATIANO: Yea, curse his better angel from his side,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.248","kind":"speech"},"5.2.249":{"play":"GRATIANO: And fall to reprobance.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.249","kind":"speech"},"5.2.250":{"play":"OTHELLO: ’Tis pitiful. But yet Iago knows","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.250","kind":"speech"},"5.2.251":{"play":"OTHELLO: That she with Cassio hath the act of shame","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.251","kind":"speech"},"5.2.252":{"play":"OTHELLO: A thousand times committed. Cassio confessed it,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.252","kind":"speech"},"5.2.253":{"play":"OTHELLO: And she did gratify his amorous works","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.253","kind":"speech"},"5.2.254":{"play":"OTHELLO: With that recognizance and pledge of love","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.254","kind":"speech"},"5.2.255":{"play":"OTHELLO: Which I first gave her. I saw it in his hand.","notes":["Malone: This signifies here, as in the sacred writings, wantonness or unchastity. So in R. of L., 556: 'Her sad behaviour feeds his vulture folly.'"],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.255","kind":"speech"},"5.2.256":{"play":"OTHELLO: It was a handkerchief, an antique token","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.256","kind":"speech"},"5.2.257":{"play":"OTHELLO: My father gave my mother.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.257","kind":"speech"},"5.2.258":{"play":"EMILIA: O God! O heavenly God!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.258","kind":"speech"},"5.2.259":{"play":"IAGO: Zounds, hold your peace!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.259","kind":"speech"},"5.2.260":{"play":"EMILIA: ’Twill out, ’twill out. I peace?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.260","kind":"speech"},"5.2.261":{"play":"EMILIA: No, I will speak as liberal as the north.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.261","kind":"speech"},"5.2.262":{"play":"EMILIA: Let heaven and men and devils, let them all,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.262","kind":"speech"},"5.2.263":{"play":"EMILIA: All, all, cry shame against me, yet I’ll speak.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.263","kind":"speech"},"5.2.264":{"play":"IAGO: Be wise, and get you home.","notes":["Johnson: As water that will support no weight, nor keep any impression."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.264","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.264.1":{"play":"[He draws his sword.]","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.264.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.265":{"play":"EMILIA: I will not.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.265","kind":"speech"},"5.2.266":{"play":"GRATIANO: Fie, your sword upon a woman!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.266","kind":"speech"},"5.2.267":{"play":"EMILIA: O thou dull Moor, that handkerchief thou speak’st","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.267","kind":"speech"},"5.2.268":{"play":"EMILIA: of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.268","kind":"speech"},"5.2.269":{"play":"EMILIA: I found by fortune, and did give my husband—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.269","kind":"speech"},"5.2.270":{"play":"EMILIA: For often, with a solemn earnestness","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.270","kind":"speech"},"5.2.271":{"play":"EMILIA: (More than indeed belonged to such a trifle),","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.271","kind":"speech"},"5.2.272":{"play":"EMILIA: He begged of me to steal ’t.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.272","kind":"speech"},"5.2.273":{"play":"IAGO: Villainous whore!","notes":["Booth: With vigour; in justification of what he has done."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.273","kind":"speech"},"5.2.274":{"play":"EMILIA: She give it Cassio? No, alas, I found it,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.274","kind":"speech"},"5.2.275":{"play":"EMILIA: And I did give ’t my husband.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.275","kind":"speech"},"5.2.276":{"play":"IAGO: Filth, thou liest!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.276","kind":"speech"},"5.2.277":{"play":"EMILIA: By heaven, I do not, I do not, gentlemen!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.277","kind":"speech"},"5.2.278":{"play":"EMILIA: O murd’rous coxcomb, what should","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.278","kind":"speech"},"5.2.279":{"play":"EMILIA: such a fool","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.279","kind":"speech"},"5.2.280":{"play":"EMILIA: Do with so good a wife?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.280","kind":"speech"},"5.2.281":{"play":"OTHELLO: Are there no stones in heaven","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.281","kind":"speech"},"5.2.282":{"play":"OTHELLO: But what serves for the thunder?—Precious villain!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.282","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.282.1":{"play":"[The Moor runs at Iago but is disarmed.]","notes":["Johnson: The abruptness of this soliloquy makes it obscure. The meaning, I think, is this:—I am here (says Othello in his mind) overwhelmed with horror. What is the reason of this perturbation? Is it want of resolution to do justice? Is it the dread of shedding blood? No; it is not the action that shocks me, but 'it is the cause, it is the cause, my soul.'","Holland's Translation of Pliny: The Topaze or Chrysolith, hath a singular green colour by it selfe, for which it is esteemed very rich, and when it was first found, it surpassed all others in price."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.282.1","kind":"stage"},"SD_5.2.282.2":{"play":"[Iago kills his wife.]","notes":["Hudson: In classical poetry the Moon is Diana, the goddess of chastity, and the stars are the train of virgins attending on her. The epithet 'chaste' thus applied suggests the nature of the cause which the purity of the stars forbids to be named in their presence."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.282.2","kind":"stage"},"5.2.283":{"play":"GRATIANO: The woman falls! Sure he hath killed his wife.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.283","kind":"speech"},"5.2.284":{"play":"EMILIA: Ay, ay! O, lay me by my mistress’ side.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.284","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.284":{"play":"[Iago exits.]","notes":["Abbott, §419a: For many instances of this transposition of the adjective, see Abbott, and Walker (Crit. i, 160)."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.284","kind":"stage"},"5.2.285":{"play":"GRATIANO: He’s gone, but his wife’s killed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.285","kind":"speech"},"5.2.286":{"play":"MONTANO: ’Tis a notorious villain. Take you this weapon","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.286","kind":"speech"},"5.2.287":{"play":"MONTANO: Which I have here recovered from the Moor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.287","kind":"speech"},"5.2.288":{"play":"MONTANO: Come, guard the door without. Let him not pass,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.288","kind":"speech"},"5.2.289":{"play":"MONTANO: But kill him rather. I’ll after that same villain,","notes":["Walker (Crit. ii, 203): To be pronounced as one syllable. See i, ii, 34; iii, iv, 195."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.289","kind":"speech"},"5.2.290":{"play":"MONTANO: For ’tis a damnèd slave.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.290","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.290.1":{"play":"[Montano and Gratiano exit.]","notes":["Hunter (ii, 288): I confess the sense is not clear to me. It seems as if it should be that Othello is the 'betrayed,' not Cassio, or any other person whom the Moor, in his disordered mind, may suppose to be a second Cassio. I would therefore suggest as worthy of consideration, that the words may have been originally, 'else she'll betray me more.'"],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.290.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.291":{"play":"OTHELLO: I am not valiant neither,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.291","kind":"speech"},"5.2.292":{"play":"OTHELLO: But every puny whipster gets my sword.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.292","kind":"speech"},"5.2.293":{"play":"OTHELLO: But why should honor outlive honesty?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.293","kind":"speech"},"5.2.294":{"play":"OTHELLO: Let it go all.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.294","kind":"speech"},"5.2.295":{"play":"EMILIA: What did thy song bode, lady?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.295","kind":"speech"},"5.2.296":{"play":"EMILIA: Hark, canst thou hear me? I will play the swan","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.296","kind":"speech"},"5.2.297":{"play":"EMILIA: And die in music.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.297","kind":"speech"},"5.2.299":{"play":"EMILIA: Moor, she was chaste. She loved thee, cruel Moor.","notes":["Booth: With deep emotion, not harshly."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.299","kind":"speech"},"5.2.300":{"play":"EMILIA: So come my soul to bliss, as I speak true.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.300","kind":"speech"},"5.2.301":{"play":"EMILIA: So speaking as I think, alas, I die.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.301","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.301":{"play":"[She dies.]","notes":["Malone: The poet, I think, meant merely to say: 'I will now put out the lighted taper which I hold, and then put out the light of life;' and this introduces his subsequent reflection and comparison, just as aptly, as supposing the latter words of the line to be used in the same sense as in the beginning of it, which cannot be done without destroying that equivoque and play of words of which Shakespeare was so fond."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.301","kind":"stage"},"5.2.302":{"play":"OTHELLO: I have another weapon in this chamber.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.302","kind":"speech"},"5.2.303":{"play":"OTHELLO: It is a sword of Spain, the ice brook’s temper.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.303","kind":"speech"},"5.2.304":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, here it is.—Uncle, I must come forth.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.304","kind":"speech"},"5.2.305":{"play":"GRATIANO: If thou attempt it, it will cost thee dear;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.305","kind":"speech"},"5.2.306":{"play":"GRATIANO: Thou hast no weapon and perforce must suffer.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.306","kind":"speech"},"5.2.307":{"play":"OTHELLO: Look in upon me, then, and speak with me,","notes":["Walker (Crit. iii, 291): That is, express her gratitude for, recompense."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.307","kind":"speech"},"5.2.308":{"play":"OTHELLO: Or naked as I am I will assault thee.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.308","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.308.1":{"play":"[Enter Gratiano.]","notes":["Dyce (ed. iii): I agree with Malone and Walker that [thy light] is the true reading, though Boswell objects to it as introducing 'a cold conceit' (he, we may suppose, having suddenly forgotten what a crop of 'conceits' there is in Shakespeare)."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.308.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.309":{"play":"GRATIANO: What is the matter?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.309","kind":"speech"},"5.2.310":{"play":"OTHELLO: Behold, I have a weapon.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.310","kind":"speech"},"5.2.311":{"play":"OTHELLO: A better never did itself sustain","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.311","kind":"speech"},"5.2.312":{"play":"OTHELLO: Upon a soldier’s thigh. I have seen the day","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.312","kind":"speech"},"5.2.313":{"play":"OTHELLO: That with this little arm and this good sword","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.313","kind":"speech"},"5.2.314":{"play":"OTHELLO: I have made my way through more impediments","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.314","kind":"speech"},"5.2.315":{"play":"OTHELLO: Than twenty times your stop. But—O vain boast!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.315","kind":"speech"},"5.2.316":{"play":"OTHELLO: Who can control his fate? ’Tis not so now.","notes":["Johnson: 'Villainy' has taken advantage to play upon the weakness of a violent passion."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.316","kind":"speech"},"5.2.317":{"play":"OTHELLO: Be not afraid, though you do see me weaponed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.317","kind":"speech"},"5.2.318":{"play":"OTHELLO: Here is my journey’s end, here is my butt","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.318","kind":"speech"},"5.2.319":{"play":"OTHELLO: And very sea-mark of my utmost sail.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.319","kind":"speech"},"5.2.320":{"play":"OTHELLO: Do you go back dismayed? ’Tis a lost fear.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.320","kind":"speech"},"5.2.321":{"play":"OTHELLO: Man but a rush against Othello’s breast,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.321","kind":"speech"},"5.2.322":{"play":"OTHELLO: And he retires. Where should Othello go?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.322","kind":"speech"},"5.2.323":{"play":"OTHELLO: Now, how dost thou look now? O ill-starred wench,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.323","kind":"speech"},"5.2.324":{"play":"OTHELLO: Pale as thy smock, when we shall meet at compt,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.324","kind":"speech"},"5.2.325":{"play":"OTHELLO: This look of thine will hurl my soul from heaven,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.325","kind":"speech"},"5.2.326":{"play":"OTHELLO: And fiends will snatch at it. Cold, cold, my girl?","notes":["Booth: He starts at this word."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.326","kind":"speech"},"5.2.327":{"play":"OTHELLO: Even like thy chastity.—O cursèd, cursèd slave!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.327","kind":"speech"},"5.2.328":{"play":"OTHELLO: Whip me, you devils,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.328","kind":"speech"},"5.2.329":{"play":"OTHELLO: From the possession of this heavenly sight!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.329","kind":"speech"},"5.2.330":{"play":"OTHELLO: Blow me about in winds, roast me in sulfur,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.330","kind":"speech"},"5.2.331":{"play":"OTHELLO: Wash me in steep-down gulfs of liquid fire!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.331","kind":"speech"},"5.2.332":{"play":"OTHELLO: O Desdemon! Dead, Desdemon! Dead! O, O!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.332","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.332.1":{"play":"[Enter Lodovico, Cassio in a chair, Montano, and Iago, with Officers.]","notes":["Johnson: Othello means that Desdemona's crime is the sole motive or reason that impels him to the present act; that in this alone he has a justifying cause, a 'compelling occasion,' for what he is about to do; so that he cannot justly lie under the reproach of having acted from any subjective or self-generated animus of revengeful jealousy."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.332.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.333":{"play":"LODOVICO: Where is this rash and most unfortunate man?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.333","kind":"speech"},"5.2.334":{"play":"OTHELLO: That’s he that was Othello. Here I am.","notes":["Johnson: She means to say, 'I have in this cause power to endure more than thou hast power to inflict.'"],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.334","kind":"speech"},"5.2.335":{"play":"LODOVICO: Where is that viper? Bring the villain forth.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.335","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.335.1":{"play":"[Iago is brought forward.]","notes":["Johnson: This line is difficult. 'Thou hast hardened my heart, and makest me kill thee with the rage of a murderer, when I thought to have sacrificed thee to justice with the calmness of a priest striking a victim.'"],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.335.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.336":{"play":"OTHELLO: I look down towards his feet; but that’s a fable.—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.336","kind":"speech"},"5.2.337":{"play":"OTHELLO: If that thou be’st a devil, I cannot kill thee.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.337","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.337.1":{"play":"[He stabs Iago.]","notes":["Walker (Crit. iii, 291): That is, plead, as in the old sense of solicitor; yet I do not know that plead exactly expresses the meaning."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.337.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.338":{"play":"LODOVICO: Wrench his sword from him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.338","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.338.1":{"play":"[Othello is disarmed.]","notes":["Booth: Paces the room."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.338.1","kind":"stage"},"5.2.339":{"play":"IAGO: I bleed, sir, but not killed.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.339","kind":"speech"},"5.2.340":{"play":"OTHELLO: I am not sorry neither. I’d have thee live,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.340","kind":"speech"},"5.2.341":{"play":"OTHELLO: For in my sense ’tis happiness to die.","notes":["Booth: Short and sharp. He darts a quick, steely glance at her in defiance, yet quails as she proceeds, and speaks line 212 with desperation."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.341","kind":"speech"},"5.2.342":{"play":"LODOVICO: O thou Othello, that wert once so good,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.342","kind":"speech"},"5.2.343":{"play":"LODOVICO: Fall’n in the practice of a damnèd slave,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.343","kind":"speech"},"5.2.344":{"play":"LODOVICO: What shall be said to thee?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.344","kind":"speech"},"5.2.345":{"play":"OTHELLO: Why, anything.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.345","kind":"speech"},"5.2.346":{"play":"OTHELLO: An honorable murderer, if you will,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.346","kind":"speech"},"5.2.347":{"play":"OTHELLO: For naught I did in hate, but all in honor.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.347","kind":"speech"},"5.2.348":{"play":"LODOVICO: This wretch hath part confessed his villainy.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.348","kind":"speech"},"5.2.349":{"play":"LODOVICO: Did you and he consent in Cassio’s death?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.349","kind":"speech"},"5.2.350":{"play":"OTHELLO: Ay.","notes":["Booth: lago gloats over this quietly. Emilia sits on divan, c."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.350","kind":"speech"},"5.2.351":{"play":"CASSIO: Dear general, I never gave you cause.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.351","kind":"speech"},"5.2.352":{"play":"OTHELLO: I do believe it, and I ask your pardon.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.352","kind":"speech"},"5.2.353":{"play":"OTHELLO: Will you, I pray, demand that demi-devil","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.353","kind":"speech"},"5.2.354":{"play":"OTHELLO: Why he hath thus ensnared my soul and body?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.354","kind":"speech"},"5.2.355":{"play":"IAGO: Demand me nothing. What you know, you know.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.355","kind":"speech"},"5.2.356":{"play":"IAGO: From this time forth I never will speak word.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.356","kind":"speech"},"5.2.357":{"play":"LODOVICO: What? Not to pray?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.357","kind":"speech"},"5.2.358":{"play":"GRATIANO: Torments will ope your lips.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.358","kind":"speech"},"5.2.359":{"play":"OTHELLO: Well, thou dost best.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.359","kind":"speech"},"5.2.360":{"play":"LODOVICO: Sir,","notes":["Booth: Gratiano falls into a seat near the bed, soon after his' entrance, when he discovers his niece dead."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.360","kind":"speech"},"5.2.361":{"play":"LODOVICO: You shall understand what hath befall’n,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.361","kind":"speech"},"5.2.362":{"play":"LODOVICO: Which, as I think, you know not. Here is a letter","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.362","kind":"speech"},"5.2.363":{"play":"LODOVICO: Found in the pocket of the slain Roderigo,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.363","kind":"speech"},"5.2.364":{"play":"LODOVICO: And here another. The one of","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.364","kind":"speech"},"5.2.365":{"play":"LODOVICO: them imports","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.365","kind":"speech"},"5.2.366":{"play":"LODOVICO: The death of Cassio, to be undertook","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.366","kind":"speech"},"5.2.367":{"play":"LODOVICO: By Roderigo.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.367","kind":"speech"},"5.2.368":{"play":"OTHELLO: O villain!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.368","kind":"speech"},"5.2.369":{"play":"CASSIO: Most heathenish and most gross.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.369","kind":"speech"},"5.2.370":{"play":"LODOVICO: Now here’s another discontented paper","notes":["Booth: Iago, who has turned aside, now faces them as all look towards him."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.370","kind":"speech"},"5.2.371":{"play":"LODOVICO: Found in his pocket, too; and this it seems","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.371","kind":"speech"},"5.2.372":{"play":"LODOVICO: Roderigo meant t’ have sent this damnèd villain,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.372","kind":"speech"},"5.2.373":{"play":"LODOVICO: But that, belike, Iago in the interim","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.373","kind":"speech"},"5.2.374":{"play":"LODOVICO: Came in and satisfied him.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.374","kind":"speech"},"5.2.375":{"play":"OTHELLO: O, thou pernicious caitiff!—","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.375","kind":"speech"},"5.2.376":{"play":"OTHELLO: How came you, Cassio, by that handkerchief","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.376","kind":"speech"},"5.2.377":{"play":"OTHELLO: That was my wife’s?","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.377","kind":"speech"},"5.2.378":{"play":"CASSIO: I found it in my chamber.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.378","kind":"speech"},"5.2.379":{"play":"CASSIO: And he himself confessed it but even now,","notes":["Steevens: Compare, for the same thought: Mer. of Ven. III, ii, 44, and King John, V, vii, 21."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.379","kind":"speech"},"5.2.380":{"play":"CASSIO: That there he dropped it for a special purpose","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.380","kind":"speech"},"5.2.381":{"play":"CASSIO: Which wrought to his desire.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.381","kind":"speech"},"5.2.382":{"play":"OTHELLO: O fool, fool, fool!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.382","kind":"speech"},"5.2.383":{"play":"CASSIO: There is besides, in Roderigo’s letter,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.383","kind":"speech"},"5.2.384":{"play":"CASSIO: How he upbraids Iago, that he made him","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.384","kind":"speech"},"5.2.385":{"play":"CASSIO: Brave me upon the watch, whereon it came","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.385","kind":"speech"},"5.2.386":{"play":"CASSIO: That I was cast. And even but now he spake,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.386","kind":"speech"},"5.2.387":{"play":"CASSIO: After long seeming dead: Iago hurt him,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.387","kind":"speech"},"5.2.388":{"play":"CASSIO: Iago set him on.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.388","kind":"speech"},"5.2.389":{"play":"LODOVICO: You must forsake this room and go with us.","notes":["Booth: Goes towards the bed, near which his sword falls from his hand."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.389","kind":"speech"},"5.2.390":{"play":"LODOVICO: Your power and your command is taken off,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.390","kind":"speech"},"5.2.391":{"play":"LODOVICO: And Cassio rules in Cyprus. For this slave,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.391","kind":"speech"},"5.2.392":{"play":"LODOVICO: If there be any cunning cruelty","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.392","kind":"speech"},"5.2.393":{"play":"LODOVICO: That can torment him much and hold him long,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.393","kind":"speech"},"5.2.394":{"play":"LODOVICO: It shall be his. You shall close prisoner rest,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.394","kind":"speech"},"5.2.395":{"play":"LODOVICO: Till that the nature of your fault be known","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.395","kind":"speech"},"5.2.396":{"play":"LODOVICO: To the Venetian state.—Come, bring away.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.396","kind":"speech"},"5.2.397":{"play":"OTHELLO: Soft you. A word or two before you go.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.397","kind":"speech"},"5.2.398":{"play":"OTHELLO: I have done the state some service, and they","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.398","kind":"speech"},"5.2.399":{"play":"OTHELLO: know ’t.","notes":["Steevens: An allusion, says Staunton, to the mock tournaments, in which the combatants were armed with rushes in place of spears."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.399","kind":"speech"},"5.2.400":{"play":"OTHELLO: No more of that. I pray you in your letters,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.400","kind":"speech"},"5.2.401":{"play":"OTHELLO: When you shall these unlucky deeds relate,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.401","kind":"speech"},"5.2.402":{"play":"OTHELLO: Speak of me as I am. Nothing extenuate,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.402","kind":"speech"},"5.2.403":{"play":"OTHELLO: Nor set down aught in malice. Then must you speak","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.403","kind":"speech"},"5.2.404":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of one that loved not wisely, but too well;","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.404","kind":"speech"},"5.2.405":{"play":"OTHELLO: Of one not easily jealous, but being wrought,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.405","kind":"speech"},"5.2.406":{"play":"OTHELLO: Perplexed in the extreme; of one whose hand,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.406","kind":"speech"},"5.2.407":{"play":"OTHELLO: Like the base Judean, threw a pearl away","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.407","kind":"speech"},"5.2.408":{"play":"OTHELLO: Richer than all his tribe; of one whose subdued","notes":["Dyce: That is, the reckoning at the Judgement-day."],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.408","kind":"speech"},"5.2.409":{"play":"OTHELLO: eyes,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.409","kind":"speech"},"5.2.410":{"play":"OTHELLO: Albeit unused to the melting mood,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.410","kind":"speech"},"5.2.411":{"play":"OTHELLO: Drops tears as fast as the Arabian trees","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.411","kind":"speech"},"5.2.412":{"play":"OTHELLO: Their medicinable gum. Set you down this.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.412","kind":"speech"},"5.2.413":{"play":"OTHELLO: And say besides, that in Aleppo once,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.413","kind":"speech"},"5.2.414":{"play":"OTHELLO: Where a malignant and a turbanned Turk","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.414","kind":"speech"},"5.2.415":{"play":"OTHELLO: Beat a Venetian and traduced the state,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.415","kind":"speech"},"5.2.416":{"play":"OTHELLO: I took by th’ throat the circumcisèd dog,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.416","kind":"speech"},"5.2.417":{"play":"OTHELLO: And smote him, thus.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.417","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.417":{"play":"[He stabs himself.]","notes":["Steevens: Othello appears to have been a favourite of his author; he has bestowed on him that piety which he had refused to Hamlet. See Ham. iii, iii, 94.","See III, i, 58."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.417","kind":"stage"},"5.2.418":{"play":"LODOVICO: O bloody period!","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.418","kind":"speech"},"5.2.419":{"play":"GRATIANO: All that is spoke is marred.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.419","kind":"speech"},"5.2.420":{"play":"OTHELLO: I kissed thee ere I killed thee. No way but this,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.420","kind":"speech"},"5.2.421":{"play":"OTHELLO: Killing myself, to die upon a kiss.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.421","kind":"speech"},"5.2.422":{"play":"CASSIO: This did I fear, but thought he had no weapon,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.422","kind":"speech"},"5.2.423":{"play":"CASSIO: For he was great of heart.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.423","kind":"speech"},"5.2.424":{"play":"LODOVICO: O Spartan dog,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.424","kind":"speech"},"5.2.425":{"play":"LODOVICO: More fell than anguish, hunger, or the sea,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.425","kind":"speech"},"5.2.426":{"play":"LODOVICO: Look on the tragic loading of this bed.","notes":["Maginn (p. 260, note): This is strange language. Should it not be, 'I [i.e., Ay, as usual in Shakespeare], bled, sir, but not killed'?"],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.426","kind":"speech"},"5.2.427":{"play":"LODOVICO: This is thy work.—The object poisons sight.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.427","kind":"speech"},"5.2.428":{"play":"LODOVICO: Let it be hid.—Gratiano, keep the house,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.428","kind":"speech"},"5.2.429":{"play":"LODOVICO: And seize upon the fortunes of the Moor,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.429","kind":"speech"},"5.2.430":{"play":"LODOVICO: For they succeed on you. To you, lord","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.430","kind":"speech"},"5.2.431":{"play":"LODOVICO: governor,","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.431","kind":"speech"},"5.2.432":{"play":"LODOVICO: Remains the censure of this hellish villain.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.432","kind":"speech"},"5.2.433":{"play":"LODOVICO: The time, the place, the torture, O, enforce it.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.433","kind":"speech"},"5.2.434":{"play":"LODOVICO: Myself will straight aboard, and to the state","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.434","kind":"speech"},"5.2.435":{"play":"LODOVICO: This heavy act with heavy heart relate.","notes":[],"folgerAnchor":"5.2.435","kind":"speech"},"SD_5.2.435.1":{"play":"[They exit.]","notes":["Booth: Say it with all your heart and soul.","Booth: Not a savage brute. Remember this."],"folgerAnchor":"SD 5.2.435.1","kind":"stage"}},"_meta":{"textSource":"Folger Digital Texts TEI (CC BY-NC)","playId":"Oth","alignment":"nv_notes_mapped_by_scene_text_similarity","legacySceneSegments":{"ACT 2, SCENE 2":["ACT 2, SCENE 2","ACT 2, SCENE 3"]},"noteOverridesFile":"Public/Data/othello_note_overrides.json","noteOverridesApplied":[{"from":"ACT 2, SCENE 3 / 2.3.30","to":"ACT 2, SCENE 3 / 2.3.1","matchedBy":"Good Michael] Cowden-Clarke","reason":"Gloss refers to Othello's line; automated match followed legacy keying."}],"noteOverridesVersion":1}}